<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-LIGHTNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEETCH BREAKS ARM AS RANGERS TOP LIGHTNING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Even when they win, the New York Rangers lose.
</P>
<P>
   Playing desperate hockey from the start, the Rangers turned in
their most complete performance in more than a month to end the
Tampa Bay Lightning's home-ice winning streak at five games with a
6-3 victory at the Ice Palace here Wednesday night. But the victory
came at a tremendous cost as the Rangers captain, Brian Leetch,
broke his right arm blocking a shot by Fredrik Modin seven minutes
into the game.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate word on how long Leetch would be out. But
if he is out for a couple of months, the Rangers _ who won for only
the third time in their last 14 games _ are in for even more
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Rangers were without Leetch, their best
offensive defenseman, for a significant chunk of the season was in
1992-93, when Leetch missed 48 games due to injury. Leetch sat out
34 straight games from Dec. 17 to March 9 that season with a
compressed nerve in his neck, and then the final 13 games of the
season after he fractured his right ankle on March 19. The Rangers
finished last in their division that season.
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Leetch, 31, _ who signed a four-year contract
extension this summer worth $34 million _ was not the only one
suffered by the Rangers defensive corps tonight. The Rangers also
lost defenseman Stephane Quintal to a possible concussion midway
through the first period. They had to play the final 2 1-2 periods
with only four healthy defensemen, including one, Kevin Hatcher,
who had been a healthy scratch four of the team's previous six
games due to his poor play.
</P>
<P>
   And that wasn't all so far as injuries went. Center Tim Taylor,
who has been the Rangers' best forward all season despite an
appendectomy, a concussion, a foot injury and surgery to remove a
splinter from his hand, left Wednesday night with bruised ribs
after blocking a shot by Pavel Kubina with his body 4 minutes 48
seconds into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the Rangers prevailed against a much-improved Lightning
squad, thanks to goals from Kevin Stevens, Mike Knuble, Mathieu
Schneider, Michael York, Petr Nedved and Alexandre Daigle.
</P>
<P>
   Daigle, who was appearing for the first time against the Tampa
Bay team that let him go for free to the Rangers, also had a an
assist.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Leetch could not have been a more devastating injury
for the Rangers' embattled coach John Muckler and their equally
embattled president and general manager, Neil Smith, who have
presided over a 6-12-3-1 start.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning was attempting to set a club record with its sixth
straight victory on home ice. The Rangers were looking for their
first victory in nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   So both teams had something to play for this evening; and they
both came out flying from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Within the game's first 45 seconds, each team had hit a post, as
shots from Tampa's Darcy Tucker and the Rangers' Theo Fleury
clanged off the iron within 10 seconds of one another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
