 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas' Applewhite, Texas A&AMP;M's McCown share similar skills,
intangibles
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MAJOR Applewhite and Randy McCown have a lot in common.
</P>
<P>
   They are quarterbacks at the state's two largest universities
and have put up numbers this season others would envy.
</P>
<P>
   And as is the proverbial norm for quarterbacks everywhere, they
probably get too much credit when things go well and definitely
shoulder too much blame when things go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe the most shared characteristic of the two is a will to
do whatever it takes to get better.
</P>
<P>
   Now, here comes the one obligatory line that is present in every
story on Applewhite and McCown.
</P>
<P>
   (Just as Applewhite deadpanned earlier this season, ``There
can't be an article about me without at least one crack,'' the same
holds true for McCown.)
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at them. Neither looks like he is the type of guy to
lead Texas or Texas A&AMP;M onto a football field, but they will do so
for the second time against each other Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Applewhite's Longhorns prevailed in a 26-24 thriller.
This will be McCown's last chance to even the score.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' Mack Brown and Texas A&AMP;M's R.C. Slocum have talked about
the importance of their running backs _ Hodges Mitchell, Ja'Mar
Toombs, Ricky Brown, Tiki Hardeman, et al.
</P>
<P>
   And the teams' coaches have gone on at length about the boys up
front _ Casey Hampton, Semisi Heimuli, Shaun Rogers, Chris
Valletta, et al.
</P>
<P>
   Their contributions will indeed be valuable, but Applewhite and
McCown will make the difference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite, the Texas sophomore quarterback, has already topped
the school's single-season marks for pass attempts (414) and
completions (251), passing yardage (3,132) and touchdown passes
(21).
</P>
<P>
   ``He continues to play as well as any quarterback in the
country,'' Brown said of Applewhite. ``He's poised, confident and
rarely makes a mistake. With him out there, you always know you
have a chance. He makes everybody else's job easier. I know he
makes it easier on a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't make it easy on a defense, and he won't make it easy
on the Aggies this week.
</P>
<P>
   Last year against A&AMP;M, Applewhite completed 24 of 35 passes for
232 yards, and led the Longhorns on a scintillating 70-yard,
11-play drive in the final two minutes to set up Kris Stockton's
game-winning field goal with five seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great quarterback,'' A&AMP;M linebacker Jason Glenn said.
``He's just a redshirt sophomore, but he plays like he's a senior.
I believe he's going to be a Heisman candidate next year.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Applewhite cannot be stopped. At least the
Aggies hope not.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M hopes to take a page out of the Kansas State book in
getting after the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   K-State disguised its blitzes, sending people from different
spots than it normally does. Even when Texas had the blitzes picked
up, K-State beat blockers one-on-one to get pressure on Applewhite,
resulting in three fumbles and three interceptions in his worst day
as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let a quarterback like him sit back there and have
all day to pass; he'll pick you apart,'' Glenn said. ``You've got
to put pressure on him, let him know he's going to get hit over and
over. Hopefully, he'll get nervous and start making some
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazzled nerves are far from the norm for Applewhite, who Texas
receiver Kwame Cavil refers to as the ``Ice Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Cavil should know. He has been on the receiving end of 85
Applewhite tosses this season, establishing a Texas and Big 12
Conference record. Cavil, who will be the third Longhorn and first
since Bob Bryant in 1956 to lead a conference in receptions, needs
just 72 receiving yards to set a school mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you know is Major will get the ball to you,'' Cavil
said. ``You can count on that. He gives you the chance to make
plays. He makes the right reads and the right throws. We just have
that connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite has found a connection with Ryan Nunez as well.
Nunez, who with 53 receptions is second in the conference in
catches, has been a solid compliment to Cavil, as has Montrell
Flowers, who leads the Longhorns in yards per catch (17.1) and is
tied with Cavil for receiving touchdowns with six.
</P>
<P>
   But the key to their success is Applewhite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is a real good player, he makes really good
decisions,'' Slocum said of Applewhite. ``He is very poised, he
does a good job of protecting the football, he's a very accurate
passer, and he is the key to their offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Though everyone heaps praise on his football intelligence,
Applewhite said he cannot afford to rest on his laurels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great compliment, but you realize you don't rest on
that, obviously,'' said Applewhite, one of 10 semifinalists for the
Davey O'Brien Award, which is given yearly to the nation's top
quarterback. ``You understand why they say that. (It's) because you
have coaches preparing you, you have a will to prepare yourself and
you have a will to try to lead and help others.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCown, A&AMP;M's senior signal-caller, hasn't gotten the acclaim
that Applewhite has, but he is just 246 yards from Kevin Murray's
A&AMP;M mark for passing yards in a single season (2,463 yards in
1986).
</P>
<P>
   McCown got his first start as a sophomore against Texas Tech in
1997, but more than half his 18 career starts have come this
season. Applewhite is only a sophomore, but he has started 20 games
for the seventh-ranked Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy has been a solid guy,'' Slocum said. ``He worked to
become a starter and was very supportive as a backup player. When
we have called on him to play, he has done a good job for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy has had a good career, we won a Big 12 Championship last
year (when he started seven games) and we're going to a bowl game
this year. I think he has been a good representative of the program
on and off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown's season ended last year against the Longhorns when he
broke his collarbone diving for a fourth-quarter touchdown that was
part of a spectacular 17-point comeback, but he is not thinking
about that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys did kind of cost me a lot of fun last year, but
that's water under the bridge,'' McCown said. ``This is my last
game at Kyle Field, so I'm not thinking about that kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticism from some corners, he will be only the third
Aggie to finish a season with an average of more than 200 passing
yards a game. With just 48 passing yards against Texas, he will
move past Gary Kubiak and finish his career fifth on the all-time
Aggies passing chart.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 games this season, McCown has completed 144 of his 273
attempts for 2,218 yards and 13 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectations are so high and because of that, perhaps
people sometimes can look at things positively or negatively,''
Slocum said. ``You look at the numbers Randy has put up this year,
he certainly has done a credible job. You look at him, and he has
had one of the best passing seasons A&AMP;M has had.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said injuries at running back and the Aggies'
inefficiency at times on offense have overshadowed McCown's
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies had their first 100-yard rusher in their 10th game,
and much of freshman Joe Weber's total came in garbage time against
a soundly whipped Missouri team.
</P>
<P>
   Without a solid rushing attack (3.6 yards a carry), McCown's
numbers are even more impressive. Mitchell has eased the burden on
Applewhite with 1,227 yards (Toombs leads A&AMP;M with 457) and Texas
averages a half-a-yard more per carry than the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely difficult to (put up good passing numbers) when
your running game is not there,'' Applewhite said. ``They'll play
the corner(backs) off and then put everybody else in and start
blitzing you. It helps when you have a guy to take the load off
your back.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M had its season high in rushing (254 yards) in its last
outing, a 51-14 spanking of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally got the running game and passing game going in the
same game,'' McCown said. ``There's no telling where we'd be now if
we had jelled like that at the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things might have been a lot different. But you can't go back
and do anything about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe McCown can't do anything about the previous 10 games, but
he is looking to do damage in this one. It will be a challenge
against the sixth-rated defense in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' defense has been stingy when it comes to rushing attacks
(11th in the nation at 92.5 yards a game), so the Aggies will
likely have to lean on McCown's arm to earn a win.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Longhorns will lean on Applewhite's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
