<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Gailey might be walking tightrope
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRVING _ Jimmy Johnson has warned the Dolphins. He has put them
on notice, loudly and frequently. If their minds are still
wandering, it's out of his hands now. If they're determined to look
past the Dallas Cowboys to the big game, which is their next one
against Indianapolis, what can he do?
</P>
<P>
   Such is the upside-down state of the NFL in 1999. The mice have
become men. The cabbages are kings. The meek have inherited the
earth. The Cowboys are the undercard, the Colts the main event.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for Jimmy personally, of course. Oh, no. Hook him up to a
polygraph, then inquire as to whether he would rather whip Dallas
or Indianapolis, and we'd have a pretty good idea which answer
would make the machine go ``beep!''
</P>
<P>
   For Johnson, the Colts are merely an important division rival,
steeped in youthful talent. They are a steppingstone to the
playoffs and perhaps the home-field advantage once there. The
Cowboys? They represent a far more volatile, complicated mix of
emotions, running the gamut from love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has nothing but good tidings for the Dallas players he
knows, the guys he shaped and honed into twice Super Bowl
champions. He'll never have a bond with Dan Marino equal to the one
he forged with Troy Aikman. Together, Jimmy and Troy made a lot of
something out of 1-15 nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Flopping in the fourth
</P>
<P>
   Then, just like that, it all ended. Jerry Jones thought Jimmy
had become bigger than the Cowboys, a luxury only one man _ Jones _
would be permitted. Their egos clashed openly after the second of
the back-to-back titles, and Johnson wound up a talking head on TV,
biding time until the Miami job came open.
</P>
<P>
   Jones felt he was vindicated for chasing Jimmy off when his
stooge, Barry Switzer, copped another Vince Lombardi Trophy for him
two seasons later. But the Cowboys' travails of late have made
Jones look more like a chump than a champ. Somebody must be
accountable. For Dallas' current coach, Chan Gailey, Johnson is the
last guy he needs to have visit him at Texas Stadium for
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Given the subplots and side issues, a Dolphins victory,
particularly if it's by a lopsided margin, may mark the formal
beginning of the end for Chan. If the Cowboys appreciate Gailey
anywhere near as much as they once did Jimmy, they will play their
hearts out for him. Jones will not suffer more foolishness gladly
today.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is 5-5 despite having scored first in every game and
leading nine of the 10 at halftime. In their five defeats, the
Cowboys have lost the fourth quarter 50-9. Such facts aren't
reflective of a coach who makes sound strategic adjustments as the
game wears on or who inspires supreme effort when fatigue and
frustration have set in.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's Cowboys teams had the intangibles Gailey's team lacks.
But Johnson's Cowboys teams also had the tangibles. Aikman, Emmitt
Smith and Michael Irvin were gods and monsters back then, both
low-mileage and high-performance. Jimmy most definitely was in the
right place at the right time. He hasn't been quite the genius in
Miami as he was in Dallas, has he?
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Turner a possibility
</P>
<P>
   Gailey suffers by comparison nonetheless. He's an X's and O's
wonk, a rumpled, slightly lumpy fellow who casts no aura
whatsoever. Jones hired him because he was highly thought of as an
offensive tactician in Pittsburgh and because his presence would
pose no threat to that of the boss. Like Barry, he wouldn't cross
Jerry. Unlike Barry, he would be a credible authority figure, not a
cardboard cutout of a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry gambled that Chan's coaching would put the Pokes back on
top after emperor Switzer's nakedness was finally noted, and he,
Jerry, could bask in the glory. The scheme might have worked, too,
if the Cowboys hadn't been so beaten down by injuries, starting
with the loss of wide receiver James McKnight, who blew out a knee
in a dumb exercise called the Blue-White game in training camp.
McKnight was brought in from Seattle to stretch defenses and take
the weight off Irvin. Now, Irvin is gone as well, perhaps
permanently because of a spinal condition.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, meanwhile, plays with a broken hand, and Aikman, who
returns after a forced two-game respite, tries to clear the cobwebs
from his bruised brain.
</P>
<P>
   However, all their problems notwithstanding, the Cowboys trail
only Washington in the NFC East, and they have beaten the Redskins
twice.
</P>
<P>
   More irony: It's the Redskins' coach, Norv Turner, whose shadow
dogs Gailey daily. Another guy Jones could keep on a short leash,
Turner is himself likely to be fired by the Skins. Jerry had much
affection for Norv when he was Johnson's offensive coordinator, so
speculation has begun that he'll replace Chan.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine a Redskins reject coaching the Dallas Cowboys? I
suppose if it's possible to imagine the Colts being of more
consequence than the Cowboys, you can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
