u s BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      11-25 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
In wake of tragedy, rivalry gains dignified air
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The will to win remains strong for both sides. The dislike of the
color orange in College Station and maroon in Austin hasn't
changed. But something is missing from the Texas A&AMP;M-Texas rivalry
this season.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be a lessening of the vitriol between the sides
in the wake of the Aggie Bonfire accident that claimed the lives of
12 people last week.
</P>
<P>
   Players, fans and administration of the University of Texas have
responded with sympathy and support to the A&AMP;M family. Even the
most intense fans of both teams have reached out and grieved
together in the wake of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   According to Texas coach Mack Brown and Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C.
Slocum, the ratcheting down of the hate factor in the rivalry could
usher the series into the new millennium with a degree of dignity
that has been lacking recently.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with the annual game Friday morning, Brown and
Slocum appeared Wednesday at the Houston Touchdown Club luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been remarkable no matter how hard-core of a Texas fan
you are, you still have sympathy for what has happened,'' said
Slocum. ``Likewise, A&AMP;M people, regardless of their feelings about
Texas, realize it's really nice of them to be sympathetic toward
us. It's brought out some good feelings on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have had to go on the line in terms of what their
reaction is. The University of Texas has stepped forward boldly.
There's been no question about what their position is. Coach Brown
and their student body and their administration have been very
supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has served to say, `Hey, wait a minute. Don't even try to
trash this team or the players or the coaches or alumni.' This game
is about college kids going out on the field and competing fiercely
against each other and then walking off the field, the loser
congratulating the winner and saying see you next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in his second season at Texas, said he has been
overwhelmed with the bonding between the bitter rivals in the wake
of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have gained more respect for Texans than ever before,''
Brown said. ``Everyone knows the passion they have for football and
for life, so you know the A&AMP;M-Texas rivalry will continue to be one
of the best rivalries in the history of college football.
</P>
<P>
   ``But maybe something positive will come out of the way that the
people throughout the state of Texas responded. Many of the people
handle the rivalry for what it is _ a great rivalry between two
great schools. But some have brought some anger into the rivalry.
Maybe this will let them understand that we should not and cannot
bring that anger to this rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the accident on Nov. 18, the chat rooms on both teams'
fan Internet Web sites were full of the usual back-and-forth
banter. Some of it was good-natured, but there were angry and, at
times, hateful messages. After the accident, Longhorns fans offered
sympathy and prayers via the Internet, and Aggies responded with
heartfelt thanks.
</P>
<P>
   There have been indications from Longhorns fans that they will
not chant ``Poooooor Aggies'' if Texas is ahead late in the game.
Aggies fans have asked that yell leaders stay away from the ``Beat
the hell outta TU'' chants. It's hard to say if those well-intended
feelings will carry over once the game starts.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, several Aggies players said they were
impressed with how the fans of the rival teams banded together in a
time of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't surprise me because, I mean, they're people up
there just like we are,'' said A&AMP;M guard Chris Valletta. ``They
understand that honoring the victims and the families is much more
important than honoring a football game. That's the attitude
they've taken, and we appreciate that more than anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad in a sense that this has grown to be a hated rivalry.
That's not something that any fan should want to be a part of. A
hated rivalry is not a good rivalry. In the past years, there has
been an attitude of wanting to beat Texas just because `We hate
Texas.' But that's not the attitude this year. Of course, Texas is
our biggest rival, and we want to win this game more than any other
game. But the circumstances are different this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said he, too, had noticed an increased amount of hatred
in the rivalry in recent years. The reaction of Aggies and
Longhorns in the last week has eased some of that in-your-face
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some deep feelings between these two schools, but I
have always resented the minority on both sides of the fence who
try to make it into an annual hate contest,'' Slocum said. ``You
know, `We hate those guys. They're this and that.' That has no
place in college football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think hate is one of the worst emotions there is. Many of
the problems in our world are caused by hate. Without a doubt, hate
had been a part of this rivalry. Not to a great extent, but people
on both sides have tried to inflame things. We had an element; so
did they.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the rivalry, though, is in a friendly, wholesome way.
I think the tragedy we've had here has put that on the top shelf.
People understand we're in life together, we're in this state
together. We want to win, and they want to win, but beyond all
that, it's just a bunch of college kids out playing a football
game.''
</P>
<P>
   At least a few of those players usually can be counted on for a
few put-down remarks in the build-up to the game. Not this week,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we have a couple comments from them saying this and
that about us, and there's comments from us about them,'' said
Aggies linebacker Jason Glenn. ``This week, it's been like a
bonding thing, which is what we need after what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say, of course, that the players will act so
gentlemanly once the ball is kicked at Kyle Field Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did the decent thing, and I respect them, and I'm
thankful for it,'' said Aggies center Seth McKinney, an Austin
native. ``But I'm telling you that once the game starts Friday,
that rivalry will be there. It's not like we're going to say,
`Well, we've got to treat these guys nice because of what they
did.' That rivalry's still going to there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
