</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIP WORTH IT FOR TWO TEAMS OF WILDCATS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the Arizona Wildcats, getting to New York was not
half the fun. But winning Wednesday night was pleasant enough and
it put them halfway to a championship in the Preseason National
Invitation Tournament
</P>
<P>
   In the opener of a doubleheader at Madison Square Garden, which
looked to be about two-thirds full, Arizona defeated Notre Dame,
76-60.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wright scored 22 points and had 11 rebounds for Arizona
(3-0). Troy Murphy scored 22 points and had 10 rebounds for Notre
Dame, which fell to 3-1. The Wildcats will play in the title game
Friday night against Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   In the second game, Kentucky guaranteed an all-Wildcats
championship with a 61-58 victory over Maryland. Tayshaun Prince
led Kentucky with 21 points. Terence Morris scored 25 for Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona players and coaches shared much in common with other
travelers in and out of New York during this holiday week. Their
journey from the West was delayed twice, once by fog and then by
mechanical difficulties. Instead of arriving on Monday night, they
got here on Tuesday night and were unable to hold their scheduled
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a horrible experience, but we finally made it and we
are relaxed now,'' said Loren Woods, Arizona's 7-foot-1-inch junior
center, who had 13 points, 10 rebounds and seven blocked shots.
``If we would have practiced yesterday, we would be so dead. We
were so tired. It was in everybody's eyes. We were exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   After arriving about 8:30 p.m. on Tuesday, the players ate
dinner, studied films and went to bed by 10:30. But Wednesday
night, they seemed fresher than the Irish, who practiced Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona sprang to a 4-0 lead and never trailed, although the
Fighting Irish drew as close as nine points with 7 minutes
remaining, but fell behind by 20 with 1:15 left as the substitutes
took the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stayed in the game,'' Wright said of the Irish. ``They
didn't let us push them over.'' But he said coach Lute Olson had
told his players to take advantage of what seemed like Irish
fatigue. ``Coach just said `Let's keep pounding it to them' because
they looked tired in the first half,'' Wright said. ``That's how we
blew the game open.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said of the fatigue factor: ``I think that we have a
little bit more depth than what they have. Murphy played 38
minutes. That's asking a lot when I think our big guys run the
court really well. It's not a case of where he can take his time in
getting back defensively because we're probably going to hurt them
if that's the case. I thought our big guys did a good job of
forcing him to play both ends of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressive for Notre Dame was Murphy, a 6-9 sophomore
forward from Morristown, N.J., who showed a shooting touch from the
outside, but tended to play low on offense. Many of the Irish plays
were high passes to Murphy, who turned and bulled his way toward
the basket, often against two or three defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to play inside,'' Murphy said. ``They doubled
well. They had a lot of tough guys inside the post. I had trouble.
I brought the ball down. I got stripped. It gave them more
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson did not underestimate the value of keeping Notre Dame off
the free-throw line. The Irish were just 3 for 6 from the line,
compared to 13 of 19 for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the game, that was the last thing I told the
guys,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   David Graves scored 17 points for the Irish. Impressive for
Arizona were Gilbert Arenas, who had 15 points, and Richard
Jefferson, who had 13. As a unit, the Wildcats were quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky and Arizona, two teams with the same nickname, have met
only four times, but one of the recent games was rather important.
In the 1997 NCAA championship game, Arizona defeated Kentucky,
84-79, in overtime. At the time, Kentucky was the defending
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, they have met just once, in the Maui tournament two
autumns ago, and that game ended in an 89-74 Arizona victory. The
following spring, Kentucky defeated Utah for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday night's thrilling finale, Kentucky led Maryland by
16 points in the first half and by 13 points at the intermission.
But Maryland tied the score at 52-52 with a tip by Morris with less
than seven minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Stone gave Kentucky the lead back with a layup and the
margin gradually increased to five points. Maryland got back to
within one point with less than two minutes to play, and trailed by
only 59-56 with 32.6 seconds to play. But Juan Dixon's 3-point
attempt hit the rim and bounced out.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
