<HEADLINE>
BRYANT ISN'T READY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kobe Bryant missed his target return date
Wednesday night, and coach Phil Jackson now expects Bryant won't
play again for another two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is presumably healing on schedule, Bryant was recently
ordered by doctors to stop shooting with his broken right hand. He
will undergo X-rays and a CT-scan again Tuesday, but Jackson _ who
hoped Bryant might play that same night _ now figures he'll be out
``at least'' another week after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like it's going to be Dec.3 or 2nd or 1st,''
he said. ``They have to reassess what the process is. It's not
there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bryant, ``That's news to me.''
</P>
<P>
   If he's out another two weeks, it will bring the total missed
time to eight weeks and perhaps 20 games. Bryant had hoped to be
back in six weeks, in time to play Utah on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. (Stephen) Lombardo told me not to really get down because
this was the healing process to begin with,'' Bryant said. ``I was
just hoping I'd come back a lot earlier. I wanted to come back
tonight. That's my expectation, that's what I was hoping for. The
doctor is another story. The bone is not ready to go. There's
nothing I can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he's participating only in noncontact drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shooting still is a little bit iffy,'' Jackson said, ``but
most of the shooting he's participating in. He's kind of like a
student trainer or assistant coach, you know, who makes passes to
the big guys.... We're just not taking the risk of an accidental
thing where someone can (hit his hand).
</P>
<P>
   ``But I anticipate (next week) that they'll say, `OK, this is
looking a lot better, now you can do some things with protection.'
Then the decision has to be made how debilitating the protection is
going to be for his game.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bryant will continue to count the days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't concentrate on what I'm going through right now,'' he
said. ``I'll focus on what to do when I get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: The Lakers' other hobbled guard, Tyronn Lue, is
eligible to return from the injured list for Friday night's game
against New Jersey, but Jackson said he's not ready.
</P>
<P>
   Lue is recovering from a bone bruise in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't practiced,'' Jackson said. ``He'll probably get a
practice in Friday at shootaround. And then we'll see what the next
week brings.''
</P>
<P>
   Streaking: A.C. Green played in his 1,041st consecutive game
Wednesday, tying the professional basketball record (for any pro
league) held by former Jazz player Ron Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who two years ago broke the NBA's ironman record,
received a standing ovation when the mark was announced during the
second quarter Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
