r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LETT-TEX     11-25 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS TEAMMATES SEE DIFFERENCE IN LETT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It was a typical Thursday at the Dallas Cowboys'
Valley Ranch training complex.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly five minutes before noon, Deion Sanders, cornerback,
kick returner and minister, made his usual come-hither speech over
the loud speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hear ye, hear ye, it's time for the Cowboys' Bible study,''
Sanders announced. ``If you get warmth from a bottle or a woman,
the only person who can give you true warmth is Jesus Christ. Come
one, come all. This is the final call.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1998 season, humbled defensive tackle Leon Lett, then
a four-time violator of the NFL's substance-abuse policy and a year
past a 16-game suspension, heeded the call on a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks removed from his third substance-abuse suspension,
Lett was back at Bible study last Thursday. He is once again on the
recovery road and trying to right a career path that has been
sidetracked by so many on- and off-the-field transgressions,
including the drug violation that caused him to be suspended for
the first eight games of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   No one is spouting of a spiritual rebirth in the vein of Sanders
or defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman. And no one is promising that
there will be no more relapses by the five-time drug-policy
offender who will take the field against the Dolphins at 3:15 p.m.
Thursday at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the feeling around Valley Ranch these days is, as defensive
coordinator Dave Campo said, ``It's time for him to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's come back with a good attitude,'' Campo continued. ``I
hope he's got it together. After three or four times, it's time for
him to do it the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lett still doesn't talk much about the litany of off-field
issues. His thoughts on his return from the latest suspension
amounted to: ``I'm excited to play again. But I want to ease into
it and take a low-key approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates, coaches and friends, however, say they notice a
difference in Lett's overall demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has more inner strength now,'' Sanders said. ``He was in
the Bible study last year, but it's one thing to be in it and it's
another to be ``in'' it. He's putting in his heart this time. I
just see him having more inner strength and inner peace. And he's
taking more control and being more responsible on and off the field
and in life.''
</P>
<P>
   While the substance-abuse issues have hogged all the latest
headlines regarding Lett, his melancholy nine years in the NFL are
dubiously notable for
</P>
<P>
   contrasting on-field images.
</P>
<P>
   On one side there's the rags-to-riches story of a 6-foot-6,
280-pound unblockable behemoth, who made the journey from being a
seventh-round long shot by way of Emporia State, Hinds (Miss.)
College and the Fairhope (Ala.) High School basketball team to
being one of the league's premier defensive linemen. Nicknamed the
``Big Cat'' because of his quickness, Lett was selected to the Pro
Bowl in 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, there's the image of a bumbler, who will be
forever known for two goofball plays in the 1992 and 1993 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The first came in the waning moments of the Cowboys' 52-17
victory over the Buffalo Bills in the 1993 Super Bowl. Lett
recovered a fumble and sprinted toward the end zone. Once he got
inside the 10-yard line the excitement of the moment caught up to
him. The normally subdued Lett began to showboat, brandishing the
football in one hand. Bills receiver Don Beebe caught Lett from
behind and knocked the ball away.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cowboys were being hailed for their first Super Bowl
title of the 1990s, Lett was being assailed nationally for a
boneheaded play.
</P>
<P>
   The humiliation intensified a year later by another error in
judgment during a nationally televised Thanksgiving Day battle,
against the Dolphins, no less. After the Cowboys blocked a Miami
field-goal attempt, Lett touched the ball after it rolled
downfield. Miami recovered and turned it into the winning field
goal in a 16-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in some sad situations,'' Campo said. ``It's like a
dark cloud has been over his head. I don't know why. Sometimes
things don't go exactly how you've planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Combine those two gaffes with the drug problems and you have an
unflattering picture that sent the already-shy Lett further into a
shell, causing a feeding frenzy for critics and pity from overly
protective friends.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, whose staunch defense of Lett in the past has been
criticized as condoning behavior, acknowledges that people close to
Lett may have been too protective of him at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a little bit of that,'' Campo said. ``But it
was because I think Leon was a unique case. In my opinion, there
are people who are caught in some bad situations and there are bad
people. I am more apt to give leeway to a bad situation than a bad
person.''
</P>
<P>
   The two people who spent the most time with him during the
latest suspension say Lett is ready to do it himself.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mavericks star Mark Aguirre played basketball daily with
Lett at the North Dallas Athletic Club from August until October.
Other than finding out that Lett has a nice hoops game, he said,
``Leon is more focused on what he has to do and what he has to
maintain than any time I've known him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith, who joined the team in 1992 and
struck up a friendship with Lett, grew even closer to him this past
August. Smith had been sent home from training camp because of back
problems. With both feeling ostracized from the team, they hung out
for comfort and companionship.
</P>
<P>
   Smith agreed with Aguirre, saying Lett knows what he has to do.
More important, however, Smith said Lett is determined to change
his life and NFL legacy before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``His whole mind-set is that he's a little disappointed in
himself, in what's happened,'' Smith said. ``He's appreciative for
the fact that he has another chance. He doesn't know how much
longer he will play. But he wants to finish his career up right and
go out on a good note. He has that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Lett is also mindful that this might be his last
chance if he fails again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels like his back is up against the wall,'' Smith said.
``He knows he can't screw up. That's pressure. But it's something
he has to deal with. For him not to know would be fooling himself.
The ball is in his court.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
