<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTICS-SPURS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS POUNDED BY SPURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a suggestion for the Big Dig types to relieve traffic
congestion in the North End: Bring the San Antonio Spurs to town
more than once a year.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio brought its ``A'' game to the FleetCenter Wednesday
night and beat the Celtics like a drum, 121-98. The world
champions, the real Men in Black, started fast and never let up.
They shot 58 percent, had 35 assists, scored a season high in
points and, in the understated assessment of coach Gregg Popovich,
``probably played our best game of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   That comes as no news to the Celtics. They trailed by 13 after
one quarter, by 24 at the half, and by 31 after three. They had no
answer to Tim Duncan, who abused them mercilessly, with 31 points,
15 rebounds, 2 blocks, and one giant, painful reminder of the
quirky nature of bouncing lottery balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an awful night for us in so many different phases of
the game,'' Celtics coach Rick Pitino said, also an understatement.
``They physically dominated us. They kicked our ass in every
conceivable phase of the game. And we deserved an ass-kicking for
playing that kind of defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics went into the game with a long list of do's and
don'ts, all of which were moot by halftime. They also went into the
game being told that the Spurs shot 50 percent from international
waters in their nine wins and 29 percent in their three losses. The
Spurs were 8-of-16 Wednesday night but were 4-of-5 in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   It was a clinic at both ends. The Spurs had the answers inside
and outside. David Robinson shook off a shoulder scare at the end
of the first half and had 10 points and 9 rebounds in 25 minutes.
Mario Elie made 10 of 12 shots and had a season-high 25 points, 2
shy of his career high. Through three quarters, the Spurs were
shooting 63 percent to the Celtics' 35.
</P>
<P>
   And the Spurs moved the ball. Did they ever move the ball. When
Chucky Brown gets six assists, you know you're moving the ball. At
the half, they had more assists (19) than the Celtics had hoops
(17). Avery Johnson had nine assists in 26 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Boston was in it for a quarter, to be generous. History will
record it actually led, 2-0. It was the Celtics' only lead. The
Spurs broke it open in the second with a Terry Porter-led 7-0 run
(40-22) and a Robinson-led 6-0 burst (46-26).
</P>
<P>
   Then Duncan took over. He had 14 points and 8 rebounds at the
half and then submitted a 14-point (on 5-of-5 shooting), 6-rebound
third. The lead went into the 30s, and the fans flocked to the
exits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to execute,'' Duncan said, ``and everything went
as we had hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   Duh. As for the Celtics, well, their miserable night was best
summed up in two telling sequences, one which spoke to the overall
confusion generated by playing a team like San Antonio and the
other to yet another exasperating evening for Antoine Walker, who
was 5-of-21.
</P>
<P>
   The first came with San Antonio leading 40-22 in the second
quarter. The Celtics had come out of a timeout and worked the ball
around until it was in Kenny Anderson's hands at the top of the
circle. The 24-shot clock expired. Every Celtic looked as though he
had just been told their per diem was being withheld. No one from
the bench was yelling down the seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The other came in the third. Walker wasn't taking bad shots _
well, not too many. But he wasn't clicking. He'd drive and miss.
He'd pop out and miss. He took four treys and missed.
</P>
<P>
   With the Celtics trailing, 60-39, Walker went in for a layup and
missed. He got the rebound and missed another layup. The ball
squirted away, and the Celtics retained possession. Walker
subsequently got the ball in front of the Boston bench and fired a
trey. It missed. Later, near the end of the third, Pitino took him
out of the game after another missed trey prompted a chorus of
boos. Walker sat for the final 15:02, his 25-minute stint his
shortest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep shooting if I get those same looks,'' Walker
said. ``That's basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino also got into it a little with the crowd, but said
afterward, ``I just coach the team. I'm not concerned about the
other stuff. We're 7-5 right now, in the thick of it, and we have
to come out and play much better defense against Milwaukee
(Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   He's right about that. It would be hard for them to play worse
defense. But the Spurs are world champions for a reason. They
showed why Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
