<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AGGIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES' LINEMAN TOUCHED BY TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Semisi Heimuli, who spent most of his
formative years in California, remembers the exact moment he
connected Texas A&AMP;M with its 12th Man football tradition.
</P>
<P>
   It came during his recruiting trip, when he noticed a sign in
Kyle Field proclaiming the place ``Home of the 12th Man.'' He
recognized the sign from casual exposure to college football
highlights through the years but never knew which school made the
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `So, this is the place,' '' said Heimuli, a
graduate of Trinity High School in Euless, Texas. ``But I had no
idea what the 12th Man was.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fifth-year senior, in the minds of many A&AMP;M fans, became
the embodiment of the school's 12th Man spirit when he became the
ringleader in organizing football players to help move fallen logs
after the collapse of the A&AMP;M bonfire tower that killed 12 students
on Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Heimuli is scheduled to make his 50th consecutive start
for the Aggies, the most by any offensive lineman in school
history. When he lines up at right guard during his final home game
at 10 a.m. against Texas, Heimuli said he will draw on images he
witnessed at the bonfire site. He will reflect on emotions he felt
during the tragedy and lessons he has learned during a college
career that have made the 12th Man notion of Aggies supporting
Aggies very real to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's neat to me because I'm not used to that kind of stuff,''
said Heimuli, who moved from suburban San Francisco to Euless as a
teen-ager in 1993. ``In California, things are different. People
don't say `hello' on the street or wave to each other when they're
driving. In hard times, they go their own way and just worry about
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you walk around campus at A&AMP;M, and people say, `Howdy.'
It's the friendliest campus around. When I saw that, I didn't know
what an Aggie was. But I knew I wanted to be one.''
</P>
<P>
   Heimuli also knew his place when he began hearing reports of
dead and injured students at the bonfire site. While living in San
Bruno, Calif., he'd lost friends to gang-related shootings.
Although not a member of a gang himself, Heimuli said such
incidents were common in his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing reports of peers dying at A&AMP;M spurred him to action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd dealt with death before. It always hurts to see young
people who never got the chance to live out their lives,'' Heimuli
said. ``Back in San Francisco, people were dying from doing bad
things. It was all gang stuff. But these guys were doing something
good when they died. That makes it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Heimuli rushed to the bonfire site, encouraging a handful of
teammates to join him. Eventually, A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum canceled
practice and urged all players to assist in the rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Images of A&AMP;M players in their sweat-stained football
undershirts, caked with dirt from lifting logs, burn brightly in
the minds of fans and fellow students. Without question,
quarterback Randy McCown said, the experience bonded the team more
tightly and Heimuli deserves credit for leading the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys went out there without truly understanding what
being an Aggie meant,'' McCown said. ``We came back with a
different perspective. You work your butt off with each other
lifting those logs, and you understand the camaraderie Aggies feel
for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken type in most public settings, Heimuli said the
emotional nature of the bonfire tragedy struck a chord within him.
As one of the first on the scene, he arrived in time to see dead
bodies removed from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they brought another one out, I'd just pray, `Not
another one. Please, God, let them find someone alive down there,'
'' Heimuli said.
</P>
<P>
   Those memories, he said, will inspire him in his final
appearance at Kyle Field. Heimuli is on pace to tie Dat Nguyen's
school record of 51 consecutive starts at the Aggies' bowl game, a
record for iron-man endurance that left guard Chris Valletta
considers ``incredible'' for an offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, the guy is unbreakable,'' Valletta said of the
6-foot-3, 309-pounder who is the first player of Tongan descent to
suit up for A&AMP;M. ``He's the kind of guy that, when he wants to do
something, you can't hold him back.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if Heimuli wants to lend a helping hand to fellow
Aggies. A week after the bonfire tragedy, he still is uncomfortable
with praise he has received for simply helping out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole time we were out there, people kept coming up to us
and saying, `Thanks for being out here.' It's like they thought we
were special,'' Heimuli said. ``I don't think that. We're Aggies,
too. We may play football, but we're no different than anyone else
at this school. We should have been out there. There were people in
need and we responded.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
