<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WRECK OF KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Saturday, November 27, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While President Clinton lectured the Kosovars about tolerance
earlier this week, the ethnic cleansing that has been going on
under the noses of NATO continued. The Serb population is being
systematically reduced by hostile Albanians, and every day, smoke
rises from the burning of yet another Serb house. The Czech Jiri
Dienstbier, the UN representative on human rights, put it
succinctly: ``The spring ethnic cleansing of ethnic Albanians,
accompanied by murders, torture, looting, and burning of houses,
has been replaced by the autumn ethnic cleansing of Serbs, Romas,
Bosniaks, and other non-Albanians accompanied by the same
atrocities.'' Romas are Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked the Albanian Kosovars whether they want revenge or
a better life. The answer is they want both. The Serb population of
Kosovo numbers between 60,000 and 70,000, down from more than
200,000 a couple of years ago. NATO is hopelessly unable to protect
the Serb population, and the UN efforts are underfunded,
understaffed, and demoralized.
</P>
<P>
   The shadowy Kosovar Liberation Army is lying low. Nobody who
knows anything about the Balkans believes these fighters will
simply fold their tents and accept the peaceful role that NATO has
prepared for them and that they have pretended to accept. They want
power and mean to have it.
</P>
<P>
   This century began with nationalistic wars in the Balkans,
taking advantage of the waning Ottoman power. Those wars have
resumed at century's end. The ethnic sorting out is not yet over,
and the humpty-dumpty dream of multiethnic harmony will not soon be
put back together again despite the idealistic American belief that
everyone can and should act just like Americans.
</P>
<P>
   With a typical predilection for euphemism, the State Department
now likes to talk about ``Southeast Europe'' to avoid the negative
connotations of ``the Balkans.'' But the dictionary definition of
balkanization still remains the breakup of societies into ever
smaller and hostile units.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, a new tyranny is waiting in the wings to replace the
old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
