<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-RELAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READERS, DIGEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Saturday, November 27, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Relax. It's still Thanksgiving weekend, still fall, still
November. The crunch doesn't have to start until next month.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the world may be acting as though a starter pistol just
went off, but a person can resist. A person can recall the immortal
words of Mom: ``If everybody jumped off the Brooklyn Bridge, would
you have to do it too?''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the season of joy often feels like a leap off a
bridge, from relative calm into chaos, and retailers try to push
consumers toward the edge earlier each year. The prodding begins in
the summer now, and by September, jolly holly elves are muscling in
on the Halloween outfits. Cardboard turkeys can hardly hold their
shelf space as in-between decorations anymore, which heightens the
frazzle factor for a person who can remember when the bird flew
solo for at least a month.
</P>
<P>
   Some people insist on mailing their Christmas cards before the
bird is cooked, which is really scary. Greetings received in the
middle of November should be returned to sender, stamped
``Undeliverable In Any Month Not Beginning with the Letter `D' or
'J.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Compulsiveness kills the spirit, which must be given special
care and feeding. The TLC should begin this weekend with real time
off _ a Saturday and a Sunday with nothing planned but sitting
around, much like that turkey carcass.
</P>
<P>
   A person does not have to get out there and shift those seasonal
gears. A person can wait until Wednesday at least _ the first day
of December _ or until next weekend, even, starting slowly in, say,
a small local shop with not too much merchandise on a quiet street
far from any parking garages. Figure on buying one present max, and
then plan on a nice quiet coffee break or a movie.
</P>
<P>
   The coming weeks will be easier, perhaps even fun, if the goal
isn't to get it all done but to pace oneself and extend the season
of giving to one's own mall-rattled psyche. What's your pleasure _
a walk, a swim, a massage, an afternoon with a book? Take the
relaxation pledge and make time for joy, starting now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 0034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
