SWEET TALK CAN'T COVER UP THE FEUD BETWEEN JJs 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listening to Jerry and Jimmy all week, it makes you wonder where
was this mutual-admiration society five years, seven months, and 25
days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Jerry and Jimmy all week, it also makes you think
about investing in a polygraph machine.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they're being less than truthful with the nice stuff, to
such a degree one of our most treasured holidays has become
Thanksfibbing Day.
</P>
<P>
   What was heard from both parties seems to be a blatant attempt
to bring personal closure to the Great Macho War of 1994. That
parting of Jerry and Jimmy will live forever in national and local
sports lore. That parting has now brought happiness to both.
</P>
<P>
   But should closure be accepted? ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not never. If Jerry will make a public admission
that he was wrong to allow a battle of egos to break up the
greatest NFL dynasty of all time, then, OK. Closure could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Jones answered Wednesday, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't think so, but it was a good try.
</P>
<P>
   Then, however, Jones continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being wrong and being responsible, those are different
words,'' he added. ``I do really believe my No. 1 role with the
Cowboys is to create incentives by putting a foundation in place
where players and coaches really want to be here, and be
invigorated and energized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that, for whatever the reasons, I didn't do that in
this case, then I will shoulder the responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But regrets? Jerry says there are none. So does Jimmy. The large
egos won't permit regrets. Those same egos caused the breakup. So
much success so soon was responsible for huge head-swelling that
led to chest pounding that led to the bye-byes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't disagree more,'' Jones said. ``First of all, none
of what was accomplished was totally about just us. That's unfair
to a lot of people around here who played a role in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you break it down to us, Jimmy came to the Cowboys with
a history of success. I came to the Cowboys with a history of
success. Neither of us got there by making decisions based on ego
or instant gratification. Certainly the egos were there, but so
were all the other factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the NFL bottom in 1989, within five years the
Cowboys of Jerry and Jimmy had run off consecutive Super Bowl
victories. The dynasty was built in a hurry. The dynasty appeared
to have the life-span of the Roman Empire. A thousand years, if not
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professionally, there has never been anything for me so
satisfying,'' Jones said, ``or never anything more intense. And
when I say intense, this is coming from a guy who prior to the
Cowboys had once owed every bank in the country. And a guy who when
in his 20s couldn't hold a glass in his hand because his hand shook
so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would say to me, ``you're shaking like someone 70 years
old.'' My answer was they'd be shaking too if they owed as much
money as I did. But from that, to come to Dallas, and face the
level of heat both Jimmy and I received, and then to have the
success, Jimmy is always going to be someone special to me. Just
for what we went through together, how could he not be.''
</P>
<P>
   To Jerry, the breakup with Jimmy was all about ``the time had
come for both of us.'' And Jerry, of course, also doesn't buy into
the common theory that by parting with Jimmy, it cost at least one
more Super Bowl and maybe two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good argument,'' he admitted, ``but would having Jimmy
have made any difference in the championship game in San Francisco
(in 1994) when we spotted them 21 quick points? Or if Jimmy had
been here, would we have had homefield for that game? It's all
speculation. Then the next year, we won the Super Bowl again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The run we went on was three Super Bowls in four seasons.
Could it have been any better than that? I just don't necessarily
think so. I certainly don't look back and wonder about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Jerry added something strange. ``Remember this,'' he
said. ``Sometimes it's very positive for both coaches and
columnists to move on to another opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what he meant by that?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. One other thing _ the Dallas Cowboys and Miami
Dolphins are scheduled to play a football game Thursday afternoon
at Texas Stadium. But due to other circumstances involved in this
encounter, honk if you actually care about the game itself. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
