<HEADLINE>
HOODING THE EXECUTIONER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, November 28, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Political leaders in Florida are pondering whether to scrap
their rickety, 1923-era vintage electric chair for a neater, more
orderly way of putting criminals to death. But sanitizing the death
penalty with lethal injections does not make it any less barbaric.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's electric chair has been an embarrassment to both
opponents and supporters of capital punishment. Three times in
recent years it has malfunctioned; hoods covering the faces of the
condemned have burst into flames, and this summer a man contorted
horribly, hemorrhaging blood from his nostrils. After the power was
turned off, witnesses say, he was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The latest outrage provoked the US Supreme Court to put a stay
on executions in Florida while it considers whether the electric
chair constitutes cruel and unusual punishment. The court's
decision could spell the end of electrocutions in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Florida's Governor Jeb Bush, an enthusiastic
supporter of capital punishment, has said he may call a special
session of the state Legislature to consider replacing the chair
with lethal injection, the preferred method of execution in 34
states. Lethal injection imparts a certain gloss of legitimacy to a
fundamentally inhumane act. It has been condemned as unethical by
the American Medical Association and by physicians' groups around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wish to tidy up the death penalty don't want to
confront the horrible reality of what they are sanctioning, which
is the deliberate execution of men, women, and, increasingly,
children by the state. The method used _ firing squad, hanging, gas
chamber, electric current, or intravenous injection _ is just a
detail.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Florida and elsewhere want to keep the electric chair
precisely because of its brutality, saying convicted killers should
be made to suffer. That view lifts the pious veil from ``humane
executions'' to describe what capital punishment is really about:
not deterrence, not restitution, not justice, but revenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
