<HEADLINE>
SLOWDOWN IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, November 29, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a sad comment on the nature of international trade
negotiations these days that the most favorable outcome of the
World Trade Organization conference beginning Tuesday in Seattle
could be simply the status quo. While the conference should endorse
another round of talks designed to ease barriers to trade in a
number of fields, the political realities in many countries make it
increasingly difficult for them to embrace still freer
international commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Protectionist impulses are difficult to stifle and occur in
virtually all countries. Europeans, with a long history of
encouraging (and benefiting from) international trade, dampen their
ardor when their farmers are involved _ to the disadvantage of
their consumers. The United States, the world's largest single
importer and exporter, clings to elaborate quota systems to shield
steel, textile, and clothing manufacturers. Japan, a demon exporter
itself, constantly scatters administrative barriers in front of
potential imports.
</P>
<P>
   Given the will, delegates could endorse detailed negotiations on
agriculture, intellectual property, manufactured goods, dumping
practices, apparel, and a host of topics on the meeting's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On a broader scale, they could back the next round of full-scale
trade negotiations projected at the end of the last round in 1993.
Those Uruguay Round talks took seven years to complete _ an index
of their complexity and of the difficulty in satisfying competing
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The international trading system, however, is the target of
almost constant shortsighted sniping from all directions. Some of
the criticisms touch on valid issues _ the environment, widely
varying wage and labor practices, health questions _ but many of
them cloak hostility to the increasingly international nature of
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the system's flaws, growing international trade holds
by far the best hope for expanding the economic well-being of
people everywhere, especially in the poorer nations still left far
behind. The Seattle delegates owe them all the resolve to keep
moving ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
