<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' STORR A QUICK HEALER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The day after an injury can be the most telling for a
player. Kings goaltender Jamie Storr, who nearly tore his right
groin in Tuesday's 5-2 victory, said Wednesday his condition had
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Storr, injured in the first period, still did not dress for the
Kings game against Dallas. But after icing and stretching the groin
throughout the day, Storr's groin improved and so did his mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt a lot better,'' said Storr, who was named NHL Player
of the Week earlier this month after taking over for injured
Stephane Fiset. ``I still can't play, but a lot of the pain is
gone. I didn't' expect it to feel this good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are off for Thanksgiving today, but Storr will
continue to rehabilitate the injury at an optional therapy session
at the Forum. Fiset still is two weeks away with a deep bone bruise
on his right hand and Marcel Cousineau started in goal in
Wednesday's 3-2 overtime loss to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Mike O'Neill, who arrived from the minor-league Long Beach Ice
Dogs on Wednesday afternoon, served as the Kings backup goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously are very pleased that Jamie is getting better and
that is why we did not put him on injured reserve,'' Kings coach
Andy Murray said. ``We didn't want to put him out with the chance
he could be back for Saturday's game (vs. San Jose).''
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti sent down? Without Storr, Finnish defenseman Jere
Karalahti, who finally arrived last week after a lengthy battle
with immigration, was sent down to make room for O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   But that was only part of the story. Karalahti, whose arrival
was delayed because of legal wrangling over his history of drug
abuse, was with the Kings but couldn't fly back to join Long Beach
because he did not have the required picture I.D. for commercial
air travel.
</P>
<P>
   John Wolf, assistant to Kings general manager Dave Taylor, had
Karalahti's birth certificate back in Los Angeles, but obviously it
did not have a picture.
</P>
<P>
   So although he was technically a member of the Ice Dogs,
Karalahti remained with the Kings until they chartered home after
Wednesday's game. Players are not required to have picture
identification for charter flights.
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti was expected to join one of the Kings' minor-league
clubs after he arrived, but Murray decided to keep him with the
club to evaluate his conditioning. Karalahti has practiced
regularly with the club since his arrival Nov.15 but has not
played.
</P>
<P>
   Karalahti has regularly been tested for substance abuse since
his arrest two years ago for possession of heroin. After undergoing
a nine-month rehabilitation, he developed into the finest
defenseman in Europe when the Kings signed him last summer.
</P>
<P>
   No.2 goalie: O'Neill, who has 21 games of NHL experience,
arrived Wednesday afternoon but did not work out because the Kings
canceled their morning practice. O'Neill started in goal Sunday for
Long Beach in Houston. He was scheduled to accompany the Ice Dogs
to Salt Lake City for a game Wednesday when he got the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard from them about 10 o'clock last night and got here at
2:30 this afternoon,'' O'Neill said. ``It was the busiest day of
the year at the airports and it sure was crowded. But this is your
chance and you want to make the most of it. You don't think about
the inconveniences. You only think about playing your best if you
get the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille getting closer: Luc Robitaille tested his broken left
foot for the third consecutive day, skating for more than 30
minutes at the club's training facility in West Hills. Robitaille,
who might be back by the Dec. 3 game in Anaheim, was put through
simulated game conditions and reported no discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille and Murray will work out today at the Forum. If
Robitaille is ready to go for Saturday's game against San Jose,
Murray wants to hold him out because the team has the next five
days off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
