<HEADLINE>
A FINE LINE ON TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, November 29, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington's role as arbiter in the recurrent quarrel between
the governments in Beijing and Taipei resembles that of a policeman
called in to prevent a domestic spat from turning violent.
</P>
<P>
   The intervening constable must see to it that Beijing does not
carry out its threats and ceases trying to intimidate Taiwan. But
Washington's interest in preserving a neighborhood's tranquility
also requires it to prevent Taiwan from provoking the Beijing bully
into an irrational act.
</P>
<P>
   In the current issue of Foreign Affairs, Taiwan's President Lee
Teng-hui staked out that democracy's position on entering into a
political dialogue with mainland authorities. It is a position the
Communists in Beijing abhor, but it has certain undeniable virtues,
among which is a lucid recognition of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fiction to claim that the Chinese nation is not divided
_ and pernicious fiction to assert that the People's Republic of
China has any right or imperative to claim sovereignty over
Taiwan,'' Lee wrote. His purpose is to avoid a negotiation whose
outcome is predetermined by the ground rules for dialogue. If the
negotiations are conducted between one sovereign state and a
``renegade province'' belonging to that state, then the destination
of the dialogue is a foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   From Beijing's perspective, however, Lee's demand that the
dialogue be conducted on the basis of ``special state-to-state
relations'' also prejudges the outcome. The Communists will not
participate in a dialogue that could lead to recognition of Taiwan
as an independent state.
</P>
<P>
   Since the reality is that Taiwan and the mainland are
intertwined economically and that both stand to suffer considerably
from any violent conflict, the United States should be able to
prevail on them to put aside semantic arguments about the status of
the parties to a dialogue. Let them negotiate as equals but not as
two states. This is one world crisis that is best handled by
solving small problems and procrastinating about the big ones _
until there is a democratic state on the mainland that is worthy of
absorbing Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
