r s BC-FBC-BIG12FOOTBALLREPO     11-25 1683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FEARSOME RIVALS' KNOW WHAT'S IMPORTANT
</HEADLINE>
 12 FOOTBALL REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ryan Nunez heard the horrible news and raced for the telephone.
It was 6 a.m., but the Texas wide receiver needed to set his mind
at ease.
</P>
<P>
   He called the College Station apartment of Will Blackbird, a
childhood chum and Texas A&AMP;M student. Multiple rings, no answer.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez redialed. Same result. He began to panic.
</P>
<P>
   Logically, Nunez realized the odds were against his buddy being
one of the students injured or killed during the collapse of the
A&AMP;M bonfire tower. But he knew it was possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me, having a friend over there and knowing it
could have been him (among the casualties),'' Nunez said. ``It was
a very disturbing feeling. I couldn't imagine how parents might
have felt in the same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, this story has a happy ending. The two friends
eventually made contact. Blackbird was safe. He plans to be in Kyle
Field on Friday when Nunez and the seventh-ranked Longhorns (9-2,
6-1) meet No. 24 A&AMP;M (7-3, 4-3). A thankful reunion beckons, one
day after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Words cannot adequately sum up the profound sadness of the
tragedy that cost 12 A&AMP;M students their lives when the 40-foot
bonfire tower toppled Nov. 18. But they can be used to call
attention to the underlying message in the Nunez-Blackbird
situation: Deep down, Longhorns care about Aggies. And vice versa.
Especially in trying times.
</P>
<P>
   That's been proven in the past week through blood drives, unity
rallies, prayer vigils and supportive calls placed between friends
and loved ones from both sides of this rivalry. In situations such
as this, labels fade. And we are reminded, once again, that when
you take away the maroon or orange jerseys, you are left with
people who share many of the same hopes, fears, dreams and values.
</P>
<P>
   You're left with a lot of Texans whose hearts are in direct
proportion to the size of their home state. You're left with
citizens who are quick to help in a crisis, regardless of rooting
interest.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe that, listen to Texas A&AMP;M offensive guard
Semisi Heimuli. A Trinity High School graduate, Heimuli lived in
suburban San Francisco until moving to Euless as a teen-ager in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   He experienced the 1989 earthquake that rocked San Francisco and
interrupted the World Series between the San Francisco Giants and
Oakland Athletics. And he saw the tragedy that unfolded last week
at the Aggie Bonfire. What he'll never forget is the differing
reactions to both events: chaos at one, caring at the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the earthquake, people started looting. All they
worried about was getting something for themselves. No one pitched
in to help,'' Heimuli said. ``Since I've lived in Texas, I've
noticed this state is different. In hard times, people help each
other out. It's a Texas thing.''
</P>
<P>
   No group of Texans, said Heimuli, have been more persistent in
offering comfort and condololences to the Aggies than the
Longhorns. A&AMP;M linebacker Brian Gamble echoed that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot for someone to be able to console the people
you're supposed to hate. But that's what we've been seeing for the
past week, so you can forget about hate,'' Gamble said, referring
to Texas students. ``They came to our memorial services. They held
one of their own. They've really supported us, and I thought it was
great. And we'd have done the same for them if the tables were
turned.''
</P>
<P>
   In a heartbeat, added A&AMP;M cornerback Jason Webster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never hated Texas,'' Webster said. ``It's an intense
rivalry, sure. But I'm not surprised they've sent their support.
I'm thankful.''
</P>
<P>
   This rivalry works because of mutual respect, not hatred. At
least, that's how players and coaches see it. It's how the
countless families with loyalties to both sides see it. Hopefully,
A&AMP;M and Texas players said, that's how the world will see it once
they finish Friday's contest.
</P>
<P>
   Like his A&AMP;M peers, Texas quarterback Major Applewhite said he
would dedicate Friday's game to the A&AMP;M students who perished at
the bonfire site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't we play for the same things they play for? It's a
tragedy we all share,'' Applewhite said. ``There are lives
involved. It only seems right to play in a spirit to honor the
traditions of this rivalry on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, look for Applewhite and Webster _ leaders in
their school's respective Fellowship of Christian Athletes chapters
_ to gather players from both teams in a postgame prayer as a show
of unity before leaving the field. Look for former high school
teammates to embrace and cry, one wearing maroon, the other orange.
Look for evidence, in the words of A&AMP;M student body president Will
Hurd that ``We have seen the most fearsome of rivals become the
best of friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for the youth of America, once again, to remind the rest of
us about putting life and football in their proper perspectives.
With football finishing a distant second. FOR TEXAS COACH, ADVICE
FROM TRAGEDY HITS HOME
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Mack Brown found himself struggling with what to
tell his team in the wake of the bonfire tragedy. That changed
after a phone call with former A&AMP;M athletic director John David
Crow, whose son died in a car wreck three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``John David said to tell the kids that every time you see your
family members or your friends, be sure you hug them and tell them
that you love them. Never leave one of them upset because you may
not see them again,'' Brown said. ``Death is final. You have a
chance to grow as a person if you can take this crisis and put your
own priorities in order.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Brown said, he parroted Crow's sentiments to his
players. And he took them to heart. He recalled that, in his final
conversation with his late father, the elder Brown asked Mack to
fax him a document to settle a disagreement he was having with a
friend. His father had an agitated tone to his voice, and the
conversation ended abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since, I've always wished I could've had one more
conversation with my dad, one last chance to say, `I love you,'''
Brown said. ``When John David mentioned the part about never
hanging up mad with a loved one, that really came back to me.
That's good advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it has been passed along to more than just Brown's football
players.
QUICK HITS RED RAIDERS IN LIMBO
</P>
<P>
   Because of an unclear future, Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes did
not have his team practice this week and will mandate only
conditioning workouts when players reconvene Monday. The Red
Raiders (6-5) are bowl-eligible. But so are six other Big 12
schools, and the league is assured of only six postseason berths.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Tech finds itself in college football's equivalent
of no-man's land. Players have no remaining games on the schedule
but will not know until Dec. 5 if they are done for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely, somebody will take us to a bowl game, won't they?''
said Dykes, who announced his retirement after a 38-28 victory
Saturday over Oklahoma. ``I know there are a lot of teams going,
but I feel like we'll be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tech lands a bowl bid, Dykes and his current staffers will
handle the game, Tech athletic director Gerald Myers said.
BEAR NECESSITIES
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a repeat of this year's 1-10 season, the next edition
of the Baylor Bears will need a thicker skin. Coach Kevin Steele
said he may have erred on the side of positive feedback in his
initial season, rather than challenging the team as much as it
needed.
</P>
<P>
   That will change in 2000, Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our greatest struggle was not talent or ability. It was the
psyche of the football team,'' said Steele, who vows to be more
direct about shortcomings in future discussions with players.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't he do that in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have lost some players because of the mental psyche of
the team,'' Steele said. ``I still believe this year's team
couldn't have handled it. Next year's team is going to have to be
able to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   PEERS DON'T ENVY SLOCUM
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 coaches expressed sympathy for everyone at Texas A&AMP;M in
the wake of last week's tragedy at the bonfire site. None said he
would relish the task of preparing a team to play against that
backdrop, as coach R.C. Slocum must do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a tough week. Our hearts go out to the whole A&AMP;M
family,'' Kansas coach Terry Allen said. ``Having dealt with deaths
of family members and other players, I've found that (playing a
game) is three hours where we can put it in the back of our minds,
put aside the tragedy and go play. It can be therapeutic. I hope it
will be for them.''
</P>
<P>
   BURCH'S PICKS
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Jimmy Burch picks (against the line) this week's
Big 12 football games:
</P>
<P>
   Texas at Texas A&AMP;M (plus 2 1/2). Pick: Texas. An upset is
possible. But bank on Texas' consistency to outlast A&AMP;M's emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska (plus 14 1/2) at Colorado. Pick: Colorado. If the
Cornhuskers don't cure their fumblitis, this may not be their
steppingstone to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (plus 13) at Oklahoma. Pick: Oklahoma. Sooners
burst the Cowboys' bowl bubble in convincing fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's record: 2-1-1. Season record: 50-31-2.
