<HEADLINE>
KID KINGS COME UP SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Dallas Stars had the Stanley Cup in the lobby and
an unbeaten streak almost five years old. The Kings had the Long
Beach Ice Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Andy Murray didn't mind those odds, taking a team
overloaded with minor-leaguers against the Stars, who haven't lost
to the Kings in 19 games. Hard work beats style points in his mind
even if the Stars beat the Kings 3-2 in overtime Wednesday night in
front of 17,001 at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Murray started Marcel Cousineau in goal a day after Jamie Storr
went down with a groin injury and two weeks after he was called up
from the minors to replace injured Stephane Fiset. Cousineau had a
tie game until Richard Matvichuk poked in his own rebound with 2:55
gone in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Murray got goals from Jason Blake, who has taken the Blue Train
to and from Long Beach several times this season, and Len Barrie,
who played with the Ice Dogs until Jozef Stumpel was lost to
abdominal surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you want to win, especially with the effort we gave
the night after the win in Colorado,'' Murray said. ``But we got a
point out of this (for the tie in regulation) and three points for
the trip. It was good to see those guys really step up. I think
they know how I felt by the numbers of minutes they got.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray didn't see that jump in the Kings power play, which was 0
for 4 and is scoreless in its last 28 opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But he saw plenty in Blake, who played a season-high 16 minutes.
He had four shots on Stars' goalie Ed Belfour, who stopped 19 shots
and held the Kings (13-7-4) without a scoring chance in overtime.
Blake also got playing time with the first unit, a group he hoped
to join when Luc Robitaille went down two weeks ago with a broken
left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Blake was overwhelmed by Philadelphia in the one game he played
on that line, and shuttled in and out of Long Beach to stay in
shape. It obviously paid off. Blake now has two goals in the last
two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a game where we needed the fresh legs,'' captain Rob
Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   And not just because they played in Colorado the night before.
The Kings hadn't defeated the Stars since April 6, 1995. They were
0-6 last year, including five losses by one goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, now 9-10-3 but still last in the Pacific Division,
also are banged up. They have been doing more whining than winning
in defense of their championship, but Wednesday they looked like
they might have an easy night.
</P>
<P>
   The weary Kings came out flat and Dallas left winger Mike Keane
scored a short-handed goal just 1:08 into the game. After Stars'
defenseman Darryl Sydor was whistled off for interference, Keane
picked up the puck along the right board and fired a cross-ice pass
to captain Derian Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Cousineau stopped Hatcher's wrist shot, but Keane got the
rebound and gave the Stars a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie tied the game midway through the first period by
rebounding a Ziggy Palffy shot past Belfour. It was Barrie's only
shot of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings looked like they might get out of the period with just
one goal, but Jamie Langenbrunner gave the Stars a 2-1 lead with
just 3:21 to play on a power-play goal. Blake came back to tie the
game with 12:29 left in the second and it lasted until overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nervous,'' said Cousineau, who probably will be back
in goal Saturday against San Jose. ``This is a chance for me. It's
a chance for a lot of guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
