<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WARRIORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS ARE FEELING BETTER AFTER DOSE OF WARRIORS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The New Jersey Nets ran into the perfect
pick-me-up Wednesday night at the Arena in Oakland. Instead of
meeting a group of high-flying, fancy-passing, sweet-shooting
gamers, they faced the Golden State Warriors, a West Coast crew
that is as injured as it is hapless. It was just what a loser of
seven straight games needed.
</P>
<P>
   Behind one of their most balanced performances of the season,
the Nets beat the Warriors, 92-84, to improve to 2-10 and replace
their sullen expressions with smiles, if only for a night.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Van Horn, who started at small forward, and Johnny Newman,
who came off the bench, led the Nets with 22 points apiece, while
Stephon Marbury followed with 21. Coincidentally, the Nets'
victories have come in the only two games in which Marbury has not
led them in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Farmer paced Golden State with 19 points, and Antawn
Jamison had 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets did not outdistance the Warriors (2-8) by much. Leading
by 64-63 after three quarters, they surged ahead, 78-68, midway
through the period. But Golden State closed within 80-75 and the
crowd of 10,017 began smelling a rare victory. Marbury gave the
Nets some room by sinking a 3-pointer with former Knick John Starks
hanging on him with 4 minutes 2 seconds to play. Marbury hit the
ensuing free throw to put the Nets up, 84-75.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Warriors rallied, moving within 88-84 with less than
a minute to play, but Elliot Perry (nine points) hit an 18-footer
in transition to push the lead back to six points with 36 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets began with their fifth starting lineup of this young
season. Jim McIlvaine (corneal abrasion, right eye) and Sherman
Douglas (sprained right ankle), both casualties of Tuesday's loss
to Sacramento, sat out, and Kendall Gill went on the injured list
before the game with a bruised bone in his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   All of that cleared the way for 37-year-old Michael Cage, who
was activated from the injured list Wednesday , to start at center.
Along with Marbury, Van Horn and Cage, Lucious Harris and Jamie
Feick rounded out the first five.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State was playing without its second-leading scorer,
Chris Mills (left Achilles' tendinitis), Erick Dampier (left knee)
and Jason Caffey (right Achilles' tendinitis).
</P>
<P>
   What would usually be categorized as a meaningless game between
noncontenders became a heated confrontation with plenty on the
line. Because of each club's precarious start to the season, Gary
Fitzsimmons, the Warriors' assistant general manager, was saying
beforehand: ``It's Game 7! It's Game 7!''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly was a must-win situation for both teams. After
playing the Nets, 10 of the Warriors' next 11 games are against
sure-fire playoff teams, while the Nets visit the Los Angeles
Lakers on Friday and Phoenix on Saturday. Then, after playing
Washington on Tuesday, the Nets will play host to San Antonio, the
Knicks Sacramento and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident early on that the Nets were not on the floor with
a superior team. Whereas the Nets had been outclassed on many
occasions, the Warriors appeared to be perhaps a notch below them.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' biggest advantage was on the backboards, where they
outrebounded the Warriors, 54-43. It was clear how sad Golden
State's rebounding corps was when Cage grabbed four in the first
two minutes and finished with 10 in 14 minutes. Van Horn led the
Nets with 11 rebounds. Johnny Newman, who pulled down three
straight offensive rebounds on one sequence, had 10.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their dominance on the glass, the Nets trailed, 22-21,
after one quarter because of a familiar problem: poor transition
defense. On the rare occasion it did secure a rebound, Golden State
ran with ease, scoring 16 first-half points in transition.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 26-21, the Nets charged, putting together a
13-0 run to take brief command. Harris got hot, scoring eight of
his 10 first-half points, and hit a 21-footer to give the Nets
their biggest lead, 48-36, three minutes before intermission.
</P>
<P>
   But a couple of late turnovers, including two by Marbury,
allowed the Warriors to remain in contention and pull within 51-45
at the break. Van Horn had 14 points and Marbury 11 before the
break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
