<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JUDGE KAYE'S COURT REFORMS  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Nov. 25:
</P>
<P>
   In her six years as New York's chief judge, Judith Kaye has been
proved a dedicated and effective reformer of the state's sprawling
court system. Each of her hard-won changes has had a positive
impact _ whether it be the repeal of automatic exemptions from jury
service that let many citizens escape their civic duty, various
physical improvements in court facilities, or innovations like the
creation of specialized courts to better handle domestic violence
and nonviolent drug cases. All this has justly earned Judge Kaye
national recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month she was honored at an event in Washington
sponsored by the National Center for State Courts and attended by
several Supreme Court justices and other legal luminaries. ``There
are many who are working hard to better process the many cases that
come before the state courts,'' the president of the state court
group, Roger Warren, observed in his remarks, ``but there are few
working any harder or more successfully to better serve the people
who use the state courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The event was also a reminder of how much more Judge Kaye could
accomplish if she had better cooperation from the state
Legislature. Lawmakers continue their dawdling over the sensible
court reorganization plan she submitted almost three years ago, as
well as her proposal to finally end the mandatory sequestration of
deliberating juries in all but death-penalty cases _ a costly
boondoggle that results in needless inconvenience to jurors. Judge
Kaye has made it her priority to improve the administration of
justice in New York. But she cannot do it alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 0134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
