<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DRUNK-DRIVING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A REPORT CARD ON DRUNKEN DRIVING  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Mass., Conn., N.J.)  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Nov. 25:
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving weekend is a dangerous time to be on the road.
Experts estimate that roughly half of all traffic fatalities in the
next few days _ about 250 deaths and 13,000 injuries _ will be
attributable to drunken drivers. That is a much higher death rate
from drunken driving than for other weekends of the year. Still,
the overall annual numbers for alcohol-related deaths have declined
in recent years because of grass-roots education efforts by groups
like Mothers Against Drunk Driving and tougher laws against drunken
driving in most parts of the nation. In 1998, alcohol-related
driving deaths reached a record low of 15,935, down from about
28,000 in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Any rejoicing should be tempered, however, by the fact that the
downward trend in fatalities appears to be slowing, and there is
less political will to push forward with laws that could help save
more lives.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers Against Drunk Driving issued a national survey this week
rating all the states on their efforts at combating drunken
driving. California was rated best in the nation for reducing the
percentage of alcohol-related traffic deaths between 1995 and 1998
and for passing stricter laws, including one lowering the blood
alcohol limit to .08 percent from .10. Only 17 states and the
District of Columbia have adopted that lower level.
</P>
<P>
   New York state, with 365 alcohol-related deaths last year,
earned only a B- for its less aggressive law enforcement and
failure to adopt a .08 standard. Connecticut, New Jersey and
Massachusetts were rated even less favorably. Gov. George Pataki
has pushed to lower the limit in New York to .08, but has been
blocked in the state Legislature by the restaurant and liquor
industries. Likewise, the Clinton administration supported a
national standard of .08, which was approved in the Senate but was
not acted on by the House.
</P>
<P>
   There is debate about how much difference a lower blood alcohol
limit makes in reducing vehicle crashes. But drivers are
substantially impaired at .08, making that level a reasonable limit
to set. The lower level can be made even more effective with
increased enforcement, more education and stronger laws that revoke
licenses and increase penalties for repeat offenders. The battle
against drunken driving has not yet been won, and recent gains in
reducing fatalities are no reason to become complacent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
