<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RACE AND GENDER IN THE MILITARY  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Nov. 25:
</P>
<P>
   Harry Truman's 1948 executive order integrating the armed forces
created a black management class and got blacks and whites to live
and work together on relatively peaceful terms long before the
society as a whole was ready to tackle this issue. The military is
still well ahead of the private sector when it comes to
incorporating women and minorities into management positions. But a
pair of surveys released by the Pentagon this week revealed that,
though progress continues, racial friction is still a pressing
problem and prejudices based on race and gender remain a serious
obstacle to full integration of the officer corps.
</P>
<P>
   The data provided some reasons for optimism. For example, a
report on promotion rates showed that minority officers, who
constituted just 7 percent of the total officer corps in 1977, made
up 15.3 percent two decades later. Women have shown comparable
progress, going from under 6 percent of the officer corps 20 years
ago to more than 14 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   But women and minorities tend to be concentrated in
administrative and supply areas and underrepresented in tactical
operations, the area that yields two-thirds of the general and flag
officers in the services. The report takes special notice of
aviation _ ``a greatly valued path for officers'' _ noting that few
minorities are selected for flight school and that their attrition
rates are higher than those for whites. Part of the problem, the
report says, is that blacks and women tend to receive initial
assignments that give their careers ``a slow start'' and have
limited access to peer and mentor networks.
</P>
<P>
   The most distressing news comes from a survey of more than
40,000 service members showing that large numbers have experienced
racially offensive encounters, often with superiors. About a third
of the whites who responded and nearly half the blacks and Latinos
said the racial incidents had caused them to lose trust in their
fellow soldiers, undermining efforts to work effectively together.
About half the respondents said that nothing was done when the most
bothersome episodes were reported to superiors. Despite these
difficulties, however, 46 percent of all respondents said that race
relations were better in the military than in the nation as a
whole, versus 30 percent who said that the national picture was
more favorable.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon, which has taken pride in its progress on
integrating minorities and women into the services, has clearly
been embarrassed by this last group of findings. But now that the
obstacles to fuller integration and racial harmony have been
revealed, commanders can get busy finding ways to remove them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
