<P>
   JAPAN-SUBWAY (Tokyo) _ In its ceaseless effort to prod its
maddeningly lifeless economy into action, Japan has spent more than
$1 trillion, much of it on bridges, tunnels, airports, concert
halls and pavement aimed at propping up the economy and satisfying
political promises. Then there's the new Tokyo subway line. The
problem: It does not run in a complete circle. ``It's like a
Rolls-Royce that you can't shift into reverse,'' said Shintaro
Ishihara, Tokyo's outspoken governor. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 16 is being sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   OPERATION-SMILE-II (Beijing) _ Early last August, an
impoverished farmer brought his young son to the Plastic Surgery
Hospital in Beijing to take advantage of a once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity: For one week, plastic surgeons from the U.S. charity
Operation Smile were operating for free on poor Chinese children
with cleft lips and palates, the congenital condition that
afflicted his boy. But that elation quickly turned to anguish when
his son returned from surgery and he discovered that the wrong
operation had been performed. A Special Report, the second of two
parts, by Elisabeth Rosenthal and Reed Abelson.
</P>
