r a BC-CHINA-WTO-SFCHRON &LR;      11-25 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-WTO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO DEAL WITH CHINA MAY CUT INTO PIRACY, SMUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  From Silicon Valley to Hollywood, California businesses have
much to gain from China's planned entry into the World Trade
Organization.
<P>
   They certainly have little left to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The state's high-tech and entertainment industries already are
deprived of many millions of dollars in China each year because of
piracy, smuggling and red tape. It's now hoped that the trade deal
signed last week by Washington and Beijing will create a more level
playing field.
</P>
<P>
   However, no one expects changes to come overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a huge, huge challenge,'' said Anne Craib,
director of international trade for the Semiconductor Industry
Association. ``Anyone who thinks everything has been solved has
never been to China.''
</P>
<P>
   By that, she means Chinese authorities have a track record of
promising the moon and delivering little more than green cheese.
Case in point: The Clinton administration reached an agreement with
Beijing in 1995 for protection of intellectual property rights. But
aside from a handful of highly publicized closures of pirate CD
factories, little came of the pact. Most pirates simply changed
locations and stepped up production.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America estimates that at
least 90 percent of the CDs sold in mainland China are pirated
versions, costing U.S. music companies approximately $80 million in
annual losses.
</P>
<P>
   The rip-off of the U.S. film industry is even greater. The
Motion Picture Association estimates that pirated versions of
American films cost Hollywood about $120 million a year in lost
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Mulan,' the Disney picture, bombed at the box office in
China because the tapes were available on the street before the
film hit theaters,'' observed Jack Valenti, the association's
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The software industry, meanwhile, says no fewer than 95 percent
of applications on Chinese computers are pirated _ a figure
surpassed only by Vietnam's 98 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Piracy is a real steep mountain to climb,'' said Mario Correa,
trade policy manager for the Business Software Alliance, which
includes Bay Area firms such as Autodesk and Adobe Systems. ``But
you have to start somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   China's new pact with the United States is seen as just such a
start.
</P>
<P>
   The accord will cut tariffs on industrial and agricultural
goods, and allow easier market access for U.S. financial
institutions, insurers and telecommunications firms.
</P>
<P>
   And it brings China a big step closer to its long-held goal of
joining the WTO, which sets the rules for global commerce and
mediates disputes among its 135 member countries.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing now needs to cut similar deals with the European Union,
Canada and other nations. At the same time, the U.S. Congress must
grant China permanent ``normal trade relations'' status, which
won't come easily, given next year's election and the media's focus
on Chinese political repression.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the AFL-CIO and other labor groups have sworn to fight
China's entry into the WTO, and the textile industry has said it
will lobby hard on Capitol Hill to protect safeguards for its
products.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the tech business will push for Congress to give
its blessing to the U.S.-China pact and to China's WTO accession.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be one of the biggest lobbying efforts in recent
history,'' said Dave McCurdy, president of the Electronic
Industries Alliance, a confederation of tech and telecom groups.
``We're organizing like never before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The public and members of Congress will have to be educated on
this,'' said Jennifer Guhl, director of international trade policy
for the American Electronics Association, which represents about
3,000 high-tech corporations.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand why the tech industry is pushing so
hard.
</P>
<P>
   China's tech market is only about one-tenth the size of
America's. But sales of personal computers on the mainland are
expected to double over the next five years, and are projected to
equal American PC sales by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   By the same year, China is likely to have the world's
second-largest semiconductor market, after the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's accord covered just about everything on the tech
industry's wish list. For example, U.S. companies in China now will
be able to import and distribute their own goods, rather than being
forced to use state-run firms as intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
   An important condition laid down by Washington was for China to
become a signatory of the Information Technology Agreement, a
separate treaty that calls for most tariffs on tech products to be
eliminated by 2000. The agreement affects $500 billion in annual
global technology trade, including as much as $100 billion in U.S.
exports.
</P>
<P>
   For companies such as Santa Clara chipmaker Intel Corp. and San
Jose's Cisco Systems, such changes will vastly improve efficiency
and profitability in their dealings with mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   But China retreated from an earlier pledge to allow U.S.
companies to hold 51 percent stakes in mainland telecommunications
ventures. Instead, Beijing drew the line at 50 percent ownership,
thus barring foreign firms from holding a majority position.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes perhaps the hardest part: getting China to comply with
the terms of the deal. Many in the business community hope that the
carrot of WTO membership will compel the Chinese to abide by
international conventions regarding patents and copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will make a huge difference when multilateral pressure is
brought to bear on China,'' said the American Electronics
Association's Guhl. ``It will hold China to its commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., a persistent critic of the
Beijing regime, is highly dubious about Chinese compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you give China permanent normal trade relations status,
there's no turning back,'' she said. ``We're relinquishing our
leverage. Once they're in (the WTO), and if they don't comply, we
can file a complaint. ... And then what? Nothing. And then
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Craib and other industry leaders agree that WTO membership would
not be a quick fix for the various obstacles faced by foreign
companies in China. For example, Craib estimated that 80 percent of
microchips in the country are smuggled in illegally by parties
seeking to avoid taxes and tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how systemic such problems have become, it has been
widely reported that the powerful Chinese military is one of the
leading purveyors of smuggled goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``WTO is not a magic wand that's going to eliminate these
problems overnight,'' Craib said. ``But it would be worse to just
let things go and not do anything at all.''
</P>
<P>
   While the concessions China has made will help Congress feel
more comfortable conferring normal trade relations status, it won't
be easy for the trade deal's backers to overcome opponents'
objections to China's human- and labor-rights policies and the
well-entrenched interests of the textile industry.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, a fierce critic of the
U.S.-China pact, vowed last week to muster thousands of union
members and environmentalists for a huge march in Seattle on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will call upon the (WTO delegates) to address workers'
rights and human rights as well as environmental and consumer
protections in the rules that govern the global economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi had harsh words for Clinton, saying: ``The president
wants to redeem his failed China policy, which hasn't accomplished
anything. It's this big cosmetic thing, but he won't have to deal
with the ramifications because he'll be out of office by then.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``If there's ever an argument for campaign finance
reform, if there's ever a gravy train, it's the corporate lobby for
China.''
</P>
<P>
   The Electronic Industries Alliance's McCurdy acknowledged that
struggle lies ahead: ``Just because we have an agreement doesn't
mean it's all done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
