<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      11-25 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FIRDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ASSISI-BASILICA (Assisi, Italy) _ Three years after a
devastating earthquake, Assisi's famous basilica is to reopen on
Sunday. But new housing for the thousands left homeless has yet to
materialize. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SHIP (Beijing) _ Thousands of rescue workers scoured
wind-whipped seas and shores Thursday for survivors from a ferry
that caught fire and foundered off eastern China, killing more than
150 people and leaving more than 100 others missing. (Summary from
wires.) By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-KURDS (Istanbul) _ Turkey's appeals court has upheld the
death sentence given Abdullah Ocalan, the Kurdish rebel leader
convicted of treason. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ Russian President Yeltsin falls ill,
prompting the Belarus president, Alexander Lukashenko, to cancel
his trip to Moscow to sign a union treaty. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-TUDJMAN (Zagreb) _ Political and medical developments
surrounding President Tudjman. By Stephen Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SHOE-FASHION (Tokyo) _ The height of fashion _ shoes with
eight-inch soles or six-inch heels _ is taking a toll on young
Japanese women. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Democrats call it a do-nothing
Congress; Republicans are only slightly more enthusiastic, saying
it was all that could be expected with such narrow majorities in
the House and Senate and a Democratic president. But business
lobbies like the Chamber of Commerce think they had a great year in
Congress. Not only did they get most of what they wanted, but they
were able to block the things they did not want. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-HOMELESS (Philadelphia) _ Inside the Back Home Cafe,
where the homeless people, mainly the mentally ill, serve meals. By
Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-SUIT (Austin, Texas) _ A federal judge has ordered the FBI
to turn over 12 bullet shell casings to the special counsel
re-investigating the Branch Davidian siege.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-MISSING-CUBANS (Key Biscayne, Fla.) _ Rescuers searched the
Atlantic Ocean on Thursday for a dozen or more Cubans after a man
and a woman, badly dehydrated, came ashore on the remnants of
makeshift rafts and said 12 to 14 others were missing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MRSCLINTON (Washington) _ The parallel paths of Hillary
Clinton and Al Gore, who each have held on to their day jobs and
White House offices, but who each have moved (to Chappaqua, to
Nashville) almost full-time into their lives as candidates. A
Political Memo by Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ASTRO-MICROWAVES (Undated) _ Like the great navigators who first
sailed around the world, establishing its size and the curvature of
its surface, astronomers have made new observations that show with
startling directness the large-scale geometry of the universe and
the total amount of matter and energy that it contains. By James
Glanz. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITE-TV (Washington) _ Looking at what the new satellite
television legislation means for the industry and for consumers. By
Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ECON (Frankfurt) _ Looking at how the Mannesmann
situation has shaken Germany's belief in an economy ruled by
consensus among government, labor and management. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Shopping is something that, for better
and for worse, Americans have done a lot of in recent years. This
week's economic report showed that the economy grew a healthy 4.2
percent, year-over-year, through the third quarter. But that
headline figure severely understates just how fast our purchases
are increasing. Real sales to domestic purchasers were up 5.6
percent. The difference is largely a surge in imports, funded by
borrowing. But while change is not imminent, it is coming. ``It
is,'' says Robert Barbera, the chief economist of Hoenig &AMP; Co.,
``extremely hard to believe that we can spend at a growth rate of
5.6 percent in perpetuity.'' By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   SODAS-CITIES (Huntington Beach, Calif.) _ Nearly a dozen cities
across the nation have in the last year signed contracts with
Coca-Cola or Pepsi giving the soft-drink company exclusive rights
to sales on city property. Such sponsorship deals are increasingly
coming under attack from consumer advocates. By Verne G. Kopytoff.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-LOANS (Tokyo) _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's Tokyo office
on Thursday sold the first set of securities linked to
non-performing Japanese real-estate loans, paving the way for what
may be a flood of deals aimed at redressing a big portion of the
excessive lending that all but bankrupted the Japanese financial
system. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, U.S. markets are closed Thursday for the Thanksgiving
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Gail Collins' ``Public Interests.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be
listed by 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
