<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JOHN-ADAMS-MUSIC-3TAK     11-25 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN-ADAMS-MUSIC-3TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMING UP JOHN ADAMS AT MIDCAREER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When John Adams cruised onto listeners' radar screens in 1980,
with his ``Shaker Loops'' and ``Phrygian Gates'' (both composed in
1977), on an LP from the small, now defunct label 1750 Arch, three
things were immediately apparent.
</P>
<P>
   One was that the Minimalist school, pioneered a decade earlier
by Philip Glass, Steve Reich and Terry Riley, would have legs.
Adams, who is now 52, was a decade younger than the founders of the
style, and he came to it from an unlikely direction.
</P>
<P>
   He studied at Harvard with Leon Kirchner, whose emotional,
rigorously structured works were a world apart from Minimalist
abstractions and simplicities, and in 1971 he moved to San
Francisco, a continent away from Minimalism's home ground. Not that
others hadn't picked up on the style and its growing popularity;
but no one had crashed the Minimalist party with the energizing
freshness heard in Adams' early works.
</P>
<P>
   That originality was the second ear-catching aspect of his
music. Perhaps it should not have been surprising that a newcomer
to Minimalism could quickly develop a distinctive voice. The early
practitioners, though dealing in music that both supporters and
detractors described as stripped down, had established unmistakable
personal styles.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most newcomers seemed like apprentices either to Glass,
whose early fascination with additive process was then giving way
to an interest in drama, or to Reich, who was focused on the
intricacies of interlocking rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Adams brought something new to the Minimalism of the time:
chromaticism and gesture, both varied to create an expressive
effect. ``Phrygian Gates,'' which makes its way around the harmonic
circle of fifths, touching on every key, and ``Shaker Loops,''
which made peace with the Romanticism that Minimalism had until
then rejected, came as a jolt to listeners who thought they knew
what Minimalism was about.
</P>
<P>
   And the third thing made apparent by that first recording was
that unless those works were flukes, Adams would bear watching. Two
decades later, he has been duly watched and commented on, both
admiringly and harshly, as he has followed paths his early
listeners could not have predicted.
</P>
<P>
   A current of sometimes schoolboyish humor quickly became an
important part of his palette, and he has shown an uncanny ability
to assimilate other compositional styles and twist them into
something recognizably his own, just as he did with Minimalism.
While he is too young to be considered venerable, he has become an
established presence on the American compositional landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a busy presence at the moment. Nonesuch, the record
label with which he has developed a personal affiliation (although
others record his music) has just issued a 10-CD retrospective,
``The John Adams Earbox,'' which invites even listeners who know
his work to hear it afresh in a careerwide context. And Robert
Spano and the Brooklyn Philharmonic are presenting a concert
version of the better of his two operas, ``Nixon in China,'' on
Friday and Saturday at the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, still a Californian, will be in New York on those
evenings but otherwise engaged, conducting the New York
Philharmonic in a Copland program at Avery Fisher Hall.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting, given this confluence, to wonder whether Adams
might have been a kind of Copland for the '90s. The equation
doesn't ultimately work; the composers, the times and the
constitution of the American musical world now and in Copland's
heyday are too different. Still, there are peculiar parallels.
</P>
<P>
   Each composer worked in a formal, academically approved style
before discovering the popular language that helped him make a
splash. What Minimalism did for Adams, the Stravinsky ballets based
on Russian folk sources did for the young Copland, becoming a
template for the ``prairie'' style that made him famous. Each
composer grew stylistically restless once he had established
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Copland explored Neo-Classicism and serialism, but he remained a
neo-Romantic at heart, revisiting his folksier style, if only in
passing. The recordings in the ``Earbox'' (Nonesuch 79453-2),
selected by Adams and in many cases conducted by him, chronicle the
array of styles on which he has touched, including the almost
Ligetian density of the first movement of ``Harmonium'' (1981) and
the decidedly non-Minimalist angularity of the Violin Concerto
(1993).
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Adams seems not to have shared Copland's
fascination with Middle Americana, beyond the un-Coplandesque
``Hoedown'' in ``Gnarly Buttons'' (1996) and the quirky country
fiddling movement in ``John's Book of Alleged Dances'' (1994). Yet
the broad, open string chords of his ``Christian Zeal and
Activity'' (1973), the earliest work in the ``Earbox,'' are a
deconstructed hymn, and they bear a striking resemblance to the
devotional orchestral fabric of Copland's ``Lincoln Portrait,''
though the tape component of the Adams work, an electronically
manipulated snippet from a radio sermon, takes its lineage from
Reich's ``It's Gonna Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Adjust for the difference in eras, and the composers' populist
connection becomes even more apparent. Where Copland used hymns and
folk melodies to create his aural image of America, Adams, a child
of the 1950s and '60s, draws on pop music in all its variety. Rock
references abound, as in the brawny riffs of ``Lollapalooza''
(1995), and Adams flirts with theatrical pop in ``I Was Looking at
the Ceiling and Then I Saw the Sky'' (1995), jazz in ``Eros Piano''
(1989) and New Age in ``Hoodoo Zephyr'' (1992).
</P>
<P>
   He touches on earlier pop music in ``The Chairman Dances''
(1985), an eccentric fox trot with a hint of Gershwin. And he
alludes to world music, with a Middle Eastern accent, in ``John's
Book of Alleged Dances,'' a wide-ranging compendium for string
quartet; in Copland, the parallel would be works like ``El Salon
Mexico.'' What links Adams to Copland in the end is that both are
essentially neo-Romantics, with a taste for music that moves
people, whether popular or more formal.
</P>
<P>
   But there the comparisons must end. Since Adams is relatively
young and evidently not lacking in inspiration, it would be
pointless to speculate about his eventual stature; now that
American music has its place in the international repertory, there
is no need for a towering figure in the Copland mold.
</P>
<P>
   Still, although Copland had the kind of relationship with CBS
Masterworks (now Sony Classical) that Adams has with Nonesuch, he
did not live to see his composer-directed discography compiled in a
comprehensive boxed overview. Indeed, Sony has yet to treat his
legacy seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The Adams compilation paints an expansive portrait. Its details
are already familiar to collectors who have kept pace with the
composer, for only three previously unissued recordings are
included. They account for a mere 52 minutes, and one of the
pieces, the 31-minute ``Harmonium,'' is a known commodity, having
long been available in recordings conducted by Edo de Waart (ECM)
and Robert Shaw (Telarc); here Adams leads the Orchestra of St.
Luke's. The other two pieces are new to disc, and one of them,
``Slonimsky's Earbox'' (1996), gives the set its title.
</P>
<P>
   On glancing acquaintance, both this frenetic, thick-textured
work, with its turn-of-the-(last-)century Russian accent, and the
other newcomer, ``Lollapalooza,'' sound like patches of orchestral
bombast, curtain raisers that demonstrate Adams' facility as a
colorist. Composers have done worse with similarly limited aims,
but there is more to these works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slonimsky's Earbox,'' a memorial to the musical lexicographer
Nicolas Slonimsky, is full of involving counterpoint, juxtaposing
interesting modal themes, and it continues Adams' longstanding
project of combining Minimalist techniques with complex structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The John Adams Earbox'' offers the misses as well as the hits,
but one of its surprises is that over time, some of the composer's
works have either gained or lost weight. Figuratively, for the most
part, although ``Shaker Loops,'' written as a chamber piece, is
heard here in the orchestration Adams considers its finished form.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestration magnifies the music's incipient Romanticism,
but there is much to be said for the sparer septet version heard on
that old 1750 Arch recording in a performance featuring the Ridge
Quartet (now on a New Albion CD with ``Light Over Water,'' an
appealing work for synthesizers and brass, otherwise unavailable).
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoodoo Zephyr,'' a collection of synthesizer pieces, seemed
little more than fluffy doodling when it was first released, in
1993. Adams, with the wisdom of hindsight, may concur (although a
defensive program note suggests otherwise); he includes only three
of the seven original selections here. In the context of this
anthology, they seem more consistent with Adams' output and more
listenable overall.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps insufficient time has elapsed to help ``I Was Looking at
the Ceiling and Then I Saw the Sky,'' his theatrical collaboration
with June Jordan; more likely, trying to harness the insufferable
cliches of the moribund musical theater style was simply a dreadful
idea. The work was meant to be current and topical, a snapshot of
Los Angeles at the time of the Northridge earthquake in 1994, with
characters of various ethnicities.
</P>
<P>
   It has its moments; the song ``Crushed by the Rock I Been
Standing On'' stands out. But the characters are generally
one-dimensional, and they engage in predictable posturing. Although
the instrumental accompaniments show glimmers of Adams' style, the
vocal lines could be taken as parodies of the Broadway cadence if
they were not so earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixon in China'' (1987) and ``The Death of Klinghoffer''
(1991), immensely superior works musically, are represented by
excerpts, one disc each. ``Klinghoffer'' has always caused
uneasiness. Adams and his librettist, Alice Goodman, may have meant
to empathize with both Jews and Palestinians, but they left hardly
anyone satisfied and many aggrieved (not least, the family of Leon
Klinghoffer, whose murder by Palestinian terrorists on the hijacked
cruise ship Achille Lauro is the opera's central event).
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixon'' fared better in its time; it is, after all, a fantasy
on a diplomatic breakthrough. Yet it left furrowed brows as well,
and not without reason.
</P>
<P>
   What proved most interesting about ``Nixon in China'' was the
contrast between the buffoonish character of Nixon, whose arias
portray either megalomania (the fabulously parodistic ``News Has a
Kind of Mystery'') or self-absorbed triviality, and the more
serenely philosophical Mao and Chou En-lai. In terms of the
contrast between cultures, it still works. In fact, both operas
work if you can divorce them from the actual events they portray
and regard their characters not as real people but as archetypes
embodying grander human qualities and foibles.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But such a conceptual leap may be too much to ask. The
characters are real people, and the events occurred in living
memory. The tensions plumbed in ``Klinghoffer'' remain open wounds
on both sides. And while the philosophical disparities between East
and West, ancient and modern, are intriguingly explored in
``Nixon,'' the fact that Mao and his circle were bona fide tyrants,
carrying out the oppressive Cultural Revolution at the time of
Nixon's visit, makes it unseemly to present them as philosopher
kings.
</P>
<P>
   If these are missteps _ and there is room for debate _ they seem
to have been taken honestly, in the belief that operas based on
contemporary events would have greater immediacy than fiction, and
that if the characters worked as archetypes (as they eventually
may), the works would have a long shelf life. There is, in any
case, superb music and imaginative text setting in these operas,
and they form an important part of the evolution the ``Earbox''
traces.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, it is in the works not intended for the
stage that the composer's more characteristic innovation really
shines. And listening to those works, one is struck by the sheer
variety of what Adams has produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand Pianola Music'' (1982), with its rippling keyboard
roulades and big orchestral gestures, pokes fun at the heroics of
Romantic concerto writing. ``Fearful Symmetries'' (1988) toys
similarly with symphonic textures, and the Chamber Symphony (1992)
takes yet another tack, offsetting a Neo-Classicism rooted in
Stravinsky and Schoenberg with bursts of cartoonish humor. These
pieces aren't brain surgery; they insist that symphonic music can
be slyly funny, and fun.
</P>
<P>
   Adams has a contrastingly sober side, evident in ``The Wound
Dresser'' (1989), an eerily vivid _ and entirely non-Minimalist _
setting of Walt Whitman's wrenching battlefield poetry. The Violin
Concerto, searingly played by Gidon Kremer, is as substantial an
addition to that corner of the repertory as any composer has made
in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eros Piano'' extends Adams' language in a different way.
Written after an evening with Toru Takemitsu, it embraces the
atmospheric gracefulness of that composer's later style through
inventive string voicings, and its solo piano line hints at the
shapely improvisations of Bill Evans, to whom the work is in fact a
tribute. ``Harmonium'' and ``Harmonielehre'' (1985), Adams' big
treatises on harmony, orchestration and color, become more
compelling with each hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Nonesuch has packaged the ``Earbox'' handsomely, in a slipcase
that holds the 10 thin jewel boxes and a generously illustrated
180-page booklet. The notes include a work-by-work rumination by
Adams and appreciations by Robert Hurwitz, the president of
Nonesuch, and Renaud Machart, a French critic, who provides a
European perspective on Adams. Shorter encomiums (by Michael Tilson
Thomas, Peter Sellars, Kremer, Sir Simon Rattle and others) are
scattered throughout the booklet, which also offers vocal texts, a
chronology and a discography.
</P>
<P>
   There are holes in the set, but very few. ``Phrygian Gates,'' a
piano work pivotal in Adams' canon, is not included, but it is
available in several fine accounts. Among them are discs by
Christopher O'Riley (Albany) and Gloria Cheng-Cochran (Telarc),
both of which also include ``China Gates,'' a rarer work also
absent from the ``Earbox.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1973 triptych ``American Standard,'' represented in part by
``Christian Zeal and Activity,'' would have been welcome in its
entirety. And although the ``Earbox'' renders most of Adams'
individual Nonesuch releases superflous, completists will have to
keep ``Hoodoo Zephyr'' for its four missing pieces, and ``El
Dorado'' for Adams' Liszt and Busoni orchestrations as well as the
complete recordings of ``Nixon'' and ``Klinghoffer.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Earbox'' is, of course, hardly the double bar on Adams'
career. Perhaps when ``The John Adams Earbox II'' is released in 20
years or so, these gaps will be filled.
</P>
</TEXT>
