<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW FAIR AND A NEW VIEW ON `BOUNDARIES'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Calif., Miss., France)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You don't have to wait until the millennium for the
20th century to be reinvented. It's happening Saturday. The
International 20th-Century Arts Fair, which is at the Seventh
Regiment Armory on Park Avenue at 67th Street Saturday through
Wednesday, may be the first ``antiques'' fair with contemporary
works of art and design.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a psychological thing,'' said Brian Haughton, an
organizer of the fair. ``As we go over the cusp of the next
millennium, people suddenly see what was made in this century as
antique.''
</P>
<P>
   David Revere McFadden, chief curator of the American Craft
Museum and the author of an essay in the show's catalog, said:
``It's a crossover show where the normal boundaries between fields
are not being paid attention to. It may be the first time that
contemporary craft, industrial design and fine art from the turn of
the century up to the present are being shown on the same level.''
</P>
<P>
   This new fair is the fourth initiated in New York by Haughton, a
native of Dublin, and Anna Haughton, his wife. The couple, who live
in London, produce the 10-year-old International Fine Art and
Antiques Dealers Show as well as the International Asian Art Fair
and the International Fine Art Fair in the city.
</P>
<P>
   It all started in London in 1982, when Haughton, an actor turned
Bond Street porcelain dealer, put on a ceramics fair during the
Grosvenor House Fair. It was such a success that he decided to go
global.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days an object was considered antique only if it was
at least 100 years old. ``We don't feel that way,'' Mrs. Haughton
said. ``Age does not qualify a piece for quality. Nor should age
bar it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new fair is a bold move. ``It's extremely expensive to set
up a new fair,'' Haughton conceded. ``We probably won't break even
for two years.'' Unlike Sanford Smith's Modernism show, this fair
is vetted: outside experts and museum curators review each dealer's
offerings, to verify authenticity, quality and labeling. Any
questionable pieces are relabeled or removed before the show opens.
</P>
<P>
   It's also costly for the 44 exhibitors. Booth rentals are $7,000
to $40,000 for the six days, in addition to shipping, booth
decoration and lodging costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some dealers are also nervous about having a show over the
Thanksgiving weekend. ``We know that 55 percent of our other fair
visitors are from out of town,'' Haughton said. ``We went ahead
after we learned that this weekend is one of the busiest ones at
the Met.''
</P>
<P>
   The fair (information: 212-642-8572) was also timed to coincide
with the 20th-century auctions. Christie's East is conducting its
first ``Important Design'' sale Saturday at 219 East 67th Street,
and Christie's ``Important 20th-Century Decorative Arts'' sale is
on Monday. Saturday Sotheby's begins previews for its 20th-century
decorative arts sales, to be held on Dec. 3 and 4. Treadway Toomey
Galleries' 20th-century auction, with 1,116 lots, will be held on
Dec. 4 and 5 in Oak Park, Ill. The Phillips 20th-century design
sale is Dec. 7 in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's East has fine examples of Bauhaus furniture; early
Noguchi pieces designed for Zenith, Knoll and Herman Miller; a 1943
molded plywood Eames sculpture; and several less well known
offerings. Among the latter are a tubular steel and caned armchair
designed in 1931 by Erich Dieckmann, who studied at the Bauhaus in
the early 1920's, and a mirror with a spiraling glass frame
designed by the Italian architect Gio Ponti for Venini about 1938.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia architect Robert Venturi designed chairs for
Knoll International between 1979 and 1984. His whimsical takeoffs
on the Chippendale, Queen Anne, Gothic and Art Nouveau styles are
in laminated plywood painted in bright colors. Christie's East is
selling five models that never went into production, each estimated
at $3,000 to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's decorative arts sale includes six vessels by George
Ohr (1857-1918), a Mississippi art potter. (Abbeville published a
fascinating illustrated 1989 biography of Ohr, ``The Mad Potter of
Biloxi,'' by Garth Clark, Robert A. Ellison Jr. and Eugene Hecht.)
Ohr made bizarrely shaped vases with paper-thin folded walls and
sumptuous glazes. One bowl for sale looks like a green-flecked
gourd. A spotted purple pitcher has a curled back rim. Estimates
range from $3,000 to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 102 is a Deco piano designed by Jacques-Emile Ruhlmann in
the 1920s that is as important historically as aesthetically. Made
of exotic striped Macassar ebony and Amboina wood with ivory
inlays, it was designed for the Paris Exposition of 1925, which
gave Art Deco its name.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's auctions include six lots of Ruhlmann furniture that
Altina Schinasi Miranda purchased on her Paris honeymoon in 1928,
including an amaranth and sharkskin-covered dressing table, a
burled elm desk and an amaranth chest. A New York artist, designer
and filmmaker, she was credited with creating Harlequin eyeglasses,
the large glasses made famous by Clare Boothe Luce and Katharine
Cornell. The designer married four times and lived in Los Angeles,
Washington and Santa Fe, but always had her Ruhlmanns with her.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillips 20th-century sale has a molded glass vase from the
Lalique series ``Tourbillions,'' of etched swirls that suggest
whirlwinds. First introduced at the 1925 Paris Exposition, the vase
was made in many colors. Lot 49 is a brilliant turquoise, a result
of adding cobalt to the glass before firing, an expense reserved
for the finest pieces. Estimate: $50,000 to $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   A stunning Deco steel gate attributed to Gilbert Poillerat has
overlapping steel circles that look like bubbles. ``The way it has
been constructed and the workmanship is closely in line with
Poillerat's studio,'' said Lora Krizelman, director of 20th-century
decorative arts at Phillips. Its estimate is $15,000 to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   At the Haughtons' fair, Historical Design is showing a white
Secessionist vase designed by Karl Klaus in 1911 with silver and
gold motifs. It was in a 1912 show, ``New Interiors by Viennese
Architects,'' at the Museum for Art and Industry in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The Gansevoort Gallery is selling a lamp designed in 1928-29 by
the Danish architect Poul Henningsen (1894-1967). The shade is made
from three upside-down brass saucers, to cut glare. McFadden
illustrated his catalog essay with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henningsen understood technology and engineering so well that
he created a new aesthetic,'' McFadden said. ``He knew how to
create magical light. He had an artistic approach informed by
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20th-century decorative arts have become a big business.
Lars Rachen of Christie's New York said sales from its 20th-century
department (not including Christie's East) totaled $28 million last
year, and that was without anything like the celebrity sale of
Barbra Streisand's Arts and Crafts collection scheduled for Monday.
Sotheby's 20th-century department in New York made $17 million last
year.
</P>
<P>
   So now let's see how the Haughtons do.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
