<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ADULT-MUSIC-2TAKES-NY     11-25 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADULT-MUSIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP MUSIC FOR GROWNUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes Randy Newman just 2 minutes and 43 seconds to deliver
``The World Isn't Fair,'' the year's most searching song about the
state of the Union on the edge of the millennium, from his recent
album, ``Bad Love.'' Carrying on a one-sided conversation with Karl
Marx, the singer, in his most insinuating pseudo-New Orleans drawl,
regales the dead philosopher with a personal anecdote about
attending a private-school orientation at which the trophy wives
and mothers were as beautiful as princesses, and their husbands
(including himself) looked like frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be glad that you're dead,'' he tells Marx, after explaining
sadly that the philosopher's idealistic theories, when applied to
real life, ended up bringing only misery. Then he adds: ``Just like
I'm glad I'm living in the land of the free/Where the rich just get
richer/And the poor you don't ever have to see/It would depress us,
Karl/Because we care/That the world isn't fair.'' Ouch!
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Isn't Fair'' is a lean little song for a fat era.
And in cutting against the grain of a pop-music climate in which so
many younger songwriters spill all their feelings out in messy,
sloppily rhymed and metered, often impenetrable five- and
six-minute effusions, it can be taken as an aesthetic guidepost to
this critic's annual adult pop consumer guide.
</P>
<P>
   Another model of restraint, thoughtfulness and craft, from a
different area of music, is Diana Krall's performance of Irving
Berlin's ``Let's Face the Music and Dance,'' on her recent album,
``When I Look in Your Eyes.'' Like Newman's song, this Berlin
classic, from the 1936 movie ``Follow the Fleet,'' silhouettes
present pleasures against the darker backdrop (``soon we will be
without the moon/humming a different tune'') of a looming world
war.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Krall's rendition, half murmured in a dark, slightly husky
alto and delivered with no ornamental frills, is an ominous
countercurrent pulling against a gossamer bossa nova arrangement by
Johnny Mandel. Throughout this album of standards, Ms. Krall
carries forward the intensely focused vocal minimalism of singers
like Peggy Lee and the young Nat ``King'' Cole, injecting a dash of
Carmen McRae's hard-headed psychological insight. Her emotive
understatement and utter lack of exhibitionism attest to her
astonishing integrity in a flamboyant vocal era of improvisatory
showoffs, melismatic overkill and wretchedly excessive belting.
</P>
<P>
   What Newman and Ms. Krall represent, in very different forms, is
an intractable artistic high-mindedness in a contemporary musical
climate overrun and corrupted by marketing. The artistic ill
effects of that marketing mentality are painfully evident on the
latest albums by singers like Celine Dion, Barbra Streisand, Mariah
Carey and Paula Cole. One of several new cuts on ``All the Way: A
Decade of Song'' (Epic/550 Music), Ms. Dion's just-released
greatest hits album, is a gimmicky, beyond-the-grave duet with
Frank Sinatra that sounds as though it were emanating from some
rhinestone-studded station in outer space rather than from the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of two hardy show tunes, ``Isn't It a Pity''
and ``The Music That Makes Me Dance,'' Ms. Streisand's wedding
album, ``A Love Like Ours'' (Columbia), is a smarmy package of
overproduced, predigested schlock mostly crooned in a voice that
shows the Streisand sound to be intact. But the emotional
risk-taking and commitment to superior songs that made Ms.
Streisand great have all but vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Following the trend toward youthful street music, Ms. Carey is
aggressively pursuing ``street credibility'' on her new, heavily
hip-hop flavored album, ``Rainbow'' (Columbia), and undercutting
her vocal strengths to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cole's song lyrics on ``Amen'' (Imago/Warner Brgthers), her
follow-up to the hugely successful ``This Fire'' (which contained
the hit ``Where Have All the Cowboys Gone?''), are dragged down by
a forced, strident preachiness that is also mirrored in the
singing.
</P>
<P>
   These and numerous other disappointing adult-oriented albums are
symptoms of a climate in which mainstream pop radio has virtually
eliminated adult contemporary music from its play lists. It used to
be that a powerful, straightforward ballad like Bette Midler's
``From a Distance'' could buck the trends and make its way up the
charts. But those days are gone. As any major-label record company
marketing expert will tell you, releasing an album without a
potential hit single is a commercially risky proposition.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the most startling indication of how far the pop
pendulum has swung toward rude, beat-driven street music was the
MTV Music Video Awards, at which what might be called lout music
(fusions of rap and metal) held sway. Raging testosterone ruled.
</P>
<P>
   What then is an old fogey who still harbors a passion for pop
music to do? Following is a selection of pop and a few jazz albums
(listed alphabetically by artist) recommended for people over 40 or
thereabouts. Some may be challenging for middle-of-the-road tastes.
(Compact discs range in price from $15.97 to $18.97.)
</P>
<P>
   ``TONY BENNETT SINGS ELLINGTON HOT AND COOL'' (RPM/Columbia).
Bennett sings 14 Duke Ellington songs, from swingers to lush
ballads, with his usual heartfelt bonhomie and a swinging authority
that's so assured that rhythm seems to be seeping out of his pores.
But why did he feel obliged to change ``I've Got It Bad (and That
Ain't Good)'' to ``She's Got It Bad''?
</P>
<P>
   ``IBRAHIM FERRER'' (World Circuit/Nonesuch). This great old-time
Cuban singer whose career was resurrected by Ry Cooder's Buena
Vista Social Club has been compared to Nat ``King'' Cole. And there
is a distant resemblance in the relaxed dreaminess of his crooning.
Cooder produced this solo album, in which Ferrer (backed by an
assembly of top-notch Cuban musicians) sings everything from
string-laden boleros that almost seem to float in the air to
harder-edged pre-salsa numbers.
</P>
<P>
   BRYAN FERRY: ``AS TIME GOES BY'' (Virgin). The epitome of
high-toned British suavity with a rock twist applies his twirling
vibrato to 15 popular standards. The loose swinging chamber
arrangements (some with strings) have a Django Reinhardt lilt.
Tasteful and fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ADAM GUETTEL: ``MYTHS AND HYMNS'' (Nonesuch). If the next
generation of theater composers is to rise above the grandiose
schlock of Andrew Lloyd Webber and Frank Wildhorn, Guettel (Richard
Rodgers' grandson) has the melodic brilliance to lead the charge.
His debut album of original music features a top-flight rotating
cast, including the composer, singing songs inspired by Greek myths
and Protestant hymns. Lofty but accessible and intensely
passionate.
</P>
<P>
   ``CHARLIE HADEN AND QUARTET WEST: ``THE ART OF SONG'' (Verve).
In this languidly moody album, the eminent bassist and his group _
the pianist Alan Broadbent, the saxophonist Ernie Watts and the
drummer Larence Marable _ rummage through a collection of standards
with Bill Henderson and Shirley Horn as guest vocalists and a small
orchestra. Killer cuts: Ms. Horn's quiet, string-swaddled versions
of ``I'm Gonna Laugh You Right Out of My Life'' and ``The Folks Who
Live on the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FRED HERSCH: ``LET YOURSELF GO'' (Nonesuch). An unaccompanied
solo concert is the ultimate test of a jazz pianist. This
impressive solo album, which includes works by composers ranging
from Weill to Monk (and including an original composition), is
knotty, idea-filled and absorbing. Just when it threatens to become
too intellectual, it relaxes into sunbursts of feeling. It
concludes with a version of ``The Nearness of You'' that Keith
Jarrett might envy.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA KRALL: ``WHEN I LOOK IN YOUR EYES'' (Verve). In her first
orchestrated album (by Johnny Mandel), this British Columbian jazz
singer and pianist takes another huge artistic step forward. Its
heart-stopping centerpiece is the title song, written by Leslie
Bricusse for the movie ``Dr. Doolittle,'' of all things. More
performances like this and Ms. Krall will find herself counted
among the greats.
</P>
<P>
   ALISON KRAUSS: ``FORGET ABOUT IT'' (Rounder). Ms. Krauss'
delicate, silver-threaded voice is one of the tenderest in all
country music. Here she applies it to wistful pop nuggets like Todd
Rundgren's ``It Wouldn't Have Made Any Difference'' and the killer
cut, ``Empty Hearts'' (by Michael McDonald and Michael Johnson).
</P>
<P>
   PAUL McCARTNEY: ``RUN DEVIL RUN'' (Capitol). The former Beatle
revisits the early days of rock 'n' roll with an infectious
exuberance, mixing original '50s-style songs with golden oldies by
Elvis, Ricky Nelson, Chuck Berry and others. Well done.
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE NDEGEOCELLO: ``BITTER'' (Maverick). This suite of songs
about sexual betrayal slices to the bone and is delivered in an
intimate speech-song that finds every shade of meaning in the word
``bitter.'' Craig Street's production fleshes out Ms. Ndegeocello's
inner world with a quirky subterranean ambience.
</P>
<P>
   RANDY NEWMAN: ``BAD LOVE'' (DreamWorks). An artistic key to
Newman's serious fun is the way he incriminates himself in his
stinging first-person critiques. One example in ``Bad Love'' is his
admission in ``I Miss You,'' a pining love song to a distant
ex-wife, that he is selling his soul by exploiting their
relationship in the song. And by implicating himself, he implicates
us. As for the music on ``Bad Love,'' it is as spare and allusive
as ever, with styles from New Orleans marching bands to echoes of
Mahler, and with tunes that stick.
</P>
<P>
   BRENDAN PERRY: ``EYE OF THE HUNTER'' (4AD). These arching gothic
folk-pop ballads by the male half of the defunct duo Dead Can Dance
echo the gloomy grandeur of Leonard Cohen, with Perry sounding at
moments like Bruce Springsteen at his most ruminative, with an
added touch of Neil Diamond. The haunting, somewhat morbid album
has the kind of music that inspires cults.
</P>
<P>
   PET SHOP BOYS: ``NIGHTLIFE'' (WEA/Sire). Orchestrally
embellished disco remains the British duo's chosen medium. But the
songs (which deal with gay culture and relationships) continue to
deepen. Songs like ``I Don't Know What You Want But I Can't Give It
Anymore'' and ``You Only Tell Me You Love Me When You're Drunk''
plunge us into the well-heeled urban jungle.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN PRINE: ``IN SPITE OF OURSELVES'' (Oh Boy). The
singer-songwriter, whose voice is as plain as dirt, duets with Iris
DeMent, Lucinda Williams, Trisha Yearwood, Emmylou Harris, Melba
Montgomery and others in this collection of 15 country classics
augmented with one brilliant original, the title song sung with Ms.
DeMent. What you get is the raw texture of life in an idealized,
rollicking portrait of the rural South decades before ``Urban
Cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   SANTANA: ``SUPERNATURAL'' (Arista). A rare case of inspired
multimarketing savvy (credit the Arista Records chief Clive Davis)
brought the great guitarist Carlos Santana back to the top of the
charts by teaming him with everyone from Dave Matthews (crooning
``Love of My Life'') and the gravelly voiced Rob Thomas (the
pop-salsa hit ``Smooth'') to the hip-hopper Lauryn Hill (``Do You
Like the Way'') to his fellow guitar giant Eric Clapton (the
crunchy, gospel-flavored ``The Calling''). Stylistically diffuse
and gimmicky, but still worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   RON SEXSMITH: ``WHEREABOUTS'' (Interscope). The singer and
songwriter's wonderful third album of pared-down parables and
exquisitely calibrated mood swings is like a private primer of
rueful, sometimes scarily wise apercus. They're rendered without a
wasted word or note in a voice whose shy, quavering intensity
echoes Tim Hardin.
</P>
<P>
   STING: ``BRAND NEW DAY'' (A&AMP;M). Sting's ambition to be all
things to all musical genres, from bossa nova to country to North
African music, can exceed his accomplishment; his country songs
sound forced. But when he lands a knockout punch like ``A Thousand
Years,'' a hypnotic chant that spirals into the stars along a minor
key, pop music doesn't get more deeply entrancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``DAWN UPSHAW SINGS VERNON DUKE'' (Nonesuch). Lovely,
beautifully measured performances of songs by the underappreciated
composer of ``Autumn in New York'' and ''April in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   CAETANO VELOSO: ``LIVRO'' (Nonesuch). The music on this
far-reaching album by Brazil's greatest singing poet is about as
diverse as that nation's countryside, with feathery love songs
juxtaposed with percussive carnival sambas, and subject matter
ranging from the beauty of books to the life of Alexander the
Great. The album has the color and scope of a sprawling mural
created by a hypersensitive pantheist.
</P>
<P>
   CASSANDRA WILSON: ``TRAVELING MILES'' (Blue Note). Ms. Wilson's
tribute to the spirit of Miles Davis, whose music she has set with
brilliant impressionistic lyrics that mirror his mixture of
romanticism and bitter sarcasm, is an extraordinary collision of
sensibilities. Both as a lyricist and a singer, Ms. Wilson matches
Davis in the depth and twisting complexity of her singing and
writing.
</P>
<P>
   JESSE WINCHESTER: ``GENTLEMAN OF LEISURE'' (Sugar Hill). The
gifted singer-songwriter, seldom heard from since the 1970s (and
even then under-recognized), resurfaces with an album of original
blues and soul-tinged country-folk songs. The lyrics are diamond
hard and confessional. His rich, silky baritone, shot through with
vulnerability, is as compelling as ever. Killer cuts: ``That's What
Makes You Strong'' and ``No Pride at All.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
