<SLUG> BC-VELAZQUEZ-EXHIBIT-ART-1060(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TASTE OF VELAZQUEZ PROVES A BANQUET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the principle that there are no small shows, only
small artists, the six paintings brought together for ``Velazquez
in New York Museums'' at the Frick Collection add up to a very big
show indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion is the 400th anniversary of the birth of Diego de
Velazquez (1599-1660), and to honor it the Frick has surrounded its
own splendiferous portrait of King Philip IV of Spain with an
intimate, A-list gathering of nearly all the paintings by this
baroque master in local public collections.
</P>
<P>
   Two are from the Metropolitan Museum, including the famous
``Juan de Pareja.'' (A third, the early ``Supper at Emmaus,'' could
not be lent, because of restrictions attached to its bequest. It's
on view at the Met now.) And new to many viewers will be three
works owned by the Hispanic Society of America that have not left
their northern Manhattan home in 90 years.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen paintings presented in a strictly no-frills
installation feels a mite thin, hardly a show at all in the age of
the megaretrospective. But Velazquez didn't paint much; only
100-plus works survive, the bulk now in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several explanations for his skimpy output. His
chief patron, Philip IV, called him lethargic, which was a nice way
of saying lazy. The art historian Jonathan Brown, who organized the
show, points to conflicted ambition: Velazquez wanted to be a
gentleman more than he wanted to be a painter (the two were
mutually exclusive in 17th-century Spain), so he turned on creative
steam only when he absolutely had to.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, a handful of Velazquezes packs more of a
punch than a museumful of work by nearly anyone else of his time.
And the six paintings at the Frick neatly manage to touch on key
periods in a 40-year career.
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the 17th century, Spain was the most powerful
country in Europe but artistically somewhat out of the Continental
loop. Velazquez, born in Seville, had the luck to be apprenticed to
the painter Francisco Pacheco, a cosmopolitan man who grounded his
students in classical art and literature.
</P>
<P>
   The young artist developed a precocious, eye-catching realist
style and from the start had his sights set on an appointment at
the Spanish court. The opportunity came through Gaspar de Guzman,
Count-Duke of Olivares, whose full-length portrait by Velazquez,
from the Hispanic Society, is the earliest entry in the show.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares had made himself an indispensable adviser to the newly
crowned Philip IV. And his demeanor in the portrait, at once
baby-faced and commanding, suggests his appeal to an insecure king
still in, or barely out of, his teens. Olivares was interested in
art and had personal links to Seville. So it was inevitable that
Velazquez would come to his attention and be brought to Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   There he landed the job of court painter, a position he held for
decades. His main assignment was as royal portraitist, and Philip
would have no other, except Rubens, who visited the Spanish court
briefly. From the Frick portrait one can understand why.
</P>
<P>
   Painted in 1644 just after a Spanish military victory, it was
whipped up on a tight deadline in a makeshift studio near the
battlefield. The result was pure propaganda: the equivalent of a
victory photo taken at the front. But in it the artist integrates
his early penchant for unidealized realism with the Titianesque,
proto-impressionist brushwork of his mature style.
</P>
<P>
   The king's face, with its high, pale forehead and massive
Hapsburg chin, is exactingly executed: One can almost see the pulse
beating at his thin-skinned temple. But his silver-embroidered
jacket is something else: an atomized flurry of white and black
daubs, a painterly illusion of scintillating fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Velazquez also made promotional images of Philip's family. When
the infanta Maria Teresa came of marriageable age, she was heavily
advertised in portraits sent to the French and Austrian courts.
(She ended up as queen of France, married to Louis XIV.) Velazquez
produced the prototype studies for them, an example of which is on
loan from the Met.
</P>
<P>
   Executed quickly by a painter who helped establish
``unfinished'' as a new category of masterpiece, it depicts a
self-composed young woman who is also a kind of living sculpture:
Her bean-shaped, rouged face is surmounted by a boulderlike wig on
which bows seem to have alighted like butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   The other portraits in the exhibition are of less socially
exalted beings. Among them is the Hispanic Society's picture of
Camillo Astalli, known as Cardinal Pamphili, painted in Rome late
in the artist's career.
</P>
<P>
   Astalli was a distant relative of Pope Innocent X and, for
reasons no one could quite figure out, was elevated overnight to a
position of tremendous power. Velazquez, who had come to Italy to
buy art for Philip, was counting on the pope to help him secure a
Spanish knighthood and produced a sparkling portrait of the papal
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Velazquez eventually got his knighthood, but Astalli's career
was over in a flash. He leaked military secrets from the Vatican,
but was found out and stripped of every privilege. The Roman
establishment was glad to see him go; he had a reputation for being
a wise guy, and there's a hint of this in the portrait, in which he
wears his cardinal's hat at a cocky, home-boy angle.
</P>
<P>
   About the likeness of Juan de Pareja, also painted in Rome, much
has been written since it was bought by the Met in 1971. The
sitter, of Muslim descent, was Velazquez's slave and studio
assistant and an artist in his own right. Velazquez intended the
painting to be his professional calling card in Italy; it was
renowned in its day, and still is, as one of the supreme European
portraits.
</P>
<P>
   There is a final portrait in the show, however, of which
virtually nothing at all is known. It is a small, unfinished,
bust-length likeness of a little girl with dark hair and eyes and
luminous, light-bathed skin. She has sometimes been identified as
Velazquez's granddaughter, but there is no firm evidence for this.
</P>
<P>
   What can be said is that she represents a rare departure from
this artist's cool, courtly approach to the human subject. He was
impressed by many of his royal sitters, and he made them look
impressive in turn. But he clearly loved this grave child, as
anyone will who encounters her today.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She is seldom seen except by habitues of the Hispanic Society's
headquarters at 155th Street and Broadway, where she usually
resides. And the most valuable function of the Frick show may be to
draw attention to the Hispanic Society itself. It is a gold mine of
Spanish and Latin American art, and two of its images give a sense
of its scope.
</P>
<P>
   One is a painting by Velazquez's contemporary Zurbaran of St.
Rufina depicted as a Spanish beauty dressed to the nines in rose
pink and apple green, her eyes cast heavenward.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a portrait by Goya of his formidable mistress, the
duchess of Alba, who stands hand on hip, staring straight out, with
a finger pointing to the ground as if to say, ``Kneel, you besotted
wretch.'' (Goya's name is written in the sand at her feet.)
</P>
<P>
   She's divine, as is much else in a collection that embraces
painting by El Greco and Ribera, monumental Gothic tomb sculptures,
Hispano-Islamic ivories and a huge collection of printed books from
Spain and the New World, all adding up to one of the city's
unforgettable museum experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The Frick Collection, needless to say, is another. And it is
seen at its generous best in ``Velazquez in New York Museums,'' a
show that might best be approached as the visual equivalent of
chamber music _ an instrumental sextet _ modest in scale, rich in
tonal variety and in execution beyond compare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Velazquez in New York Museums'' remains at The Frick
Collection, 1 East 70th St., New York, (212) 288-0700, through Jan.
16. The exhibition is a collaboration between the Frick and the
Hispanic Society of America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
