<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Nov. 26 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Democrats call it a do-nothing
Congress; Republicans are only slightly more enthusiastic, saying
it was all that could be expected with such narrow majorities in
the House and Senate and a Democratic president. But business
lobbies like the Chamber of Commerce think they had a great year in
Congress. Not only did they get most of what they wanted, but they
were able to block the things they did not want. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCH-DEVELOPING-NATIONS (Undated) _ Angry that they have not
profited from the animal and plant life within their borders,
Ecuador and many other developing countries have begun restricting
the freedom of scientists to collect biological samples and
demanding compensation in exchange for permits. Some scientists
warn that scores of research projects that might lead to
breakthroughs in medicine and agriculture, as well as to the study
and preservation of endangered species, are being impeded or
abandoned. A Special Report by Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   With two photos, NYT6 and NYT12.
</P>
<P>
   ASTRO-MICROWAVES (Undated) _ Like the great navigators who first
sailed around the world, establishing its size and the curvature of
its surface, astronomers have made new observations that show with
startling directness the large-scale geometry of the universe and
the total amount of matter and energy that it contains. By James
Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-LESSON-PLANS (Chicago) _ Though almost every American
school district has begun, in just the last three years, to check
student progress against specified academic standards, the nation's
third largest district has gone a giant step further this year:
supplying every teacher with a virtual script, a detailed,
day-by-day outline of what he or she should be teaching _ and when
_ in the language arts, mathematics, science and social studies.
The standardized lesson plans, which were drafted over two years by
a committee of 100 teachers, are optional. But central
administrators, most notably the system's chief executive, Paul
Vallas, have made clear that all teachers should draw on the
lessons in some way _ and many apparently are. By Jacques
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   SOMALILAND (Burao) _ The self-proclaimed Republic of Somaliland,
founded nine years ago when people in northwest Somalia decided to
declare themselves separate from the chaos engufling the rest of
the country, has become one of Africa's fledgling success stories _
but a success the outside world has been reluctant to help. The
reason is that no one is quite sure what to do with it. A Special
Report by Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SHIP (Beijing) _ At least 119 people are dead and more
than 150 missing after a ferry in stormy seas burned and broke
apart off China's northeastern coast, official news media reported
Thursday. By Thursday night, according to differing accounts from
the shipping company and the New China News Agency, either 22 or 36
survivors had been found from the ship, which that had been
carrying 312 passengers and crew members. Sixteen-foot waves and
freezing temperatures hampered the rescue effort near the port city
of Yantai, in Shandong province. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
