<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Nov. 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moderate to heavy rains will fall Friday across parts of the
Southeast, the central Appalachians and the eastern Great Lakes as
a cold front and a trailing trough of low pressure at 18,000 feet
move slowly eastward across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and a few thunderstorms, fueled by Atlantic moisture,
will develop along the cold front Friday or Friday night from
extreme northeast Florida to the Carolinas and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains are possible across the central Appalachians from
the mountains of West Virginia to the high ground of western and
central Pennsylvania as moist Atlantic air is drawn up the sloping
terrain ahead of the cold front. Moderate to locally heavy rains
are also possible across parts of the eastern Great Lakes in
northwest Pennsylvania and western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing ocean winds, averaging 15 to 30 mph, will import
moisture across the Northeast Seaboard, paving the way for low
clouds, patchy drizzle or spotty showers. However, the brunt of the
rain associated with the approaching system will stay west of the
Northeast Seaboard on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, strong gusts will lash parts of eastern Colorado as
fast winds cresting the lofty Rockies careen down eastern slopes.
Gusts could exceed 70 mph in spots. In the Pacific Northwest, the
siege of wet weather will gradually ease from north to south as a
Pacific ridge of high pressure builds toward the coast at 18,000
feet. Nonetheless, some heavy snow is still possible in the
mountains of southwest Oregon and parts of northern California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: High Winds &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A high wind warning was posted Thursday for the mountains and
foothills of northeast and north-central Colorado. Gusts to 100
miles an hour were expected in some of the high mountain passes at
elevations above 10,000 feet. Strong winds cresting the Rockies
Thursday careened down eastern slopes, setting the stage for high
winds in the valleys below. Strong winds also brought warmth as air
descending the eastern slopes warmed rapidly by compression. Strong
``Chinook'' winds are again possible Friday in parts of eastern
Colorado, with gusts of 70 mph or more in a few places.
</P>
</TEXT>
