<HEADLINE>
INSIDE ART: NEW AUCTION FOR OLD MASTERS; AGREEING TO DISAGREE;
PAINTING STAYING PUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (lb) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More prized works of art confiscated by the Nazis and recently
returned to their rightful owners are coming to auction. The latest
_ old-master paintings by artists including Tiepolo, Canaletto and
Strozzi _ follow the hugely successful auction of art and
decorative objects in June by the Austrian branch of the Rothschild
family at Christie's in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chicness and high profile of the Rothschild sale did bring
other things to the surface,'' said Anthony Crichton-Stuart, head
of Christie's old-master paintings department in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 27, Christie's in New York will be selling six
old-master paintings that had belonged to Federico Gentili di
Giuseppe, an Italian businessman who lived in Paris. After
Giuseppe's death in 1941, his family fled occupied France for the
United States, leaving the art in Paris. That same year, a
Nazi-appointed administrator sold the paintings in a forced sale at
a hotel there.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, the Allies turned over five of the paintings
to the French government, which exhibited them at the Louvre under
the label ``Musees Nationaux Recuperation.'' The sixth was bought
in 1941 by a German dealer, who sold it to the Gemaeldegalerie in
Berlin in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years Giuseppe's heirs have petitioned the
French and German governments, claiming that the paintings were
rightfully theirs and that the 1941 sale was illegal. Earlier this
year, the French and German governments returned the paintings to
the family.
</P>
<P>
   Included in Christie's sale is Tiepolo's ``Apelles Painting
Campaspe'' from the late 1730s. The easel-size painting depicts
Alexander the Great and his favorite concubine, Campaspe, being
painted by Alexander's court painter, Apelles. (While working on
the painting, Apelles fell in love with Campaspe, and Alexander
allowed them to marry.)
</P>
<P>
   Tiepolo painted this subject three times. ``This is the last
version,'' Crichton-Stuart said. ``It has a sober dignity and
elegance typical of the artist's more classical period.'' Its
estimate is $1.5 million to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also for sale is a Tiepolo sketch, ``Rinaldo Abandoning Armida''
(circa 1752-1753), estimated at $600,000 to $800,000. It had been
on view at the Gemaeldegalerie. A third work is Strozzi's ``Holy
Family,'' which dates from his mature period, 1620-1632, and also
carries an estimate of $600,000 to $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although London is traditionally the center of the old-master
market, the sale will be in New York. ``There has been a succession
of successful Tiepolo shows in this country,'' Crichton-Stuart
explained. ``We think the market is particularly strong here for
Italian pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing to Disagree
</P>
<P>
   Herzog &AMP; de Meuron, the architects who won an international
competition last year to design the Jack S. Blanton Museum of Art
at the University of Texas in Austin, have resigned from the
project after months of trying to resolve aesthetic differences
with the school's Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   The 150,000-square-foot, $60 million museum, at one of the main
entrances to the campus, was scheduled for completion in January
2002. Now the project is expected to be delayed at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   The selection committee that chose Herzog &AMP; de Meuron and the
Board of Regents were separate entities with different
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was that the architects were hired by one group
but they ended up working for another,'' said Larry Faulkner,
president of the university.
</P>
<P>
   After submitting 14 models and three different schemes to house
the more than 700 works of European art in the museum's
collections, Herzog &AMP; de Meuron settled on a one-story building,
like a garden pavilion, with a central courtyard, atriums and an
undulating roof of red and clear tiles.
</P>
<P>
   The regents preferred a more traditional two- or three-story
building and wanted Texas limestone and a red tile roof, which
board members said would be more compatible with the campus master
plan. That plan calls for new buildings to be similar in style to
those on the original campus, many of which were designed by the
architect Paul Cret.
</P>
<P>
   ``The selection committee was looking for cutting-edge
architecture while the Board of Regents were more traditional, and
they weren't happy with our design approach,'' said Harry Gugger,
Herzog &AMP; de Meuron's project manager for the job. ``We were not
prepared to compromise our architectural philosophy and felt it was
better to free up the university, allowing them to make a fresh
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner said the university would ``pick up the pieces and
start again with an architectural committee that has a stronger
connection to the Board of Regents.''
</P>
<P>
   Herzog &AMP; de Meuron, based in Basel, Switzerland, is completing
the new Tate Gallery of Modern Art in London, which is to open this
spring, and is also designing the new home of the de Young Museum
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Painting Staying Put
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth, Texas, will not get
Botticelli's ``Virgin Adoring the Christ Child'' (circa 1480), a
$24 million painting being sold by the Wemyss Heirloom Trust from
the Earl of Wemyss home in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago the Kimbell applied for an export license to allow
the painting to leave Britain, but Britain's Lottery Fund has
raised three-quarters of the money needed to match the museum's
offer and keep the painting in Britain, and other funds have
contributed the rest. The painting went on view this week at the
National Galleries of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things happen,'' said Timothy Potts, director of the
Kimbell. ``I am pleased that it is going into a public
collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Mauro, managing director of Dickinson Roundell in New
York, whose London gallery represented the trust, said: ``We're
obviously sad this painting is not coming to America after so much
effort was put into acquiring it for the Kimbell. But we are
pleased it is going into a museum in the United Kingdom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
