<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKE     11-25 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN BEAUTY,' starring Kevin Spacey, Annette Bening, Chris
Cooper, Wes Bentley and Thora Birch. Written by Alan Ball. Directed
by Sam Mendes (R, 116 minutes). With heavenly finesse, Spacey plays
a buttoned-down 42-year-old suburbanite who flips his lid for a
teen-age cheerleader. And he never gets it back on. The midlife
crisis motif is familiar, but the stage director Sam Mendes brings
terrific visual flair and dry humor to this barbecuing of the
bourgeoisie. All the actors display coolly expert timing,
especially Ms. Bening as the antihero's grasping wife. Although the
story spreads itself thin among many characters, the film coalesces
for a devastating finale (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE BUENA VISTA SOCIAL CLUB,' with Ibrahim Ferrer, Compay
Segundo and Ry Cooder. Directed by Wim Wenders (not rated, 106
minutes). When the American guitarist and producer Ry Cooder
assembled a group of all-but-forgotten Cuban musicians to record an
album, no one expected that the record would become a phenomenon,
selling more than a million copies worldwide and revitalizing the
Cuban music scene. Wenders' ebullient documentary follows the group
on tour from Amsterdam, Netherlands, to New York and includes
interviews with the group's main members. The music pulsates, and
the pictures of Havana compare the city's grand but faded
architecture with the musicians' weather-beaten faces (Stephen
Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN MOVIE,' featuring Mark Borchardt and friends. Directed
by Chris Smith (R, 104 minutes). An insightful, funny,
not-to-be-missed documentary about a no-budget Wisconsin filmmaker
who makes a horror film as if his life depended on it. And as Smith
so affectingly reveals, Borchardt's hopes really do hang in the
balance. This knowing and often hilarious look at try-anything
indie filmmaking becomes a moving portrait of one man's uphill
struggle and finds Borchardt often describing success and
prosperity as his goals. Meanwhile his own life is eloquently
presented as a very different, no less authentic kind of American
Dream (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ANYWHERE BUT HERE,' starring Susan Sarandon and Natalie
Portman. Directed by Wayne Wang (PG-13, 113 minutes). In a knowing
film adaptation of Mona Simpson's widely praised, if not often
wildly eventful, first novel, Ms. Sarandon is show-stopping as the
14-year-old heroine's mother and main nemesis. And Ms. Portman, who
proves her mettle in a fully formed dramatic role, does a terrific
job of holding her own in the film's battle of wills. Even when the
material meanders, Wang supplies insightful, affectionate
direction, just as he did for ``The Joy Luck Club.'' A women's
picture made with feeling and acted with great flair (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `BEING JOHN MALKOVICH,' starring John Cusack, Catherine Keener,
Cameron Diaz and (of course) John Malkovich. Written by Charlie
Kaufman and directed by Spike Jonze (R, 112 minutes). Welcome to
the fun house: In this exhilaratingly quirky first feature by a
stellar video director, the reigning fears and obsessions of a
technology-crazed, voyeuristic culture are given an even wilder
workout than they got from ``The Truman Show.'' Cusack plays a
discouraged puppeteer who accidentally finds a way into Malkovich's
mind. While the ordinary science-fiction plot might go downhill
after revealing its gimmick, this one's inspired craziness goes on
and on. Originality and cleverness abound (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE BACHELOR,' starring Chris O'Donnell and Renee Zellweger.
Directed by Gary Sinyor (PG-13, 90 minutes). This crude, frantic
yuppie farce stars O'Donnell as a selfish, marriage-shy bachelor
who botches his proposal to his sweetheart (Ms. Zellweger) days
before his grandfather dies and leaves him $100 million on the
condition he marry before his 30th birthday. That gives him 27
hours either to win back his true love or find another wife. After
running through his ex-girlfriends, he finds himself besieged by a
horde of prospective brides chasing him through the streets of San
Francisco. Based on a 1925 Buster Keaton classic, the movie lands a
few satiric thrusts at the money-mad workaholic '90s (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE BONE COLLECTOR,' starring Denzel Washington and Angelina
Jolie. Directed by Phillip Noyce (R, 118 minutes). One of the
year's most gruesome movies, the ingenious but preposterous
whodunit stars Washington as a quadriplegic forensic detective
tracking down a serial killer who plays cat and mouse with him by
leaving elaborate clues at the crime scenes. Ms. Jolie is the
police officer (and former model) whom he instructs by cell phone
on how to gather evidence. Crammed with the usual manipulative
jolts, this urban creepshow at least succeeds in sustaining an
atmosphere of menace, and Washington's and Ms. Jolie's star
chemistry smolders without the two exchanging so much as a kiss
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `BOYS DON'T CRY,' starring Hillary Swank and Chloe Sevigny.
Directed by Kimberley Pierce (R, 114 minutes). This stunning debut
feature tells the strange and resonant story of Brandon Teena, who
despite being born Teena Brandon went on to create a charismatic
identity as a young man. Brandon's ultimately wrenching tale may
sound tabloid-ready, but on screen it turns into Theodore Dreiser's
idea of American tragedy. The film makes it hauntingly real and
even tenderly romantic, with the astonishing acting needed to make
it work. One of the year's best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `BRINGING OUT THE DEAD,' starring Nicolas Cage and Patricia
Arquette. Written by Paul Schrader from a novel by Joe Connelly.
Directed by Martin Scorsese (R, 115 minutes). An intense, volatile
film full of sorrow and wild, mordant humor. This time it took prop
garbage on the streets of Hell's Kitchen to create a sufficiently
hellish ambience for another nighttime tour of Manhattan. But
Scorsese has mellowed significantly since his ``Taxi Driver'' days,
and his uneven but impassioned, visually inventive new film is more
contemplative than it looks. Cage gives a fine, soulful performance
as a New York ambulance driver haunted by ghosts. Ving Rhames is a
major scene-stealer as one of his partners (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `DOGMA,' starring Matt Damon, Ben Affleck, Linda Fiorentino,
Chris Rock and Salma Hayek. Directed by Kevin Smith (R, 130
minutes). Smith's idea of angels in America is the notion of two
cool dudes who take a hair-splitting, legalese approach to Roman
Catholic doctrine and think it would be amusing to nullify all
existence. And nothing in this wildly brazen, unexpectedly devout
comedy is any less outrageous than that. Smith again shows off a
rare gift for fusing his comic-book sensibility with serious
debates and big, big laughs, even if some parts of his film (Ms.
Fiorentino's performance, Rock's and semi-repartee from the
ubiquitous Jay and Silent Bob) work better than others (an
excrement monster). Making a gutsy leap into matters of faith,
Smith miraculously emerges with his humor intact and his wings
unsinged (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `FELICIA'S JOURNEY,' starring Elaine Cassidy and Bob Hoskins.
Directed by Atom Egoyan (PG-13, 116 minutes). In the brilliantly
realized surreal thriller, adapted from William Trevor's popular
novel, Felicia (Ms. Cassidy), a pregnant Irish girl searching for
her boyfriend in the English midlands, is befriended by Joseph
Hildritch (Hoskins), a catering manager who also happens to be a
serial killer. Egoyan, Canada's most gifted filmmaker, elevates
this cat-and-mouse game into a film that transcends genre by
entering the characters' consciousness and implying a world of
half-discernible connections in which the weather, the landscape
and the chance encounters of strangers suggest the sense of a grand
design (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `FLAWLESS,' starring Robert De Niro and Philip Seymour Hoffman.
Written and directed by Joel Schumacher (R, 110 minutes). De Niro
is a retired New York City policeman recovering from a stroke and
Hoffman the drag queen upstairs who gives him speech therapy in the
form of singing lessons in this stridently campy comedy. Their
flashy performances can't add dimension to a movie that is a
message-laden duet for two caricatures, a homophobe and the angry,
self-loathing drag queen who gets him out of his depression
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE INSIDER,' starring Al Pacino, Russell Crowe and Christopher
Plummer. Directed by Michael Mann (R, 155 minutes). Mann directs
this taut thriller about the tobacco industry whistle-blower
Jeffrey Wigand with pulse-quickening panache. And he illustrates
why, in the corporate climate of the '90s, truth-telling is a
riskier business than it was circa ``All the President's Men.''
While Pacino delivers galvanizing moral outrage as a producer for
``60 Minutes,'' and Plummer wickedly mimics Mike Wallace, Crowe
movingly captures the complexity of Wigand's situation. Shaky
docudrama ethics cloud the film's take on ``60 Minutes.'' But this
is an inordinately well-played thriller, with Mann's stylistic brio
at its best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `LIBERTY HEIGHTS,' starring Adrien Brody, Bebe Neuwirth, Joe
Mantegna and Ben Foster. Directed and written by Barry Levinson (R,
134 minutes). This semi-autobiographical comedy-drama remembering
teen-age life, anti-Semitism and racism in mid-1950s Baltimore is
the fourth movie by Levinson to be set in his native city. A deeply
felt nostalgia trip, the movie adrgitly aaptures the look and
social attitudes of the city 45 years ago. But the screenplay and
performances are too muted for the movie to come to terms with
growing pains cushioned in the nostalgic haze (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `MANSFIELD PARK,' starring Frances O'Connor and Jonny Lee
Miller. Written and directed by Patricia Rozema (PG-13, 105
minutes). In Ms. Rozema's skillful screen adaptation of Jane
Austen's third novel, the protagonist Fanny Price (Ms. O'Connor)
has been sharpened into a proto-feminist heroine who triumphs over
the materialist, patriarchal values of her wealthy relatives
through a combination of wit, beauty and daring. Without bearing
down too heavily, the screenplay (which incorporates fragments of
Austen's letters and diaries) equates early 19th-century
slave-trading with the oppression of women. The message is leavened
with smart humor and warm three-dimensional performances (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE MESSENGER: THE STORY OF JOAN OF ARC,' starring Milla
Jovovich, John Malkovich, Tcheky Karyo and Faye Dunaway. Directed
by Luc Besson (R, 130 minutes). The Hundred Years' War feels twice
that long in this shrill, frenetic account of Joan of Arc. It's a
film whose main revelation is that the Middle Ages may have been a
lot more lurid than previously reported. Besson directs plenty of
grisly, hand-held battle scenes and absurd scenes of royal
scheming, while Ms. Jovovich talks. Like this. And doesn't seem
faintly plausible as France's teen-age martyr. Here's a case where
``Don't shoot `The Messenger''' would have been sound advice
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MUSIC OF THE HEART,' starring Meryl Streep, Aidan Quinn, Angela
Bassett and Gloria Estefan. Directed by Wes Craven (PG, 110
minutes). Not many of us enjoy being lectured by dressed-down
Hollywood stars in gritty classroom situations. But the true story
of Roberta Guaspari, a music teacher in East Harlem and a single
mother surviving a nasty divorce, has been given a blunt,
no-nonsense tone that works. Ms. Streep gives a down-to-earth
performance that is sheer award bait. The story is inspirational
enough to take Ms. Guaspari from no job prospects to watching her
proud students play alongside Itzhak Perlman, Isaac Stern and other
violin stars. Not a bad reason for Craven to have sidelined the
claws and hatchets for a while (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `POKEMON: THE FIRST MOVIE,' with the voices of Veronica Taylor,
Philip Bartlett, Rachael Lillis, Eric Stuart, Addie Blaustein and
Ikue Otani. Directed by Kunihiko Yuyama (G, 90 minutes). Parents
don't have to know all 151 monsters to understand ``Pokemon: The
First Movie,'' but they can observe several in action, including
Pikachu, cutest of them all. The magic doesn't bridge the
generation gap; whatever makes ``Pokemon'' such a huge pop-culture
phenomenon is still a secret of the grammar school set, but the
film is energetic and the animation is fun to watch. The plot is
about a bioengineered Pokemon who lures young Pokemon trainers
(including 12-year-old Ash of the television series) into a
showdown. Characters spout pacifist profundities while pairs of
monsters punch each other silly (Anita Gates).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `PRINCESS MONONOKE,' with the voices of Billy Crudup, Claire
Danes, Billy Bob Thornton and Minnie Driver. Directed by Hayao
Miyazaki (PG-13, 133 minutes). A landmark feat of Japanese
animation from the acknowledged master of the genre. This
complicated, exotically beautiful epic features gods and demons
locked in battle for the future of the forest, and its visions are
breathtakingly rendered. But it is the film's stirring use of
nature, myth and Japanese history that makes it so special. Worth
seeing just for its Forest Spirit, which takes animal form by day
and roams the night as a diaphanous, Godzilla-like divinity. The
image of plants and flowers springing to life beneath his hooves is
ravishingly presented. Despite a superb blend of hand-drawn cels
and fluid, computer-generated animation, the film's look is
gratifyingly understated (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `RIDE WITH THE DEVIL,' starrang Skeet Ulrich, Tobey Maguire and
Jewel. Directed by Ang Lee (R, 134 minutes). This contemplative
Civil War epic, instead of concentrating on the major battles,
looks at the outskirts of the conflict _ the Kansas-Missouri border
_ where Confederate and Union guerrillas raid each other's
outposts. The dramatic high point is a re-creation of Quantrill's
Raid, in which a Confederate force swooped down on Lawrence, Kan.,
massacring 150 people. Maguire and Ulrich are childhood friends on
the Confederate side, and the pop star Jewel (in her movie debut)
is a young widow they both love. Even cooler in tone than ``The Ice
Storm,'' the movie is visually stunning and historically
provocative but dramatically flat (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `ROSETTA,' starring Emilie Dequenne. Directed by Luc and
Jean-Pierre Dardenne (R, 90 minutes). This grim quasi-documentary,
filmed with hand-held cameras (it's almost as jiggly as ``The Blair
Witch Project''), picked up the Palme d'Or (the top prize) at the
Cannes Film Festival earlier this year. Ms. Dequenne was also
chosen best actress for her portrayal of a miserable 17-year-old
Belgian girl living in a trailer camp with her alcoholic mother.
Her desperate quest for a job and what she calls a ``normal life''
leads her to betray her only friend, who works in a waffle stand,
by stealing his job. Unlike the Dardenne brothers' last film, ``La
Promesse,'' the movie's social realist angst feels contrived, and
its main character never fully comes to life (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `SLEEPY HOLLOW,' starring Johnny Depp, Christina Ricci, Miranda
Richardson, Michael Gambon, Jeffrey Jones, Michael Gough and
Christopher Walken. Written by Andrew Kevin Walker and directed by
Tim Burton (R, 110 minutes). This ornate visual fantasy, artfully
concocted using a palette that suggests nuclear winter, has little
to do with Washington Irving's story and everything to do with
Burton's macabre vision. Depp makes a dashing hero as the film's
shy detective, but the story (by the writer of ``Seven'' and
``Fight Club'') is determined to put the ick into Ichabod Crane. A
first-rate cast and extraordinary technical talents are
attention-getting here, but so is the film's penchant for sardonic
beheadings. It's possible to admire Burton immensely, for the
secret tenderness and rich imagination of his work, without wanting
to peer at the exposed brain stems of his characters (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE STRAIGHT STORY,' starring Richard Farnsworth and Sissy
Spacek. Directed by David Lynch (G, 110 minutes). As the least
likely filmmaker on the planet to pull off a G-rated miracle, Lynch
rises to the challenge with exhilarating vigor. It may not sound
like much, but this account of an old man making a long trip on a
riding lawn mower turns out to be a slow-moving, folksy-looking,
deeply spiritual film with the power to hold audiences in thrall.
And as Oscar may well note next spring, it would not have been
possible without Farnsworth's terse, no-nonsense honesty at its
heart. Lynch's famously unwholesome imagination crosses a new
frontier to explore simple virtues and natural beauty. The result:
a supremely improbable triumph (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TUMBLEWEEDS,' starring Janet McTeer and Kimberly Brown.
Directed by Gavin O'Connor (PG-13, 100 minutes). An astoundingly
vital performance by the British actress Janet McTeer makes this
small, beautifully acted slice of contemporary Americana a must-see
film. Ms. McTeer is Mary Jo Walker, a sexy, free-spirited woman
with four marriages behind her who travels across the country with
her 12-year-old daughter, Ava (Ms. Brown). Like few other films,
this one captures an intimately loving (though not conflict-free)
relationship between a parent and child without becoming
saccharine. The director plays Mary Jo's trucker boyfriend, who is
only the latest in a series of her romantic disasters (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WORLD IS NOT ENOUGH,' starring Pierce Brosnan, Sophie
Marceau, Dame Judi Dench, Robert Carlyle and Denise Richards.
Directed by Michael Apted (PG-13, 128 minutes). This director is
much admired for his ``Up'' series chronicling the lives of former
schoolchildren as they mature. And he has managed to make James
Bond grow up a little, too. Brosnan has grown much more comfortable
with the role of Bond, and most of the other characters are also
more interesting than might have been expected. Ms. Marceau slinks
memorably through the role of a treacherous oil heiress. Ms.
Richards seemed a lot smarter playing high school vixens than she
does as a brilliant scientist here. The itinerary roams from
Scotland to Central Asia. And Apted handles the action as well as
he does the talk (Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
