r l BC-TV-GOODYKOONTZ-AZR &LR;      11-25 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODYKOONTZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STORY OF 1 PROPHET WHO HAS PROSPERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   man walked up to you and claimed God had spoken to him in the
woods, you would probably shuffle away quickly before he handed you
a pamphlet.
</P>
<P>
   But when Joseph Smith made that claim in 1820, many people
called him a prophet. Many still do _ as membership in the Church
of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has risen to more than 10
million people in 160 countries.
</P>
<P>
   But it all started with a 14-year-old boy caught up in the
religious fervor sweeping early 19th-century America and wondering
which church he should join. Any Mormon knows the rest of the
story; anyone who watches ``American Prophet: The Story of Joseph
Smith'' will learn the bulk of it as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a story of faith and belief,'' Lee Groberg, who
directed the film, said from his home in Bountiful, Utah. ``I think
the LDS viewer will come away with a greater respect and a deeper
conviction of their own beliefs. The non-LDS (viewer) will simply
look at it and have a respect for the story. I don't know that it's
meant to sway anyone to call 1-800 and call your missionary.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor should it. ``American Prophet'' airs on public television,
after all. You're much more likely to be converted to the Mormon
faith by a nice young man in a white shirt and tie on a bicycle
than you are from watching this. It's doubtful non-believers would
sit through two hours of proselytizing anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Groberg, himself a Mormon, set out to document Smith the man,
not the Mormon faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he stands on his own,'' Groberg said. ``There were a
lot of prophets who came and went. There were a lot of religions
that started and died. His remained. I think that is a significant
piece of the story: What caused it to prosper?''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, according to ``American Prophet,'' the answer is Smith,
through his perseverance, personality and good, old-fashioned hard
work.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a man who stirred people up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a radical preacher of extreme ideas,'' Nathan O. Hatch,
provost of the University of Notre Dame, says in the film. And,
indeed, Groberg doesn't shy away from laying at Smith's feet some
of the responsibility for the extreme reactions of believers and
non-believers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the religious scholars point out, there are things that
Joseph Smith did and that the early Mormons did in their
zealousness that caused some of their own problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To someone outside the church, some of Smith's claims and
revelations sound a little odd and not just today. When someone
says an angel told him where to find plates of gold to translate,
it's going to raise some eyebrows, no matter what century you're
living in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people could point to scripture,'' Richard T. Hughes, a
historian, says in the film. ``Or they can point to their
interpretation of scripture. . . . Joseph said, `I spoke with God.
God spoke with me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The early church was something of a moving target as well, with
Smith changing its tenets often enough to frustrate even some of
his closest friends and followers.
</P>
<P>
   But to outsiders, Smith and his new church posed even bigger
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joseph breached one of the sacred lines in American political
culture of his time,'' historian Richard Lyman Bushman says in the
film. ``He joined the powers of church and state. He claimed to be
a prophet, to speak from God, to command men's consciences, their
understanding of the world. And at the same time, he liberally
accepted offices of mayor, leader of his city.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Americans, that combination of religious and political
power was just explosive. They could not abide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a Mormon, Groberg was, of course, familiar with Smith.
That familiarity meant a rethinking of how to tell his story so
that no assumed knowledge seeped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, as we shared the first draft of the script with
PBS for review, they sent back a number of comments,'' Groberg
said. ``PBS wrote back and said, `What happened to the golden
plates that you talk about in the show? Do you have them in a
museum? Are we going to see them in the show? We had to go back and
resolve that. We had to keep catching ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   (Note to non-Mormons: According to church history, the angel
Moroni retrieved them, so don't expect to see them in the film.)
</P>
<P>
   The film is curiously paced, with much time spent on Smith's
early days. But the section dealing with the end of his life seems
rushed. And while Groberg's intent to separate the man from the
religion is noble, at times they're too separate, leaving the
non-Mormon without the context he needs to understand Smith's
influence.
</P>
<P>
   But ``American Prophet'' does go a long way toward satisfying
one of PBS' goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their words, they said many people know something about
(Smith) or have heard of him,'' Groberg said. ``But nobody knows
anything about him really.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who watch, ``American Prophet'' will change that. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974 or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
