<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Nov. 26. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
CRUNCH (Phoenix) - Thanksgiving and Christmas/Hanukkah are close
together this year, and there's a push on for bigger expenditures
this New Year's, with the millennium. More and bigger holiday
parties. The regular stress and outlay of cash at this season are
even worse. We talk to folks and get some advice from experts on
how to handle the finances, so we're not paying for the season well
into the next millennium. BY KERRY FEHR-SNYDER. Story will move in
the ``F'' and ``L'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
APPEALS (Phoenix) - A ``plain error of fact'' committed by the U.S.
Supreme Court and compounded by a lower court has thrown the
handling of criminal appeals into chaos in Arizona and must be
corrected quickly, the state's top prosecutor contends. In a
request this month for a rare review by all 21 active judges of the
Ninth Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco, the state
Attorney General's Office is trying to undo a pair of decisions
that allow most criminal appeals either to bypass the state's
highest court altogether or to be filed in both state and federal
court, doubling the workload. By JON KAMMAN. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODYKOONTZ
</P>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Today, if a young man walked up to you and claimed
God had spoken to him in the woods, you would probably shuffle away
quickly before he handed you a pamphlet. But when Joseph Smith made
that claim in 1820, many people called him a prophet. Many still
do, as membership in the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints has risen to more than 10 million people in 160 countries.
By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
