<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-APPLES-CHARLESTON-ART     11-25 1566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-CHARLESTON-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLESTON'S SOUTHERN LEGACY AND NEW SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The 3rd take is a list of attractions.) (ART ADV: Photos,
NYT2 and NYT3, have been sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ You can't say it about many cities, but you
can certainly say it about this one: One man changed its destiny.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Joseph P. Riley Jr. He is Charleston's mayor. He
halted its long decline, which lasted for a hundred years after the
Civil War, turning it from a proud but rotting relic into a model
modern city. After 24 years on the job, in an era of pervasive
skepticism about politicians, he was elected to a seventh term on
Nov. 9 with 71 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Even the cynical cabbies believe in him. One old-timer told me,
``I'd bet my life that he's never stolen a nickel or cheated a
soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley has had help, of course: from a business community
galvanized into action when the 95-year-old Charleston Naval Base
was closed in 1996; from a devoted band of preservationists
determined to restore the beauties of antebellum Charleston; from
an unconventional police chief, Reuben Greenberg, a black Jew with
two degrees from Berkeley whose Deep South brand of tough love has
slashed the crime rate and forged better race relations; and from
Gian Carlo Menotti, who rejuvenated the city's cultural life when
he established an American version of his Spoleto festival here.
</P>
<P>
   Riley has also been helped by history. Charleston is steeped in
it, and tourists flock here to trace its footprints in the
jasmine-scented streets and aristocratic houses. They admire the
porches, called piazzas, positioned to catch ocean breezes, and the
Mediterranean interplay of light, sea and shade, and the narrow
gardens, full of boxwood, old roses and neat brick paths. A few may
recall the watchwords of the beloved Emily Whaley, whose
blossom-filled plot at 58 Church St. measures only 30 feet by 100
feet: ``Early to bed, early to rise, work like hell and
fertilize.''
</P>
<P>
   They visit the ruined Fort Sumter, toward which Confederate
gunners under the grandiloquently named Gen. Pierre Gustave Toutant
Beauregard directed the first shots of the Civil War on April 12,
1861. They sit in the box pews at St. Michael's Episcopal Church,
finished in 1761, where George Washington and Robert E. Lee both
came to pray. Its noble white steeple, a near replica of the one at
St. Martin's-in-the-Fields in London, may well have been designed
by the same architect, James Gibbs. They stroll past the Italianate
and Greek Revival mansions of the rice planters along the Battery,
the tourists do, and gaze out upon the point where, as the natives
like to say, the Ashley River meets the Cooper to form the Atlantic
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   While they are here, the visitors account for a third of
Charleston's economy. There is money in those old buildings, which
Charleston was once ``too poor to paint, too proud to whitewash,''
and in those oh-so-courtly Southern ways, which year after year win
Charleston the No. 1 position on a list of Most Mannerly Cities in
America compiled by Marjabelle Young Stewart, an etiquette expert.
</P>
<P>
   Wiser travelers come in spring and fall, for Spoleto and the
house and garden tours, avoiding the long, suffocating days of
summer. But Charleston seldom seems crowded or hurried, regardless
of season.
</P>
<P>
   Life ambles along with all the speed and urgency of a drawl.
This is a small city, centered on a narrow peninsula, with only
75,000 people, though the metropolitan area is several times that.
</P>
<P>
   The scale is human. The streets are clean, free of graffiti and
litter. You can stroll down Ropemaker's Lane or Price's Alley,
leaving the 20th century far behind, yet this is a real city, not a
museum like Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that at this point I should declare an interest, as
British politicians say. My wife's maiden name was Betsey Pinckney,
and she comes from the storied clan that more or less invented
Charleston. Two of her forebears signed the Constitution; one of
them, Charles Pinckney, later served as minister to Spain; the
other, Charles Cotesworth Pinckney, was named envoy to France and
ran unsuccessfully as the Federalist nominee for president (twice)
and vice president. Charles Cotesworth's brother, Thomas, served as
minister to England. All three fought in the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th-century Low Country elite was ``a vast cousinage,'' one
prominent historian has written, a hugely prosperous extended
family. In 1774 the per capita wealth of Charleston and the Low
Country was four times that of the Virginia plantations, six times
that of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   They say that Charlestonians are like the Japanese, in that they
eat rice and worship their ancestors. The Pinckney-tude of
Charleston can be a bit much. There are a Pinckney Street, Pinckney
Island and Castle Pinckney, and the graveyards are full of
Pinckneys. Betsey once rode in a carriage pulled by a horse named
Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
</P>
<P>
   But Eliza Lucas Pinckney won me over. Born in Antigua, the
daughter of a colonial governor, she married the first Charles
Pinckney in 1744. In short order she bore three children (including
Charles Cotesworth and Thomas), compiled one of the very first
colonial recipe books and took over the management of several large
plantations, where she taught many slaves to read and write. Most
important, she introduced the cultivation of indigo to the state.
It was a crop so valuable to the British textile industry for dyes
that it made South Carolina a favored child of the mother country.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the early settlers, the Pinckneys came from England
by way of Barbados. Others came directly from Britain and France.
These last were almost all Huguenots, or French Calvinists, and
their tradition lives on in Charleston names like Manigault and
Huger (pronounced you-GEE).
</P>
<P>
   The piazza, which on many houses functions as an outdoor room,
is an adaptation of a Barbadian architectural style; in this
particular form, it is found only in Charleston. St. James', an
Episcopal church that also draws on West Indian traditions,
survives in the northern suburb of Goose Creek, all but hidden in a
copse of trees. The pale pink stucco building, without a steeple,
has a dozen fine Palladian windows and, in a pediment over the main
door, a relief of a pelican nourishing its young, the symbol of the
missionary Society for the Propagation of the Gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Built about 1713, set in a walled graveyard overhung with live
oaks, the church still displays George I's coat of arms behind the
pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   The planters who lived around Goose Creek and along the Low
Country rivers maintained ties to Britain for generations. In 1715
Palladio's treatise on classical styles was first published in
England, and 30 years later John Drayton built a porticoed
plantation house on the Ashley whose Tuscan and Ionic columns come
directly from Palladio's pages.
</P>
<P>
   Drayton Hall stands alone among the great houses in its
neighborhood. It was spared by Sherman's soldiers because, it is
said, the owner had his slaves tell the federal troops that the
house was being used as a smallpox hospital. Never converted to
central heating or electric lights, and painted only twice, the
interior of the house retains its elaborate architectural details
and elegant plaster moldings and ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Boone Hall, with a famous half-mile allee of live oaks planted
in 1743, is a 1935 re-creation of the original. Cypress Gardens and
Magnolia Gardens, both laid out amid blackwater swamps, are set
alight by a riot of camellias and azaleas every spring. Medway
Plantation, on the Cooper, was built in 1705 and is probably the
oldest brick building in the state. It is privately owned and open
only for the garden tours.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Middleton Place that always lures us out of the city
on fine days. Its manor house is a ruin; only one small flanking
building survives, and it has been much altered. Never mind. It is
filled with family portraits by Benjamin West, valuable silver,
18th-century beds with posts carved to resemble rice stalks and
other furniture from the workshop of Thomas Elfe, Charleston's most
noted cabinetmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Bookshelves and tables hold rare first editions by Catesby and
Audubon, who came here to draw the ospreys and egrets that still
nest in local marshes. Audubon formed a friendship with Joel
Poinsett, an erudite Charleston-born diplomat, who brought the
Christmas plant named for him to this country from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Middleton began to plot his classical gardens in 1741.
They are anchored by a pair of lakes shaped like a butterfly's open
wings, which lie just below a series of scalloped terraces. On
another part of the plantation a flock of sheep grazes. A pathway
leads beneath arching camellia bushes that carpet it in pink in
early March. Everywhere there are stupendous trees _ gums,
magnolias, crape myrtles _ and a mighty oak, a marker on an Indian
trail before Columbus reached America, has a circumference of 30
feet and a spread of 145.
</P>
<P>
   It took 100 slaves 10 years to lay out the terraces, the canals
and the rest of the rigorously geometric design. To my mind they
created the greatest garden that we have from Colonial America.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Slavery and its legacy, white supremacy, hung over Charleston
like a pall for generations.
</P>
<P>
   The French author Simone de Beauvoir came here in 1947. She was
bewitched by the place, especially the Spanish moss, exulting in
her journal that ``it is the color of smoke, the color of amber and
twilight.'' But the plantations haunted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creating those private Edens, which are as extravagant as the
Alhambra,'' she wrote a few pages later, ``required the vast wealth
of planters and the hell of slavery; the delicate petals of the
azaleas and camellias are stained with blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1700 and 1775, the peak years of the slave trade, 40
percent of the Africans brought to America in chains passed through
Charleston. Ever since, blacks have formed a big portion of the
city's population.
</P>
<P>
   DuBose Heyward's 1925 novel, ``Porgy,'' transformed by George
Gershwin into the folk opera ``Porgy and Bess'' in 1935, portrayed
the lives of some of the poorest of them, who lived on Church
Street in the onetime slave dependencies of houses on Cabbage Row,
or Catfish Row, as Heyward renamed it. The city's blacks gave
another gift to Broadway, the kinetic dock workers' dance that was
transformed into the Charleston for ``Runnin' Wild,'' a 1923 hit.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, Charleston has moved well beyond its bleak days, and in
casting off the shroud of white supremacy it has gradually begun to
remember and to acknowledge the black role in its history. The
other half of the story is displayed for visitors in the slave
quarters at Boone Hall and the Aiken-Rhett House downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The College of Charleston's Avery Research Center delves into
the African-American past, maintaining collections of manuscripts
and papers, including the records of the 54th Massachusetts
Regiment, the black unit that mounted the heroic assault on Fort
Wagner depicted in the Civil War film ``Glory.'' That battle, in
which the 54th's commander, Robert Gould Shaw, lost his life, is
fully described at the wonderful Charleston Museum.
</P>
<P>
   But the process is just beginning. Important moments of black
history remain submerged. The plaque at the Emanuel African
Methodist Episcopal Church on Calhoun Street says simply, ``Founded
1818, closed 1822, reopened 1865.'' What lurks behind that simple
word ``closed''! The church was closed because it had been burned
down by a white mob in revenge for the actions of Denmark Vesey, a
parishioner who tried to foment a slave uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Riley told me that economic opportunity had provided the key to
the dramatic improvement in relations between the races in his
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make the table bigger,'' he said when we met in his
office, which was piled high with files, newspapers and official
documents. ``You don't tell some people that they have to leave.
We've made progress in housing, in police work, in guaranteeing the
full participation of all our citizens in the affairs of the city
council. But you can never relax. In a diverse society, there are
always a lot of opportunities for misunderstanding, so you have to
be sure that new bridges are built and old ones are maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley has pioneered ``scatter-site'' public housing in an effort
to combat the ghetto mentality. He has passed ordinances banning
T-shirt shops, neon and tour buses in the historic district and
hotels on the waterfront, lest the very element that brings
visitors to Charleston, its charm, be submerged in tourist
tattiness. He has built things that appeal to locals and visitors,
rich and poor, like a brand-new Waterfront Park, which helped to
revive a crumbling old port district, and a new minor-league
ballpark. On King Street an old movie theater has been turned into
a convention hall, a new Saks Fifth Avenue has opened and a bank
now houses a Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   What sets Riley apart from run-of-the-mill mayors is a genuine
passion for his work. He is _ dare we use the word in this cynical
era? _ a true visionary, and it is his vision of a city reborn that
has carried him and Charleston through nightmares like Hurricane
Hugo in 1989, which damaged 90 percent of the city's roofs and made
a shambles of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The closing of the naval base, Riley said soon after it
happened, ``was like death, because no one had ever imagined life
in Charleston without the Navy.'' The city's longtime congressman,
Mendel Rivers, had poured Pentagon dollars into the city for
decades; his slogan was, ``Rivers Delivers.'' But the city not only
survived the blow, it surged rapidly ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're way on the plus side by now,'' said Ben Cole, the
president of the Charleston Regional Development Alliance. ``We
lost about 22,500 jobs when the Navy left. Since then we've gained
around 35,000 new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance, founded in February 1995, brought capital
investments of more than $1.75 billion to the area in its first
three years of existence, and it has kept up that pace. Ninety new
companies have arrived, a third of them foreign, lured by the
climate, the mostly nonunion labor force and above all the booming
port.
</P>
<P>
   Charleston, quaint little Charleston, is now the largest
container port in the South and second only to New York on the east
coast. There are plans afoot to make it much bigger by building
port installations on Daniel Island, northeast of the city, but
that worries conservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the restoration of old Charleston continues apace. At
the moment scaffolding obscures the Market Hall, a little Doric
temple that stands at the head of the city's public market, and the
Fireproof Building, designed in 1826 by Robert Mills as a county
records office. A draftsman for Thomas Jefferson at Monticello,
Mills became South Carolina's greatest architect, building
courthouses and churches, including the First Baptist on Church
Street in Charleston, in a severe Classical Revival style. He later
designed the Treasury and the Washington Monument in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite of mine in the same style, though not by Mills, is
the Hibernian Hall on Meeting Street, a chaste white structure with
a gilded harp above the door, across from the Fireproof Building.
It was designed by Thomas U. Walter, who also went on to greater
architectural glory in Washington, designing the dome of the
Capitol. Since the years after the Civil War the hall has been the
site, on the third Thursday in January, of the annual St. Cecilia
Ball, Charleston's oldest, most exclusive social function.
</P>
<P>
   When they say ``exclusive'' in Charleston, they mean it. The
right to attend is inherited. A favorite local put-down, Betsey's
cousin Jane Hanahan told us, is to say of someone, ``He doesn't go
to the ball.'' To which Betsey's irreverent brother, Tom, replied,
``It's the only thing left, now that the House of Lords is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Portraits of the ancestors of today's ballgoers can be seen at
the Gibbes Museum of Art, whose collection includes important works
by Samuel F.B. Morse, Gilbert Stuart and Thomas Sully. The gem of
the collection is an unforgettable image of John C. Calhoun, the
ardent champion of states' rights, by Rembrandt Peale.
</P>
<P>
   But the real monuments to the men and women who built Charleston
are their houses, no fewer than 3,500 of them built before 1860.
Two that should not be missed are the Nathaniel Russell House, with
an oval staircase that vaults upward with no visible means of
support, and the Heyward-Washington House, whose pine floors and
cypress paneling date from 1772. Its unmatched collection of
Charleston furniture includes a chest-on-chest-on-chest, one of
only three in existence.
</P>
<P>
   When you have had your fill of houses, there are plays at the
Dock Street Theater, where the Charleston Stage Company presents
120 performances a year, and at the Footlight Players' intimate
240-seat house. The Charleston Symphony, for which Riley dreams of
building a proper hall, has attracted soloists of the caliber of
Itzhak Perlman and Sherrill Milnes.
</P>
<P>
   But it is at festival time that the city comes culturally alive.
Next year's Spoleto Festival, accompanied by its ``fringe,'' known
as Piccolo Spoletto, is scheduled for May 26 through June 11.
</P>
<P>
   In late September comes the Mojo Arts Festival, a celebration of
African-American and Caribbean art, with a rich array of jazz,
gospel and storytelling. Another part of Charleston's enthusiastic
rediscovery of itself.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of attractions, along with travel
information:
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY:
</P>
<P>
   Charleston Place, 130 Market St., (843) 724-8410. With a prime
location, two top-flight restaurants and an indoor-outdoor rooftop
pool, this 450-room sister ship of Venice's Cipriani easily tops
the roster of Charleston hotels. The bustling lobby, dominated by a
huge white Murano chandelier, is the city's crossroads. But too
many little things misfire: front-desk phones go unanswered after
25 rings, for example, and bathroom lights are placed so the
makeup-applier's or shaver's face is cast into shadow. Double room:
$175 to $395.
</P>
<P>
   Planters Inn, 112 N. Market St., (843) 722-2345. Nothing is more
characteristic of Charleston than the piazza or veranda overlooking
a brick-paved, palmetto-shaded courtyard. The Planters Inn has
both, plus high-ceilinged rooms, many with four-poster beds, and a
warmly welcoming attitude at the reception desk. The inn belongs to
the well-regarded Relais &AMP; Chateaux group, and it offers all the
modern electronic paraphernalia. Double room: $175 to $225.
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth Mansion, 149 Wentworth St., (843) 853-1886. It was
built by a cotton merchant in the Gilded Age and looks it. Crystal
chandeliers, tile and marble floors, carved paneling and
Tiffany-style windows give the place an air of tasteful opulence.
Each of the 21 rooms has a CD player, a big-screen television, a
fireplace and lots of antiques; many have Jacuzzis, and the suites
are seignorial. Sweeping views from the rooftop cupola. Double
room: $275 and $375.
</P>
<P>
   Harbour View Inn, 2 Vendue Range, (843) 853-8439. Despite the
mock-English spelling of its name, the Harbour View really does
have harbor views. Only 15 months old, it is just across the street
from the arching fountains of Charleston's handsome new Waterfront
Park. And the agreeably furnished rooms (52 of them) are rather
gently priced. Double room: $129 weekdays; $179 weekends.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO EAT:
</P>
<P>
   Hominy Grill, 207 Rutledge Ave., (843) 937-0930, is as
unpretentious as they come _ a former barbershop with clapboard
walls and butcher paper on the tables _ but everyone in town knows
how good and how fairly priced it is. One day not long ago, two
pickups and a Rolls-Royce were parked outside. Try shrimp and grits
or toasted banana bread for brunch, a pimento cheese sandwich with
arugula (!) for lunch, Southern fried chicken with spiced peach
sauce for dinner. Robert Stehling, the chef, earned his stripes in
Chapel Hill, N.C., from Bill Neal, a culinary legend in the New
South.
</P>
<P>
   Louis', 200 Meeting St., (843) 853-2550. Some people like Adam
Tihany's hip decor and some don't (this is Charleston, after all),
but nobody doesn't like Louis Osteen, a sweet-natured country boy
with a golden touch at the stove. He blends Europe with the South
in black-eyed pea cassoulet and sweetbreads braised with Madeira,
Vidalia onions and country ham. Other dishes speak pure Carolina,
like oyster stew with benne (sesame) seeds and pork porterhouse
with corn bread dressing. It is all meltingly delicious, and Mrs.
Osteen, Marlene, has chosen 350 pedigreed wines to go with it.
</P>
<P>
   Magnolias, 185 East Bay, (843) 577-7771. Magnolias is always
packed. With good reason; Donald Barickman, the clever chef,
produces a host of crowd-pleasers like Down South egg rolls,
stuffed with chicken, collard greens and spicy tasso ham, and fried
green tomato BLTs. Bright paintings, ancient pine floors and a mix
of locals and tourists enhance the casual mood.
</P>
<P>
   Peninsula Grill, in the Planters Inn (see above), (843)
723-0700. A cosmopolitan, subtly lighted room with velvet walls,
the grill delighted me with foie gras served with duck rillettes
and peach jam, and a veal chop with cheesy, peppery grits. It let
Betsey down with over-the-hill oysters and overbreaded sweetbreads.
But the smiling service, the superb wines and the memorable
five-layer coconut cake more than tipped the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly North of Broad, 192 East Bay Street, (843) 723-3424.
Like a lot of Charleston restaurants, SNOB, as it's known locally,
is a bit inconsistent. Saucing can be heavy-handed. But its mixed
grill of quail, homemade sausage and apple-smoked bacon over
cabbage is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Woodlands, 125 Parsons Rd., Summerville, (843) 875-2600. Ken
Vedrinski produces the closest thing to haute cuisine in the Low
Country at this inn 30 minutes from Charleston. The regional accent
is muted, with turbotin and skate displacing shrimps and crab meat.
But don't go on Sunday: Woodlands serves a limited menu, and no
wine at all, on the sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ATTRACTIONS:
</P>
<P>
   Charleston Museum, 360 Meeting St., (843) 722-2996. ``City Under
Siege: Charleston and the War Between the States,'' through Sept.
4. Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 1
to 5 p.m. Admission: $7; $4 for children.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbes Museum of Art, 135 Meeting St., (843) 722-2706.
``Treasures From the Collection: Three Centuries of Art in the
American South,'' ``Elizabeth O'Neill Verner: Charleston
Renaissance Artist,'' ``Beyond the Spanish Moss: The Contemporary
Perspective in Charleston'' and ``A Different Perspective:
20th-Century African American Artists in the Collection,'' all
through Aug. 27, 2000. ``Water: A Contemporary American View,''
through Dec. 12, 1999. Hours: Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m.
to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 5 p.m.. Admission: $6; $5 for the elderly,
students and members of the military; $3 for children.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Sumter, Sullivan's Island, South Carolina, (843) 883-3123.
Boats leave from the city marina on Lockwood Drive and from
Patriot's Point in the town of Mount Pleasant. For schedules: Fort
Sumter Tours, (843) 722-1691. Boat fee: $9.50; $4.75 for children
under 12; children under 6 free.
</P>
<P>
   Aiken-Rhett House, 48 Elizabeth St., (843) 723-1159. Audio tour
available. Opens at 10 a.m.; last tour at 4:15 p.m. Fee: $7;
combination ticket with Russell House, $12.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Russell House, 51 Meeting St., (843) 724-8481. Docent
tours available. Opens at 10 a.m.; last tour starts at 4:15 p.m.
Admission: $7; combination ticket with Aiken-Rhett House, $12.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward-Washington House, 87 Church St. (843) 722-0354. A branch
of the Charleston Museum and affiliated with the Joseph Manigault
House. Opens at 10 a.m.; last tour starts at 4:30 p.m. Admission:
$7; two-museum combination ticket, $12; three- museum combination
ticket, $18.
</P>
<P>
   Dock Street Theater, 135 Church St. (843) 720-3968. Dark this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Footlight Players Theater, 20 Queen Street, (843) 722-4487. N.
Richard Nash's ``The Rainmaker.'' Today and tomorrow at 8 p.m.;
Sunday at 3 p.m. Admission: $18; $13 for students and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Charleston Symphony. Next concert is Handel's ``Messiah'' at 8
p.m. on Dec. 4 at the Gaillard Auditorium, 77 Calhoun Street, (843)
577-7400. Admission: $10 to $35.
</P>
<P>
   Middleton Place, 4300 Ashley River Rd., West Ashley, (843)
556-6020. Daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $22; $7 for children.
</P>
<P>
   Drayton Hall, 3380 Ashley River Rd., (843) 766-0188. Self-guided
tours of the marsh are available. An African-American Focus Program
is held daily at 1:15 and 2:45 p.m. Hours: Opens at 9:30 a.m.;
tours begin at 10 and run every hour, with the last tour beginning
at 3 p.m. Admission: $8; $6, ages 12 to 18; $4, ages 6 to 11; free,
under 5.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE:
</P>
<P>
   By Air: Flights from New York City to Charleston are offered by
U.S. Airways, (800) 241-6522; Midway Airlines, (800) 446-4392;
Continental Airlines, (800) 525-0280; and Delta Airlines, (800)
221-1212. A 14-day advance purchase is $298 and a three-day advance
purchase is $398, leaving from Newark Airport. It is the same price
from Kennedy and La Guardia Airports, but travel is limited to
Saturdays and Sundays.
</P>
