<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-JUSTICE-REVIEW-NYT     11-25 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JUSTICE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EXECUTION OF JUSTICE': A PASSION FOR DOING RIGHT GOES HORRIBLY
WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (Eds.: Production notes appear at end of review. Time and channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were gay in the late 1970s and happened to live in San
Francisco, the city (or at least the Castro) probably felt a lot
like Camelot. Only nine years after Stonewall, the Greenwich
Village uprising that gave birth to the gay rights movement, shame
had turned into pride and lurking into strutting. Laws were being
changed, as were attitudes, and you were at the center of it all.
That's beautifully clear in the scene of an exuberant gay parade in
``Execution of Justice,'' with Harvey Milk campaigning in a
convertible on a sunny day, accompanied by the sounds of the
Village People singing ``YMCA.''
</P>
<P>
   But we all know how real-life Camelots end. Milk, who became San
Francisco's first openly gay city supervisor, was assassinated,
along with Mayor George Moscone, in November 1978. They were shot
to death in their offices in the middle of the day by Dan White,
who until a few days before had been one of Milk's fellow
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Execution of Justice,'' a Showtime film that has its premiere
on Sunday night, is the story of White, his trial and his tortured
psyche. The film doesn't solve the puzzle of what makes a man like
White commit such hideous acts, but it offers clues and
intelligent, effective drama.
</P>
<P>
   It would be interesting to know what method-acting associations,
if any, Tim Daly used to portray White. Daly, who has played much
sunnier roles (on the NBC comedy series ``Wings,'' for instance) in
the past, gives White a crazy, almost blank stare in all kinds of
situations, eyes that convey amorality in a frightening way; even
White's wife (Amy Van Nostrand) can sometimes see that.
</P>
<P>
   White's resume was straight-arrow all the way: former police
officer, former firefighter (and son of a firefighter), married
with children. Several scenes, though, reveal his volatile temper
and a twisted side. In one, he plays pool, drinks beer and
badmouths gay people (using several colorful epithets) with a
fellow firefighter. In another, he makes a speech against
``radicals, social deviants and incorrigibles.''
</P>
<P>
   In the most morally complex scene of all, set in a police
station, another police officer starts beating up a purse-snatcher.
While several other officers calmly watch and do nothing, White
stops the attack, demands that the guilty officer be punished and
quits his job in protest when he isn't. White's sense of doing
right (``I just wanted to do a good job for the city'') and the
belief that he is surrounded by immorality (``I've seen the city
going downhill'') sometimes had a basis in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Coyote is also wonderful as Milk. Both he and Stephen
Young, who plays Moscone, display the easy charm and infectious
energy of successful, good-looking politicians, and even though the
two characters clearly have their faults, their deaths are felt as
a great loss.
</P>
<P>
   The film's standout, however, is Khalil Kain, in a small but
splashy role as Sister Boom Boom, a sassy transvestite in a nun's
habit with lavender trim who serves as a sort of Greek chorus for
the proceedings. In Emily Mann's 1986 Broadway play, on which the
film is based, Sister Boom Boom was played by Wesley Snipes. The
other notable account of the story is Robert Epstein's film ``The
Times of Harvey Milk,'' which won the 1984 Oscar as best
documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The final outrage was that White was found guilty only of
voluntary manslaughter and served less than six years. The
so-called Twinkie defense, which contended that White had
temporarily lost his mind from eating too much junk food, was only
part of the reason; having old friends on the force didn't hurt
either. White was released from prison in January 1985 and
committed suicide eight months later.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EXECUTION OF JUSTICE'
</P>
<P>
   At 8 p.m., EST, Sunday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by Michael Butler and based on a story by Emily Mann.
Leon Ichaso, director; Jeff Freilich, producer; Claudio Chea Ariza,
director of photography; Tim Daly and Steve Burleigh executive
producers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Tim Daly (Dan White), Peter Coyote (Harvey Milk), Stephen
Young (George Moscone), Amy Van Nostrand (Mary Ann White), Khalil
Kain (Sister Boom Boom), Frank Pellegrino (Frank Falzon), Trulie
MacLeod (Eileen White), Shannon Hile (Diane Feinstein), Richard
Blackburn (Charlie White) and Lisa Rhoden (Denise).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 1829EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT     11-25 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE KIDS TO THE MOVIES: TOYS, POKEMON, 007, HEADLESS
HORSEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `TOY STORY 2'
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Tom Hanks, Tim Allen, Joan Cusack, Kelsey
Grammer, Don Rickles, Jim Varney, Wallace Shawn, John Morris, Annie
Potts, John Ratzenberger &QL; 
Directed by John Lasseter.
</P>
<P>
   Rated G _ 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   It's a busy morning in Andy's room, with the computer-animated
characters introduced four years ago in ``Toy Story'' hustling
around doing chores and noting postings of coming classes (``what
to do if part of you is swallowed''). But then disaster. About to
go off to day camp with Andy, Woody the cowhand gets one of his
shoulders ripped and is discarded on the top shelf. Next, Andy's
mom sweeps the room looking for old toys to put out for a yard
sale.
</P>
<P>
   After a dangerous mission to free their fellows about to be
bought, Woody and his friend the astronaut Buzz Lightyear grapple
with still another calamity. Woody is stolen by a fat toy dealer,
Big Al McWhiggin, who recognizes the cowpoke as the hero of an old
television show and wants to sell him and some other toy Westerners
to a museum in Japan. Trapped in Big Al's house, Woody meets the
others destined for display in a glass case: a cowgirl named Jessie
and a prospector, Stinky Pete, who hangs out in the box he was
packaged in.
</P>
<P>
   To spring Woody, Buzz rallies all the folk from Andy's room, a
gung-ho Buzz Lightyear knockoff and some hard-partying Barbie dolls
they run into in Big Al's superstore. But Pete and Jessie want
Woody to go to Japan with them because without him the deal is off
and they'll be put back in storage. Torn between old and new
friends, Woody ponders which way to turn.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: Playthings get some rough treatment, both physical and
emotional, but nothing is too disturbing for too long.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9: Strongly focused on standing by friends in times of
trouble, the film is also highly entertaining, which will delight
children all through this bracket, and is droll enough to engage
their parents, too, at least for as long as it needs to.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-11: By this age, a mixed reaction will set in, but most
viewers will enjoy themselves.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP: A rating milder than a PG-13 usually sounds the
evacuation, but perhaps not so loudly for a film that some
teen-agers will find more entertaining than they bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   `POKEMON: THE FIRST MOVIE'
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Veronica Taylor, Philip Bartlett, Rachael
Lillis, Eric Stuart, Addie Blaustein, Ikue Otani
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kunihiko Yuyama
</P>
<P>
   Rated G _ 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in another animated film that is undergoing multiple
viewings by many very small children and their flagging parents,
basic questions are posed about the ability of all creatures to get
along with their cloned likenesses.
</P>
<P>
   In a laboratory on New Island, evil scientists bioengineer
Mewtwo, a large, nasty flying cat who is about 10 times the size of
his model, Mew, the rarest of the 151 little monsters who
understand Pokemon. But Mewtwo, a clone who asks questions, demands
to know what his purpose is and, finding no good answer, finally
determines he has been made to rule the world. Chasing off the
scientists, the clone lures the best Pokemon monsters and trainers
to New Island for a showdown with all the cloned Pokemons he has
created.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he whips up a terrible storm, which threatens
all those at sea and on land. Staying true to their pacifistic
tendencies, the real Pokemon refuse to fight. Eventually the
message gets through to Mewtwo, who calls off the battle and calms
the waters.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: There is much violence, both real and threatened, but
it is presented in ways that are not disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: None.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-12: Supposedly teaching children about responsibility,
teamwork and obedience, the Pokemon craze has taken firm hold
within this age band, but without the brand name the film makes
very ordinary kiddie fare.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `THE WORLD IS NOT ENOUGH'
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Brosnan, Sophie Marceau, Robert Carlyle, Denise Richards,
Dame Judi Dench
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Apted
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13 _ 128 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Apologies for the commotion but that rocket-assisted speedboat
passing through a couple of crowded restaurants needs to reconnect
with the water if it's to cut off the streaking craft driven by the
raven-haired assassin. Yes, it's James Bond ( Brosnan) again, along
with Q (Desmond Llewelyn), the weapons designer who devised the
Bond boat; Q's new assistant, R (John Cleese), and M (Dame Judi),
who passes out assignments to the agent numbered 007.
</P>
<P>
   This time Bond's task is to protect Elektra (Ms. Marceau) from
Renard ( Carlyle), a lugubrious terrorist with a droopy eye. In the
recent past, Renard kidnapped Elektra, the daughter of an oil
baron, in a celebrated case and now threatens humanity with schemes
no one is quite sure of but could involve unauthorized use of
nuclear materials. Unfazed by the threat and convinced that no man,
including Bond, can resist her, Elektra tends to her pipeline by
the Caspian Sea, which, if she plays her politics right, should all
but corner the oil flow from the former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
   Renard's plans include a little bomb factory in the desert
staffed by Dr. Christmas Jones (Ms. Richards), a nuclear weapons
expert who looks good in shorts, has a sassy attitude and speaks
both Russian and MTV. Nevertheless, Elektra is the one to watch
here. Bond is captivated (up to a point), but then M is kidnapped
and Renard appears to have gained the upper hand in ways entirely
unanticipated.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: Expect the usual Bondfire: explosions, sprays of
gunfire, knifings, stranglings, falls from high places, suffocation
in tight places and much hand-to-hand combat. But there is little
blood, let alone any sense of reality, and whatever the damage,
everybody quickly moves on.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Bond, of course, goes to bed with almost every woman he
comes across. As with violence, however, sex is sanitized and
limited to decorative shots of pretty half-covered people lolling
about like mannequins. (And while product placement is inevitable,
one wishes there was at least something Bond could do without
flashing his wristwatch.)
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: None.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10: Some parents will take small children to this
film, and while no one will emerge lastingly traumatized, maybe
``Toy Story 2'' or another round of ``Pokemon'' would be more
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP: Bond movies play old for many teen-agers, who
like their action harder, hipper and undandified. But for all the
violence and sex, the film is about the most harmless parents can
hope for from the genre.
</P>
<P>
   `SLEEPY HOLLOW'
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Depp, Christina Ricci, Miranda Richardson, Michael
Gambon, Christopher Walken, Casper Van Dien
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tim Burton
</P>
<P>
   Rated R _ 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In Burton's darkly expressionistic reworking of the Washington
Irving story, Ichabod Crane (Depp), now a squeamish and rather
brainy investigator from New York City, is sent up the Hudson River
to the village of Sleepy Hollow, where select members of the shady
little citizenry have been getting their heads lopped off by, it is
said, a horseman who apparently was relieved of his own in the same
manner.
</P>
<P>
   Packing elaborate investigatory implements of his own invention,
young Crane no sooner pronounces that there could be no such thing
as a headless horseman than he is fleeing one at a full gallop. On
a great black steed, the headless fellow swings his sword with
precise efficiency, but he is mysteriously choosy about his
victims, who include women and children. In flashbacks to his
earlier existence, he has a head ( Walken's) and turns out to be a
Hessian soldier who lived and died by the sword during the
Revolutionary War 25 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the mercenary has returned from hell, but what he's
after and why remain unresolved. Steeling himself, Ichabod scraps
with the horseman occasionally and follows developments to a tree
of evil, stuffed with heads, from which the horseman emerges for
his murderous rides. Exposed neck stems are examined and a village
conspiracy is uncovered. Maybe the Hessian just wants his head
back.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: The beheadings are graphic and gory, with much time
spent peering into open neck stumps.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: There are brief semiclothed situations.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: This being 1799, whatever blasphemies there are
escape modern ears.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 14: As is always the case with R-rated films,
particularly ones by Burton, many young viewers will gain entry.
Obviously this isn't a film for young children.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14-17: The director of wildly imaginative films like
``Edward Scissorhands,'' Burton appeals to young audiences, and,
gore or no gore, this one is no exception. Parents can take a stand
or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
