<HEADLINE>
THE STARS OF OFF BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT9,10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Acting awards may be self-indulgent and tacky. But as
long as we're stuck with them, why shouldn't there be a
high-powered set of them for Off Broadway? Within the theater
industry, the Obies, administered by The Village Voice, have
considerable prestige, and the Drama Desks, parceled out to actors
and productions on Broadway and off, certainly merit mention in
Playbill bios.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no one has devised the widely recognizable acting prizes
that Off Broadway has so abundantly earned. I raise the issue (and
not for the first time) not so much to encourage the further
glitzing of New York's serious theater as to point out that when
one has a hankering for great performances, more often than not the
first places to look for satisfaction these days are the city's
smaller stages.
</P>
<P>
   Why this is so has a lot to do, of course, with the desperate
recession of the straight play on Broadway: Apart from John
Pielmeier's failed thriller, ``Voices in the Dark,'' no new
Broadway play will have opened this season until David Hirson's
``Wrong Mountain'' bows in January. No such drought parches Off
Broadway's landscape, however. There are, as always, a diverse and
exceptional array of performers originating roles in new works and
offering audiences that tantalizing drug of the theater: hope.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year you could share the theatrical wealth with
Viola Davis as the pitiable murderess in ``Everybody's Ruby'' at
the Joseph Papp Public Theater; Lynne Thigpen setting off the bulk
of the fireworks in ``Jar the Floor'' at Second Stage; Geoffrey
Nauffts, Jodie Markell and David Alan Basche as unsettled yuppies
in ``Snakebit'' for Naked Angels; and Darius de Haas as the young
man lost to heroin and heartbreak in the Music-Theater Group's
``Running Man.''
</P>
<P>
   They are only a sampling of who has come and gone of late
(although there is talk of an impending transfer of ``Jar the
Floor'' to Broadway). The pleasure of Off Broadway is that the door
to discovery is a revolving one; the next terrific turn by an actor
of note _ whether a familiar face or a complete unknown _ is only a
matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   As this is the season for giving, it's the ideal moment for a
few reminders of the ways in which seamless, stylish performances
are prizes unto themselves. Here, then, are a half-dozen examples
of why casting directors for new Off Broadway plays may be the
luckiest people in town.
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN SPINELLA: What a touching portrait of foolishness
Spinella provides in ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' the new musical
based on the famous Joyce short story, now at Playwrights Horizons
and moving to Broadway next month. On a stage overrun with fine
singing actors _ among them Blair Brown, Marni Nixon, Sally Ann
Howes and Emily Skinner _ Spinella sets his own ebullient pace as
Freddy Malins, the happy drunk who so good-naturedly puts his foot
in his mouth and leaves it there.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is given such a beautifully drawn character in this
musically rich if dramatically flawed evening; in thick mustache
and natty bow tie, Spinella, who won back-to-back Tonys in 1993 and
1994 for his work in the two parts of ``Angels in America,'' makes
of Freddy a poignant party clown.
</P>
<P>
   The actor, thankfully, avoids the pitfalls of ethnic stereotype.
His bar song, ``Three Jolly Pigeons,'' lifts the spirits as it
celebrates spirits. Yet his Freddy is also a vaguely tragic
character, drifting and remote, you intuit, whenever the music
isn't playing.
</P>
<P>
   LISA EMERY: In a crucial Act 2 encounter in ``Dinner With
Friends,'' Donald Margulies' splendid dissection of the anxiety
that exists side by side with the comfort of long-term
companionship, Ms. Emery's Karen sits down to lunch on a patio with
her best friend, Beth, who is recently divorced and newly ecstatic
over finding love again.
</P>
<P>
   The scene progresses amiably until Beth, played wonderfully by
Julie White, announces that she is going to marry again. The news
upsets Karen in ways that seem unreasonable, and Beth lets her have
it, accusing Karen of casting her as the perennial loser, of always
needing her to remain a basket case.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Ms. Emery process the information at the Variety Arts
Theater is like peering into the back of a television set: You
marvel at the sophisticated circuitry. Ms. Emery's Karen is a fuse
that never burns completely down in ``Dinner With Friends,'' and
you are thankful for that. There is the sense in her performance of
a fury that is better kept in check, and the thrill of her work
here is that the danger of it exploding is ever present.
</P>
<P>
   MARK MCKINNEY: Daffy plays can go skin-crawlingly awry in the
wrong hands. In the right ones, they're lighter than lemon
meringue. And no one in the seriously loopy ``Fuddy Meers'' is
righter or lighter than McKinney, who is emerging as one of the
top-flight comic actors on the New York stage.
</P>
<P>
   You may know his face from television, mostly squeezed into the
wee hours: He performed for many years with the all-male Canadian
comedy troupe ``Kids in the Hall.'' His Spanish ambassador was the
funniest player in the Roundabout's ``Flea in Her Ear'' a couple of
years back, and his Millet, the dimwitted master of the sock puppet
in David Lindsay-Abaire's hilarious new seven-character play on
Stage II at the Manhattan Theater Club, is a goofball whom any fan
of ``The Three Stooges'' can love.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Fuddy Meers,'' the puppet, Hinky Binky, which looks like a
golf club cover with hands, is Millet's alter ego. Think of a
Muppet with the mouth of Andrew Dice Clay, and you're in Hinky
Binky's ballpark. Playing Millet and the puppet off each other,
McKinney is a regular riot. One-man shows in New York have played
to acclaim with a lot less going for them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   LINDA EMOND: Ms. Emond is one of those heroes of the theater who
seem incapable of anything but excellence. In ``An Experiment With
an Air Pump'' on the Manhattan Theater Club's main stage, she
contributes yet another deeply intelligent and fully rounded
performance to a growing list of personal successes, in shows like
``The Dying Gaul,'' ``Baby Anger'' and ``1776.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast of Shelagh Stephenson's ``Experiment,'' which deals
with the price of progress in two eras 200 years apart, is
uniformly good. (Daniel Gerroll and Seana Kofoed are among the
other standouts.) Ms. Emond, though, provides an extra level of
satisfaction in the difficult task of doubling in the roles of two
women _ one a frustrated wife in 1799, the other an ambitious
geneticist in 1999 _ who offer a concise history lesson in the
changing role of women across the ages.
</P>
<P>
   Her introductory moments as the geneticist are some of her best.
Called upon to reveal the character's passion for science, Ms.
Emond takes us through a study of the 18th-century painting that
gives the play its title. As related by the actress, it's a lovely,
inviting prologue that offers immediate access to the interlocking
themes of Ms. Stephenson's time-traveling play.
</P>
<P>
   SEAN MARTIN HINGSTON:
</P>
<P>
   Everyone makes a fuss about the Girl in the Yellow Dress. But
what about the Guy in the Hairnet? Hingston is one of only two
members of the 22-person ensemble who appears in all three of the
dance plays that make up ``Contact,'' the hit evening of
dance-driven narrative at the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater (and moving
to the Beaumont in March).
</P>
<P>
   Can you spot him in all three? In the first, ``Swinging,'' a
teasing curtain-raiser inspired by an 18th-century painting, ``The
Swing,'' Hingston is the hunky, poker-faced servant, pushing a
sexually available young maid on a swing at her afternoon tryst
with another man. In the third piece, ``Contact,'' he plays one of
the virile young swing dancers rejected again and again by the
woman in yellow (Deborah Yates).
</P>
<P>
   The inside joke is apparent in the second piece, ``Did You
Move?'' in which Hingston is disguised as a cretinous restaurant
employee, in glasses and hairnet, dragging Italian foodstuffs
across the floor of the Queens restaurant in which Karen Ziemba
dances her whimsical dream ballet. The gamut he runs in
``Contact,'' from desirable to repulsive, is in both choreographic
and dramatic terms, a leap of imagination.
</P>
<P>
   PAULA PIZZI: Ms. Pizzi has a slightly mysterious accent: It
sounds vaguely Mediterranean. Her character's name, Susie Monahan,
sheds no light on her origins. But there's nothing the least bit
inauthentic about her performance as the empathetic nurse in
``Wit,'' the Pulitzer Prize-winning and astonishingly long-running
play at the Union Square Theater about a poetry professor's
intellectual, emotional and terminal struggle with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   If it is surprising that a play that deals so realistically with
illness has developed a loyal following _ any drama that runs more
than a year in New York has to qualify as a minor miracle _ the
work of actors like Ms. Pizzi goes some way in explaining why. Her
rendering of a nurse who ministers as much to the person as to the
disease is the playwright Margaret Edson's sole acknowledgment here
of the medical world's ability to feel as well as heal.
</P>
<P>
   The director Derek Anson Jones could not have cast the role with
a more profound sense of where the play's conscience lies. Ms.
Pizzi's Susie is a lamb until her patient requires a tiger, and it
is when this actress crosses over to fierceness in the climactic
scene that ``Wit'' gives full vent to the outrages against the soul
that some doctors may perpetrate in the name of fixing the body.
</P>
<P>
   Where and When They're Playing
</P>
<P>
   Here are the Off Broadway shows discussed above:
</P>
<P>
   `AN EXPERIMENT WITH AN AIR PUMP.' Manhattan Theater Club, 131 W.
55th St., (212) 581-1212. Tuesdays through Fridays at 8 p.m.;
Saturdays at 2:30 and 8 p.m.; Sundays at 2:30 and 7 p.m. Tickets:
$50.
</P>
<P>
   `CONTACT.' Newhouse, Lincoln Center, (212) 239-6200. Tuesdays,
Thursdays and Fridays at 8 p.m.; Wednesdays and Saturdays at 2 and
8 p.m.; Sundays at 3. Tickets: $55 and $80; very limited.
</P>
<P>
   `FUDDY MEERS.' Manhattan Theater Club, 131 W. 55th St., (212)
581-1212. Tuesdays through Fridays at 7:30 p.m.; Saturdays and
Sundays at 3 and 7:30 p.m.; Tickets: $40.
</P>
<P>
   `JAMES JOYCE'S `THE DEAD.'' Playwrights Horizons, 416 W. 42nd
St., (212) 279-4200. Special matinee Friday at 3 p.m.; Tuesdays
through Fridays at 8 p.m.; Saturdays at 3 and 8 p.m.; Sundays at 3
and 7 p.m. Tickets: $55; very limited.
</P>
<P>
   `DINNER WITH FRIENDS.' Variety Arts, 110 Third Ave., at 13th
Street, East Village, (212) 239-6200. Special matinee Friday at 3
p.m.; Tuesdays through Fridays at 8 p.m.; Saturdays at 3 and 8
p.m.; Sundays at 3 and 7:30 p.m. Tickets: $30 and $55.
</P>
<P>
   `WIT.' Union Square, 100 E. 17th St., (212) 505-0700. Special
matinee Friday at 3 p.m.; Tuesdays, Thursdays and Fridays at 8
p.m.; Wednesdays and Saturdays at 3 and 8 p.m.; Sundays at 3 p.m.
Tickets: $35 and $49.50.
</P>
