<HEADLINE>
ON STAGE AND OFF: SETBACK FOR SONDHEIM; TWO FOR MAE WEST; IRISH
MOTHER LODE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Confirming widely held suspicions, the producers of
``Wise Guys,'' the new musical by Stephen Sondheim, said this week
that the show would not transfer to Broadway in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came less than a week after the completion of a
monthlong ``workshop presentation'' at the New York Theater
Workshop, where the creative team, including Sondheim and the
director, Sam Mendes, had put together a rough version of the
musical.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation, which was seen by the workshop's subscribers
and most of the city's theatrical elite, apparently confirmed
producers' sense that the musical needed more work before being
offered to an uptown audience. The show had tentatively been
scheduled to open on Broadway in April; sets had been designed and
a theater promised.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond confirming the postponement, neither the creative team
nor the producers would comment on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wise Guys'' was not open to critics, but several producers who
saw it said the score showed many of the hallmarks of Sondheim's
career, including clever, ironic lyrics and complex, filigreed
melodies. What was lacking, they said, was a cohesive dramatic
vision of how and why the story should be told.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem at the center was `Why are these people
interesting?''' one producer said.
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim first came upon the story behind ``Wise Guys'' in 1952
but only began to work on the piece in earnest in 1995. The musical
follows the lives of Wilson and Addison Mizner, real-life brothers
whose exploits in con games and Florida real estate, respectively,
earned them minor celebrity status in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Lane and Victor Garber starred as Wilson and Addison, and
there were more than a dozen new songs by Sondheim and a book by
the playwright John Weidman, who collaborated with Sondheim on
``Pacific Overtures'' (1976) and ``Assassins'' (1991).
</P>
<P>
   The show had a reading last spring before embarking on its
unconventional stint at the workshop in late October. Early
presentations included only the first act while Sondheim and
Weidman worked to complete the show. Although strides were made,
production members said that by mid-November it became evident that
the piece wasn't ready for Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders said the issue of dramatic style was also present from
the early days of the workshop, with Sondheim and Weidman
preferring a lighter, more vaudevillian feel for the piece, while
Mendes and others favored a more substantial narrative. Weidman's
book was also battled over, though production members said the
artistic differences did not blow up into fights, firings or bad
blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were never any raised voices,'' said one production
member. ``The furrowed brows were people trying to work things
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step is an open question. Mendes has offered to take
the production to Donmar Warehouse in London, where he is the
artistic director. Another director or an additional writer may be
considered, and more work on the book and score is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several people in the audience said there were signs of
real, combustible dramatic life in the last week of the
presentation, when the whole piece was on its feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an enormous pity,'' one member of the production
said, ``if the world didn't get a chance to see this show again.''
</P>
<P>
   Two for Mae West
</P>
<P>
   Mae West just loved quipping _ especially on twos. ``It takes
two to get one in trouble,'' she used to say or be quoted as
saying. ``Between two evils,'' she'd testify, ``I always pick the
one I never tried before.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's appropriate that next month, West and her fabulous
vocabulary will come to life in two productions. First up is her
rarely seen play, ``Sex,'' in which West, not surprisingly,
chronicles the life of a good-time girl. The play, which West wrote
under the pseudonym Jane Mast, got off to a somewhat notorious
start and was not particularly loved when it opened in April 1926
at Daly's 63rd Street Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``A crude, inept play,'' wrote a displeased Brooks Atkinson in
The New York Times in a different era, adding breathlessly that its
``torrid love scene'' had sent ``several couples out into the
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers this time around, the Hourglass Group, have jazzed
up the script with original music after negotiating for three years
with West's estate to stage the first revival of the piece in New
York City. It begins Dec. 9 at the Gershwin Hotel on East 27th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 11, meanwhile, performances begin at New York Theater
Workshop for ``Dirty Blonde'' by Claudia Shear. Set in modern-day
New York, the play follows two fanatical fans on the trail of
West's legacy. All of which is enough to throw in one last apercu
from West: ``Virtue has its own reward, but has no sale at the box
office.''
</P>
<P>
   An Irish Mother Lode
</P>
<P>
   Word this week that Gabriel Byrne would make his U.S. stage
debut in Eugene O'Neill's ``Moon for the Misbegotten'' at the
Walter Kerr Theater in March makes him just the latest prominent
Irish actor to make his way to Broadway from the humble stages of
the Project Theater.
</P>
<P>
   An introduction may be necessary. The Project Theater, formally
known as the Project Arts Center, is the oldest alternative arts
center in Ireland, if one of its least known outside Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in an old printing works in the hip Temple Bar section of
town, the Project has nurtured an esteemed list of actors,
including Colm Meaney, Liam Neeson and Stephen Rea, who performed
there alongside Byrne in the early 1980s. Other alumni include the
filmmakers Neil Jordan and Jim Sheridan, whose brother Peter
Sheridan once helped run the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne remembers it thus: ``It was about the size of a
medium-size garage. You could fit maybe four or five cars in it. Or
60 or 70 people. We did contemporaries and classics and revivals,
everything. And none of us knew anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in its 33rd year, the Project is about to give up its old
home for a $5.2 million new building with two theaters and a
gallery. ``They've dickied it up nice,'' Byrne said, ``but I'll
remember its former beauty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
