<HEADLINE>
COPPOLA LOOKING FOR ATTENTION  
 NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS  
 BEST-SELLERS SHOW GROWING STRENGTH OF DVD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AN `AUDITION' FOR COPPOLA: Francis Ford Coppola said he hoped
the DVD of his film ``Apocalypse Now,'' released this week by
Paramount, makes a good impression. Not that the director feels in
need of critical stroking, but he hopes the production work on the
disc catches attention because it was performed by the DVD
laboratory he has started at American Zoetrope, his film company in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The lab transfers films to disc, and Coppola is offering one of
his own as an example of the kind of work Zoetrope does, both for
his films and the work of others. ```Apocalypse' was kind of an
audition for us to determine if we can do our other things as
well,'' he said. ``I'm hoping they'll allow us to do the
`Godfather' films.'' Like ``Apocalypse Now,'' those three movies
are also owned by Paramount, which, like other studios, distributes
the videos but farms out the technical transfer work to others.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola wants studios and filmmakers to engage Zoetrope for the
process called ``authoring,'' or the analysis of a movie to
determine how digital information can be added or deleted in each
scene to make it the strongest for the home screen. If a scene has
an empty spot or two, some of its information might be shifted to
strengthen busier areas of the scene. ``It's a psychological and
artistic decision on where to spend your little digital pennies,''
Coppola said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are a lot of pennies to spend on a DVD, which
has oceans of space. That's true overall, he said, but not
necessarily within particular scenes that may need different
allocation. ``So we say let's spend them here because that's where
the filmmaker wants the beauty or the luster or the detail to be.''
</P>
<P>
   While Coppola prefers the theater screen, video is a reality.
``Of all the people who see your work, 90 percent of them will see
it on some sort of home electronics video medium,'' he said. ``With
these new sound systems and plasma screens, little by little the
home experience is edging up to a more theatrical-style
exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers, he said, are invited to go to Zoetrope and take part
in the transfer of their films. ``I want a hand in my own films, so
that's how this happened,'' he said. Typically, he added, directors
don't get involved. Such was the case when his film ``Bram Stoker's
Dracula'' (1992) was transferred in the early days of DVD. ``No one
called me and said, `Hey, take a look at this master,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At American Zoetrope, the emphasis is on the transfer, not on
the extra features that crowd other top-of-the-line discs. ``The
master is vital,'' Coppola said. ``You have to get it right because
that's the way it will be passed along.'' On the disc of
``Apocalypse Now'' there are few extras and only a short director's
commentary, in which Coppola explains why he rejected an alternate
ending to the film.
</P>
<P>
   A full commentary was never his intention. ``I would have wanted
to go back to the earliest cut,'' he said, meaning a longer version
that hadn't been through postproduction and therefore hadn't been
mixed or scored. ``If we had gone to that length, it would have
been too much time and money,'' he said. ``It tends to be like the
string on your socks.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   A MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM
</P>
<P>
   1999. Fox. $104.16. 116 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Pot luck Shakespeare being the thing, Michael Hoffman's film
transports humans and fairies to Tuscany, where everybody runs and
bicycles around the forest in romantic exasperation. Forbidden to
wed, Hermia (Anna Friel) and Lysander (Dominic West) are pursued by
Helena (Calista Flockhart) and Demetrius (Christian Bale). Having
problems with Titania (Michelle Pfeiffer), the forest king Oberon
(Rupert Everett) has the horned sprite Puck (Stanley Tucci) mix up
a little something to tamper with everybody's affections. ``But,''
Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``there's no magic in the
potion to banish the film's awkwardness or make it more than a
string of intermittent acting highlights.''
</P>
<P>
   WILD WILD WEST
</P>
<P>
   1999. Warner. $22.96; DVD, $24.98. 105 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   West is the U.S. marshal James West (Will Smith), who is
dispatched by President Ulysses S. Grant to apprehend the
mechanical genius and master fiend Dr. Arliss Loveless (Kenneth
Branagh). On his way to Utah, West teams with Artemus Gordon (Kevin
Kline), who rides in his lavish railroad car knitting bulletproof
vests. Having lost his body from the waist down, Loveless propels
himself around in a steam-powered wheelchair and commands a
gigantic mechanical spider. Unfortunately, though, Barry
Sonnenfeld's film ``leaves reality so far behind that its
storytelling would be arbitrary even by comic-book standards''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   THE CASTLE
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16. 84 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   The dwelling of the title may be a dilapidated eyesore built on
toxic landfill, but Darryl Kerrigan (Michael Caton), a
happy-go-lucky Australian tow-truck driver, fights to save his home
from demolition. A sentimentalized version of a John Waters family,
the wacky Kerrigans _ Darryl, his wife and four children _ revel in
the sheer tackiness of the place, which is a veritable palace
compared to his summer retreat under high-voltage lines by a grim
little lake. ``If `The Castle' is essentially a one-joke movie, the
sheer giddy stamina with which it insists on the Kerrigans' joie de
vivre keeps it afloat'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   THE LOVE LETTER
</P>
<P>
   1999. Dreamworks. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 88 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   An attractive divorced woman in her 40s (Kate Capshaw) finds a
mysterious love letter, addressed to no one, tucked in her mail.
Her erotic imagination in overdrive, she imagines it has been sent
by a 20-year-old college student (Tom Everett Scott), whom she
lures into a passionate affair. But then a nice and more
age-appropriate suitor (Tom Selleck) begins hanging around. What's
not so wonderful about this slender wisp of a movie is its ``bland
dialogue and dull sitcom acting'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BEST SELLERS
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of four Disney animated titles _ ``Mulan,'' ``101
Dalmatians,'' ``Hercules'' and ``Pinocchio'' _ on DVD best-seller
lists signals the disc's growing strength. Here are some other
films that are best sellers and best renters on both DVD and
videocassette.
</P>
<P>
   BIG DADDY: A fine specimen of belching movie manhood, a highway
toll taker named Sonny (Adam Sandler) finds himself more or less
permanently responsible for a 6-year-old boy. 1999. Columbia
Tri-Star. $21.96, VHS; $24.95, DVD. 95 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   THE BLAIR WITCH PROJECT: Definitely the camping trip of the
summer, Daniel Myrick and Eduardo Sanchez's pseudo-documentary
loses three film students in the Maryland woods. 1999. Artisan.
$22.98, VHS; $24.95, DVD. 87 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   JACK FROST: Killed in a car crash, a Colorado rock musician
(Michael Keaton) returns to his wife (Kelly Preston) and son
(Joseph Cross), only this time he's a snowman. 1998. Warner.
$19.96, VHS; $24.98, DVD. 95 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE: After 60 years in the big house together, Ray (Eddie
Murphy) and Claude (Martin Lawrence) are still trying to endure
each other. 1999. Universal. $107.37, VHS; $29.98, DVD. 100
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON ROAD: A professor in urban terrorism (Jeff Bridges)
finds that his neighbors (Tim Robbins and Joan Cusack) practice
what he preaches in the classroom. 1999. Columbia Tri-Star.
$107.37, VHS; $24.95, DVD. 119 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   NOTTING HILL: There's no twisty concept here: Julia Roberts (as
a major American movie star) browses in a bookshop run by Hugh
Grant (as a gawky, charming English fellow). 1999. Universal.
$107.37, VHS; $29.98, DVD. 123 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
</TEXT>
