<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      11-25 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONE SPECIAL NIGHT': ANDREWS IS FLINTY AND GARNER IS STUBBORN.
PERFECT. 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``One Special Night,'' the film that reunites Julie Andrews and
James Garner, lives up to its title. These dependable performers
can still generate enough sparks to warm two hours on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Time (and other interventions) may have rearranged their
familiar faces a little, but these actors can slip so easily into
their expected personas _ she's a bit too flinty for her own good;
he's a bit too pigheaded for his _ that you'll be charmed.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has wisely found the stars a script about opposites
attracting, one that subtly nudges memories of the pair's two
movies, ``The Americanization of Emily'' in 1964 and
``Victor/Victoria'' in 1982. This film cannot stack up to those,
and it doesn't try to. But it does offer a sweet tale of autumnal
romance that your heart will believe. (Give your head the night
off.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie is winningly directed by Roger Young. The script, by
Nancy Silvers (which opens up the play ``A Winter Visitor'' by Jan
Hartman), begins on a frosty Thanksgiving in a picturesque town
that's covered with snow and Christmas wreaths. Ms. Andrews plays
Dr. Catherine Howard, a pediatric cardiologist still grieving for
her husband, who died a year before. Garner is Robert Woodward, a
building contractor whose wife, suffering from Alzheimer's, can no
longer recognize him.
</P>
<P>
   They meet at a hospice where they are both seeking connections
to the past, the place where Catherine's husband died and Robert's
wife is dying. A whopping snowstorm kicks up, and Robert can't get
a cab home.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine considers offering him a lift, then warns herself,
``Don't do this.'' She rejects her own advice, of course, and after
telling her boorishly that she's pretty dumb to be driving a Jaguar
in the snow, he accepts her offer. He doesn't like the way she
drives or the classical music on her radio. She doesn't like his
chauvinist attitude. When they skid off the road and get stuck in a
snow bank, he orders her to wait in the car. She fires back: ``You
go hunt and gather. I'll knit something for the harvest.''
</P>
<P>
   What luck! They find a comfy, well-equipped and unoccupied cabin
in which they can wait out the night by the fire, swap life stories
and discover that they have nothing in common but a primal need for
human contact.
</P>
<P>
   She confesses her regret at never having children. He reminds
her how many young lives she has saved. He confesses his heartbreak
that his wife has forgotten him. Catherine says, ``In her soul a
woman never forgets a man who has occupied her life for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   In their isolation, they develop a bond, slim but strong. You
can see it form in their eyes, hear it in their changing tones of
voice. These scenes, with just Ms. Andrews and Garner on screen,
are the film's generous payoff.
</P>
<P>
   There is more to the movie, but, happily, not too much more.
Subplots focus on Robert's dippy daughters (one of whom is
extremely pregnant), his whiny son-in-law and his
greeting-card-cute grandson. Yes, the whole enterprise is more than
a bit manipulative. (Toward the end, that plaintive saxophone solo
of ``Have Yourself a Merry Little Christmas'' qualifies as cruel
and unusual punishment.) But the flaws are easy to overlook.
</P>
<P>
   There must be people who have no fond memories of Ms. Andrews,
Garner or various mooshy-hearted holiday films, and those who do
not believe in the redeeming power of love. They are advised to
keep the clicker handy. Everybody else, put your feet up and relax
by the fire.
</P>
<P>
   RICKY MARTIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Need a bit of a workout after all that turkey and whatnot? Well,
here's an idea. Watch Ricky Martin Friday night, and try to do
everything he does. When he jumps, you jump. When he wiggles, you
wiggle. Or you can sit down. Either way, you may have fun, although
you probably won't have as much fun as he seems to be having.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know that Martin is one of the hottest pop stars in
the world, where have you been?
</P>
<P>
   In Friday night's hour, he sings some of his familiar hits _
``Livin' la Vida Loca,'' ``She's All I Ever Had,'' ``Maria,''
``Shake Your Bon-Bon'' _ before a deliriously happy outdoor crowd
at Liberty State Park in Jersey City, with the Manhattan skyline as
a backdrop. For one medley Martin, who proudly extols his Puerto
Rican heritage, is joined by two Latin music legends, Carlos
Santana and Jose Feliciano.
</P>
<P>
   The show is slickly packaged, with lots of changing camera
angles and a stage full of lithe bon-bon-shaking dancers. But
viewers who are used to Martin's dynamic videos may find the
proceedings a bit static. His boyish comments about how thrilled he
is with his success come across as a bit too gee-whiz for an
international icon.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his evident delight is hard to resist. And even if you
are sitting down, when he smiles, you smile.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ONE SPECIAL NIGHT'
</P>
<P>
   At 9 p.m. Sunday on CBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written by Nancy Silvers and directed by Roger Young and based
on the play by Jan Hartman. Gary L. Pudney, co-executive producer;
Mark Bacino, producer; Gary Dufaux, director of photography. Music
by Ed Kalnins. Produced by Green/Epstein Productions. Jim Green and
Allen Epstein, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Julie Andrews (Dr. Catherine Howard), James Garner (Robert
Woodward), Patricia Charbonneau (Lori Woodward), Gary Plaxton (Dr.
William Michaels), Daniel Magder (Michael), Stacy Grant (Jaclyn),
Kim Roberts (Nurse Sara) and Stewart Bick (Jeff Campbell). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `RICKY MARTIN'
</P>
<P>
   At 8 p.m. Friday on CBS
</P>
</TEXT>
