<HEADER>
A1418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     11-25 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN LEWIS: `EVOLUTION' 
</HEADLINE>
   By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are some statements that can't be made in youth, and
``Evolution'' (Atlantic), the new solo piano album from John Lewis,
the former Modern Jazz Quartet pianist, is one of them.
``Evolution,'' programmed with jazz standards and some of Lewis'
compositions, captures the burned-off essence of his style _ which
is full of straightforward elements, major harmonies and two-note
chords _ in a context of shifting rhythm. The album was recorded in
a concert hall without an audience, a production technique that
favors his light touch and his even legato. It's a good album for
the stillness of winter.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has applied as much thought to the arrangement of these
songs as he would if he were playing with a group, and then made a
music that's utterly at peace with itself.
</P>
<P>
   A little bit after the model of Baroque preludes, he introduces
a concise melodic or rhythmic motif at the beginning of each track,
then he brings that motif to bear on the tunes and improvisations
that follow. When he becomes expansive, it feels like a
well-considered choice: there's a 32-bar stretch in his performance
of ``September Song'' that lifts up out of the quiet, wintry
surroundings; suddenly he goes into four-four time, uses strides
and accents, moves around thicker chords, plays blues figures that
try to bend keyboard notes. And then the music returns to serenity,
the album's overriding quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
