<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS DEAD OR MISSING IN FERRY DISASTER OFF CHINESE COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ At least 119 people are dead and more than 150 missing
after a ferry in stormy seas burned and broke apart off China's
northeastern coast, official news media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday night, according to differing accounts from the
shipping company and the New China News Agency, either 22 or 36
survivors had been found from the ship, which that had been
carrying 312 passengers and crew members.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-foot waves and freezing temperatures hampered the rescue
effort near the port city of Yantai, in Shandong province. A
helicopter, dozens of ships and thousands of soldiers and residents
along the shoreline joined in the search for survivors from the
wreck, which occurred about one-and-a-half miles offshore, the news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The ship, which belonged to the Yanda Ferry Company in Shandong,
left Yantai on Wednesday afternoon for what is normally a
seven-to-eight-hour journey 100 miles north to the city of Dalian.
</P>
<P>
   It was forced to turn back because of the extreme conditions,
but then around 4:30 p.m. Wednesday, flames were discovered on the
second deck, and the ship sent out a distress signal, the news
agency said. The wind and waves prevented other ships from
immediately approaching.
</P>
<P>
   Some four hours later, apparently engulfed by fire, the ship
began drifting. That evening it apparently started to break up, and
at least parts of it sank, according to the New China News Agency.
</P>
<P>
   One survivor, a 28-year-old man, told the French news agency
Agence France-Presse that around 4 p.m. Wednesday, all the
passengers rushed to the upper deck because of heavy smoke from
below, where some 60 cars were making the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to jump into the water because the smoke was so
strong it was hard to breathe,'' he said, adding that he and five
other men had jumped at once. He lost track of the others and swam
for an hour, he said, before reaching the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials said many bodies had washed ashore, along with a
few people who were found unconscious but still alive.
</P>
<P>
   According to local news media, this was the second accident in
five weeks for a vessel operated by Yanda Ferry Co. In October, a
ship caught fire and sank near Dalian, but all but three people
were rescued.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 1906EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ASSISI-BASILICA-750(2     11-25 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSISI-BASILICA-750(2TAKES)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAKE-DAMAGED ASSISI BASILICA IS RESTORED BUT THE PEOPLE ARE NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(gm) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASSISI, Italy _ When a powerful earthquake crushed the vaulted
ceiling of the Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi two years ago, the
damage to priceless 13th- and 14th-century frescos was so
devastating that it overshadowed the loss of 11 lives and many
thousands of homes.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the basilica, one of the most revered shrines of the
Roman Catholic Church, will be fully reopened to the public. The
extraordinary restoration of the early Renaissance masterpiece was
so speedy and efficient that it has been dubbed ``the miracle of
Assisi.''
</P>
<P>
   But another expected miracle _ a free-market experiment in
disaster relief that was supposed to find new shelter for thousands
of victims within two years _ has not materialized. In the rolling
hills surrounding Assisi, medieval towns and mountain villages are
still dotted with makeshift camp sites, bleak rows of corrugated
metal huts that Italians call ``containers,'' which were hastily
erected to shelter many of the 40,000 people in Umbria and the
Marches left homeless by the 1997 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 people are still living in containers, looking
ahead to their third Christmas in crowded, 375-square-foot metal
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them complain that the fate of the basilica monopolized
international attention and government concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you show the world the reconstructed basilica, people
will assume that the earthquake emergency is over,'' said Dante
Amici, the head of the Falling Star camp ground in Colfiorito, a
mountain village 24 miles from Assisi that was the epicenter of the
quake and one-fifth of whose 500 inhabitants live in containers.
``But in reality the emergency is still here, we are it.''
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake on Sept. 26, 1997, was by no means the most
devastating in recent history. The 1980 earthquake in Irpinia, near
Naples, left 2,500 dead and 300,000 homeless. That disaster remains
etched in the national psyche as an act of God made worse by human
greed: much of the $27 billion in state funds sent for
reconstruction was siphoned off by corrupt officials and local
organized crime. Even today, some Irpinia victims are still living
in containers.
</P>
<P>
   That and other bad experiences prompted the Italian government
to do two things. It proposed a law to mandate private earthquake
insurance, a deeply controversial innovation in a country where the
state is expected to provide in a catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   And immediately after the Assisi quake, the government passed a
measure to allot state funds directly to victims, to allow them to
hire their own contractors to rebuild their homes _ bypassing the
local authorities, lessening the opportunities for corruption and,
in theory, bulldozing through bureaucracy and speeding up the
reconstruction process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The model presupposes the fashionable view that the less
government the better,'' said Vincenzo Riommi, deputy mayor of
Foligno, a regional center that was also badly hit by the quake.
``People could chose their own builders and take responsibility for
themselves instead of waiting for the state to do everything. But
what we didn't foresee in this free market system is that supply
and demand would end up so imbalanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, there were several thousand people in need of new
homes. The regional council of Umbria drew a list of 570 companies
that could execute the plans. But most of the contracts ended up
going to fewer than than 100 companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We relied on private initiative, the desire of individual
homeowners to build as soon as possible,'' said Bruno Bracalente,
president of the Umbria regional government. ``But people had
different reactions. They hired contractors and architects the way
they choose family doctors, somebody they knew and trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   That backlog was compounded by bureaucratic delays in inspecting
sites, approving blueprints and granting building permits. ``Italy
is the land of paper,'' complained Giuliano Ricci, head of the
Colfiorito reconstruction committee. ``Every time you try to
present your building proposal, they ask you for your social
security number 50 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor has fraud been totally eliminated from the process. The
police in Foligno announced this week that they had uncovered a
scam by a phony construction company that bilked both suppliers and
homeowners for just over $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, Bracalente confidently predicted that 4,500
dislocated families would be back in their own homes within 12
months. Now he concedes that it could take several more years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END END; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the repair of the Basilica of St. Francis proved a
model of speed and almost superhuman cooperation. Friars,
government bureaucrats, art restorers, construction crews and
hundreds of volunteers worked around the clock to bolster the
structure against future quakes and to reconstruct the vault of the
nave, famous for its brilliantly colored frescos by Giotto and
Cimabue. The images of only two saints, St. Rufino and St.
Vittorino, traditionally attributed to Giotto, were reconstituted
by piecing together more than 3,000 tiny fragments like pieces of a
jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   And even many of the people left homeless by the same disaster
say the basilica deserved priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's St. Francis, and it is also the main draw for tourism
around here _ they had to fix it first,'' said Giovanni Polveri,
21, who has spent the last two years in a container in Foligno with
his parents and sister. He said his contractor had so many other
commissions that his reconstruction permits had not yet been
processed. ``There is nothing we can do, but we are very sick of
living in this place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has spent $39 million on the basilica and the Sacred
Convent attached to it, but that expense is small compared with the
$5 billion it has earmarked over the same time to reconstruct
ruined homes, churches and historic buildings.
</P>
<P>
   By Italian standards, however, the pace is exemplary. It took
three years for the first reconstruction sites to go up after the
earthquake in Friuli in 1976, and 12 years to rehouse all 80,000
victims, a vast public works project that is considered a model
compared with Irpinia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly having these many families still in containers is a
problem,'' Bracalente said. ``But in reality, things are moving
very fast: in Umbria alone, we now have 4,500 open construction
sites. Many should be finished by spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many small communities are less sanguine. They are using
some state funds to throw up apartment buildings to offer better
housing to residents stuck in containers. Once their own homes are
finally reconstructed, those new buildings will be turned into
public housing.
</P>
<P>
   After the quake, the homeless were given the option of receiving
government assistance to rent temporary housing, about $140 per
person a month with a ceiling of $330 per family. Or they could
move into containers, supplied for free, with discounted utility
charges. In larger towns like Foligno, most people chose the rental
money. Many who chose containers were immigrant workers who viewed
the boxes as an improvement over the crowded tenements they lived
in before the quake.
</P>
<P>
   In rural areas, however, there were very few apartments
available to rent, and almost all chose containers that allowed
them to stay near their farms, herds of cattle and jobs. After two
years, most camp grounds have their own makeshift playgrounds,
satellite dishes, metal chapels and cafes, and look eerily settled
_ like lunar colonies plunked down on pastures and potato fields.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the inhabitants are elderly villagers, passively waiting
to be told what to do. But there are also young couples who felt
they had no better choice. ``I couldn't keep my job and commute
from an apartment,'' said Marcello Massimiani, 31, who works as a
butcher in Colfiorito, 15 miles from Foligno, the nearest large
town.
</P>
<P>
   While they wait for an apartment, he and his wife, Monica, and
their 7-month-old twins live in a container they fixed up with lace
curtains, a television and microwave, squeezing two cribs next to
their bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first two months, we lived in a tent, so this seemed
luxurious,'' Mrs. Massimiani said with a smile. ``That wore off
once the twins came.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had adjusted to the cramped living quarters and
solitary walks across muddy camp grounds with her double-stroller.
``We have to live with it, and so we got used to it, this is our
reality, but we don't have any idea when it will end,'' she said,
adding with a grimace, ``I dread the day the twins start to walk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1428 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CHICAGO-LESSON-PLANS-     11-25 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-LESSON-PLANS-ART-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS IN CHICAGO SCHOOLS FOLLOW DETAILED SCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was the 53rd day of the school year at Joyce Kilmer
Elementary, a fact that was hardly lost on Christine Jabbari.
</P>
<P>
   That's because ``Day: 053'' was printed at the top of the
recommended lesson plan open on her desk, a thick white binder
crammed with goals for each day, conversation starters and
step-by-step questions that had been given to her and the city's
26,000 other teachers by the school system's administrators at the
start of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   And in case the document's importance was lost on Ms. Jabbari,
the page also identified the section of the Iowa Test of Basic
Skills to which that day's entry corresponded _ even though Ms.
Jabbari's 48 kindergartners will not take the standardized test,
which determines who may be held back, until the end of the first
grade.
</P>
<P>
   Like an explorer following a map to buried treasure, Ms. Jabbari
proceeded to guide her pupils through that day's lesson, which, at
the city's prodding, centered on a story about a child's bath, in
which the letter ``b'' figured prominently.
</P>
<P>
   When her instructions suggested that Ms. Jabbari advise the
children to ``think of other pictures that make the same sound bath
begins with,'' she complied, telling them, ``I want you to raise
your hand and give me words that start with the `ba' sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Although almost every American school district has begun, in
just the last three years, to check student progress against
specified academic standards, the United States' third-largest
district has gone a giant step further this year: supplying every
teacher with a virtual script, a detailed, day-by-day outline of
what he or she should be teaching _ and when _ in the language
arts, mathematics, science and social studies.
</P>
<P>
   The standardized lesson plans, which were drafted over two years
by a committee of 100 teachers, are optional. But central
administrators, most notably the system's chief executive, Paul
Vallas, have made clear that all teachers should draw on the
lessons in some way _ and many apparently are doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Informal surveys by several principals and the leaders of the
teachers union suggest that several thousand teachers have already
begun incorporating the curriculums into the daily fiber of their
classrooms, often following the instructions word for word.
</P>
<P>
   The program, believed to be the most comprehensive of its kind,
is being tracked by educators across the country, at a time when
the pedagogical pendulum is swinging away from the free-form,
anything-goes instruction of the 1970s and 1980s, and toward a
regimented style more reminiscent of the 1950s. (Even in the 1950s,
though, lessons were rarely orchestrated down to the day.)
</P>
<P>
   In scaling back teachers' autonomy, Chicago is building on
smaller experiments in dozens of other districts, which have
encouraged the use of a choreographed, drill-oriented curriculum
called ``Success for All'' in reading classes in its
lowest-performing schools, as well as a similar program in a new
charter school.
</P>
<P>
   To some educators, curriculums like Chicago's are the logical
complement to the standards movement, providing an almost ironclad
guarantee that all students will be exposed to the same material
and that all teachers, regardless of qualification, will know
exactly how to present it .
</P>
<P>
   ``I think creativity had just gotten out of hand,'' said
Johnetta James, who has been principal at Kilmer Elementary on
Chicago's North Side for a decade, and who has mandated that her
teachers use the new curriculum in English and math.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Ms. James recalled walking into a second grade
``reading'' class, only to find students filling the blackboard
with a simple bar graph charting the number of cans raised in a
food drive. (``They're learning how to read a graph,'' Ms. James
quoted the teacher as saying.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jabbari, 31, a six-year veteran who must corral four dozen
kindergartners each day, said the new lesson plans had been
invaluable in helping her avoid such moments. And she was one of
many teachers interviewed _ including Tom Reece, president of the
Chicago Teachers Union _ who were impressed with the quality of the
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come into class,'' Ms. Jabbari said, ``and you know what
you're going to teach.''
</P>
<P>
   But to others, Chicago is sapping the creativity from the
teaching process, with some teachers reduced to being robots who
have one eye trained on the test calendar and the other on a
suggested list of talking points, exercises and questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger in scripting teachers,'' said Judith Rizzo, the
deputy chancellor for curriculum and instruction for the New York
City schools, ``is that people will say: `I followed the script.
It's not my fault that the kids didn't learn.'''
</P>
<P>
   Others worry that by having so much of their time spoken for,
teachers might be reluctant to be spontaneous _ for example, to
turn the tables and allow their students to teach. ``Good teachers
are open to the moment,'' said Roberta Grabler, who has taught
elementary school for 25 years in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago lesson plans, known as the ``structured
curriculum,'' were largely the idea of Vallas, the peripatetic
former city budget director who was entrusted with the keys to the
school system in 1995 when it was taken over by Mayor Richard M.
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, Vallas has instituted sweeping changes,
including holding back tens of thousands of students, that have
already begun to lift the system above its perennial, rock-bottom
national rating.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Vallas said he had found his inspiration for
the daily lesson plans in an unlikely place: the officers' training
manuals that he had received from the National Guard during more
than a decade as a reservist.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Vallas envisions a school system with far more
flexibility than one might expect. He encourages teachers, for
example, to bounce around as they sample the lesson plans, fusing
the elements of several days' lessons into one class and lingering
on others for a week, if they like.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover committees are already at work on two alternate
curriculums to fulfill Vallas' dream that some day soon, each
teacher will begin the day standing at the fork of three very
different paths. How much those lessons will vary, however, remains
to be seen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Some critics out there will say, `Oh my God, you're
lobotomizing teachers,''' Vallas said. ``No. What we're saying is
`What every major successful corporation is doing, what the
military is doing, is giving teachers a model of quality
instruction and curriculum so they'll feel supported in the
classroom.'''
</P>
<P>
   For all that hand-holding, Vallas refuses to soften the sting of
the standardized tests to which the curriculum is linked. Last
summer, for example, two out of every three students in the third
and sixth grades were required to attend summer school in Chicago _
and half of those who attended were required to repeat the grade.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of retention, which hangs like a cloud over every
elementary and middle school, has made for some strange-sounding
conversations this year at Kilmer Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowa, Iowa, Iowa! We're in Iowa!'' Joanne Turko bellowed at
her sixth-graders one morning in early November in response to a
wrong answer during a 90-minute English lesson. ``That's where
they'll nail you on the Iowa test!''
</P>
<P>
   During the class, Ms. Turko, who has been teaching for 30 years,
had her city-provided lesson notebook open on her desk. The goals
of the day that Ms. Turko scribbled on the blackboard were lifted
almost verbatim from the city's daily lesson plans; where she
wrote, ``Make inferences and draw conclusions,'' the book
suggested, ``Draw conclusions, deduce meaning not explicitly
stated.'.
</P>
<P>
   But in an example of the flexibility encouraged by Vallas, Ms.
Turko had cobbled together her lesson from days eight and 49, even
though it was day 53, in a lively lesson that she made her own by
having her students ask one another questions to compare the Great
Wall of China with the wall built by the Roman Emperor Hadrian.
</P>
<P>
   Though her students said that they had little idea that she was
teaching from what, in a sense, is a lot like a cookbook, they said
they had noticed that Ms. Turko invoked the Iowa test all day long
_ and that the threats of their failure had succeeded in keeping
them hanging on her every word, scripted or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally I wouldn't pay much attention, because I'd know I
could pass without doing much work,'' said Jason Olivares, 12, who
sat front row center. ``It's not like that now. I know I've got to
study harder and learn so that I can go on to the seventh grade _
and life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
