<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1435 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-BUSINESS-CONGRESS-NYT     11-25 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS LOBBYISTS PLEASED WITH '98-99 CONGRESSIONAL SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats call it the do-nothing Congress, one that
failed to come to grips with issues like gun control, campaign
finance and Medicare coverage of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans speak only slightly more favorably about the
congressional session that ended last week, saying they did as well
as could be expected given their narrow majorities in both houses
and a Democrat in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But lobbyists here for the main organizations representing large
numbers of businesses are downright enthusiastic. They managed,
they say, to get several important measures through Congress and
were able to block bills they opposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to do two things in the Congress,'' said Thomas
Donohue, president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``You try to
advance things of high importance and significance, and you try to
retard things that you don't want to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Baroody, chief lobbyist for the National Association of
Manufacturers, said he and the members of his organization were
disappointed that a big tax cut was not enacted this year, but he
added, ``We should not let the disappointments blind us to some
very significant accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Many bills before Congress, like one that would require cable
companies to give Internet service providers access to high-speed
lines, were favored by some businesses and opposed by others. The
national business lobbies tended to sit those issues out.
</P>
<P>
   But these organizations had their way on a surprising number of
bills where businesses were more or less united.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant victory, say representatives of large
corporations and small businesses alike, was enactment of the law
that will limit lawsuits arising from Year 2000 computer
breakdowns. Many Democrats in Congress complained mightily when
President Clinton agreed to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   The substance of the law is important to businesses. It sets a
ceiling on punitive damages against small companies, gives all
companies a grace period to fix problems before they can be sued,
places particular limits on class-action suits and protects wealthy
companies against being held responsible for computer failures
caused by businesses with less resources.
</P>
<P>
   But lobbyists for industry said passage of the legislation was
perhaps even more important symbolically and politically because it
meant a victory in Congress for businesses over trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again in recent years, business interests and the trial
bar have been in fierce combat on the legislative battlefield _ on
product liability, on tobacco, on health maintenance organizations.
Each side has donated millions of dollars to lawmakers and
political parties. What was called the Y2K legislation amounted to
a rare knockout for the business side.
</P>
<P>
   The matter was so important to the Chamber of Commerce that the
organization spent more than $500,000 promoting the legislation in
television advertisements around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue said this was just the beginning of a drive to bring
trial lawyers to their knees. ``We are going to continue to
challenge that very small group of people who are trying to suck
the vitality out of American industry and put it in their
pockets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce has vastly expanded its lobbying
operation in Washington. It now has 17 full-time lobbyists,
compared with only 3 when Donohue became president two years ago,
and the lobbying budget has been increased by millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is also throwing much more muscle and money
into electoral politics. Donohue said it had plans to become
heavily involved in 35 to 40 House races and 10 to 12 Senate races
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other legislative victories for business this year was
the repeal of Depression-era laws that had limited the ability of
banks, securities firms and insurance companies to enter into one
another's businesses. The lobbies also won a five-year extension of
tax credits for businesses to help offset their research and
development expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those measures passed because of unusual political
circumstances. The banking law was one of the rare pieces of big
legislation where the divisive issues were not partisan ones. And
on the popular research tax credit, the Republican chairmen of the
tax-writing committees may have allowed a long extension because
their own political circumstances have changed:
</P>
<P>
   To the consternation of business, Congress has insisted in the
past on approving the tax credit year by year, in large part
because that helped the lawmakers raise annual campaign donations
from business interests eager to have the tax break extended. But
now, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, is not running for re-election. And Senate Finance
Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del., 78, is running next year
for what is probably the last time and therefore is not likely to
need contributions again.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important to the business lobbyists was that a number of
measures they opposed did not become law: an increase in the
minimum wage, regulation of health care plans, limits on campaign
contributions, a ban on agribusiness mergers and a bill that would
have given many state and municipal statutes primacy over federal
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many measures favored by business interests were
rejected. Among them were bills that would have given the president
a freer hand to negotiate trade agreements, made it harder for
consumers to avoid paying debts by declaring bankruptcy and blocked
new rules by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration on
work-related injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest disappointment to many business interests was that
Congress did not enact a big tax cut. But tax reduction may not
have the same cachet it once had in business circles. Dirk Van
Dongen, president of the National Association of
Wholesaler-Distributors, said a poll of his members showed that
they overwhelmingly favored using the federal budget surplus for
debt reduction rather than tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Large-scale tax reduction is not likely to come before Congress
next year, but many of the other issues that failed this year will
be considered again.
</P>
<P>
   Some form of an increase in the minimum wage is expected to be
approved, possibly in conjunction with the bankruptcy bill. The
business lobbyists will be trying to make sure the increase is
accompanied by tax breaks for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   If regulation of health maintenance organizations is adopted,
the business interests want to make sure it is done in a way that
does not increase insurance premiums and that gives tax offsets to
the self-employed and to workers whose employers do not provide
health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual alliance with Clinton, business leaders are
expected to throw their weight behind a measure that lifts barriers
against trade with China and allows Chinese membership in the World
Trade Organization. It will be a tough fight, with Republican
isolationists and Democrats aligned with labor unions against the
measure and moderates from both parties supporting it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
