<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 11/25/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) HARGEISA, Somalia -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- SOMALILAND-3,
11-25 -- Currency traders wait for business earlier this month at a
stand set up in front of rubble left from Somalia's years of civil
war. Unheard of in Somalia, the traders here are able to keep cash
out in the open with little fear of robbery. The self-proclaimed
Republic of Somaliland has become one of Africa's fledgling success
stories. But it is a success the outside world has been reluctant
to help because no one is quite sure what to do with it. (Ian
Fisher/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LAKE OF THE WOODS, Canada -- Nov. 25, 1999 --
CANADA-FISHING-2, 11-25 -- Donna Hanson, owner of a local lodge,
speeds through the waterways on Lake of the Woods, in Canada's
Ontario province, past one of 14,000 islands in the lake system. At
right is fellow lodge owner Tom Pearson. Ontario's lodge owners
have been battling with their counterparts on the Minnesota side of
the lake over fishing limits. The Canadians claim anglers from the
Minnesota side of the lake regularly break Canadian fishing limits.
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KENORA, Canada -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- CANADA-FISHING-1,
11-25 -- ``Husky the Musky,'' a two ton, steel and fiberglass
rendering of a muskellunge fighting fish, towers over Lake of the
Woods in Kenora, Ontario. Lodge owners in the Canadian province
have been battling with their counterparts on the Minnesota side of
the lake over fishing limits. The Canadians claim anglers from the
Minnesota side of the lake regularly break Ontario's fishing limit
while fishing in the Canadian side of the lake. (Kevin Moloney/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BURAO, Somalia -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- SOMALILAND-2, 11-25
-- Mohamed Ibrahim Egal, president of Somaliland, in his office
during an interview earlier this month. The self-proclaimed
Republic of Somaliland has become one of Africa's fledgling success
storie. But it is a success the outside world has been reluctant to
help because no one is quite sure what to do with it. (Ian
Fisher/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- NY-THANKSGIVING-4, 11-25 --
Deidre Dzugay, 3, from Little Ferry, N.J., waves as the Barney
balloon floats past during the Thanksgiving Day parade on Thursday.
Despite a little rain, spirits remained high for participants as
well as the crowds watching the 73rd Macy's Thanksgiving Day
parade. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BURAO, Somalia -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- SOMALILAND-1, 11-25
-- Instructors drill former clan militia members during their
training to become police officers earlier this month. The
self-proclaimed Republic of Somaliland has become one of Africa's
fledgling success storie. But it is a success the outside world has
been reluctant to help because no one is quite sure what to do with
it. (Ian Fisher/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- NY-FULANI-POLITICS, 11-25
-- Leonora Fulani looks at columnist Jack Germond during taping of
her television show earlier this week. Ms. Fulani, long known as a
far-left espouser of Marxist-Leninist politics, has promised to
help Pat Buchanan, a Reaganite and Cold Warrior known for his
far-right politics, in his quest for the Reform Party nomination
for president. Everyone agrees the alliance is unusual; some would
call it unholy. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Nov. 25, 1999 --
RESEARCH-DEVELOPING-NATIONS-2, 11-25 -- A Mayan couple in a town in
Chiapas, southern Mexico, share their knowledge of medicinal plants
with researchers from a Mexican university and the University of
Georgia. Angry that they have not profited from the animal and
plant life within their borders, Ecuador and many other developing
countries have begun restricting the freedom of scientists to
collect biological samples and demanding compensation in exchange
for permits. (National Institute of Health/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PLYMOUTH, Mass. -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- MA-THANKSGIVING,
11-25 -- Meredith Tate, 5, speaks out from her mother's cloak
during a re-enactment of the pilgrim's thanksgiving on Thursday.
After landing in the New World in 1620, a small band of Pilgrims
set aside several days to give thanks to God for their survival of
their first winter and a boutiful first harvest. The ceremony is
now celebrated throughout the U.S. as Thanksgiving. (Matthew J.
Lee/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- OFF-BROADWAY-2, 11-25 --
Sean Martin Hingston with Stephanie Michels in ``Contact,'' the hit
evening of dance-driven narrative at the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater.
When one has a hankering for great performances, more often than
not the first places to look for satisfaction these days are the
city's smaller stages. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- OFF-BROADWAY, 11-25 --
Stephen Spinella with Paddy Croft in James Joyce's ``The Dead,''
now at Playwrights Horizons and moving to Broadway next month. When
one has a hankering for great performances, more often than not the
first places to look for satisfaction these days are the city's
smaller stages. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Nov. 25, 1999 -- VELASQUEZ-EXHIBIT, 11-25 --
``Juan de Pareja,'' painted in 1650, left, and ``King Philip IV of
Spain,'' 1644, both by Diego Rodriguez de Silva y Velzquez, are
two of the works on display in an exhibit called ``Velazquez in New
York Museums'' at the Frick Collection in New York. The exhibit
runs from November 16 to January 16, 2000. (The Frick
Collection/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON-- Nov. 25, 1999 -- GORE-MRSCLINTON, 11-25 --
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Vice President Al Gore embrace during a
rally to draw the support of women to Gore's campaign in June. Mrs.
Clinton and Gore, the two most famous students of the Bill Clinton
political school, have graduated. But now that they are finally out
on their own politically, they seem to be sticking to the same
text. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) FORT COLLINS, Colo. -- Nov. 25, 1999 --
RESEARCH-DEVELOPING-NATIONS, 11-25 -- Lab technician Lana Wheeler
of the National Seed Storage Laboratory pulls the lid from a
cryogenic storage tank where seeds are stored at -160 degrees
Celsius in liquid nitrogen. Angry that they have not profited from
the animal and plant life within their borders, Ecuador and many
other developing countries have begun restricting the freedom of
scientists to collect biological samples and demanding compensation
in exchange for permits. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
