<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-EUROPE-FORCE-535&AMP;ADD-     11-25 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-FORCE-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN LEADERS PLAN A RAPID INTERVENTION FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ European leaders are now aiming to create within three
years a rapid intervention force that could field 50,000 soldiers
and 300 to 500 aircraft for up to a year to a future conflict like
the one in Kosovo earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The principal European defense and foreign ministers agreed
loosely on this goal in Luxembourg earlier this week, and on
Thursday Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain and President Jacques
Chirac of France met in London to reaffirm both countries'
determination to cooperate so that Europe could take care of its
own military problems if the United States was not available to
help.
</P>
<P>
   Whether France and Britain are in full accord on the
relationship that any future European force should have with the
NATO alliance is less clear, however.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Robertson, a former British defense secretary who is now
secretary general of the NATO alliance, said Thursday that U.S.
fears that an independent European defense would weaken
trans-Atlantic ties were groundless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who are nervous in the United States that with the
Europeans carrying more of the burden, that they would break away,
are wrong,'' he said on a visit to Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   His successor as British Defense Secretary, Geoff Hoon, also
said Thursday, ``What we want to see is a stronger European
contribution to NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept that different countries have different views,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what Britain will do is negotiate effectively to ensure,
first of all, that European nations can pull their weight within
NATO military operations but at the same time preserve the
essential link with NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   But France's foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine acknowledged here
recently that France was out in front of some of its allies in
arguing that a European reaction force should be able to operate
with complete autonomy even if it was put together from units that
formally belonged to the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   French officials tell U.S. listeners that European defense
autonomy would be in the best interests of the United States, which
only reluctantly got involved in stopping the war in Bosnia in 1995
and led the air war in Kosovo but not the peacekeeping force that
went in on the ground last June after Serbian forces withdrew from
the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Americans and we Europeans ourselves had decided that
Europeans should take charge of operations against Serbia, that
would not have been possible,'' French Defense Minister Alain
Richard said 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to his European Union colleagues in Brussels, Belgium,
about the need for stronger European defenses in a meeting on Nov.
15, Richard said not a word about the relationship that a European
military staff would have to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance, separately, is encouraging the Europeans to build
a stronger defense ``pillar'' within it. The United States has
agreed to let a European officer take command of NATO units in
future military operations like those in Kosovo if the allies agree
that European countries alone should handle them.
</P>
<P>
   But the French, among others, worry that this procedure would
still give the Americans what amounts to a veto power over a
European force that was fully integrated within the alliance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As a small first step toward a European defense, Germany,
France, Spain, Belgium and Luxembourg have asked the U.S. officer
who is the allied supreme commander in Europe, Gen. Wesley Clark,
to consider allowing the military staff that the five European
countries maintain in Strasbourg, France, to take over command of
peacekeeping operations in Kosovo next spring.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Kosovo peacekeeping force has been commanded first
by a British general and then by a German general, but both
reported to Clark and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the rest of the discussion about Europe and its role in
its own defense is academic at this point, since the European Union
has not agreed on the details of how a European defense force would
be built. But the European countries have tried to reassure their
North American allies that they don't intend to go off on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's chief security policy coordinator is Javier
Solana, Lord Robertson's predecessor as secretary-general of the
alliance, and Solana is now also secretary-general of a 10-nation
European defense group that might become the core framework for any
future European army.
</P>
<P>
   The real question, as the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung pointed
out Thursday, is whether the European countries are really ready to
spend the billions of dollars it would take for them to catch up
with the United States and acquire the technology, communications
and intelligence systems, along with the rapid deployment aircraft
and helicopters that they found they lacked in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``A European security and defense identity, that could turn into
a European defense union some day, will not come to pass without
great political effort,'' the newspaper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
