<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-KURDS-NYT &LR;      11-25 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-KURDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKISH APPELLATE COURT BACKS KURD CHIEF'S DEATH SENTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ A Turkish appeals court Thursday upheld the
death sentence given to the imprisoned Kurdish rebel leader
Abdullah Ocalan, but whether the sentence will be carried out
remained highly uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous ruling, the five-judge panel found that Ocalan's
trial on treason charges, which ended June 29, was conducted ``in
accordance with legal procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan's lawyers said they would appeal to the European Court of
Human Rights, whose jurisdiction Turkey has accepted in the past.
It could take a year or longer for the European court to make a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   In the period following Ocalan's capture in February, public
opinion in Turkey, which has been fanned by countless speeches and
articles depicting him as a ``butcher'' and ``baby-killer,'' seemed
overwhelmingly in favor of executing him. But at his trial, the
51-year-old militant acknowledged ``historical errors,'' offered to
cooperate with the state and asked his fighters to lay down their
guns. As a result, emotions have cooled considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting in the mostly Kurdish provinces of eastern Turkey has
diminished in recent months, although sporadic clashes continue.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders have rejected Ocalan's calls for reconciliation,
saying they cannot accept any compromise or dialogue with
terrorists. They have also rejected his suggestion that they permit
the establishment of Kurdish-language schools and television
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Many Turks detest Ocalan and blame him for the 15-year conflict
led by Ocalan's Kurdistan Workers Party in which more than 30,000
people have been killed. Several hundred of them gathered in Ankara
Thursday to cheer the court ruling. They waved placards depicting
Ocalan as a vampire and chanted, ``Hang! Hang! Hang!''
</P>
<P>
   Many Kurds in Turkey and abroad view Ocalan as a heroic figure.
Some of his supporters assembled Thursday in London and other
cities to protest the ratification of his death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is a rejection of peace, human rights and
democratic values,'' leaders of Ocalan's rebel movement said in a
statement issued in Brussels. ``It cannot be interpreted otherwise
because it comes at a time when our forces have stopped the war and
are in a process of withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders are weighing the effect that Ocalan's execution
would have on their ambition to join the European Union, which
forbids its member states to practice capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   At a summit in Helsinki in December, European leaders are
expected to decide whether to accept Turkey as a candidate for
membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget the Helsinki summit if Ocalan is executed,'' warned
Hans-Joachim Vergau, the German ambassador to Turkey, in a speech
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The government is divided over how to proceed with the Ocalan
case. Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit, who opposes the death
penalty in all cases, has said Turkey will await the decision of
the European court. But some leaders of Nationalist Action, the
right-wing party that is his main coalition partner, favor an early
execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should carry out what our laws provide,'' said Defense
Minister Sabahattin Cakmakoglu, who is a member of Nationalist
Action. ``We have no obligation to wait for a decision from the
European court.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Turkish law, both Parliament and the president must
approve every execution. No one has been executed here since 1984,
although there have been dozens of death sentences. By tacit
agreement among all political parties, the sentences have not been
sent to Parliament for approval.
</P>
<P>
   According to estimates by foreign diplomats, the conflict in
eastern Turkey has displaced about 3 million Kurds and led to the
destruction of more than 3,000 villages. Many of the villages were
burned by Turkish military units so they could not be used as
guerrilla bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
