<HEADLINE>
AFTER TAKING ILL, YELTSIN POSTPONES BELARUS PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin on Thursday put off plans to
sign a unification treaty with Belarus, a political and diplomatic
extravaganza which had been scheduled for Friday, after falling ill
with what aides said was viral bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders immediately speculated that the illness was a pretext
to delay the treaty, which is widely seen as a political coup for
Belarus' autocratic president, Alexander Lukashenko, and a mixed
blessing for Yeltsin and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin's spokesman said later that the treaty would be
signed in about two weeks, after the president had time to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's recurring bouts of bronchitis have sometimes sidelined
him for a month or more, and have twice worsened into pneumonia.
But some aides indicated that the latest infection was not serious
so far.
</P>
<P>
   The president ``just lost his voice and has a cold,'' said Prime
Minister Vladimir Putin on Thursday, shortly after Yeltsin
completed a cabinet meeting at which his remarks were said to have
been barely audible.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, 68, was taken to his usual country home, Gorky-9, north
of Moscow to rest after stopping at a hospital for a checkup. His
office canceled a meeting next week with the president of Lithuania
and said that Yeltsin would not see foreign visitors until he meets
with Ukraine's newly re-elected president, Leonid Kuchma, on Dec.
6.
</P>
<P>
   For Lukashenko, who had planned to fly to Moscow on Friday,
Yeltsin's illness once more postpones an event for which he has
already waited three years.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called unification treaty would stop somewhat short of
what its nickname suggests. It proposes that the two nations remain
independent states, but form a political confederation which would
lead by 2005 to common tax and customs laws and a single currency.
A new council of leaders would oversee the confederation.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of union is politically popular in both nations. Many
analysts say that is precisely why the treaty signing was set for
Friday, just before crucial parliamentary elections in Russia, on
Dec. 19. Lukashenko, who is struggling with hyperinflation and
increasing attacks on his regime by human-rights critics, could
also use some political help.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, it is unclear whether the treaty would do
much more than give its signers a political bounce. It would
require both ratification and a constitutional change to take
effect in Russia, and the union faces powerful opposition from some
political sectors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Substantively, analysts say, the document is not much different
from a previous declaration that Yeltsin and Lukashenko signed with
flourish in 1996, flanked by the patriarch of the Russian Orthodox
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Putin said that negotiations between the two
nations had not been completed and that ``there are different
viewpoints on the form of treaty to be signed and the forms of
integration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no doubts over the idea of union itself,'' he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   After a seemingly endless string of colds and bouts of
exhaustion in 1998, Yeltsin has seemed somewhat heartier during
recent, if rare, public appearances. Those who saw him a week ago
in Istanbul, where he gave a speech before the Organization on
Security and Cooperation in Europe, said he seemed unusually fit.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin has fallen ill during or after various trips abroad,
and he apparently weakened on returning to the coldest weather of
Moscow's young winter, with temperatures brushing zero.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
