<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-LOANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BONDS MAY HELP REDUCE JAPANESE INSTITUTIONS' BAD DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Tokyo office of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter priced
the first set of bonds linked to nonperforming Japanese real estate
loans Thursday, paving the way for what may be a flood of deals
aimed at clearing away the mountain of bad debt on the balance
sheets of Japanese banks and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time a capital markets solution has been
used to bring new investors and liquidity into the real estate
market here,'' said Douglas Kennedy, executive director of the
securitized products group at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was worth 21 billion yen, or about $200 million, making
it larger than many in the market thought it would be. Kennedy said
all but 4 billion yen of the bonds had AAA or AA credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought about 60 percent of the securities would be
sold to Japanese investors, with the remainder distributed about
equally between Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment bankers have long advocated the development
of a market in securities tied to Japan's vast pool of
nonperforming real estate debt. The precise figures are still
unknown, but rough estimates suggest that Japanese financial
institutions hold 80 trillion to 100 trillion yen, or $766 billion
to $957 billion, in bad debt. As much as 50 percent of it is
related to real estate, which lends itself to securitization, in
which loans are packaged together and sold as bonds to investors.
</P>
<P>
   That has had investment bankers salivating. Kennedy said that
even if only 10 percent of those real estate loans were suitable
for securitization, underwriters would have the opportunity for 250
deals, and lucrative ones at that.
</P>
<P>
   But until a year or so ago, banks and other financial
institutions had been slow to jettison their bad debts, afraid of
damaging long-held relationships. Banks have tended to write off
their bad loans by gathering reserves against them, which leaves
the assets on their books.
</P>
<P>
   That is changing, Kennedy said, noting that the mortgages that
Morgan Stanley cobbled together to sell Thursday had all been
bought by Morgan Stanley between August 1998 and March 1999.
``Financial institutions are really serious about cleaning up their
balance sheets now, but it's only happened in the last two years,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That, coupled with a renewed appetite for Japanese assets in
general among global investors, and changes in laws governing real
estate transactions, led to the opportunity that Morgan Stanley
took Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
