<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, November 1, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Greg Ambrose at 415-777-7219 or
the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running in
main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TEENJOBS _  &LR;  Shoppers barely glanced his way, but Nathan Smith
continued to toss a ball attached to a long elastic cord at a kiosk
in San Rafael's Northgate Mall. Time and again, the ball hit the
tiles with a loud ``thwap,'' then sprang back to his palm. Bungee
Balls weren't selling well, but Nathan vowed to keep demonstrating
even at the risk of carpal tunnel injury. He is 14, and this is his
first job. By SAM MCMANUS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1470 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TEENJOBS--SFCHRON &LR;      11-25 1713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENJOBS--SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Firms Turn to Teens as Pool of Older Workers Shrinks  &HT;     By Sam McManis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Shoppers barely glanced his way, but Nathan Smith continued to toss
a ball attached to a long elastic cord at a kiosk in San Rafael's
Northgate Mall. Time and again, the ball hit the tiles with a loud
``thwap,'' then sprang back to his palm. Bungee Balls weren't
selling well, but Nathan vowed to keep demonstrating even at the
risk of carpal tunnel injury.
<P>
   He is 14, and this is his first job.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Robinson's shift at the Paradise Bakery and Cafe at the
Sunvalley Mall in Concord had only just begun, but she was already
swamped at the cash register. It can be hectic at the food court,
no job for a slacker, but Amy keeps pestering her boss for more
hours.
</P>
<P>
   She is 15 and saving for a car.
</P>
<P>
   When the school day at Oak Grove High in San Jose is over, Sean
Sharma hacks around on a computer. This is work, not goofing off.
Sean has developed the Web site for Cypress Human Resources in San
Jose, and it's his job to maintain the site, fix glitches and
upgrade, upgrade, upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   He may be just 16, but he's got stock options and a salary that
his boss says would equal $50,000 if he were to choose to work full
time.
</P>
<P>
   From fast food to retail to high tech, more teens are working
more hours after school and on weekends, especially during the
holiday season, in which retailers are scrounging for help. And
they're starting at a younger age, too. The U.S. Bureau of Labor
Statistics recently reported that 57 percent of the nation's
14-year-olds have some work experience. For 15-year-olds, the
figure rises to 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are no previous government studies to compare, some
experts say that teens today are starting jobs at a younger age
because the pool of older workers is depleted by the 30-year low in
unemployment figures.
</P>
<P>
   Under California law, the minimum working age is 12, but most
businesses in the state abide by the federal occupational
restrictions that minors must be 14, work no more than three hours
per school day, eight hours a day on nonschool days and not more
than 18 hours per week. California law says 12-year-olds may never
work on school days. The exception is in the entertainment
industry, where children as young as 15 days cq  &LR; may work on movie
or TV sets under rigid restrictions. ``There's a huge gap in the
workforce, and it's got to be filled somewhere,'' said Rich Halberg
of Joint Venture: Silicon Valley Network, a nonprofit business
group. ``It's a sign of the times. Demand is high, but it's a
trade-off for the kids. Sure, they get jobs and some might get
stock options, but are they losing out on having fun and being
kids?''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Greenberger, University of California at Irvine psychology
professor and author of ``When Teenagers Work,'' believes most
teens in burger-flipping jobs would be better off spending more
time studying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teenagers who work long hours in today's routinized adolescent
workplace of mostly dead-end jobs are more cynical about the value
of hard work and more tolerant of improprieties on the job than
peers who don't work,'' Greenberger writes. ``Ours is the only
major industrialized nation that encourages student employment
among college-bound teenagers.''
</P>
<P>
   But several teens interviewed at jobs ranging from whipping up
lattes to solving government employees' computer problems say
working raises their self-esteem and bank accounts, doesn't affect
their grades and, in the case of high-tech teens, may lead to
lucrative jobs upon graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 14 is a little late to start working,'' said Nathan, a
freshman at Terra Linda High in San Rafael. ``When I was 11, I was
stocking shelves for a friend at the 7-Eleven. If somebody's able
to work, what difference should age have?''
</P>
<P>
   Amy, a sophomore at College Park High in Pleasant Hill who has
worked at her food service job for two months, said maturity, not
age, should determine a teen's fitness for employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a job definitely takes up a lot of your time,'' she
said. ``But if you can handle it, I definitely recommend it. It's
great to have your own money.''
</P>
<P>
   It falls upon Amy's mother, Debbie Robinson, to shuttle her
daughter to and from work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait until she's 16 and can drive herself, but it's
not too bad,'' Robinson said. ``Our concern was about her
schoolwork. So far, it's OK. At least having her work tells me
she's not lazy. She's a very motivated girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Many teens see after-school jobs, especially in high-tech
fields, as good early career moves. The Department of Labor reports
that 29,000 teens worked as computer programmers and systems
analysts in 1998, up from 5,000 programmers in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   According to Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, an international
outplacement firm that tracks workplace trends, the top teen
computer whizzes earn more than $100,000 out of high school. As
Rick Cobb of Challenger says, ``the appeal of working in a
fast-food environment doesn't have the same panache as sitting at a
real desk in front of a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case for Stephen Deem, a 17-year-old senior at
College Park High who started working as a computer technician for
Contra Costa County at 15. His salary had increased from $9 an hour
to $15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really had to prove to the people I knew what I was doing,
because most of the workers are in their 30s, 40s or 50s,'' Stephen
said. ``I'd go over to Social Services to fix teir computers, and
they'd look twice at me. I knew they were worried I was going to
blow up their computers. There's that type of discrimination. But
once you prove yourself, it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Anu Shahrabani, 15, a sophomore at Miramonte High in Orinda,
works as a free-lance Web site designer from her home after school.
She said adults listen to her and treat her like any other contract
worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would make them (the employer) look bad if they didn't
listen to me and take my advice, because they are the ones who
hired me,'' she said. ``Computer designers are in high demand and I
think (employers) accept that teens know computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Most high schools have computer classes and teach basic skills.
Some schools, mostly in Silicon Valley, offer advanced classes that
teach HTML. But Anu, whose father works in the computer consulting
industry, said she learned from reading books and
``experimenting.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In Silicon Valley, teen computer expertise is readily
accepted, if not automatically assumed. Sean got his job as
Webmaster at Cypress Human Resources after he built the company's
site last year as part of an Oak Grove High technology club called
EagleWeb. Club members are matched with small businesses in the
area to develop Internet presences.
</P>
<P>
   After word got out that Sean had helped build a Web site for the
American Electronics Association, ``a bunch of executives pulled
him aside and said, `Hey, would you like to work for us?'''
according to Dennis Barbata, Oak Grove's technology coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Rick White, CEO of Cypress Human Resources, said his firm
employs five teenagers in jobs ranging from tech support to data
entry to scouring resumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say one out of three make it,`` White said. ``It's a lot
of responsibility for a kid. But this one (Sean) is a gem.... &UR;  &LR; I
don't want the press asking me about him, because everybody on the
planet will come after him. IBM will be calling him tomorrow and
I'll lose him. (Sean) is kind of quiet, but if he's conceited it's
because he knows he's good. He's not afraid to tell you what he
thinks, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean works mostly from home via his personal computer _
presumably after doing homework _ and only huddles with Cypress
staff a few hours a week. Once Christmas break comes, Sean will be
seen around the office more, White said. But he still does not
exceed the 18-hour per week limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely no issues about him getting along with
other employees,'' White said. ``He's totally accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Other high-tech teens do face acceptance issues, however.
Barbata said his ``E-Whiz Kids'' at Oak Grove can handle computers
but ``they've got to work on their people skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Some teens, such as 15-year-old Andrew Yaneu of Orinda, avoid
dealing with wary employers by starting their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Andrew and his older brother, Alex, started a
``filmmaking and high-tech audio'' company out of their home.
Andrew has filmed everything from Eagle Scout ceremonies to dance
performances to football highlight reels. One recent weekend, he
spent three hours filming a bar mitzvah. Then, he spent 10 hours
editing the footage. He made $325. Andrew says he makes sure he
does not work more than the alloted hours for his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I enjoy it,'' he said. ``It's something I'd do for free.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Teens who work in retail or food service seem to develop
people skills quicker, said Marci Vanerstrom, general manager of
the Paradise Bakery and Cafe at Concord's Sunvalley Mall. Marci
says she gets most of her teen workers from nearby College Park
High and that she was looking for more 15-year-olds because she
doubles her staff during the holidays. She faces other problems,
such as unreliability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 15-year-olds I've had, for the most part, have been
excellent,'' she said. ``Whenever people apply, I always look at
the experience and it's blank. I say, `I hope you understand, you
have to sweep, you have to mop, you have to do the dishes.' I
always let them know, because standing behind the counter and
collecting money, that looks fun. Picking up after people isn't so
fun, and you have get a high turnover because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gini Carini, a 16-year-old sophomore at Carondelet High in
Concord, has worked at the Paradise bakery for more than a year.
Early on, she said, she almost quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real busy, really crazy and I'm like, `What am I
doing?' '' Gini said. ``It was my first job. It was hard. But after
more practice, it got easier. I'm working 15 hours a week now and
it moves fast. And I've kept my same GPA (3.3). I'm still not old
enough to use the slicer or climb a ladder. But the older I get,
the more fun stuff I get to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
