<HEADLINE>
JACKSON MIGHT SHAKE UP STARTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Coach Phil Jackson has hinted at possible changes
to the starting lineup this week, but the most obvious change
suddenly seems less likely.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has considered moving power forward A.C. Green to the
bench, where he might be more effective as a mid-game rebounding
sparkplug. That move could come as soon as tonight, when the Los
Angeles Lakers play the New Jersey Nets at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   But Green just played one of his better games of the season,
successfully negating Utah's Karl Malone while pulling down 10
rebounds in an all-around solid performance Wednesday. Green's
potential replacements, meanwhile, are struggling.
</P>
<P>
   One option is to go small and play 6-foot-7 Rick Fox. The more
likely option is 6-10 Robert Horry, who continues to look tentative
on the court.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Jackson still likes the idea of using the
36-year-old Green as a reserve, a scenario he has envisioned since
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like what happened on the court in the couple
(exhibition) games that Horry started,'' Jackson said, ``then we
went back to A.C. and then Horry was having trouble with his knee.
So it was a combination of things, and we got off to a pretty good
start, and we felt comfortable staying the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Foul indeed: The Lakers rank as the worst foul-shooting team in
the NBA, which is not surprising considering Shaquille O'Neal has
averaged below 40 percent for most of the season, and he leads the
league in trips to the free-throw line. But he's had plenty of help
in dragging down the team average.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher, normally a reliable foul shooter, has hit just 29
of 47 (61.7 percent). Ron Harper has shot 17 for 25 (68 percent).
Brian Shaw is 14 for 22 (63.6). The Lakers' best free-throw
shooters are Glen Rice and Kobe Bryant, and the latter hasn't
played. Rice is at 86.9 percent from the line (73 for 84).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
