<HEADER>
A1491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WILLIE-THEATER-REVIEW     11-25 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIE-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ABSOLUTION OF WILLIE MAE': SHE'S A CAN'T-HELP-IT KIND OF
PERSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The characters in ``The Absolution of Willie Mae''
talk about money a lot. Willie Mae's man, Bubba, has married a rich
white woman who has $11 million. Willie Mae's sister Minerva is
married to a guy who makes $150,000 or so, which is why she stays
with him. Bubba uses an immorally gained $265,000 to start a
taxicab business (his wife's millions, apparently, aren't good
enough for him). Somebody is mysteriously putting an extra $100 a
month in Willie Mae's bank account. Now if only somebody would take
a little of that and buy her a new sofa. Gmerice Carter's set makes
good use of space, but the title character's house is a dump.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's a relief to see money dealt with straightforwardly
after decades of television characters saying things like ``Well,
how about this amount?'' and coyly writing unseen figures on
notepads. Jane Austen always acknowledged the importance of
finances in people's lives, too. But in this well-meaning but
chaotic drama, the characters' references to and uses of money _
like so much else in the script _ doesn't always add up.
</P>
<P>
   That's a shame, because ``The Absolution of Willie Mae'' was
written by Joseph Walker, who made his reputation in 1972 with the
Negro Ensemble Company's production of ``The River Niger,'' which
moved to Broadway and went on to win the Tony Award as best play.
That work had a heavy father-son element, and so does the new one.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Mae (Gabrielle Lee) makes her entrance with a black eye,
courtesy of Bubba (O.L. Duke), the longtime man in her life. It's
morning, she's pouring herself a stiff drink and she can tell it's
not going to be a good day. Her son Larry (Sean Allen Rector) is
moving out because he can't stand to watch Bubba (his father) treat
his mother that way. Corey (Gregory Marlow), Willie Mae's other
son, who appears to be severely mentally retarded, is getting on
her nerves. Being the great mom that she is, she mimics him and
calls him a ``blubbering idiot.'' Her daughter, Tina (Meka
Lawrence), is walking around the house in shorts, complaining about
her singing lessons. Minerva (Joyce Sylvester), Willie Mae's
sister, drops by to establish her character as a lovably comic
slut.
</P>
<P>
   Into this lively household comes a would-be boarder. His name is
Jeff Williams (Michael Wright), which was the name of the son, the
young Air Force dropout, in Walker's ``River Niger.'' Jeff is so
soft-spoken and languid that he seems to have come out of another
decade, the 1950s at the latest (or maybe it's just his hat that
gives him that aura). He turns out to be a sensitive English
professor (and author, we presume, since there's a mention of a
bonus from his publisher at one point) whose marriage recently
ended. Willie Mae is attracted; Bubba, who stays overnight a lot
despite having a wife at home, doesn't want him around.
</P>
<P>
   If that were the only plot, the audience might be able to keep
things straight. But the play also brings in sexual abuse of
children, gunpoint and knifepoint encounters, the illicit selling
of term papers, literacy, prostitution and a miracle medical cure.
The play is alternately pretentious and melodramatic. At least a
couple of times, characters suddenly stand still onstage and recite
less than brilliant poetry. At other times they talk like newspaper
articles (``Bubba went to Tessa's Long Island estate''). And the
only absolution is the possibility that one character may be
rescued by the love of a good man as against a bad one. Early in
the play, Willie Mae defines herself as a can't-help-it kind of
person and tells Larry: ``Can't-help-its can't help themselves.
They need an anchor.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily the production has strengths as well. Wright, who played
the lead singer of a rhythm-and-blues group headed for dissipation
in Robert Townsend's film ``The Five Heartbeats,'' has a compelling
stage presence and several fine moments. He has real comic style
telling a story about two elderly white people, and he reacts
perfectly when Willie Mae reveals, after Jeff mentions irony to
her, that she thinks the word means being made of iron.
</P>
<P>
   Duke effectively makes Bubba detestable; the audience almost
hisses his entrances. Ms. Sylvester brings energy and conviction to
her role as Minerva. And Rector does well in a double role, as
Larry and as Corey's not-too-bright chatterbox pal Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Absolution of Willie Mae,'' frantically directed by Susan
Watson Turner, continues at the Kaufman Theater through Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE ABSOLUTION OF WILLIE MAE'
</P>
<P>
   By Joseph Walker; directed by Susan Watson Turner; lighting by
Alan Baron; sets by Gmerice Carter; costumes by Anne Skeete; sound
by Richard Turner; production manager, David Bonilla; management
consultant, Lauren Yates. Presented by the Negro Ensemble Company,
Ms. Turner, producing director; Carole Khan-White, executive
producer. At the Kaufman Theater, 534 W. 42nd St.
</P>
<P>
   With: O.L. Duke (Bubba), Meka Lawrence (Tina), Gabrielle Lee
(Willie Mae), Gregory Marlow (Corey), Sean Allen Rector
(Larry/Jesus), Joyce Sylvester (Minerva) and Michael Wright (Jeff).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
