<HEADER>
A1495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT     11-25 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS COMMENTARY: SEC TRIES TO MAKE COMPANIES TAKE SMALLER
BATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 C.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when the accounting police worried about
companies that tried to avoid reporting losses. Now the cops are
trying to keep companies from taking excessive write-downs.
</P>
<P>
   That such vigilance is necessary is a commentary on the fads and
fashions of Wall Street. Starting in the 1980s, companies
discovered that they could look good if they reported certain kinds
of losses that reflected efforts to become lean and mean. Analysts
were persuaded to ignore such charges and concentrate on operating
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the size and frequency of such write-offs grew.
``Call this behavior Son of Gresham,'' wrote Warren Buffett in
Berkshire Hathaway's latest annual report. ``Bad accounting drives
out good.'' He added that ``the distortion du jour is the
`restructuring charge,' an accounting entry that can, of course, be
legitimate but that all too often is a device for manipulating
earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   The accounting rule makers tried in 1994 and 1995 to put limits
on such write-offs, but their efforts met with success that can be
generously described as limited. Last year, Securities and Exchange
Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt complained that companies were
taking ``big baths'' to get costs out of the way and make their
subsequent profits look better than they were. Now the SEC has
produced a staff accounting bulletin that may reduce the abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing trend here which is disturbing,'' said Lynn
Turner, the SEC's chief accountant, in an interview just after the
bulletin was released on Thanksgiving Eve. He recalled how
Americans used to mock the way European companies could create
reserves to hide earnings swings and said that such things were now
happening in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Turner thinks the rules on such write-offs should be tightened
and said he hoped the Financial Accounting Standards Board would do
just that. But for now, the bulletin simply lays out the existing
rules with details and examples that may make restructuring
reserves smaller and less common. It should strengthen auditors'
backbones when their clients try to take the biggest possible
baths.
</P>
<P>
   When taking a restructuring write-off, companies must
specifically identify and disclose the costs involved and the
anticipated effects on future profits. They must say which plants
will be closed and which departments and locations will make
layoffs. They need to be certain that the restructuring will
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you set up one of these reserves, you have to be pretty
sure that those are the costs you'll incur,'' Turner said. ``When
you get out there two or three years down the road, I don't see how
you can do that.'' If cost estimates prove to be too high,
companies may not use the reserve to hide other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   I've talked to enough companies over the years to know that many
companies have taken a more cavalier approach than the SEC thinks
correct, either in disclosing details of restructuring charges or
in taking write-offs for things that may never happen. A couple of
weeks ago, General Motors reported that it may have to reverse a
good part of a $1.1. billion reserve because the strong economy
means that it won't be cutting jobs as previously planned.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how many companies, confronted
with the new bulletin, decide that they need to make adjustments to
previous restructuring charges. What advice, I asked Turner, would
he give to a chief financial officer in such a position?
</P>
<P>
   ``Take Maalox,'' he said, ``before you eat turkey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
