u a BC-NY-THANKSGIVING-ART-4     11-25 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-THANKSGIVING-ART-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRONT STALLS THE WEATHER, BUT NOT THE PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ohio, Texas)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1, NYT4 and NYT5 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 6:30 Thursday morning, a Macy's official told her
associates the news: The bad-weather front that was supposed to
pass through had stalled. There would be sprinkles, downpours and
only brief moments of no precipitation. The air for the 73rd Macy's
Thanksgiving Day Parade would feel frigid, despite temperatures in
the mid-40s.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of that stalled front were immediate, sharp and
persistent. A thousand cheerleaders shivered in transparent
ponchos. Clowns dressed like slices of pizza jumped up and down to
keep warm. A balloon handler cursed as he opened his gloves and
discovered he had been given two left ones. The knees of drum
majorettes were painfully crimson.
</P>
<P>
   But promptly at 9 a.m., as if with one voice, the massed
thousands shouted, ``Let's have a parade!'' As has happened since
1924, except for wartime years, the parade participants strutted
down Central Park West on a journey to Herald Square and the
beginning of the Christmas season. Along their soggy route, they
passed umbrellas of every size and color bobbing and swaying like
some kind of surreal mushroom patch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it was a lot worse than this,'' said Bruce Rossi, a
jester clown from Union County, N.J. ``It didn't dampen our spirits
then and it won't now.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade's theme, perhaps inescapably, was the millennium.
Each of 14 bands played a song relating to the passage of time. The
O'Fallon Township High School band of O'Fallon, Ill., played ``Does
Anybody Really Know What Time It Is?'' The Jackson High School band
of Massillon, Ohio, played ``Rock Around the Clock.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead balloon was Snoopy, revamped as Macy's ``Millennium
Mascot,'' a true party animal in silly hat blowing a gaudy horn.
Floats included one meant to suggest the ``mystical essence of
time,'' through a sundial, a model of Stonehenge and other
features.
</P>
<P>
   The millennial spirit appeared to be reflected by crowds that
seemed more enthusiastic and larger than last year, when the rain
and cold were both more severe. At Times Square, which will be the
center of the city's New Year's celebration, the congestion was
particularly great.
</P>
<P>
   A group of French tourists left Times Square halfway through the
parade because of the difficulty in seeing bands and floats.
``There were too many people,'' said Benoit Gress of Nice.
</P>
<P>
   The police gave no crowd estimate. Macy's guessed it was at
least the usual 2 million, despite the weather. The only crime
along the parade route was apparently one picked pocket, a police
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There seemed little discussion of the incident two years ago
when the Cat in the Hat balloon _ driven by fierce winds _ escaped
from its handlers and slammed into a lamppost, knocking off the
post's horizontal arm. The falling arm struck Kathleen Caronna,
then 33, of Manhattan in the head and knocked her to the ground.
She spent nearly a month in a coma and is now suing Macy's, the
city and the manufacturer of the lamppost for $395 million.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in a number of changes in the way the parade is
staged, including repositioning lampposts and removing the largest
balloons from the parade. Some parade goers said they missed the
huge balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger balloons added diversity,'' said Tom Olson, 41, a
public relations executive who lives in Rye. ``I miss them,
especially the Cat in the Hat _ but it's understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   One band in the parade on Thursday that marched with an added
purpose was from the Trinity Valley Community College in Athens,
Texas. When the college's band appeared in the parade eight years
ago, one of its members was Nicole Barrett, who is recuperating at
Bellevue Hospital Center after being struck with a paving stone in
a random attack on a midtown street last week. The band marched
again this year, in an appearance scheduled last spring, and wore
purple ribbons in honor of Ms. Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we like about New York?'' said band member Mark
Eubank, seeming to savor a reporter's question. ``The pizza's
good,'' he finally answered.
</P>
<P>
   One of his bandmates dismissed the notion that New Yorkers were
dangerous. ``I'm probably crazier than most people in this town
anyway,'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But the big topic on Thursday was rain, rain and more rain. Not
a few people left early, among them Sue Howell, who had taken her
13-year-old granddaughter to see her first Macy's parade. They
spent about a half-hour perched on an iron railing on Central Park
West before finally bailing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't see anything,'' Ms. Howell said. ``There are so many
people and umbrellas. My son has a nice apartment and we're going
to watch it on television.''
</P>
<P>
   A very few seemed to delight in the inclement weather. Among
them was Olson, of Rye. He built a scaffolding from an aluminum
ladder and covered it with waterproof fabric. He and his family had
an excellent view of the parade, while staying fairly dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a scout leader,'' Olson said. ``I like to be prepared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
