<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: MORE CHARGED FOR CORRUPTION
</P>
<P>
   Shahbaz Sharif has joined his older brother, the ousted former
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, on the list of those accused by the
new military government of treason and hijacking. ``I am innocent,
why am I in police custody?'' the younger Sharif said in a court
appearance. Two other Sharif family loyalists have also been
accused in the case _ Saifur Rehman, the former chief of the
government's anti-corruption unit, and Saeed Mehdi, who was Nawaz
Sharif's principal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: MORE MILITARY SPENDING SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   The military budget should be increased from 2.3 percent of
India's gross domestic product to 3 percent, Defense Minister
George Fernandes told a military conference in New Delhi, according
to the Press Trust of India. The conflict with Pakistan in Kashmir
this year demonstrated the need for more spending, he said.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS: UNESCO'S CHIEF PLEDGES REFORM
</P>
<P>
   UNESCO's new director general, Koichiro Matsuura of Japan,
warned that ``unpopular measures'' would be necessary to
reinvigorate the troubled organization. Indirectly criticizing his
Spanish predecessor, Federico Mayor, he acknowledged that
accusations of ``rampant nepotism'' in UNESCO were ``not
baseless.'' He said he hoped his reforms would woo back the United
States, which left UNESCO in 1984 charging corruption.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: FUEL DELIVERIES DELAYED
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav customs officials continued to hold up 14 tankers of
heating oil donated by the European Union in a pilot project to
help local governments of Nis and Pirot, two opposition-led towns
in southern Serbia. Customs had taken samples from the tankers and
were awaiting results, Yugoslav officials said.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: FARMERS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Some 8,000 French farmers, with animals in tow, gathered under
the Eiffel Tower and vowed to reject any effort to end European
Union farm subsidies at a key meeting of the World Trade
Organization in Seattle next week. The Europeans has resisted a
demand from an Australian-led group of food-exporting countries to
work for an end to all farm subsidies if a new round of global
trade talks is begun in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: PROTESTS FOR AND AGAINST PINOCHET
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet celebrated his 84th birthday, his second
spent under arrest in Britain, with family, friends and a visiting
delegation of high-ranking Chilean military men showing their
support for his fight against extradition to Spain to stand trial
on torture charges.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: AN ASSASSINATION PLOT
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence ministry said it had detained 20 members of a
hard-line religious group, Mahdaviyat, on suspicion of planning to
assassinate President Mohammad Khatami, his predecessor Hashemi
Rafsanjani and the former chief of the judiciary, Mohammad Yazdi.
It was not clear what link there may have been between the supposed
plot and the country's wider political struggle between reformers
and Iran's ruling Muslim clerics.
</P>
</TEXT>
