<HEADLINE>
ABORTION ISSUE BINDS AND SPLITS IN NEW YORK SENATE RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Abortion has emerged as a pivotal issue in the U.S.
Senate race in New York, even though the two presumed candidates,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton, have identical
positions on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is coming under increasing pressure from the state
Conservative Party to change his stand from opposing a ban on a
form of late-term abortion. At the same time, the leader of New
York's most powerful abortion rights group said this week that the
mayor's strong support for their position would make it hard for
the group to endorse Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Although both candidates have something to lose on the issue _
Mrs. Clinton will not be happy if the abortion rights group remains
neutral in the race _ both Democrats and Republicans said this week
that it is Giuliani who seems backed into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Kelli Conlin, the executive director of the New York State
affiliate of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League, known as NARAL, said she was ``personally very torn''
between ``two people who I know and like.'' She added that while
Mrs. Clinton ``has been a motivating force behind the most
pro-choice presidency in our history,'' Giuliani ``has really been
there for us'' and that ``it's really important for us, if he
stands by us, to support candidates like that, because they are a
minority in their party.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Conlin said that the New York affiliate of NARAL would
likely stay neutral in the Senate race as long as Giuliani
continues to oppose a ban on the late-term abortion procedure,
which is sometimes called partial-birth abortion by its opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Michelman, president of the national organization in
Washington, said her group might not take the same course. Ms.
Michelman went out of her way this week to praise Mrs. Clinton as
deserving of special consideration because of her longstanding and
steadfast support of abortion rights. ``Her strong advocacy might
set her apart a little, even though both of them are pro-choice,''
Ms. Michelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Michael R. Long, the chairman of the state
Conservative Party, continues to insist that Giuliani must change
his position on late-term abortion before the mayor can receive the
party's endorsement in the Senate race. The endorsement is crucial
_ no Republican since Sen. Jacob Javits in 1974 has won statewide
office in New York without it _ and carries with it an estimated
200,000 to 300,000 votes. Those votes could be the margin of
victory in a race as close as the one between Mrs. Clinton and
Giuliani is expected to be.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Conlin, who served on Giuliani's transition team after his
1993 election as mayor, met last month with Mrs. Clinton and then
later with Bruce Teitelbaum, the director of the mayor's Senate
exploratory committee. Mrs. Clinton asked for the abortion rights
group's support, Ms. Conlin said. Ms. Conlin told Mrs. Clinton that
``no one has declared at this point, a lot is going to shake out
eventually, and right now we're going to have to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   In her meeting with Teitelbaum, Ms. Conlin said that she tried
to ``clarify'' the issue of late-term abortion in the hope that
Teitelbaum would take her views to the mayor. ``I have no
indication whatsoever that the mayor is wavering,'' Ms. Conlin
said. ``I just know the pressure he is under.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the mayor's position appears firm: Earlier this month,
Giuliani told The Albany Times-Union that he would not support a
ban on late-term abortions and that he supports the state's
abortion law. ``New York shouldn't be ashamed of the law,''
Giuliani said. ``That law, I think, is a fair one and works to
create the necessary scope of freedom and prohibition.''
</P>
<P>
   At a City Hall news conference this week, Giuliani brushed off a
question about late-term abortion, saying that ``my position on
abortion is precisely the same today as it was yesterday. I haven't
changed overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   If the mayor holds to his position, he risks hundreds of
thousands of conservative votes. And members of both parties say it
is unlikely that he could make them up with women voters attracted
to his abortion rights position or people who might admire him for
sticking to principle.
</P>
<P>
   If the mayor changes his position, he risks relentless bulletins
from Mrs. Clinton's campaign of flip-flopping and accusations that
he yielded in a cynical display of political expediency. ``He's got
to evaluate if he does change his position what negative fallout
there would be,'' said Guy Molinari, the Staten Island borough
president, who is a close friend and Republican ally of the mayor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Long first announced his endorsement conditions for the mayor
last summer, and almost immediately Giuliani called asking if he
was willing to discuss the issue. Long said yes. But that was in
early August, and since then, as Long has repeated his position on
television and to reporters, the mayor has responded with silence.
Long now sounds increasingly impatient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party is still open, we're willing to discuss the issue,
but quite frankly, the clock is starting to tick,'' Long said. He
added that his party's convention to decide on an endorsement is in
May, and that if the mayor should decide in, say, April, to change
his position, that would be too late.
</P>
<P>
   Long also said that he was not overly impressed with recent
actions by Giuliani that theoretically might have pleased him:
Cutting off financing for the Brooklyn Museum of Art for an exhibit
that the mayor deemed pornographic, a speech at the Reagan Library
lauding the former president and endorsements of upstate Republican
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not exactly talking about a movement conservative,''
Long said. ``That's the problem. All of the sudden it's campaign
time and he starts doing a few little things on the edges, and
people start saying, `Gee, he's moving onto Republican things.' But
I've watched him for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Conservative Party has something to lose by not
endorsing Giuliani _ its members have been awarded jobs in the
administrations of Republicans, like Gov. George Pataki, whom they
endorsed _ patronage is less important in a Senate race because a
senator controls relatively few jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Long, meanwhile, says that his party will run someone else on
its ticket if his members do not endorse the mayor. He also said he
is operating on principle. ``In my belief, it's about saving a
partially born baby,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Medically, the abortion procedure at issue is called intact
dilation and evacuation, because the feet of the fetus are
extracted first and the skull is broken before being suctioned
through the birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate has voted twice to ban late-term abortion, but
both measures were vetoed by President Clinton. As of last month,
30 states had enacted their own bans, although 17 of the bans had
been blocked or overturned by federal courts as unconstitutional.
Opponents of such bans say they are part of a conservative strategy
to limit abortion rights in general, and that the language of the
bans is written so broadly as to outlaw most abortion procedures
after the first trimester of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's position on the issue is in fact more liberal than
some other Republicans and Democrats who support abortion rights.
Those politicians who favor abortion rights and also a ban on
late-term abortion include Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the New
York Democrat who is leaving the seat expected to be sought by Mrs.
Clinton and Giuliani; Edward Koch, the former Democratic mayor of
New York City; and Susan Molinari, the former Republican
congresswoman from Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani, a Roman Catholic, once advocated that the
Supreme Court overturn Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 decision that
legalized abortion, he changed his position in his first race for
mayor in 1989. His opponents said it was merely an exercise to get
votes in a Democratic city, but Fran Reiter, who was at the time an
adviser to Giuliani and the chairwoman of the Liberal Party in New
York City, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess in a very cynical way you could look at it that way,
which is, this is New York City, you have to be pro-choice,'' she
said. ``But he's gone way beyond being pro-choice.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in fact Ms. Reiter and Ms. Conlin who say they helped
Giuliani formulate his public position on abortion in 1989. Ms.
Reiter, who became a deputy mayor under Giuliani, also says that
she helped Giuliani arrive at his position, around 1997, on
late-term abortion. ``He took a look at what the law currently was
in the state,'' Ms. Reiter said. ``He was perfectly comfortable''
with that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
