</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAMIBIA-REFUGEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS FLEEING FIGHTING IN ANGOLA OVERWHELM VILLAGE IN NAMIBIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAHENGE, Namibia _ With fighting between rebels and government
forces escalating along the southern edge of Angola, thousands
living in the area, long an Angolan rebel stronghold, have fled
across the river border over the last nine days and taken refuge
outside the police station in this rural village.
</P>
<P>
   But with no toilets, few tents and only one water faucet for the
more than 2,300 refugees encamped here, the government has been
scrambling to move them before the seasonal rains, which are
expected to begin any day and which could turn the unsanitary
environment here into a public health emergency.
</P>
<P>
   For the Namibian government, presidential and legislative
elections next week make the situation all the more urgent. The
police station in this village is a polling site, and the last
thing authorities want, they say, is a mass of refugees to confuse
or inhibit voters in the area, which is a stronghold for the
governing party.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts to bus refugees south to a resettlement camp in
central Namibia have so far failed, despite the presence of more
than 5,000 fellow Angolans at the camp, in a town called Osire.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more Angolans are believed to be dispersed throughout
northern Namibia, many staying with relatives, so this country is
not unaccustomed to refugees from its neighbor. But the stream of
people crossing the Okavango River this month is greater than ever,
authorities say. ``We have never had anything like this here,''
said Hesdy Rathling, who heads the Namibia office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, when buses arrived to begin taking
refugees to Osire, the first family took almost a half-hour to load
themselves and their belongings. By Wednesday evening only 98
people had boarded camp-bound buses, and Thursday just 269 people
made the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of Angolans, which began Nov. 16, is a result of a
major Angolan offensive in a 25-year-old war with the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, known by its Portuguese
acronym, UNITA. In recent weeks the Angolan authorities have
claimed major victories over the rebels, asserting that they are
close to capturing or killing the Unita leader, Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
   Cuandocubango, the Angolan region across the river from the
swelling refugee camp, has been a UNITA stronghold and generally
out of the government's reach, but from the refugees' vague
accounts of fighting there, Angolan government forces have made
inroads against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Bongi, said he had fled a village a few miles away from
here. ``I ran away from the fighting, from the MPLA,'' Bongi, 23,
said through an interpreter, referring to the government army by
the initials for the governing party, the Popular Movement for the
Liberation of Angola. ``I want to stay in Namibia because it's not
good in Angola.''
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Cambinda sat nearby, in the shade of one of the giant
fig trees that provide the only relief from the 98-degree heat. She
said her seven children and several other relatives had felt
compelled to leave their village, Mangonda. ``The soldiers of UNITA
every day were killing people,'' she said as she braided a friend's
hair, with her year-old son rolling around on her lap.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly women, small children and elderly men, the refugees
arrived here in Namibia not only with their tattered blankets and
rusting pots but with their herds of livestock. Thousands of
cattle, hundreds of goats and dozens of chickens, pigs and dogs
wander the sand-swept fields outside the police station. What to do
with the animals is just one complication facing the government as
it tries to move the refugees to the Osire resettlement camp.
</P>
<P>
   Separated from Namibia by nationality but not by ethnicity, many
of the refugees have said that they want to stay in the Namibian
northern border area, which is home to thousands of fellow Cuangari
and Nyemba people, many of them relatives. Despite what Namibian
officials describe as Osire's better housing and facilities, few
refugees want to be bused to Osire, more than 360 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   But the government says it cannot allow the people to stay here,
because the site is ripe for an outbreak of cholera. Even if
adequate water and sanitation could be provided, the site is too
close to the fighting, Niilo Taapopi, Namibia's permanent secretary
for home affairs, said this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stone's throw away,'' he said after an emergency
meeting with aid workers and government officials. ``If somebody
wanted to attack it, it's just across the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a plea from Taapopi, who came to the camp this week, the
refugees remained reluctant and the effort to relocate them got off
to a slow and confusing start, which was compounded by a shortage
of buses.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with the rest, quickly, is a pressing problem for the
government. ``We want the elections to be free and fair,'' Taapopi
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
