<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GERMANY-ECON-2TAKES-N     11-25 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ECON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GERMANY'S CONSENSUS ECONOMY AT RISK OF UNRAVELING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder could scarcely
conceal a triumphant grin as he announced a $2.2 billion bailout of
Germany's biggest construction company on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banks, and I say this with the utmost respect, accepted
their economic and social responsibility,'' he said after
browbeating a consortium of banks to reverse its previous decision
against rescuing the builder, Philipp Holzmann AG.
</P>
<P>
   But in reality, this has been a disastrous week for Germany's
``consensus economy'' and the deeply rooted idea that capitalism's
hard edges should be moderated though a partnership of business,
labor and government.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday, consensus capitalism has been assaulted on two
distinct but closely related fronts: the hostile bid for Mannesmann
AG, the engineering and telecommunications concern, and the
collapse of Holzmann, a huge industrial enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   First came the shock of the $127.7 billion hostile takeover
offer for Mannesmann, one of Germany's most successful companies,
by Vodafone AirTouch of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's bid has unleashed a political outcry here about
``casino capitalism,'' ruthless corporate ``sharks'' and the
reckless destruction of ``corporate culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the collapse of Holzmann, a 150-year-old pillar of
German industry that employs 17,000 people but has been mismanaged
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Schroeder's last-minute pressure and government loan
guarantees of 250 million marks, or $131 million, Holzmann will
indeed be rescued with its second major bailout in two years.
</P>
<P>
   But the rescue cannot undo the effect of events leading up to
it. In a departure from previous rescues, German banks were unable
to agree on a bailout after several rounds of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, Holzmann's biggest creditor and biggest
shareholder, tried to arrange the bailout but ran into blunt and
bruising criticism from other banks that simply refused to go
along.
</P>
<P>
   The banks repeatedly ignored political pressure and cries of
outrage from unions, forcing Holzmann to file for bankruptcy on
Wednesday. Only the combination of government sweeteners and
Schroeder's intervention turned them around.
</P>
<P>
   Though different, the Holzmann and Mannesmann cases both reveal
how far German business has evolved from ``Rhineland capitalism,''
a system based on tightly intertwined networks of banks, industrial
manufacturers and powerful labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   That system, epitomized by the role that Deutsche Bank tried to
take in rescuing Holzmann, is grounded on the idea that all the
major players in the economy work together in pursuit of consensus
rather than conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It assumed that banks would finance industry and come to the
rescue in times of need. It assumed that corporations would respect
one another's territory, partly because the big banks are
shareholders in the biggest industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   It also assumed that corporations would avoid conflict with
labor. Wages would be set through nationwide negotiations between
industry and labor. Unions would have a direct hand in corporate
``co-determination'' _ with representation on corporate supervisory
boards and union-controlled ``work councils'' that approve many
day-to-day decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that remains in force today. But the once-solid
alliances are breaking apart under the pressure of global
competition, international shareholders and Western Europe's own
unstoppable process of economic integration.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Germany Inc. was in a clear state of unraveling
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's hostile takeover bid for Mannesmann, aimed at
creating the world's biggest wireless communications company,
provoked almost predictable accusations about Anglo-Saxon raiders
intent merely on breaking up successful companies.
</P>
<P>
   This week's cover on the German business magazine Wirtschaft
Woche harks back to the Allies' D-Day assault on Normandy in World
War II, featuring an army of businessmen rushing onto a beach. The
headline was ``Invasion! Attack on the consensus society.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the attempted takeover came from a British company
appeared to provoke less anger than the hostile nature of the
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Unions and political leaders, including Schroeder, darkly warned
that the hostile bid would lead to the dismemberment of a
successful company and the loss of jobs. The chancellor said
hostile takeovers ``destroy a company's culture'' and warned that
aspiring predators ``should not underestimate the power of German
co-determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the week progressed, Schroeder's government provided
little hint of interference. Werner Mueller, the economics
minister, warned against letting nationalism dominate the
discussion, noting that German companies had bought many major
foreign corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Eichel, Germany's finance minister, suggested that the
European Union needed to harmonize its rules governing takeovers.
But he studiously avoided any suggestion that hostile takeovers be
restricted.
</P>
<P>
   All that could change. Schroeder is a man of chameleonlike
views, not at all worried about reversing his positions if the
political winds seem to call for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   From the standpoint of many German companies, it is clearly
dangerous to erect new obstacles. In the last two years, Volkswagen
has acquired Rolls-Royce Motor Cars, Deutsche Bank has acquired
Bankers Trust in New York, and Daimler-Benz has acquired Chrysler.
Mannesmann has itself been one of the most active foreign
acquirers, buying control of large cellular telephone companies in
Italy and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   It was a measure of how much things have changed that the leader
of Allianz AG, the German insurance giant that is at the heart of
the country's system of interlocking corporate ownership, adamantly
defended hostile takeovers this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hostile takeovers in Europe must not be a taboo,'' said
Henning Schulte-Noelle, chairman of Allianz, in an interview with
the newspaper Les Echos. ``The change of ownership of a company is
a matter of value and not of the national flag,'' he added. ``From
now on our domestic market is Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of Holzmann provided a dramatic counterpoint to the
debate about ``consensus'' capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Holzmann, a company with $7 billion in sales and a substantial
international presence, has been losing money for the last four
years, thanks to a steep downturn in the construction business and
real estate prices.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank led a major financial overhaul in 1997, installing
Heinrich Binder as its chief executive and naming one of its board
members as chairman of the Holzmann supervisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those efforts, Holzmann shocked its creditors and
shareholders last week by announcing that it had suddenly
discovered 2.4 billion marks' worth of soured loans dating back to
the early 1990s _ most for eastern German real estate. Why the bad
loans remained hidden until now is a matter being investigated by
German prosecutors and furious investors. Binder has blamed his
predecessors for the problems.
</P>
<P>
   But there seems little doubt that Holzmann is a sick company
that has been less than candid with both investors and creditors.
Commerzbank, one of the banks that balked at another bailout,
argued that much of the blame also rested with Deutsche Bank, which
assumed a paternalistic role and yet remained oblivious to the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of many, the banks not only failed to agree on a
bailout but angrily attacked both Holzmann and Deutsche Bank for
the mess. Talks broke down last week, then again on Sunday and once
again on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder then swooped into town Wednesday evening, vowing to
bridge the gap and bringing government loan guarantees to smooth
the talks. The guarantees, plus the intense glare of publicity and
the pressure from thousands of protesting workers, finally turned
the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on Thursday the reaction was decidedly mixed. ``If companies
in the future do what they want, and the state comes in at the end
with 250 million marks in help, that cannot make any sense for a
social market economy,'' said Mario Ohoven, president of the German
federation of ``mittelsstand'' or middle-size companies. ``If that
happens, we will have a state-run economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the developments for both Mannesmann and
Holzmann struck many Germans as bookends to the changes coursing
through their once-orderly economy.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seemed happy about either hostile takeovers or the abrupt
collapse of a company employing 17,000 people in Germany. But not
many people had good feelings about the alternatives either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, in the case of Mannesmann, one could still think
that the barbarians lurked outside'' the workplace of Germany Inc.,
wrote Andreas Molitor in Germany's weekly newspaper of opinion, Die
Zeit. ``But since the collapse of Philipp Holzmann, it is clear
that that barbarians are also right in our own midst.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
