<HEADER>
A1528 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-COX     11-25 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candlelight service replaces Texas A&AMP;M bonfire
 &HT;    By Christian Davenport
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ With a setting sun and candlelight
replacing the annual Texas A&AMP;M University bonfire, an estimated
70,000 people came here Thursday to memorialize the students killed
in last week's crash of the bonfire structure.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying candles, they stood soundlessly at the site where the
40-foot, cake-like bonfire stack came crashing down on Nov. 18,
killing 12 and injuring 27. The hand-held flames formed a
flickering ring around the site.
</P>
<P>
   The vigil was in stark contrast to the normal revelry that
charges this college town on the eve before the heralded football
game against the University of Texas. Normally, thousands gather
around the massive bonfire, which can reach 55-feet high, cheer
their team, and hold a ``yell practice,'' where they rehearse their
team's chants.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, however, there was no bonfire for only the second
time since 1909.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, there's a lot of cheering, a lot of whooping,
there's so much enthusiasm,'' said Sonny Wellmeyer, whose daughter
Kristin, 19, is a sophomore. ``But this year, it's like a wake.''
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the accident remained a mystery Thursday. Ray
Bowen, the university president, has said he will appoint a task
force to investigate the bonfire's collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Injured student Dominic Braus was released from the hospital
Thursday, while Milton ``Chip'' Thiel was released on Wednesday.
Two students remain hospitalized, with Bill Davis finishing
physical therapy at St. Joseph's Regional Health Center and John
Comstock listed in critical condition at College Station Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' mother, Cheryl Davis, who spent Thanksgiving at her son's
side, said he's ``doing great. We're very, very thankful,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, getting to the bonfire site has been its own
excitement, with drivers honking and people waving at nearly every
car on the road, said James Adams, a 20-year-old junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then, when you come across the highway, you can see the
bonfire sticking up, silhouetted against the sky. You throw your
stuff down, find your friends and get out here,'' Adams said.
``It's like waiting for a jet to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, though, Adams handed out candles to the people
streaming to the bonfire site, and the highways lacked the sounds
of exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   A fence surrounding the site became a makeshift memorial in a
town overcome with symbols to memorialize the dead. Walking slowly
and quietly as if at a museum exhibition, families walked around
the perimeter, heads down, studying the flowers, poems and ribbons
that had festooned the fence. Behind it, the bonfire logs had been
piled up neatly into rows.
</P>
<P>
   Families at the site spoke softly, if at all. And although there
were hundreds walking around at the site in the mid-day sunshine,
the only sounds were the breeze blowing through the flower
bouquets, muffled sniffles, and birds chirping in the surrounding
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Those who came to remember the students killed and injured in
the tragedy left class rings, towels, Aggie baseball caps, flags,
and signs that read, ``We will never forget you.''
</P>
<P>
   Flags across town are at half-staff, motorists who drive past
the bonfire site have their headlights on in a symbol of
remembrance, and maroon and white ribbons, the Aggie colors, are
pinned to virtually ever chest.
</P>
<P>
   On a plywood billboard that served as a giant greeting card, Kim
Harrell, a 20-year-old Texas A&AMP;M sophomore could find just a small
space to scribble her thought in between the hundreds of messages
already there. She wrote, simply: ``Always in out hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look around campus without seeing someone wearing a
ribbon,'' she said. ``This whole week has been very, very solemn.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few feet away, Pam Little laid a rose at each of the
twelve crosses erected alongside the fence. The she stepped back,
looked at them, and cried in her husband's arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes us realize how much we have in common,'' said Little,
who named her 17-year old son Kyle after the football stadium.
``This time of year we always hate the University of Texas. But now
this is bringing us together. But you hate for it to be something
like this to make you stop and realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   At their Thanksgiving table, Kyle Little said they all said a
prayer and ate. This year, he said, it was much more quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Austin American-Statesman staff writer Janet Jacobs contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
