u a BC-PHILLY-HOMELESS-NYT &LR;      11-25 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-HOMELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BACK HOME CAFE' GIVES PEOPLE A 2ND CHANCE AT LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Gary Ackerman was making sandwiches at the Back
Home Cafe with his usual devotion. He neatly stacked thick slices
of fresh roast beef, ham and turkey between rolls lined with
lettuce, and spooned up mounds of tuna salad made with broccoli and
toasted almonds.
</P>
<P>
   But just as he pulled out the Saran wrap, Ackerman, 49, a
slightly built man with graying hair and dimples, stopped. ``I
forgot the cheese,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has to constantly remind himself about the cheese in the ham
and cheese, he said, explaining, ``I hate cheese.'' While
Ackerman's aversion to cheese can sometimes be a problem on the
job, his illness, schizophrenia, which he controls with medication,
is not.
</P>
<P>
   The Back Home Cafe anchors Gary Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
   He works alongside people who understand his struggles: Tracy
Young, another sandwich maker, is also schizophrenic. Marge Kramer,
at the cash register, fights against paralyzing depression. Lanier
Evans, who makes deliveries, recently marked his one-year
anniversary without drugs. Dennis Griffin, the cook, has been
homeless, and is a recovering alcoholic. Annette Mills, also a
cook, is a 40-year-old mother of six, who has just gotten off
public assistance, thanks to her job at the Back Home Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wasn't working, I started isolating, staying up in my
room,'' Ackerman said during a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a tendency to go back in time: `If only I'd done this
differently, if I'd known about my mental illness sooner.' When I'm
working, all the bad feelings go out the window. I feel like I'm a
part of society.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman has been at the Back Home Cafe since it was started,
three years ago, by a Catholic nun, Sister Mary Scullion, and Joan
Dawson-McConnon, who have been helping people who are homeless,
mentally ill and overcoming addictions to build meaningful lives
for two decades. The restaurant, at 1515 Fairmount Ave., north of
City Hall, is inside an Art Deco building where Sister Scullion and
Ms. Dawson-McConnon have built 48 apartments for the homeless, and
which also contains the office for their organization, Project
Home.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning before Thanksgiving, the Back Home Cafe was
humming. Griffin, 42, who knows what it is to be hungry, was
dishing up enormous servings of eggs, grits and omelets. The prices
are a bargain: $1.99 for two eggs with home fried potatoes or
grits, toast and coffee; $1.79 for a three-egg cheese omelet with
toast. If the Back Home Cafe were more interested in profits _ it
barely breaks even _ Griffin's portions would be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis' servings are ridiculous,'' said Lynn Giordano, the
former cafe manager, who now does job training at Project Home and
had stopped in for coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Giordano poured a cup of tea for Georgianna Simmons. Ms.
Simmons, 61, lost her toes to frostbite during a brutal winter on
the streets, and has trouble keeping her balance. She recently
broke her shoulder, and is on a sabbatical as a vegetable chopper
at the cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Sabbaticals are freely given at the restaurant, with Mrs. Kramer
watching out for those who need time off. ``Marge will notice if
someone is off their medication,'' Ms. Giordano said. ``Every once
in awhile, someone will flip out.''
</P>
<P>
   The new cafe manager, Michael O'Halloran, took over in
September, giving up his job as a sous chef at a fashionable
downtown restaurant called Fork. The community atmosphere at the
cafe appealed to him.
</P>
<P>
   Both the atmosphere and the food have been praised by Rick
Nichols, the food essayist at The Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said he was nervous about the new manager at first.
``The hardest part was when Lynn left, and Mike came in,'' he said.
``Was he going to let me go? Is he going to change this or that? I
don't like change.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman was making sandwiches alongside Tracy Young, 32, who is
his best friend. Both men live in Project Home efficiency
apartments downtown, with their restaurant wages helping to pay the
rent.
</P>
<P>
   As everyone at the cafe knows, Young spends most of his money in
Chinatown, buying porcelain dishes and furniture. He has a passion
for everything Chinese and Egyptian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be in the restaurant business for the rest of
my life,'' he said. ``I really would like to lecture on Chinese and
Egyptian history.'' He tries to sneak Cantonese opera compact disks
onto the cafe CD player, but his co-workers can't take the music
for long.
</P>
<P>
   Young said he knows what the public thinks of the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're portrayed in the movies as trying to stab people, and
cut off people's heads,'' he said. ``People don't understand mental
illness. They put all those negative stories about mentally ill
people in the newspapers. They don't put in the paper that people
are getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I try really hard to present myself as normal as possible so
people won't be afraid of me,'' Young said. With health care,
counseling and decent housing, the 24 people who work at the Back
Home Cafe are all getting better. Ackerman says he no longer hears
voices telling him to kill himself. Now, he said, he wants to help
others. ``I want to make people happy,'' he said. `There's no use
moping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
