<HEADLINE>
APPEALS BY PASSING ARIZO NA'S HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A ``plain error of fact'' in decisions by the U.S. Supreme Court
and U.S. Court of Appeals has thrown the criminal-appeals process
into chaos in Arizona and must be corrected quickly, the state
Attorney General's Office contends.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling this month by a three-judge panel of the 9th U.S.
Circuit's federal appellate court allows appeals in most criminal
cases to bypass Arizona's highest court altogether, but in effect
also permits them to be filed simultaneously in state and federal
court, doubling the workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ensuing dramatic drain on federal judicial resources is
easy to foresee,'' says a petition for a rehearing filed by state
Attorney General Janet Napolitano's office.
</P>
<P>
   The petition seeks to undo the ruling through a rarely granted
review by a majority of the 21 appellate judges of the 9th U.S.
Circuit, based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, prosecutors for the state say, the new ``bypass the
Arizona Supreme Court rule'' set forth Nov. 2 could open the door
to thousands of new appeals in cases dating back as far as 10 years
to an Arizona decision that prosecutors say the federal courts have
misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a completely ungrounded basis, they've come up with this
devastating opinion,'' the author of the petition, Assistant
Attorney General Eric J. Olsson of the Tucson office, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the court ruling raises ``serious questions
as to whether future federal habeas proceedings in the District of
Arizona can be conducted in any orderly manner,'' the petition
says.
</P>
<P>
   A writ of habeas corpus is a federal court's order for
authorities to justify holding someone prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, after a state prisoner's direct appeal has made its
way through a mandatory review by the state Court of Appeals, it
can be forwarded for review by the state's top court. The state
Supreme Court has the option of reviewing it or not; but in the
past, none of the claims could be carried to the next higher level,
U.S. District Court, without giving the state court a chance to
consider them first.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the bulk of more than 500 such petitions filed annually
could go straight to federal court or to both places, resulting in
duplicated effort, confusion over what happens if rulings differ in
each court, and removal of the state's highest court from deciding
a number of appeals issues.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred prisoners a year already seek habeas corpus
writs in U.S. District Court, but the number of complaints in their
petitions is greatly reduced from their initial filings.
</P>
<P>
   Many times, inmates file their appeals without an attorney,
submitting briefs of varying degrees of sophistication in longhand
and often presenting long lists of complaints about trial errors,
infringement of rights and misconduct by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Sequential handling of appeals through what amounts to a chain
of judicial command is important for efficiency, prosecutors say,
because the number of claims is winnowed at each stage.
</P>
<P>
   It was a petition filed on his own in 1994 by Samuel W. Swoopes,
an inmate at the state prison in Florence, that led to this month's
decision by the 9th U.S. Circuit panel.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes has filed numerous appeals since being convicted in
Tucson in 1986 and sentenced to 42 years' imprisonment for armed
robbery, kidnapping and sexual assault. His latest appeal, which
under complex rules should be his last, reached the U.S. Supreme
Court after his claim was rejected by the 9th U.S. Circuit
appellate court.
</P>
<P>
   After the nation's highest court ruled in June in a similar case
from Illinois, it instructed the appellate court to take a fresh
look at the Swoopes petition.
</P>
<P>
   To the astonishment of prosecutors, the 9th U.S. Circuit panel's
decision has exactly the opposite effect of what the highest court
five months earlier had set forth as a rule: If a state court has
the option, but not necessarily the obligation, to review an
appeal, a prisoner must give it a chance to do so before moving on
to the federal level.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes alleges that his right to due process was violated by
the unusual way in which he was identified as one of three men who
broke into a home, robbed three occupants at gunpoint and raped a
woman. (See accompanying story.)
</P>
<P>
   A federal public defender in Tucson, Javier Chon-Lopez, was
appointed to represent Swoopes in his appeal when the issue reached
the 9th U.S. Circuit level.
</P>
<P>
   Chon-Lopez declined to comment on specifics of the case. He said
he is not allowed to submit an answer to the prosecutors' request
for a rehearing unless invited to do so by the appellate bench.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, appellate court spokesman Mark Mendenhall said
that of more than 700 requests submitted annually for rehearings en
banc _ by a majority of the court _ only 12 to 20 are granted. Most
involve civil, rather than criminal cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``bypass the state Supreme Court'' ruling affects only
Arizona. The Swoopes opinion says it applies to appeals of all
criminal cases except those involving the death penalty or life
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   The central mistake in the ruling is ``an arcane fiction'' that
grew mainly from federal court misreadings of a 1989 state
decision, according to the petition crafted by Olsson and Paul J.
McMurdie, the Phoenix-based chief of criminal appeals for the
Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a comedy of errors that just isn't funny at all,'' Olsson
said in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Both the U.S. Supreme Court and the 9th U.S. Circuit panel
interpreted the decade-old case to mean that Arizona's Supreme
Court doesn't normally handle appeals and doesn't care if the cases
go directly to U.S. District Court, Olsson explained.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not true, either as a matter of policy or in actual
practice, he said. The three-judge panel was provided statistics
disproving it before the members ruled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Swoopes panel's decision plays havoc with the long-standing
principle that state courts have the first opportunity to rule on
questions of federal constitutional law raised by state prisoners,
the petition says.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's petition denounces the Swoopes decision
as ``fraught with errors of fact and law'' and a ``gross
misperception'' of the U.S. Supreme Court's ruling in the
``O'Sullivan vs. Boerckel'' case from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The petition is worded less sharply in maintaining that the
nation's highest court misportrayed the willingness of Arizona's
Supreme Court to review appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The highest court may have relied on lower federal courts'
erroneous interpretations of earlier cases ``without questioning
their accuracy or making any independent inquiry into Arizona
law,'' the prosecutors' petition suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel in Swoopes strayed into the language of an
independent O'Sullivan opinion by Justice David Souter that,
although concurring with the result, differed from O'Connor's
majority opinion, Olsson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really an enigma to me'' how the appellate panel could
use the O'Sullivan ruling as the basis for a completely opposite
conclusion five months later in the Arizona case, Olsson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Kamman can be reached at (602) 444-4816 or
jon.kamman(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
