<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AMARILLO-TEENS-NYT &LR;      11-25 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMARILLO-TEENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A MURDER TRIAL, AMARILLO ASKS, `IS THIS A TOLERANT PLACE?'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMARILLO, Texas _ While there are all sorts of teen-age cliques
in this Texas Panhandle city, it is the punks and the preps who
have always collided. None of the insults ever escalated beyond
fistfights, though, until one of the punks, Brian Deneke, was run
over in a street brawl, killed by a prep in a Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years since, the case has stirred the city,
particularly with the verdict in September: Charged with murder,
Dustin Camp, the 17-year-old in the Cadillac, was instead convicted
of manslaughter and sentenced to nothing more than probation. He
walked out of the courthouse while Deneke's friends wept at an
outcome that has only intensified their belief that in the
conservative culture of Amarillo, some lives do not count as much
as others.
</P>
<P>
   To Camp's supporters, the outcome was just: he had no criminal
record and acted, his lawyer argued, only to aid a friend whose
life appeared endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, the events surrounding the killing have
prompted unexpected soul searching in Amarillo. Not only have those
events become a galvanizing symbol to the largely blue-collar
punks, who see themselves as marginalized and outcast, but they
have also caused much of the town to ask a painful question: Are we
a tolerant place, as accepting of young people like the punks as we
are of the clean-cut, mostly affluent preps, some of whom come from
Amarillo's most elite families?
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably be a memory of a lifetime for a great many
people,'' Rebecca King, the local district attorney, said of the
case. ``It made us turn in and look at ourselves and see if we can
do things better.''
</P>
<P>
   The very land of Amarillo seems to inspire conformity, with
uninterrupted flat prairie of cattle ranches and cotton farms
outside the city. There is a local eccentric, Stanley Marsh III, a
millionaire whose famous piece of Americana, the Cadillac Ranch and
its row of 10 Caddys buried halfway in the ground, attracts a
smattering of tourists. But the individualism chosen by Brian
Deneke, just an obscure teen-ager who dropped out of high school
and wore his hair in a spiked mohawk, carried a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always getting jumped and harassed,'' said his father,
Mike Deneke. ``We would tell him if he was going to dress that way
and live that lifestyle, it would happen. He would tell us that
people shouldn't be judged that way.''
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, Camp's lawyer, Warren Clark, aggressively trained
a focus on Brian Deneke and his friends, characterizing them as
violent thugs. The brawl occurred on Dec. 12, 1997, provoked by a
confrontation a week earlier between Camp and some friends of
Deneke's. Testimony as to what happened was often conflicting, but
there was agreement that both sides gathered outside an all-night
pancake house before moving across the street to fight. Clark
portrayed the punks as the aggressors and established that at least
one carried a bat, another a chain.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the fighting erupted, Camp drove away from the scene
with two friends in his late-model Cadillac. But he quickly doubled
back and plowed his car over Deneke. Camp returned, Clark argued,
because he had seen Deneke beating one of his friends with a chain
(a contention denied by Deneke's friends).
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors argued that Camp acted not in defense of his friend
but in a drunken fury. One of his friends in the car, Elise
Thompson, class valedictorian, testified for the prosecution that
Camp's car jumped a median and rammed Deneke and that Camp yelled
moments later: ``I'm a Ninja in my Caddy! I bet he liked that
one!''
</P>
<P>
   Although the jurors decided on manslaughter rather than murder,
it was their sentence that truly astonished many here. During the
trial's sentencing phase, Camp took the stand and apologized to the
Deneke family and to his own. The courtroom was divided into two
warring camps _ the punks seated behind the prosecution, the
football players and the preps seated behind the defense _ as the
jury handed up no long prison term but instead 10 years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   The court of public opinion reacted swiftly and, in the minds of
some, surprisingly. Letters of outrage poured into the local
newspaper. A television station's poll found that a majority of
residents thought Camp should have gone to prison. Fearing
reprisals, the judge sealed the names of the jurors, none of whom
have spoken out on their own. Callers to the city's top talk radio
program debated whether Amarillo was a tolerant place.
</P>
<P>
   Deneke's friends have created the Brian Deneke Memorial
Committee, printing T-shirts and sponsoring two concerts and a
candlelight vigil in his memory. Other groups that consider
themselves on Amarillo's margins, like gays and African-Americans,
have joined the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Kel Seliger, Amarillo's four-term mayor, said the case had
prompted him to speak out more forcefully on behalf of respect for
differences among people. But it would be wrong, he said, to
condemn Amarillo because of the verdict. ``It was not a community
verdict,'' he said. ``It was 12 people.''
</P>
<P>
   In their small house on the edge of Amarillo's affluent Wolflin
neighborhood, Mike and Debbie Camp quietly attributed the public
outrage to what they described as distorted local media coverage.
Unlike the upper-income parents of many of their son's friends, the
Camps, owners of a local garage, are middle class. They dispute any
suggestion that the case involves rich versus poor, establishment
versus outcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about Dustin seeing his friends getting killed and
doing something about it,'' Debbie Camp said. ``He was very brave
and courageous, and we're supportive of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Camps say they have received 1,000 letters of support.
Dustin, now 18, works at his family's garage, and he plans to go to
college this winter. The Camps say that ``Dustin and his friends
are the kind of people you would want your son to be or your
daughter to be.'' Mrs. Camp sees youths like Brian Deneke as ``lost
children of God.''
</P>
<P>
   In their small house in a lower-income neighborhood, Mike and
Betty Deneke quietly grieve for their son. They did not recognize
as Brian the violent aggressor whom the defense lawyer described at
the trial. They remember a nice, smiling youth _ far from perfect
but not bad, even if he looked different. Mike Deneke recalled that
he initially resisted as his son began to change his appearance.
Once, he said, he even tried to cut Brian's hair.
</P>
<P>
   But then he changed his mind, particularly as he met the
teen-agers with spiked hair and pierced noses who came into their
house with Brian. ``Some of them were kicked out and couldn't go
home,'' he said. ``Some of them didn't want to go home. We didn't
want that to happen to Brian. We thought he was a good kid. We
decided to let him be who he was and realize the goodness about
himself and not drive him away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Denekes have retained a lawyer, who says he will soon file a
wrongful-death suit against the Camps. The lawyer, Jeff Blackburn,
says the Denekes do not expect to reap much money but do hope to
get justice, at least of the sort that can be found in a
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``God,'' Mrs. Deneke said, ``is the judge in the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
