<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1537 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f BC-CRUNCH-AZR &LR;      11-25 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUNCH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING LIKE IT'S THE LAST HOLIDAY OF CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you believe the song by the Artist Formerly Known as Prince,
you're going to party like it's 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And if you buy the latest survey by American Express, you'll
spend $1,558, on average, doing it.
</P>
<P>
   The annual holiday crunch has arrived, but this year stands out
for the high hopes and even higher expectations placed on
celebrating the season.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, retailers are betting on strong consumer spending
starting November 26 from those who believe this is the last chance
to make Christmas, Hanukkah, Ramadan, Kwanzaa and New Year's Eve
the best of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a different energy that wasn't there before
because of the millennium and the idea that we're heading into a
new century,'' Brooke LeBaron of Macy's department store said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's a social aspect to it, where people are doing
things a little bigger and a little more elaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy's is making the most of the millennium mania with a new
radio ad that began airing Monday:
</P>
<P>
   ``This holiday season is the most exciting of all,'' a female
voice gushes to her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it's the end of the century, the end of the
millennium, the end of an era. We've got to decorate this place
like never before and give the 1900s a proper sendoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without capitalizing on the idea, the hype surrounding the
end of the century alone seems to be pressuring people to celebrate
the holidays in style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it with New Year's,'' Phoenix psychiatrist Mark
Wellek said. ``It's not because it's the last one; it's because
it's such a big event that everyone wants to take part.''
</P>
<P>
   In the field of psychology, the phenomenon is known as an
``infection of affect,'' Wellek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there's a lot of publicity and not a lot of
controversy, you get caught up in it,'' he said. ``Most people are
infected by the feeling that it's a big event and they should do
something to mark it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Wellek feels the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, my wife and I just sit home and relax,'' he said.
``This year, we'll probably want to do a little something more.''
</P>
<P>
   The new attitude comes as consumers seem more crunched for time
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   This year's American Express holiday spending survey indicated
that one-third of consumers plan to shop from home by ordering
gifts either through mail-order catalogs or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interestingly, they (shoppers) seem to be budgeting their time
as carefully as their money,'' American Express spokesman Tom
Sclafani said.
</P>
<P>
   Malls, where consumers can find one-stop shopping, remain the
most popular shopping destinations, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, consumers expect to spend 16 percent more this year
than last, or an average of $1,558 on everything from gifts to
decorations to holiday travel.
</P>
<P>
   Sclafani attributed the rise to a robust economy and a strong
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Another survey said that much of that holiday spending will be
made possible with credit and debit cards. During the 29-day
holiday shopping period, U.S. consumers are expected to rack up a
record $126.5 billion on credit and debit cards, according to
CardWeb.com and RAM Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate doesn't surprise Robert McKinley, chief executive
officer of CardWeb.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more places to use plastic today than ever before,''
he said. ``All the elements of the cashless society are here.
Everything can be `plasticized.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McKinley also cited the economy and high consumer confidence for
the growing use of plastic; the survey didn't delve into
end-of-the-century attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may want to party like it's 1999 and hope that
their (credit-card) balances will vanish in the New Year'' due to a
Y2K computer glitch, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think consumers really know what they think.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinley cautioned that all holiday spending estimates are just
that, pointing out that another survey released this week predicted
that consumers will spend an average of $500 per household on
gifts. That survey was conducted by the Conference Board, a
non-profit organization of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``These surveys are just guesstimates,'' he said. ``Pick a
number between the two _ say $750 _ and that's probably about
right.'' &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at (602) 444-8975 or at
kerry.fehr-snyder(at)pni.com.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-FUNDRAISING-68     11-25 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-FUNDRAISING-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS SEEK MORE CASH FROM BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alarmed and embarrassed by the recent financial
success of House Democrats, top fund-raisers for House Republicans
issued an urgent appeal this week to business interests to increase
their giving to Republican candidates and committees.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican concern arises from a startling shift in
political donations from businesses to the House fund-raising
committees. After long benefiting from a huge disparity in
contributions from corporations and trade groups, Republicans saw
their advantage virtually disappear in the first six months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Business interests gave the National Republican Congressional
Committee $9.99 million and the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee $9.96 million through June 30, according to an analysis
by the Center for Responsive Politics, an independent research
group.
</P>
<P>
   While House Republicans still have an overall financial lead
over House Democrats, the gap has narrowed markedly as the parties
head into a highly competitive contest for control of the House
next year, prompting a shakeup at the Republican congressional
committee. The Republicans hold a precarious five-seat margin in
the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are running scared,'' said Stuart Rothenberg, publisher
of a newsletter on Congress. ``The money is an accurate gauge of
just how close this race for the House is going to be. People who
can count believe the Democrats have at least a 50-50 chance of
taking over the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the directors of corporate campaign accounts and
political action committees are pouring money into the Democratic
congressional committee in an apparent hedge strategy, according to
federal campaign records.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T gave the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
$12,900 in the first six months of 1997; this year the company has
already donated $102,200. Fannie Mae increased its contribution to
$100,000 this year from $25,000 in 1997; Enron, the energy concern,
gave $105,000 this year compared with $16,000 in 1997, and SBC
Communications gave $85,000 compared with $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   This pattern of giving worries House Republican leaders. Earlier
this month the National Republican Congressional Committee hired
Daniel Mattoon, a lobbyist for BellSouth Corp., as deputy chairman
to try to reverse the trend.
</P>
<P>
   This week Mattoon, a longtime ally of Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois and the House Republican whip, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas,
enlisted Bill Paxon, a former congressman from upstate New York and
chairman of the Republican congressional committee, and Haley
Barbour, a former Republican national chairman, to try to persuade
business representatives to step up their donations to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast and lunch on Monday with 90 business lobbyists,
Mattoon, Paxon and Barbour sought to address complaints that House
Republicans were poorly led, spent money foolishly and were in
danger of losing their majority.
</P>
<P>
   Mattoon told the lobbyists _ representing major
telecommunications companies, banks, health-care interests, tobacco
companies and energy concerns _ that he was unhappy at the new
corporate generosity to Democrats. He assured them that Republicans
had strong candidates and a viable strategy to keep their majority
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   And he issued a strong appeal to the lobbyists to step up their
contributions and to solicit donations from others to strengthen
the Republican congressional committee's bottom line by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was embarrassed by figures on June 30 showing that
the House Democratic campaign committee had more money in the bank,
$10.7 million, than its Republican counterpart, with $10.1 million.
The Republican committee had raised $27 million to the Democrats'
$17 million, but had spent more than twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them we certainly would appreciate any help they could
give and their friends could give before we close the books on Dec.
31,'' Mattoon said in an interview. ``It's helpful to have all
those people together in one room and, frankly, you don't let them
go untouched.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Paxon told the lobbyists that Republicans should be proud of
their record in the current Congress, although very little
legislation was passed except for a major revision of bank
regulation pushed by Wall Street. The Republican sales pitch,
curiously, revolves around the virtues of inaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most Americans, Congress not doing a lot is not a bad
thing,'' Paxon said. ``It's a lot better not to make big
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who attended the breakfast session on Monday was Tim
McKone, vice president for congressional relations at SBC, the
regional telephone giant. McKone said that although he considered
himself a loyal Republican, his company so far this year had split
its contributions between Democrats and Republicans because ``we
have friends on both sides of the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   The company virtually matched its $85,000 gift to the Democratic
congressional committee with $87,000 in contributions to the
Republican committee, according to federal records. Overall this
year, SBC has given Democratic Party committees $211,000 in
unregulated donations, or soft money, while giving the Republicans
$216,000.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997-98, SBC gave Republican Party committees $293,000,
almost twice what it gave to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are delighted with the Republicans' discomfort. The
House minority leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, is leading
an aggressive drive to regain the House majority and using the
prospect of the Democrats' retaking the House as a fund-raising
tool.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Equale, an insurance lobbyist close to Gephardt, said,
``The Democrats remember what it's like to be in the majority and
want to be in the majority again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are clearly letting it be known that the train is leaving
the station and they want everyone on board,'' Equale said. ``It
makes for some very interesting financial politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SATELLITE-TV-ART-2NDT     11-25 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLITE-TV-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: satellite customers. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Echostar's chairman and chief executive, Charlie Ergen, said
earlier this month that the final bill ``limits consumer channel
choices and takes more money out of the consumer's pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no question that the legislation unlocks true
competition between the satellite and cable industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a perfect bill, `` said Marsocci of DirecTV. ``We
are not happy with every provision, but on balance we do support
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The rates for satellite television are very competitive with
those of most cable services, ranging from under $10 a month for a
basic package to upwards of $100 for access to extensive packages
that include hundreds of channels of digital quality entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The price of satellite dishes required for reception have
dropped as low as $100, and are often accompanied by special deals
on service to help offset the initial purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Marsocci said his company's new marketing campaign was already
in place, targeting the top 25 television markets just in time for
the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been gearing up for this and preparing for quite some
time,'' he said. ``We'll be placing primarily print advertisements,
full-page print ads in the daily newspapers in each of the
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Judi Anne Atencio, director of communications for EchoStar, said
similar plans were in the works at that company's Littleton, Colo.,
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's like yellow tape around the marketing department right
now,'' she said. ``That is a dangerous place to be. The president
is expected to sign the bill around noon on Monday, and about five
minutes later we'll be selling.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Egan, a cable and satellite analyst with Paine Webber in
New York, said consumers would quickly see the effects of the
legislation in the rollout of new services over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going to happen is every few months month there is
going to be a new development,'' he said. ``I think what will
happen is they will try to compete less on price and try to compete
more on services.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan said he expected cable companies to focus their energy on
high-speed Internet and new digital services, while satellite
companies will be focusing on increased programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning. It is going to get very exciting
in the year 2000.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2204EST &QL; 
