<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRITAIN-BUSINESS-EDUC     11-25 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BUSINESS-EDUC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH MBA COURSES SHAKE UP OLD SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, England _ Li Lingping from Beijing and Cory Elysa
Cohen from New York could hardly represent more disparate
societies. Where Ms. Li, 31, lists ballroom dancing and discussion
groups as leisure time activities, Ms. Cohen, 24, prefers
kick-boxing and sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   But they agree on some of life's basics: both have career
ambitions; both sense that men tend to see them in categories
defined by gender; and both are investing time (12 months) and
money ($30,000) to acquire three letters after their names _ MBA _
which, they hope, will help propel them through the glass ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   What they share most obviously, though, is the place they have
picked to pursue their Master of Business and Administration
degrees: both chose to take a one-year MBA course in Britain. The
remarkable proliferation of business education in this country has
unleashed cut-throat competition among a growing number of schools
for talent, rankings, big-name gurus and _ the bottom line _ money.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, the number of institutions offering MBA courses has
increased from 26 to 116, according to Britain's Association of
MBAs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same period, the number of graduates has almost
quadrupled, from 2,260 in 1985 to 8,752 in 1998. And, according to
the Association of Business Schools, the business of running
business and management schools has blossomed from modest
beginnings in the 1960s to an industry worth $2.5 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion has jolted some of Britain's most august places of
learning into recognizing that the days when academia might offer
management education no more than a haughty sniff are over. During
the past few years, both Oxford and Cambridge universities have
embraced business or management schools that are openly competing
for students, faculty and acclaim with such established
institutions as the London Business School, which in one recent
survey ranked as Europe's premier business school.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Tony Blair's New Labor government says it is
seeking to transform Britain from its onetime image as a nation of
shopkeepers into a nation of aggressive, risk-taking entrepreneurs,
business education and management training appear to be set for a
further boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very lucrative area,'' said Des Dearlove, co-author of
``Gravy Training,'' a recently published study of business schools.
``More and more companies are going to put more and more managers
through some form of training.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the spread of MBA courses and others related to business
has unleashed its own sometimes venomous debate about where exactly
schools are heading and who is leading the way. Some business
teachers, for instance, argue that the proliferation of business
schools has given rise to what Nigel Piercy, a professor of
marketing at Cardiff University in Wales, termed ``the cowboy
professor'' who is ``recognized by the incessant and continuous
search for additional income,'' and ``chameleon'' academics who
flit between teaching and lucrative private consulting work.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said London Business School dean John Quelch, , since
``the only thing you need to set up a business school is a warm
body and a piece of chalk,'' some of the myriad MBA programs are
``of dubious quality.'' And, said Anthony Hopwood, the acting
director of Oxford's Said Business School, ``there's an enormous
shortage of seriously qualified faculty and there's almost no
supply in some areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Business schools not only compete with each other, they are also
engaged in a turf fight with big management consulting firms,
particularly in the field of executive development, which for many
provides an important source of revenue. Of the London Business
School's $66 million in revenue this year, 36 percent will come
from tailored training programs for executives that are designed in
conjunction with corporations, Quelch said.
</P>
<P>
   At Cranfield School of Management, near Bedford, north of
London, roughly half of last year's $42.5 million revenue came from
executive development programs, according to Gill Marshall, the
director of corporate communications there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line between consultancy and business education is
blurring,'' said Dearlove, the author. ``It's more and more
difficult to see where one stops and the other starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain's conversion to business education has come far later
than that of the United States. Business schools in this country
tend to function not simply as breeding grounds for home-grown
talent, but as a magnet for people like Ms. Li and Ms. Cohen. While
roughly three-quarters of students at American business schools are
American, some 70 percent of students at British schools graduating
from full-time MBA courses this year were foreigners seeking
overseas experience and qualifications, according to the
Association of MBAs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Britain is not alone in Europe in seeking to advance
business education through prestigious academies such as Insead in
Paris or Bocconi University in Milan. But the pressures driving
Britain's business school explosion are different. A broader
proliferation of British university education in recent years has
taken much of the luster from a first academic degree and forced
ambitious college graduates to seek the additional cachet of a
master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Quelch, at the London Business School, also sees other forces at
work. Britain's ``shift away from the social welfare state'' has
increased pressure for managers in both the public and private
sectors to develop managerial skills. In addition, the end of the
Cold War _ and the collapse of geographical and ideological
barriers _ ``means that an entire one-third of the world's
population who had been precluded from programs outside their own
markets'' are now able to study abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, said Chong Ju Choi, the director of the MBA
program at Cambridge's Judge Institute of Management Studies, the
very fact that managers are entering an uncharted world of
e-commerce, Internet business and corporate restructuring forces
them to look for advice from consultants and business schools.
``There are very few executives who feel they are up to date,'' he
said. ``Fundamentally, it's the uncertainty. They are not sure. And
that brings them back to executive education.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the change at British business schools, one feature is
changing very slowly. Before 1970, according to the Association of
MBAs, virtually all MBA graduates in Britain were men. But even in
1997, women accounted for less than one-quarter of graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason may be that business itself is
male-dominated: only one of the FTSE 100 blue chip companies,
Pearson PLC, has a female chief executive, Marjorie Scardino. And,
said Hilary Harris, a lecturer at the Cranfield management school,
research among female MBA graduates has ``shown that despite having
an MBA, if you take career progress and salaries, women fall behind
men.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason, Ms. Harris said, is that ``managing the home-work
balance is more of an issue for women than men'' _ a sentiment
echoed by some Cranfield MBA students who also argue that, since
MBA courses are usually taken in the late 20s or early 30s, they
pose a potential conflict with starting a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard time for doing an MBA is often the time a woman
is thinking of starting a family,'' said Sarah Sturrock, 29, a
government official studying part time for an MBA at Cranfield in a
group of 100 that includes only 17 women. Karen Pennington, a
29-year-old engineer in the same course, said the conflict of
career and family is more acute for women. ``It's a lot more
difficult for women with children than men with children.''
</P>
<P>
   Such distinctions are not limited to Britain, of course. ``Even
when I started my career, men and women were in different
positions,'' said Ms. Li, who works as the communications director
at the Beijing subsidiary of an international corporation which she
did not wish to identify by name. ``People tended to use women for
administration, but the men went straight into the business.'' An
MBA degree, then, was not simply a key to higher salaries and more
powerful jobs. It was a way for women to receive equal treatment
with men.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a woman, it gives you even more credibility,'' said Ms.
Cohen, the New Yorker. From her own relatively brief career in
banking, she had concluded that ``it's very difficult for a woman
to be viewed as being as effective as a man. No matter what I do,
when I walk into a room, the first thing they see is not my
brains.'' The MBA degree, she said, ``is a way of being able to
balance that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
