<HEADLINE>
DEFENSIVE COORDINATOR YOUNG TO STAY WITH USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After weighing his options, USC defensive
coordinator Bill Young decided it would be best to stay in his
current job instead of seeking the vacant head-coaching position at
the University of Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't feel really good about the situation,'' said
Young, who withdrew from consideration last week. ``There were a
lot of little things about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of the remaining Tulsa candidates is Young's
predecessor, former USC defensive coordinator Keith Burns,
currently the secondary coach at Arkansas. Others being interviewed
are Illinois State coach Todd Berry, Miami offensive coordinator
Larry Coker and Tampa Bay linebackers coach Lovie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who interviewed with the University of Hawaii last year,
said he would not apply for any other jobs and return to USC next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Curtain call: A game against Louisiana Tech doesn't evoke much
emotion from most of USC's players, but senior tailback Chad Morton
expects to get all choked up playing in his final game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably be real sad again,'' Morton said. ``Walking
through the tunnel before the UCLA game, with all the alumni lined
up, I was crying. It was a real scary moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton said that most of the Trojans still probably don't fully
appreciate the significance of snapping USC's eight-game losing
streak against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think guys realize what they've done ending the
streak,'' he said. ``They'll think about it a lot more later in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Look who's here: Among the NFL executives expected to appear at
today's game to scout Louisiana Tech quarterback Tim Rattay is
former UCLA coach Terry Donahue, who works for the San Francisco
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman of the year? The Pacific-10 Conference has come up with
a new award: Freshman of the Year. The leading candidate is USC
wide receiver Kareem Kelly, who has 53 receptions for 895 yards and
four touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Women's basketball game: USC's women's basketball team (1-0)
plays Creighton today at the Sports Arena at 12:30 p.m. Any fan who
has a football ticket will receive free admittance to the
basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   Easy ticket: To increase attendance, USC has invited 12,500
members of local youth groups to the game. Members of the U.S.
armed forces will also receive four free tickets if they show
military identification.
</P>
<P>
   Bad stat: According to USC research, this is the first time the
Trojans have lost all six games by 10 or fewer points. Then again,
how often have the Trojans lost six or more games?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Eight times in 111 years.
</P>
<P>
   Fox climbs: With his late-season reappearance, quarterback John
Fox has moved into 10th place on USC's career passing list, with
2,647 yards. Fox is 395 yards behind teammate Mike Van Raaphorst,
who is No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Last chance: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward will play his last game
today, hoping to avoid a quiet finish to an otherwise flashy
four-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Soward was barely used last week against UCLA after fumbling on
his first reception. He could have had a touchdown in the third
quarter, but Fox failed to see Soward was wide open in the corner
of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should go wring John's neck,'' Soward joked. ``But I'm just
happy we won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
