<SLUG> BC-FBC-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MARSHALL GETS LITTLE CONSIDERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course it would seem unfair, unkind and rather rotten, too.
Here is Marshall University, that doughty college located in
Huntington, in the Appalachian foothills of West Virginia, whose
Thundering Herd football team is undefeated, at 10-0. It is one of
only three Division I-A teams to be unbeaten, and yet it is given
the back of the pollsters' hand, 11th in two of the most important
polls, 12th in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall is shown no consideration to play in the Sugar Bowl on
Jan. 4, in which the two top-ranked college football teams (they
happen to be the other two undefeated teams, to be sure) will
decide the alleged national champion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one may marvel that Marshall has a football team at
all, given the trauma of 29 years ago when all 75 people aboard a
DC 9 _ 37 Marshall football players and 38 others, including
coaches, school administrators and fans _ were killed when their
airplane, returning from a game at East Carolina on a rainy
Saturday night, crashed into a mountainside on the approach to the
local Tri-State Airport. It was the worst sports team air disaster
in history.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as has been done every year on the anniversary of
that Nov. 14, 1970, fatality, a commemorative service for those who
perished was held at the Memorial Fountain, built in 1972 and
containing the names of the deceased. The Fountain is a kind of
centerpiece of the Marshall campus.
</P>
<P>
   The team in fact came back to play the season following the
crash, in 1971. It soon entered the lower I-AA division and in 1996
it won the I-AA national title, going undefeated in 15 games (Randy
Moss, the Vikings' all-pro wide receiver, was a freshman on that
team). In 1997, Marshall returned to Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   So, while the crash of nearly three decades ago remains a sad,
but real source of perspective for the Marshall players, from the
standpoint of a purely football issue, there's another element of
inequity: there is no national playoff system in place for this
year's team. Unlike in the National Collegiate Athletic Association
basketball tournament, and even in the I-AA football 16-team
playoff series, ``there is no chance for a Cinderella team in the
I-A set-up,'' said Ricky Hazel, an official for Marshall. ``And
people love Cinderella.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two undefeated teams this season, Florida State and
Virginia Tech, are ranked No. 1 and 2 respectively in the three
major national polls, while Marshall is rated only 12th in the
USA/ESPN poll and the Associated Press poll and 13th in the New
York Times computer analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Marshall behind those other two teams in those
polls, but it is, overall, also behind two teams with one loss and
eight teams with two losses.
</P>
<P>
   And to add insult to indignity, the Marshall footballers even
dropped a notch in the USA/ESPN and AP polls simply because they
were innocent bystanders. They didn't play a game last week and yet
fell from the 11th spot to an inconsiderate 12th (The New York
Times computer, in its infinite wisdom, moved them up one floor
from 14.)
</P>
<P>
   And more: The No. 1 team, Florida State, and Marshall have a
common opponent. It is Clemson. Each of them beat Clemson at
Clemson by three points. Virginia Tech beat Clemson, 31-11, but
Clemson coach Tommy Bowden believes Florida State is the better
team. And Marshall? ``Well, they'd be competitive against either
one of those teams,'' he said. ``Do they have the depth of talent
to win? I'm not sure. It would be fun to see, though, wouldn't
it?''
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen, however. The reason is that the Bowl
Championship Series committee chooses the top two teams based on a
rankings system that would make Fermat's Last Theorem look like a
game of dominoes. Much of the selection process has to do with the
robustness of one's schedule. While Marshall is in the Mid-America
Conference, where good football is often played, it is not the Big
Ten or the Big Eight, or the Southeast or Southwestern Conferences.
But in nonconference games, MAC schools not infrequently beat teams
from some of those swankier programs.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments against a national playoff system for I-A teams is
that it might be detrimental to the academic and physical elements
of the football players. But why is a I-AA schedule of a potential
15 games for the championship finalists less demanding than 12 or
13 games for a I-A team?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was strenuous, and there were bumps and bruises, but it was
challenging,'' said Andre O'Neal, a senior linebacker for Marshall
who was on that I-AA championship team in 1996. ``And we got
through it on the field and in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a I-A playoff system of eight teams (Marshall would
have needed a creative, at-large bid, to make it this season) or
even 16 teams would be less taxing than the I-AA playoffs, with
fewer games overall than Marshall played in 1996. (All Marshall's
games that year, incidentally, came before Thanksgiving.)
</P>
<P>
   The current I-A schedule of 22 bowl games are all between Dec.
18 and Jan. 4. School is out for most schools between the first
week in December and the second week in January. So, no academics
and often enough time to heal sore body parts.
</P>
<P>
   Not having playoff caliber teams would not take any luster away
from such as the Humanitarian Bowl or the Micron PC Bowl or the
Motor City Bowl (where Marshall, if it beats Ohio University on
Friday for the MAC championship, will wind up, playing Pittsburgh),
because they are what they are, simply built-in excuses for
sponsors, schools and networks to make money. And some of the major
bowls, like the Fiesta, Orange, Rose and Gator, in the years they
are not playing host to the top two ranked teams, can entertain
playoff games that have resonance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' said Lance West, Marshall's athletic director, ``would
really crown a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   But there may never be a game for Marshall like its first home
game in 1971, the season after the airplane crash. It had only
three returning players from the year before _ the three were
injured and didn't make the doomed flight _ and 20 of the 22
starters were freshmen and sophomores. Marshall was a 20-point
underdog against Xavier, and won on a last-second touchdown. It is
known by Marshall followers as ``the miracle game.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuff like that can't be accounted for in computers or polls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1556 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KEISSER-MEDIA-LAD     11-25 1551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-MEDIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTEN UP, HOOP FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coming to a website near you:
</P>
<P>
   Real-time audio of every game in the NCAA tournament. Streaming
video of press conferences. Real-time video highlights. Exclusive
postgame chat rooms with players. And stats, stats, stats and more
stats.
</P>
<P>
   And considering the pace of the Internet's growth, these could
be merely conservative predictions of what the deal between CBS and
the NCAA holds for fans.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's massive 11-year, $6 billion agreement between the
network and college association shook up the TV world, and not just
because CBS agreed to pay the NCAA more annually than it is
currently paying the NFL. The deal, which begins in 2003, also
includes Internet rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is still a New Media work in progress. But in the
last decade, it has gone from a text-based educational tool to chat
rooms to a gigantic retail and informational industry that will
only get larger. Internet-related companies are driving the latest
bull market on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   CBS holds a 20 percent stake in SportsLine Inc., the website
that has been dueling with ESPN's for sports supremacy on the net.
By adding net rights to its TV rights deal, CBS made a bold move
into the future, whatever shape it may take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal makes sense, especially when you include Internet
rights,'' CBS Sports President Sean McManus said this week. ``No
one understands what the Internet means to TV right now. But when
it';s developed, we wanted the opportunity to take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line between the Internet and television has become
thinner and thinner. Webcasting is growing, so the critical element
is who controls those rights. If you don't, there will be
cannibalization.''
</P>
<P>
   And no one in TV wants to get eaten. The over-the-air networks
have already lost weight in the Nielsen ratings thanks to cable and
the net stealing away viewers. The net's fantastic growth poses a
real threat to the way people get their information.
</P>
<P>
   The downloading of music already has that industry in a panic.
If the latest tunes from Bare Naked Ladies can be found and
downloaded at a web site, who's going to bother buying CDs?
</P>
<P>
   That's why CBS' pre-emptive move was so savvy. It will have
proprietary control over all NCAA video and audio, and all of the
branding, promotional and exclusivity benefits that creates.
</P>
<P>
   At least in regards to the NCAA tourney, CBS will not have to
worry about a competing net site offering the kind of bells and
whistles that could turn a potential viewer from his tube to his
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the way people watch TV 10 years from now will
fundamentally be the same as it is today,'' said McManus. ``The way
fans view football and basketball won't be all that different. But
the Internet will be an important adjunct to what people see. It
can provide a tremendous amount of supplementary programming.''
</P>
<P>
   That would include the aforementioned audio, video, chats and
stats. But there truly is no ceiling for the Internet. Who's to say
the Internet won't be able to deliver high-definition video that
turns your keypad into a TV studio, that allows you to watch a live
game from whatever camera angle you like or call up a replay?
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of the population might prefer a network
telecast. But the networks can't afford losing the 10 percent
gravitating to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That alone explains CBS' decision, and will explain why most TV
rights deals in the future will likely deal with Internet rights.
Major League Baseball, whose TV deal is up after 2000, already has
a relationship with SportsLine. ESPN has relationships with the NFL
and NBA. But none of those deals came as part of TV rights.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which wanted the tournament for ABC and ESPN and owns
the ESPN website, didn't include the net in its bid. It won't make
the same mistake again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think each league will look at their own situation and
analyze it separately,'' said McManus. ``Some are farther along
than others in regards to the net and digital television. Everyone
realizes that the best way to maximize revenue is to combine the
net, marketing, merchandise and TV under one umbrella.''
</P>
<P>
   That's called branding, and good business. But exclusivity may
become an even bigger issue.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL limits how much video other broadcast networks can use
of their product on Sundays, and the networks owning Olympic TV
rights has historically been stingy in what it allows anyone else
to show.
</P>
<P>
   CBS theoretically will have control over what other Internet
sites can do with the tournament. It might not be able to keep
ESPN's site from covering the tourney, but it could limit its video
and audio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't decided what kind of exclusivity to carve out,''
McManus said, ``but it could be similar to broadcast TV with
respect to how much video a service can use, and how much is
proprietary. We don't want to be restrictive, but we paid for
exclusivity.''
</P>
<P>
   It could wind up being the best money CBS has ever spent.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW THE NEWS: ESPN is down to the Top Ten in its
SportsCentury series. Nos.9 and 10 will be profiled Friday. The
remaining 10 (alphabetically): Muhammad Ali, Jim Brown, Babe
Didrikson, Wayne Gretzky, Michael Jordan, Willie Mays, Jack
Nicklaus, Jesse Owens, Babe Ruth and Jim Thorpe. ... VCR alert:
ESPN2 will air a SportsCentury marathon of all of its Top 50
profiles Dec. 30-31. The series produced by Mark Shapiro has
already won Northeastern University's Excellence in Sports
Journalism Award. Tape them so you won't have to pay beaucoup bucks
for the anticipated boxed set. ... Ex-ESPNer Keith Olbermann has
put together his own ``The Century's Real 50 Greatest Athletes''
list and began profiling them this week on Fox Sports News shows.
Terms of his list: No animals, foreign athletes are included, and
athletes who influenced sports in general are given strong
consideration. For example, Curt Flood, who paved the way for free
agency in baseball, is his No.50. The profiles will continue
through Dec. 23. ... CBS' Bryant Gumbel will host the two-hour
``Sports Illustrated's 20th Century Sports Awards,'' Thursday at 9
p.m. SI has named 42 nominees in seven categories (they're featured
in this week's issue) and will name the athlete of the century in
each category on Thursday. Seven athletes Peggy Fleming, Poly High
graduate Billie Jean King, Arnold Palmer, Pele, Richard Petty,
Jackie Robinson and Bill Russell will also be honored as ``Athletes
Who Changed The Game.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The Big West is close to signing a deal with Fox Sports Net to
televise five games on Thursdays in February and March, and three
of the telecasts will feature Long Beach State. ... USC failed in
its bid for a summary judgment for breach of contract against
former sportscasters Larry Kahn and Mike Lamb as individuals, and
now must decide if they want to pursue that suit in a jury trial.
USC already won a summary judgment against KLM, Kahn and Lamb's
former company. ... Todd Merkow is the new G.M. at Fox Sports Net
in Los Angeles, He's a native and comes from FSN's Arizona unit. He
replaces Kitty Cohen, the longtime Prime Ticket and FSN G.M. who
resigned because of issues with Fox management ... ABC, ESPN and
ESPN2 have signed a deal with the MLS to air 28 games over 19
Saturdays next year. ... The Arena Football League has signed TV
deals with ABC, ESPN, ESPN2 and The Nashville Network (TNN) worth
$25 million over the next three years. ... TVKO had only 850,000
buys for Lewis-Holyfield II, which doesn't bode well for future
heavyweight fights. Maybe the public has finally had its fill of
boxing. ...
</P>
<P>
   THE WORLD OF TV SPORTS ACCORDING TO ME: I realize the Rams are
the best team in the NFC and every Raiders game is close, but I'm a
little tired of the networks stuffing the Rams and Raiders down
L.A.'s TV throat this season. If L.A. liked either team, we
wouldn't have let them leave. ... I've always like the work of
Fox's Matt Millen, but he's straying into Dan Dierdorf's old
territory at ABC by trying to be entertaining and witty at the
expense of substance. He could do worse than watch Dierdorf's work
now at CBS, where he has returned to his old style of sharp
analysis. ... SI's website features its ``Turkeys of the Year,'' a
list that includes one broadcaster, NBC's Jim Gray. They should
have added ABC's Boomer Esiason, who has already clinched the award
as worst network ex-jock hire since NBC hired Joe Montana. ...
Salmonella alert: It's time to retire John Madden's multi-legged
turkey tradition. In a four-point game Thursday between the Lions
and Bears, the last 15 minutes of the telecast was devoted to the
turkey moving from the Maddencruiser to the field. ... Jim
Lampley's work usually draws praise here, but he gets two whacks
for recent comments. Lampley treated analyst George Foreman very
rudely on the Lewis-Holyfield PPV telecast, mocking Foreman's
comments on the fight, and he also went after newspaper reporters
who criticized Jim Gray for his inquisition of Pete Rose while
recently filling in on Jim Rome's syndicated radio talk show.
Lampley invented sideline reporting in his early days at ABC; now
there's a legacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
