<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: 15 QUESTIONS ABOUT MADISON AVE. THAT COULD CHANGE YOUR
LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Typically around holidays, this column presents a feature known
as ``20 Questions,'' examining the foibles of advertising,
marketing and the media. But rather than 20 questions, the focus
these days has been on 15 questions, as in the number of queries
that contestants must answer correctly to win the grand prize on
the phenomenally successful ABC game show, ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   So here is a quiz that could be called ``Who Wants to Be a
Madison Avenue Millionaire.'' Just reading this far has qualified
you, eliminating the need to answer a preliminary question like
``Place all the agencies that work for General Motors in
geographical order from West to East.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, there are no ``lifelines'' to help you as there are on
TV. But you are not required to ask yourself out loud after each
response, ``Is that my final answer?'' Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   $100
</P>
<P>
   A television or radio commercial is also called a:
</P>
<P>
   (a) dot (b) spot (c) rhomboid (d) dot-com
</P>
<P>
   $200
</P>
<P>
   Complete this familiar slogan for Coca-Cola: ``It's the real
...''
</P>
<P>
   (a) deal (b) carbonated sugared water (c) thing (d) Pepsi
</P>
<P>
   $300
</P>
<P>
   A compact-size newspaper usually filled with photographs, snappy
headlines and gossip is called a:
</P>
<P>
   (a) tabloid (b) tablet (c) tableau (d) tabula rasa
</P>
<P>
   $500
</P>
<P>
   Name the Saatchi brothers.
</P>
<P>
   (a) Wilbur and Orville (b) Maurice and Charles (c) Trade and
Mark (d) Groucho and Harpo
</P>
<P>
   $1,000
</P>
<P>
   Which of the following is not a symbol or logo that the Leo
Burnett agency uses to identify itself:
</P>
<P>
   (a) hand reaching for stars (b) apple (c) black pencil (d)
talking carrot
</P>
<P>
   $2,000
</P>
<P>
   Crest became a popular toothpaste after Procter &AMP; Gamble began
promoting a seal from which organization in the brand's
advertising?
</P>
<P>
   (a) American Bar Association (b) American Medical Association
(c) American Association of Advertising Agencies (d) American
Dental Association
</P>
<P>
   $4,000
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor advertising industry uses this word to describe an
illuminated, oversize billboard of the type typically found in
Times Square:
</P>
<P>
   (a) spectacular (b) extravaganza (c) goliath (d) eyesore
</P>
<P>
   $8,000
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide and J. Walter Thompson are owned by:
</P>
<P>
   (a) True North Communications (b) the WPP Group (c) the WWP
Group. (d) Group W
</P>
<P>
   $16,000
</P>
<P>
   The enormously popular Super Bowl commercial for Apple Computer
titled ``1984'' was followed the next year by a commercial that was
deemed an ineffective failure. What was its title?
</P>
<P>
   (a) ``Gremlins'' (b) ``Newton's Folly'' (c) ``Lemmings'' (d)
``1985''
</P>
<P>
   $32,000
</P>
<P>
   BBDO, Doyle Dane Bernbach and Needham Harper combined to form:
</P>
<P>
   (a) the Interpublic Group of Companies (b) the Omnicom Group (c)
the Cordiant Communications Group (d) Havas Advertising
</P>
<P>
   $64,000
</P>
<P>
   Which big cosmetics marketer was the principal sponsor of ``The
$64,000 Question'' during the quiz show craze of the 1950s?
</P>
<P>
   (a) Max Factor (b) Maybelline (c) Revlon (d) Helena Rubinstein
</P>
<P>
   $125,000
</P>
<P>
   The explanation for the shocking headline ``Lemon'' in a famous
ad for the Volkswagen Beetle was:
</P>
<P>
   (a) The car depicted in the ad had major defects. (b) The car
had only minor blemishes. (c) Volkswagen had heeded Ralph Nader's
demand to recall all Beetles. (d) After selling Beetles only in
black, Volkswagen had introduced 15 colors like yellow.
</P>
<P>
   $250,000
</P>
<P>
   Years after leaving the White House, this former first lady
endorsed Good Luck margarine at the request of David Ogilvy and
donated her fee to charity:
</P>
<P>
   (a) Lou Hoover (b) Eleanor Roosevelt (b) Bess Truman (c) Mamie
Eisenhower
</P>
<P>
   $500,000
</P>
<P>
   This agency created the campaigns for the hapless Edsel line of
Ford automobiles:
</P>
<P>
   (a) Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding. (b) Young &AMP; Rubicam (c) Kenyon &AMP;
Eckhardt (d) Cunningham &AMP; Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   $1 million
</P>
<P>
   Name the executive considered the creator of the modern agency
holding company, a conglomerate that owns shops operated separately
to avoid client conflicts:
</P>
<P>
   (a) Rosser Reeves (b) Albert Lasker (c) Claude Hopkins (d)
Marion Harper Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Answers:
</P>
<P>
   $100: b
</P>
