<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENE WASHINGTON IS NFL'S TOP COP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gene Washington is on the phone, and the 1965 graduate of Poly
High is discussing a 1987 graduate of Poly High, Mark Carrier, in
grave tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time it wasn't tough to do,'' says Washington, referring
to the one-game suspension without pay and $50,000 fine he leveled
the other day against Carrier for an illegal hit that Carrier
perpetrated last Sunday against Green Bay's Antonio Freeman. ``It
was tougher last year for me when I suspended Mark for misusing his
helmet on Tampa Bay's Brice Hunter. But this time it was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like Mark hasn't been sufficiently warned. This is
the fourth time in three years that we've had to cite him for
improperly using his helmet. His style of play has created a risky
environment for other players. Ironically, Mark is the only player
I've ever had to suspend.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Washington has met Carrier at several social functions over
the years, and likes him.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, everyone who knows Mark Carrier likes him. He's a
bright, civil fellow with a ready smile, and he's always promoting
some fund-raising event.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't let personal feeling interfere with your better
judgment,'' says Washington. ``Mark has become a head hunter in his
older years, much like Ronnie Lott was in his final years with the
49ers. And that just can't be allowed without some sort of
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Washington one-time Stanford and San Francisco 49ers
receiving star has become the NFL's top cop in his position as
director of football operations for the league.
</P>
<P>
   He metes out fines on a weekly basis during the regular season,
and has been carrying out such a task since 1995 after 13 years of
doing radio and TV both in L.A. and San Francisco and also after
serving a couple of years as an associate athletics director at
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``One paper calls me the `Duke of Discipline,''' says
Washington. ``It's not an easy job. Football is a violent sport,
and there often is such a fine line between a legal hit and an
illegal one. This is terrible that I had to fine Mark such a large
sum. I just wish he could donate the money to the Poly High
Athletic Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure that Carrier will be slightly more cautious
during the rest of the season since it's so expensive for him to
keep getting penalized.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated he blew at least $75,000 for sitting out his
team's Thanksgiving Day game against the Chicago Bears, since he
also lost 1/16th of his $400,000 a year salary (Carrier also had a
$400,000 signing bonus).
</P>
<P>
   Gene Washington came close to re-joining the San Francisco 49ers
in the off-season in an executive position, but decided to remain
with the NFL when Eddie DeBartolo wasn't able to return to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it was a good non-move by Washington, considering
the current plight of the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about my job is that it's never boring,'' he says.
``The nature of it is that I deal in controversy. It's very
challenging. But it's particularly difficult when you have to deal
with someone who went to your high school and grew up in your
area.'' ... .
</P>
<P>
   It won't surprise me if the tough, aggressive D'Cean Bryant is
starting at forward for Long Beach State by the end of the season,
and the versatile, stylish Antrone Lee is switched to the
backcourt. ...
</P>
<P>
   What impresses me most about Wayne Morgan's team so far is its
defensive tenacity. The athletically gifted 49ers figure to create
a lot of turnovers this season. ...
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure Wayne Morgan will settle on a seven or eight-man
rotation by the start of the Big West. I'm sure he realizes
alternating three point guards and shuttling other players in and
out of the lineup isn't exactly conducive to team continuity and
chemistry. ...
</P>
<P>
   Movie fans who savor classic acting performances should check
out Bob Hoskins' amazing work in ``Felicia's Journey.'' It's the
best I've seen since Emily Watson's in ``Breaking The Waves''. ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, Phil Jackson was right. His Lakers simply aren't that good
this year. But how much better will they be next year even with the
prodigal son, Kobe Bryant, in the lineup? ...
</P>
<P>
   I admit it, I'm jealous of Paul Hackett. Here's a guy who makes
a lot more money than I do and yet he's just as incompetent in his
job as I am in mine. Is there no justice in this world whatsoever?
...
</P>
<P>
   The BCS ratings are a sham. Virginia Tech would have two or
three or even four losses if it had to play a Big 10 schedule
rather than the cupcake Big East one that has allowed it to go
undefeated. ...
</P>
<P>
   Does Paul Hackett realize he has a potential superstar in Kareem
Kelly? ...
</P>
<P>
   Now that Brian Barnhart won't be returning, why are the Angels
hesitating in not selecting the only viable candidate to become
Mario Impemba's new radio play-by-play partner, Larry Kahn? ...
</P>
<P>
   Does any area have three better veteran high school football
coaches in it
</P>
<P>
   than this one in Poly's Jerry Jaso, Los Alamitos' John Barnes
and Paramount's Ken Sutch? ...
</P>
<P>
   All my life I wanted to see USC play that great football power,
Louisiana Tech. ...
</P>
<P>
   I find myself every Sunday being a passionate fan of the Oakland
Raiders' opponent. ...
</P>
<P>
   Does Al Davis realize his pregame ritual of prowling the
football field has become pure hokum. ...
</P>
<P>
   With his purchase of a $1.6 million home in Marina Del Rey,
Steve Lavin is certainly more secure about his UCLA future than I
am. ...
</P>
<P>
   It'll be interesting to me in upcoming months who Robert Daly
will have calling the shots for the Dodgers, his close friend, Tom
Lasorda, or that bumbler Kevin Malone. ...
</P>
<P>
   I'm stunned that the San Francisco 49ers released Lawrence
Phillips. ...
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Durslag, Mike (The Night Owl) DiMarzo and all my other
pals are bitterly chiding me and the Brit's New Year's Eve
destination. What's wrong with spending the millennium in Damascus?
I've always wanted to have an audience with Syria's charming
leader, Hafetz al-Assad, anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
