<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 12 
</HEADLINE>
  (A graphic of these matchups has been sent electronically to NYT
graphics clients. Call 888-603-1036 for information.) 
(rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (6-4) at Seattle (8-2), 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   These teams have rosters full of sleek, determined players and
both are capable of making a bruising playoff run. For Tampa Bay,
quarterback Trent Dilfer has begun to help his team more than hurt
it. For Seattle, quarterback John Kitna has passed for 1,888 yards,
16 touchdowns and six interceptions. Coach Mike Holmgren's move to
allow Warren Moon to leave for Kansas City and ride Kitna was
controversial initially, brilliant now. The game features two of
pro football's most glamorous defensive linemen _ Warren Sapp for
Tampa Bay and Cortez Kennedy for Seattle. Expect Sapp to dictate
the game in stronger fashion. So, too, will the Tampa Bay defense.
This unexpected victory makes National Conference teams take note
of Tampa Bay as a dangerous playoff threat.
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers, 17-16.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY 1 P.M. GAMES:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (4-6) at Giants (5-5)
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is not a playoff team and the Giants of late have not
looked like one, either. The Giants offense has been a grinding,
halting, ugly show all season long, but it looks for a jolt from
quarterback Kerry Collins. He makes his first Giants start and is
considered the quarterback for the rest of this season and beyond.
Collins possesses the tools _ nice size, strong arm, maturity and
control in the pocket. He must throw the ball downfield, loosen the
Cardinals defense and open the running game. Collins realizes the
opportunity and will be prepared. The Giants show new life.
</P>
<P>
   Giants, 23-10.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (9-1) at Baltimore (4-6)
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago the Ravens traveled to the Jaguars and held them
to six points. The problem was the Ravens could only score three
and lost. Not this time. Baltimore scored 34 last week in beating
Cincinnati but, of course, the Bengals' defense is a universe away
from the Jaguars' defense. There are numbers in Baltimore's favor:
its defense has allowed only one rushing touchdown in its last 23
quarters; it allows an average of only 3.2 rushing yards per carry;
Ravens running back Errict Rhett averages 3.8 yards per carry; and
quarterback Tony Banks has thrown more touchdowns (four) than
interceptions (two). Baltimore has never beaten Jacksonville,
having lost all seven encounters. It's time for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens, 14-13.
</P>
<P>
   New England (6-4) at Buffalo (7-4)
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are in a swoon, having lost consecutive divisional
games to the Jets and Dolphins and now find themselves in panic
mode. That could be good for a team that tends to fight best when
cornered. New England meets a club that is hot at home: Buffalo has
won 10 of its last 12 home games and is 4-1 there this season.
Also, Bills quarterback Doug Flutie is 15-2 in home games during
his NFL career. New England quarterback Drew Bledsoe has accepted
the blame for his team's poor showing in its last two games and he
is determined to rise. New England should gain good field position
from return man Kevin Faulk, who ranks second among rookies in
kickoff returns. It needs a monster game from end Willie McGinnest
and gets it.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots, 22-20.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (2-8) at St. Louis (8-2)
</P>
<P>
   Saints rookie back Ricky Williams has rushed for an NFC
rookie-most 816 yards and 524 of those have come in his last five
games. He is on pace for a 1,306-yard rushing season and could
become the Saints first 1,000-yard back in 11 years (Dalton
Hilliard gained 1,262 in 1989). As far as bright spots, that's it
for the Saints. They cannot contain Kurt Warner to Isaac Bruce (11
touchdowns). They can't block end Kevin Carter (11.5 sacks, tops in
the league). The Rams have scored more points (323) than any team.
They can swipe their divisional crown if they win and Carolina
loses. It would be the Rams first in 14 years. It would also match
the 1985 Chicago Bears for earliest title clinch (11 games) in a
16-game season. St. Louis will do its part and hope Carolina
obliges.
</P>
<P>
   Rams, 31-17.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia (3-8) at Washington (6-4)
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles tripped the Redskins 35-28 two weeks ago in a game
that could have sent the Redskins into a deep tailspin. It did not.
Washington recovered, beat the Giants, and recaptured first place
in the NFC East. Washington will not allow Philadelphia to
duplicate the initial upset. Washington has too much going for it _
the league's leading rusher in Stephen Davis, a big-play passer in
Brad Johnson and an inconsistent defense that played efficiently
against the Giants. Receiver Albert Connell (41 catches, 771 yards,
an 18.8 average yards gained per catch and six touchdowns) will get
Washington going. Then they roll.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins, 27-10.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati (1-10) at Pittsburgh (5-5)
</P>
<P>
   When in the doldrums, when losing, confused and angry, play the
Bengals. The Pittsburgh offense is in flux, but for this game,
anyway, Kordell Stewart finds open receivers, Jerome Bettis finds
open running lanes and the Pittsburgh defense, led by linebackers
Jason Gilden (7.5 sacks) and Levon Kirkland, strangles Cincinnati.
Pittsburgh has allowed only five touchdowns in its last 20 quarters
and its defense ranks second in the league in third-down conversion
rate allowed at 28.7 percent. Defense has never been the problem
this season for Pittsburgh. Offense has. Pittsburgh fans say thank
goodness for the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Steelers, 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   San Diego (4-6) at Minnesota (6-4)
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have won four straight and this one makes five. Jeff
George has yet to blow up. Most think he eventually will, but for
now he has provided stability and intelligence at quarterback for
Minnesota. His smartest move? Relentlessly seeking receiver Cris
Carter. Good things happen when Carter touches the ball. He is one
of the game's best third-down receivers. He needs two catches to
become the league's fourth player all-time with 900 or more
receptions. Carter is averaging 13.4 yards per catch, his highest
since matching that number eight years ago. George to Carter
becomes this game's staple.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings, 21-7.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (8-2) at Cleveland (2-9)
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has won 12 consecutive divisional games. It has not
allowed a 100-yard rusher this season. Its defense has scored three
safeties. Offensively, the Titans roar when the legs of quarterback
Steve McNair and running back Eddie George churn. When McNair has
rushed for a touchdown this season Tennessee is 4-0 and all-time is
13-2. George rushed for 494 yards in his last five games compared
with only 277 in his first five. Receiver Yancey Thigpen returns
for Tennessee after sitting out last week's victory over Pittsburgh
with an injured ankle. That simply gives Tennessee another weapon
against a team it already towers over.
</P>
<P>
   Titans, 23-12.
</P>
<P>
   4 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Jets (4-6) at Indianapolis (8-2)
</P>
<P>
   With all of the adversity and drama the Jets have faced this
season, their defense has stood tall. Credit Bill Belichick, the
defensive coordinator, for one of his finest coaching seasons. In
their last seven games, the Jets defense has allowed an average of
14.3 points per game. Add the consistent and inspiring play of
quarterback Ray Lucas and the Jets have finally found a formula for
winning. They could have beaten the Colts the last time except for
a hurried Jets pass near the Colts goal line that was intercepted
and returned; it set up a last-second, game-winning field goal in
the Colts' 16-13 victory. Lucas and coach Bill Parcells won't make
the same mistake. It's an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Jets, 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City (5-5) at Oakland (5-5)
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have six games left, both have identical records and
both play in the same division. Is this a big game? You bet. The
winner could rise, the loser completely sink in the AFC playoff
picture. Kansas City has won four straight over the Raiders. The
Chiefs often play their best football against them in one of the
league's longest and fiercest rivalries, which the Chiefs lead
39-36-2. Chiefs linebacker Derrick Thomas has nine sacks in his
last three games vs. the Raiders. He will harass quarterback Rich
Gannon. And the Chiefs continue their streak in this series.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs, 28-24.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (2-8) at Carolina (4-6)
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons last season earned a trip to the Super Bowl in part
by forcing turnovers and committing few. This season has been the
opposite. They face a hot quarterback in Steve Beuerlein who
completed 21 of 27 (77.7 percent) passes for 199 yards, two
touchdowns and no interceptions in Carolina's 31-17 victory over
Cleveland last week. Carolina at home this season has outscored
four opponents by 89-56. Watch Panthers return man Michael Bates,
who returned a kickoff 100 yards for a touchdown vs. Atlanta
earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers, 26-20.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (5-5) at San Francisco (3-7)
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay Coach Ray Rhodes has never beaten the 49ers, a team he
used to coach as defensive coordinator. This is a wonderful chance.
The 49ers are downtrodden and miss Steve Young. Without him, few of
their deficiencies can be masked. This game will improve Green
Bay's playoff hopes and put San Francisco's season in a
let's-just-get-it-over-with spin. Receiver Antonio Freeman will
produce a big game and the Green Bay defense will frustrate 49ers
quarterback Steve Stenstrom. Under the bright lights of Monday
night, San Francisco's varied troubles will be fully exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Packers, 30-20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
