<HEADLINE>
USC DIDN'T KNOW HOW GOOD LOUISIANA TECH WOULD BECOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ File this one in the ``sure looked good at the
time'' folder.
</P>
<P>
   It's spring 1998, and USC, under a mandate from new coach Paul
Hackett to schedule the maximum 12 games his first two seasons, is
looking for an opponent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, two opponents. The Trojans initially agreed to play
then-lowly Hawaii in the season opener. And under NCAA rules, a
trip to the islands doesn't count against your schedule, so USC was
still allowed to add another game.
</P>
<P>
   With an opening on Thanksgiving weekend, the only team
interested was Louisiana Tech, and how good could they be?
</P>
<P>
   A USC official beamed last fall that Tech wide receiver Troy
Edwards was a senior and would be in the NFL by the time the
Bulldogs came to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But did anyone know just how good quarterback Tim Rattay could
become?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, this isn't such a fun game, as Rattay has placed
red-hot Louisiana Tech in the Top 25 for today's contest at the
Coliseum (3:30 p.m.). If you believe The New York Times computer
poll, the Bulldogs are the eighth-best team in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to get up there and I think we definitely deserve
it,'' Rattay said. ``We've earned it and it's really something
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Rattay has averaged nearly 386 yards passing per game, which
will go down as the best mark in NCAA history. And if leading the
Bulldogs (8-2) to eight straight victories and into the Top 25
isn't enough, he's also trying to get his team into a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   The only remaining at-large bid is the Motor City Bowl, and
Louisiana Tech probably needs a victory to secure a matchup with
Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to give USC (5-6) cause for pause, especially while
still enjoying its 17-7 victory over UCLA last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'd better be ready and prepared or we'll be
embarrassed on our own field,'' USC strong safety Ife Ohalete said.
``I don't want to be embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hackett: ``We've just got to be able to push UCLA and
Thanksgiving aside and take care of business. It's going to be a
battle for our football team.''
</P>
<P>
   This has all the earmarks of a 42-41 contest because it may be
difficult for the Trojans to adjust to Louisiana Tech's wide-open
offense, which routinely has four, five or six receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't even been attempting to run,'' cornerback Kris
Richard said. ``They're going to be coming into the game with a lot
of confidence and we'll be the spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an interesting role reversal, but is something I have
accepted. I'm taking this game as a big push into next season. This
is our first ranked team we'll be playing all year. We don't want
to go out as losers.''
</P>
<P>
   As if Louisiana Tech needed any extra motivation, coach Jack
Bicknell III will be eager to beat the Trojans. His father, Jack
Bicknell, the former Boston College coach, lost a pair of games
against USC in 1987-88.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 0-2 so I've got to try to break the string for the
family,'' Bicknell said. ``I can remember one game was at Boston
College and I was an assistant at New Hampshire, and I came down
and watched it, and we got beat pretty good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
