<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-VIGIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIGIL HONORS BONFIRE COLLAPSE VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEPHEN KAYE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ The sun dipped behind the engineering
building at Texas A&AMP;M University shortly before 6 Thursday night.
Truth is, though, darkness hasn't left this place for a week now.
</P>
<P>
   But tens of thousands of candles pierced that darkness Thursday
night, cradled in the hands of tens of thousands of people, young
and old, who gathered on Thanksgiving evening where a tragic
accident killed 12 Aggies and injured 27 others a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The somber candlelight vigil was held on a night usually
reserved for a spirited pep rally and lighting of the traditional
massive bonfire before the annual football game against the
University of Texas. The deadly collapse of the bonfire stack Nov.
18 led university officials to cancel its lighting this year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, many turned out to pray and to say goodbye. And they
turned out to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Johnette Jarvis, a 1970 A&AMP;M graduate and the mother of two
current students, said the outpouring of emotion from Aggies past
and present has been ``wonderfully supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look around, and you see all of this, you get some
peace,'' said Jarvis, a resident of Gruver, north of Amarillo at
the top of the Texas Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Many mourners arrived hours before the vigil. Wearing ribbons,
they held hands, whispered among themselves and cried. Their
candles enveloped the fenced-off bonfire site in flickering light.
</P>
<P>
   The makeshift memorial for the dead continued to build. Flowers,
tributes to the dead and messages of hope have helped in the
healing, many said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never have imagined this tragedy,'' said senior
Tiffany Barfield of Palestine, a member of a student organization
called the Traditions Council. ``We've gotten so much support from
around Texas, really all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas A&AMP;M is a family,'' she said. ``This has been extremely
hard on the community and all Aggies. This helps us get through it.
Just look how many people have come out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherylon Carroll, associate director of university relations,
said the vigil drew about 100,000 people. Last year, attendance at
the bonfire was about 70,000.
</P>
<P>
   Families of the victims ``can look at this and see that people
really care about them here,'' said Mike Payne of Price, a 1975
graduate who helped build the bonfire stack when he was a student.
``My feelings right now are with the families. I can't imagine what
they're going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Two students remained hospitalized Thursday, including John
Comstock of Richardson, who was in critical condition at College
Station Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Several fans of the University of Texas, who were in town for
the Longhorns' annual showdown with the Aggies on Friday, came to
pay their respects. In turn, the Aggies said thanks.
</P>
<P>
   One sign along Farm Road 60, which leads into College Station
from the southwest, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Horns. Thanks for your care and support. God bless you.''
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour after the vigil began, thousands of mourners
marched to Kyle Field about a mile away to participate in A&AMP;M's
annual Yell Practice, another part of the Aggie tradition.
</P>
<P>
   University officials have said they won't decide the fate of the
90-year-old bonfire tradition until their investigation is
complete. A task force will be appointed to oversee the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
