<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-CWOBOYS-DOLPHINS-     11-25 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CWOBOYS-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO HIS CHAGRIN, JIMMY JOHNSON SEES THE OLD COWBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Jimmy Johnson looked up and through the Texas
Stadium roof. Yes, the hole was still there. He looked left and
right saw 64,328 fans who had come to watch him stroll these
sidelines once again and to view his new team, the Miami Dolphins.
He looked across the field and recognized the blue and white
uniforms, the blue star, the Dallas Cowboys. The team he had
coached for five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He looked onto the field and he easily recognized the players.
</P>
<P>
   And on this Thanksgiving Day, they looked a lot like the bunch
that twice won him Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with fever-pitch intensity and purpose, and ruining
Johnson's return, Dallas ripped Miami, 20-0. It was a startling
display, in which the Dallas defense intercepted Dan Marino five
times. The defense also watched as Miami missed three field goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins fell to 8-3 and the Cowboys improved to 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas offense won the yardage battle, 324 yards to 273
yards, and kept the ball for nearly 10 more minutes than Miami.
</P>
<P>
   For 60 minutes Dallas rose, and looked far superior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superstars when they are challenged are dangerous,'' Johnson
said of the Cowboys. ``It was national TV and they were challenged.
They played great.''
</P>
<P>
   They did so from the start. Dolphins place kicker Olindo Mare
missed a 52-yard field goal late in the first quarter. Then, early
in the second quarter, with Miami at the Dallas 9-yard line, Deion
Sanders, in the end zone, grabbed a Marino pass that had been
tipped and bobbled by safety George Teague.
</P>
<P>
   Just before halftime, Mare missed a 47-yard field goal. Mare
entered the game having converted 29 of 32 field goal attempts this
season. He would match his season total of misses in this game.
</P>
<P>
   Miami gained a clue after a scoreless first half _ it was in for
a testy fight and the ball and the momentum was not bouncing its
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's going to have on and off days,'' Miami linebacker
Zach Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mistakes,'' said Miami cornerback Terrell
Buckley. ``We just wanted the team to play well. That didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Both quarterbacks _ Marino and the Cowboys' Troy Aikman _ were
returning from injuries and layoff. Marino had suffered a shoulder
injury, Aikman a concussion, and both had to find their grooves.
Marino was 14 of 35 for 176 yards with those five interceptions and
a long pass of only 27 yards. Aikman was 16 of 29 for 232 yards
with one touchdown, no interceptions and a long pass of 65 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Miami entered with a more glamorous defense.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas cornerback Charlie Williams said every Dallas defensive
player noticed the attention the Miami defense had received.
Williams said: ``We took it upon ourselves to win this game with
defense. We talked about it all week. We just said we gotta go
play. We knew they had the better defense in reputation. So, we
just did our thing.''
</P>
<P>
   They did it for points in the third quarter, completely changing
the game's complexion.
</P>
<P>
   With 7:08 remaining in the third quarter, linebacker Dexter
Coakley stepped in front of a Marino pass and ran it back 46 yards
for a touchdown. In a scoreless game, a defensive duel, the Dallas
defense had struck gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked out into the flat and when I saw the ball coming I
prayed that I would not drop it,'' Coakley said. ``When I caught
it, all I thought about was getting into the end zone. The sky is
the limit for us if we can stick together and stay focused. We can
be a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Coakley's play set the tone for the fourth quarter. More Miami
turnovers. More Dallas domination.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas wrapped up the victory in the fourth quarter with Rocket
Ismail's 65-yard touchdown catch sandwiched between two field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami offense continued to wilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game I felt pretty good,'' Marino said. ``Right now
I don't feel well at all. They didn't do anything that we didn't
expect they'd do. We really didn't adjust to anything either. I
didn't make good decisions. It was missing, it was a timing thing.
I wasn't doing things to give us a chance to win. I had two
practices before this game. I'm not making excuses, but it's going
to take some time to get back into rhythm. I'm going to learn from
this. It's the only way I know how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas learned something, too.
</P>
<P>
   It can be better than a .500 team.
</P>
<P>
   It stood tall in Johnson's return under tremendous scrutiny,
winning a game few thought it could. It made Dallas owner Jerry
Jones beam with pride. It made Cowboys coach Chan Gailey hopeful
while remaining unbeaten (5-0) at home this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really proud of what we did, and our defense is getting
better and better,'' Gailey said. ``Our defense just may be able to
get us a long way. I said it earlier, you can't be 11-5 without
going 6-5 first. Now that we are 6-5, we just have to keep working
hard.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
