<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONS BEGIN TO RESTRICT THEIR PLANTS AND WILDLIFE
</P>
<P>
   Many developing countries, angry that others have profited from
the animal and plant life within their borders, have begun
restricting the freedom of scientists to collect biological samples
and are demanding compensation in exchange for permits.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists warn that scores of research projects that might
lead to breakthroughs in medicine and agriculture, as well as to
the study and preservation of endangered species, are being impeded
or abandoned. The countries controlling access say that their
resources have been used without compensation, acts they call
``bio-piracy.''
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN WON'T BLOCK NATWEST BID
</P>
<P>
   Britain said it would not block the Bank of Scotland's $36
billion hostile bid for National Westminster Bank on grounds of
competition, leaving it to shareholders to decide whether the bank
will be taken over.
</P>
<P>
   BONDS LINKED TO BAD JAPANESE DEBT
</P>
<P>
   The Tokyo office of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter priced the first
set of bonds linked to nonperforming Japanese real estate loans,
paving the way for what may be a flood of deals aimed at clearing
away the mountain of bad debt on the balance sheets of Japanese
banks and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   OIL PRODUCER UNDER FIRE OVER SUDAN
</P>
<P>
   Talisman Energy, Canada's largest independent oil and gas
producer, has run into a huge public relations problem because of
its operations in Sudan. The company is under attack by
representatives of church and civil-servant pension funds in the
United States and Canada for abetting a government that, according
to a U.N. report, is guilty of genocide and other abuses of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   MBA PROGRAMS MULTIPLY IN BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of business education in Britain has unleashed
cutthroat competition among a growing number of schools for talent,
rankings and money. Since 1985, the number of institutions offering
MBA courses has spiraled to 116 from 26, and the number of
graduates has almost quadrupled. The business of running management
schools has blossomed from modest beginnings in the 1960s to an
industry worth $2.5 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL MARKETS TO CLOSE EARLY
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. financial markets, which were closed in observance of
Thanksgiving, will reopen Friday for abbreviated sessions. The
stock markets will close at 1 p.m., and the bond market will close
at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's benchmark stock index rose to a record, its first in
more than a year and a half, powered by a surge in technology
stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
