<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JOHNSON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C., S.C.) 
BOXER WHO YEARNED FOR A TITLE WINDS UP IN A COMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the promoter called in September to offer him a chance to
fight in Atlantic City, N.J., Stephan Johnson knew it would
probably be his last chance to become a contender for a world title
fight and the big payday that had eluded him for his entire career.
</P>
<P>
   But something went horribly wrong last Sunday in the ring at the
Taj Mahal casino. Johnson was fighting Paul Vaden for the U.S.
Boxing Association junior middleweight championship, a relatively
meaningless belt that both men saw as a steppingstone to a world
title fight.
</P>
<P>
   Though the judges said he outboxed Vaden through nine rounds,
Johnson suddenly lost consciousness at the end of the 10th after
Vaden delivered what appeared to be two fairly light blows. Johnson
never woke up.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 31, has been in a coma at the Atlantic City Medical
Center ever since. He has remained in critical condition attached
to a respirator, while his mother, sister, trainer and girlfriend
have waited in a nearby room. Doctors have diagnosed his condition
as subdural hematoma, a buildup of blood between the brain and the
skull.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is such a gladiator,'' his manager and trainer, Kenneth
Woods, said on Wednesday, taking a break from the hospital vigil.
``He was always one fight away from hitting the big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's story is not so different from the lives of thousands
of young men from poor neighborhoods around the world who seek
solace in boxing gyms and sacrifice their bodies for the slim
chance of fame and fortune. His dream of a title fight is every
journeyman boxer's dream. His coma is their nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson might have pushed his body one step too far in
pursuit of that dream, and questions have been raised about his
health before the last fight, his friends and former trainers say.
</P>
<P>
   He had suffered a similar knockout during a fight against Fitz
Vanderpool in Toronto last April, falling unconscious after a
series of light blows when he had dominated most of the fight. He
later blamed the loss on dehydration, but the boxing authorities in
Ontario ordered a battery of tests and suspended him from fighting
in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   After that fight, Johnson confided in friends that he was
seriously considering giving up boxing to become a full-time
fitness instructor. He knew promoters saw him as what is known as a
trial horse, a fighter past his prime but good enough to test
newcomers on the way up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew that the chances for him getting a world title were
slim,'' said Brian Adams, a friend. ``He wanted to get away from
it. It was becoming just routine for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also had aspirations to become a writer and had shown
friends fiction, poetry and a screenplay he had written, all gritty
tales about the boxing world. He was one of the few fighters at
Gleason's Gym in Brooklyn who scribbled notes in a composition book
when inspiration hit, his friends said.
</P>
<P>
   But the lure of one last chance to get to the top was too much
to ignore, his trainers and friends said. He had grown up in
Brooklyn's Bedford-Stuyvesant section and learned to box at 13
after he wandered into the New Bed-Stuy Boxing Association, the gym
that produced an Olympic champion, Mark Breland, and he fell in
love with the sport.
</P>
<P>
   A Career Just Short of a Contender's
</P>
<P>
   Like many kids in his hard and unforgiving neighborhood, Johnson
came from poverty and saw prizefighting as a way out. He won his
division in the 1986 Empire State Games and became a professional
the next year. He was only 19.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career Johnson won more than he lost and got an
opportunity to fight such top-flight middleweights as Roy Jones
Jr., Willy Wise, Vincent Pettway and Wilfredo Rivera. He had fast
hands and quick feet, but he always seemed to come up a little
short in fights that would have made him a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had a lack of concentration,'' said Carlos Ortiz, a
former lightweight champion who trained Johnson until 1994. ``He's
a great kid. He has a lot of ability and a good sense of the sport.
But he becomes distracted and then he gets hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz said he urged Johnson to retire after he lost a 12-round
bout to Rivera in 1993. Rivera gave Johnson such a beating that his
retina became detached, requiring him to take a year off. He
started teaching boxing at New York fitness clubs to make money.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new trainer, Johnson tried to come back in 1996 and
1997, but lost his two fights. It looked as if his professional
career was over after Andrew Lewis knocked him out in six rounds in
June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the next year Woods agreed to take over as Johnson's
trainer. Woods thought Johnson's problem was impatience: too often
he tried to slug it out instead of boxing his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   That fall, Woods got Johnson a match in Georgia against Sam
Garr, an up-and-coming welterweight. State officials said privately
that the promoters chose Johnson as a last-minute replacement for
another fighter because they considered him a weak opponent and
wanted to build up Garr's record. But Johnson surprised everyone
and knocked out Garr in five rounds.
</P>
<P>
   That victory led to the matchup with Vanderpool last April, a
fight that would have made Johnson a contender in his division
again. But he had trouble losing enough weight to get under the
150-pound limit for superwelterweights required by Canadian rules,
Woods said. Dehydrated and perhaps weak from training to lose
weight, Johnson went down in the 11th round and had to be taken to
a hospital for the night.
</P>
<P>
   On the flight back to New York the next morning, Johnson was
severely depressed, Woods said. ``He asked me what did I think he
should do in terms of retiring,'' the trainer recalled. ``I told
him I thought he would be better if he didn't fight anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want him to box anymore, but I told him he was a
grown man and the decision was his,'' Woods added.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Johnson called Woods at his home in Charlotte,
N.C., and said he wanted to continue fighting, Woods said, and the
trainer returned to New York. That month, Woods said, Johnson had a
battery of tests done, including a CAT scan at Mount Sinai
Hospital, and was told he was in good health.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking his fighter needed to get his confidence back, Woods
promptly procured Johnson a bout in Greenville, S.C., against
Otilio Villarreal on Aug. 7, in which Johnson won a decision. Then
Woods matched Johnson against Calvin Moody in Albany, Ga., in early
October. Moody was clearly outclassed, and Johnson knocked him out
in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   $10,000, and a Shot at a World Title
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson's break appeared to come before the Moody fight,
when Carl Moretti, a matchmaker for Main Events, called to ask if
Johnson would be willing to fight Vaden in Atlantic City. He would
be paid $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, it seemed a good matchup, Moretti said. The main
attraction of the evening was to be a heavyweight bout between
Andrew Golota and Michael Grant, to be broadcast on television by
HBO. Because Vaden shares a manager with Grant, he was put on the
fight card in the earlier fight as a ritual courtesy.
</P>
<P>
   Moretti said he chose Johnson as an opponent partly because he
was from New York and could attract a local crowd and partly
because both fighters were older warriors trying to make a
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The USBA's junior middleweight championship was vacant because
the previous champion had literally outgrown the weight class.
Vaden, a former champion whose career had taken a downward turn,
was looking to become a contender again and a chance to fight
Fernando Vargas for the IBF belt.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was also trying to climb back up the rankings, Moretti
said. Moretti said the questions raised in his mind by Johnson's
loss in Toronto had been outweighed by his two more recent
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being 31 years old, he's probably a step past his prime, but
good enough to fight and compete,'' Moretti said. ``In no way do I
consider him a washed-up journeyman.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Woods said, he and Johnson met with officials from the
IBF ranking committee before agreeing to the fight. The officials
promised, he said, that if Johnson, who had a record of 26-8-1
before the fight, were to beat Vaden, he would be ranked a
contender to fight Vargas. That would mean at least one big purse
before retirement, Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew his time as a boxer was coming to an end,'' Woods
said. ``It was my job to get him the most money at the least
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did not disappoint the promoters, Moretti said. He
fought well and was leading on two of the three judges' score
cards, until the 10th round, when his world went black in a
flicker.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear how Johnson managed to fight three times in
three states while still under suspension for medical reasons in
Ontario. As a general practice, state boxing commissions will not
allow a fighter who has been knocked out in another jurisdiction to
fight until he has satisfied the authorities in that jurisdiction
that he is medically fit.
</P>
<P>
   But Ken Hayaschi, the Ontario athletics commissioner, said
Johnson had remained suspended in Canada. Although, in June,
Johnson sent Hayaschi the results of a CAT scan done at Mount Sinai
Hospital, he never sent two other neurological tests required under
Canadian law.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing officials in New Jersey said that before approving the
fight on Sunday, they reviewed a CAT scan and other tests that
Johnson presented to them. Boxing officials in Georgia said they
initially told promoters that Johnson could not fight in October
because of the Canadian suspension, but reversed themselves when
they learned from Fight Fax, a private records company, that the
suspension had been lifted. That report was erroneous, Hayaschi
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in South Carolina could not be reached for comment on
Wednesday, but Woods said they had asked to see copies of Johnson's
CAT scan results before approving the fight there in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``But something was wrong,'' Woods acknowledged. ``There was
obviously some injury that they didn't pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxing as a Metaphor for a Fighter's Life
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson has lain in the intensive-care unit, his family
has received hundreds of calls from his friends, fellow fighters
and students. Johnson was a popular teacher at the Equinox Health
Club in New York, where he trained professionals in the science of
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   His level of fitness was legendary at the club. He regularly
asked his students to do 100 push-ups with him, and when he got to
the last five, he did them on his thumbs, they said. More than 100
of his students went to Atlantic City to see him fight on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   His friends say Johnson's life centered on boxing and staying in
shape. He prided himself on eating healthy foods and started most
mornings with push-ups and a long run. After teaching fitness
classes all afternoon, he trained at Gleason's Gym every evening.
``Stephan was a health nut,'' Adams, his friend, said.
</P>
<P>
   But boxing was also something of a religion for him, they said.
Johnson relaxed by watching videos of old fights. He read
voraciously, usually about the lives of other fighters and the
history of the sport. He could often be found with a biography
under his arm. Boxing was the inspiration for his own writing, they
said, as well as the spiritual metaphor he used to understand his
life. He saw his defeats as lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing was a vehicle for Stephan,'' one of his students,
Charles Jamison, said. ``As much as it was a defining part of his
life, it was only part of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jamison said, the temptation of one last shot at a title
was one Johnson could not resist. ``He thought that if he was able
to prove himself as a legitimate contender by virtue of this
fight,'' Jamison said, ``he would get a shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
