<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-ARTAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURY FORCES RETIREMENT OF THE SPEED KING ARTAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the morning he was scheduled to enter Saturday's Cigar Mile
for a final shot at winning the title Horse of the Year, the
sprinter Artax was suddenly retired Thursday after he was found to
have torn the suspensory ligament in his left foreleg.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-year-old son of Marquetry who set three speed records this
year and won the Breeders' Cup Sprint three weeks ago, Artax was
poised to enter the race as the favorite. But his trainer, Louis
Albertrani, said he discovered a small lesion in the upper part of
the suspensory ligament after the colt seemed out of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   The injury provided another dramatic example of the cruel
fortunes of racing. Artax joins a long list of star-crossed horses
that includes A.P. Indy, who was scratched from the Kentucky Derby
on the morning of the race in 1992 with a foot injury, and
Charismatic, who won the Derby and the Preakness this year and then
finished third in the Belmont Stakes after fracturing his left
foreleg in two places in the homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   Both Albertrani and Ernie Paragallo, the owner of Artax, have
been discounting the notion that they were running their horse in
the Cigar Mile simply to clinch Horse of the Year. But they
acknowledged that winning the stakes race could not hurt his
chances. Now, two days before the race, they were left with a star
horse who had run for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame, but he is retired,'' Albertrani said Thursday
morning at his barn at Belmont Park in New York. ``But he did his
job for us, and really had a great year.''
</P>
<P>
   Artax probably tore the ligament during a fast workout Tuesday
morning when he flew half a mile in 45 4/5 seconds. Five days
earlier, he raised some concern when he worked a slow mile in 1:44
3/5. But Albertrani attributed the slow work to the fact that he
had changed the horse's routine and tried to rate him, or get him
to conserve his speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all of my horses, I jog them the day after they breeze,''
Albertrani said. ``After he jogged Wednesday, we noticed he was
off. We checked him out, and that's when we discovered a small
lesion in the upper part of the suspensory.''
</P>
<P>
   Paragallo, who endured a series of misfortunes with Unbridled's
Song two years ago, said he had no control over Horse of the Year,
which is left to a complex vote by racing writers and officials.
But he extolled his horse's success even while lamenting his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artax had a phenomenal year,'' Paragallo said. ``He broke or
tied three track records, and I don't know any horse that did that.
He won three Grade I races.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strange thing was that, when we first saw that he was off,
we thought it was his foot. So, we called in a bunch of
veterinarians and the hoof specialist Ian McKinlay. When we
couldn't find anything, we X-rayed him up and down. When that
showed nothing, we scanned him up and down. That's when we found
the suspensory injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Paragallo said he still was not sure the ligament was causing
the problem, ``but I'm not going to take any chances with Artax.''
He said Artax would stand as a stallion in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Paragallo entered another of his horses, the
3-year-old Adonis, in the Cigar Mile. It will be run for a purse of
$350,000 with a field of nine. Adonis won the Wood Memorial last
April but proved a disappointment in the Triple Crown races. Also,
Affirmed Success became a late entry when Artax became a late
dropout and even inherited Artax's jockey, Jorge Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Artax won only four of his 15 starts this year, and he was a
sprinting specialist, which meant that he had two strikes on him in
the voting for Horse of the Year. But no horse rose above the herd
as the logical candidate for Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens lost his final three races and ran poorly in the
Breeders' Cup Classic. Victory Gallop was retired with a leg
injury. Charismatic, after winning the Kentucky Derby and the
Preakness, was retired after his misfortune in the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   But Artax became one of the year's dramatic stars because of his
speed.
</P>
<P>
   In May in the Carter at Aqueduct, he broke Dr. Fager's track
record by sprinting seven furlongs in 1:20. In October in the
Forest Hills Handicap at Belmont Park, he broke Groovy's track
record by dashing six furlongs in 1:07 3/5. And in November at
Gulfstream Park in the Breeders' Cup Sprint, he tied Prospector's
track record and broke the Breeders' Cup record for the race by
flying six furlongs in 1:07 3/5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
