u a BC-NY-COLUMN-MENTAL-NYT &LR;      11-25 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-MENTAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC COLUMN: MENTALLY ILL AND ADRIFT ON STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Breathes the New Yorker whose thoughts and prayers
are not with Nicole Barrett this holiday season?
</P>
<P>
   But let's be honest with ourselves. One reason her plight stirs
us is that it pushes every ``there but for the grace of God go I''
button. Any of us could have been walking in midtown Manhattan and
suddenly had life turned upside down, as hers was last week when
she was smashed in the head with a brick.
</P>
<P>
   There is a group of New Yorkers _ not a large one _ who can also
put themselves in the shoes of Ms. Barrett's attacker. While
nothing is publicly known about this fellow, everyone seems to be
working on the theory that he is homeless and mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Eugenia Burgess has been there. She has been on the street, on
drugs and, she acknowledges, not 100 percent in the head. She has
also been the victim and perpetrator of terrible violence. ``When I
heard voices,'' said Ms. Burgess, 42, ``they'd tell me to do things
so bad, they'd frighten me.''
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Fonville, only 20, has been there, too. It would not
surprise him if the brick-wielder was trapped in the same mental
labyrinth. ``Maybe somebody did something to him, or a girl
disrespected him,'' Fonville said. And while not excusing the man's
violence, Michele Nesbitt, 37, suggested that ``maybe it was
because he wasn't getting proper treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   That much seemed a safe bet to her and other former homeless
people who are living these days in Queens residences run by
Phoenix House, the drug-treatment center. Eight of them got
together the other day to talk about life on the street and the
long, uncertain road out of it.
</P>
<P>
   They formed a quorum of misery, these troubled souls with their
criminal records, histories of violence, addictions to a laundry
list of drugs and assorted mental problems: bipolar disorder,
voices in the head, severe depression, you name it. They are, or
were, the kinds of people the rest of us step around when we see
them on the street, or pretend do not exist by burying our heads in
the newspaper when they stumble into the subway car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people consider us normal,'' said Jeanine
Matteo, 31. ``They look down on us. Nobody would ever reach out to
people like us to say, `Do you need help?'''
</P>
<P>
   Her Phoenix House roommate gave only her first name, Kelly,
because she did not want to embarrass her family on Long Island.
Kelly is 21. She has done a lot of living in those few years, not
much of it good, certainly not the part when she was strung out and
homeless in Tompkins Square Park in the East Village. She had come
mentally unhinged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voices told me to rob people,'' Kelly said. ``I looked at
people not as people, just purses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We get looked at like we're bad people who do sick things,''
she said. ``But in treatment you realize that we're sick people who
do bad things.''
</P>
<P>
   David Muse, 36, recalled how it used to be. ``I get these
outbursts when I get so very emotional, my chest rises up, '' he
said. ``But I've had proper medication for four or five months. It
balances me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly picked up on his point. ``If a person has diabetes, he has
a chemical imbalance, and you give him insulin,'' she said. ``But
if a person's mentally ill or addicted to drugs, he's got a
chemical imbalance, too. But they throw him in jail. What happens
if you put a diabetic in jail without treatment? He dies. And what
happens to us? Well, we wither and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Treatment, they all agreed, is the underplayed component in the
Giuliani administration's latest roundup of street people, which to
them suggests not so much a thought-out policy as a knee-jerk
reaction to lurid tabloid headlines after the assault on Ms.
Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Even the mayor acknowledged last week that neither the city nor
the state has come up with enough money for programs needed by the
mentally ill homeless. But the focus for now is on the area of
governance he is most comfortable with: law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   That approach alone will lead to failure, predicted Joan Jones,
49. ``There's more drugs in jail than on the street,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Ms. Jones added, homeless people themselves have to
want to get a grip. Francisco Harkless, 29, said that he finally
decided to enter a treatment program early this year because ``I
got tired of getting high, and I knew it was time to give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Burgess simply ``got sick and tired of being sick and
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty lucky that I'm here to tell the story,'' she
said. ``God must've been looking over me, because with the things
that I did, I should be dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
