<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-MEDIAT     11-25 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-MEDIATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MICROSOFT REFEREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Nov. 26:
</P>
<P>
   Neither Microsoft nor the Justice Department appears ready to
negotiate an out-of-court settlement of the government's antitrust
charges. But Thomas Penfield Jackson, the trial judge whose initial
ruling three weeks ago labeled Microsoft a bullying monopolist,
wants a quick settlement anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Last week he made an artful move to get one, appointing one of
the country's leading antitrust experts, Richard Posner, a federal
appeals court judge, to serve as mediator for renewed settlement
talks. Posner has a rare qualification. He strikes fear in the
hearts of both sides of this epic battle _ enough fear, perhaps, to
compel them to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Posner is an intellectual leader of a conservative brand of
jurisprudence associated with the University of Chicago. Justice
officials will note with some alarm that his writings on antitrust
caution against aggressive remedies, pointing out that
government-imposed breakups of monopolies often backfire. Posner's
credentials will also give him the credibility to warn government
negotiators that they risk defeat if they do not settle soon. Based
on Jackson's initial ruling, Microsoft is almost certain to lose
the first round. It will then appeal. The appeals court includes
prominent conservative justices who, Posner can explain, may be
more hostile to the government's case than Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   William Kovacic, an antitrust expert at the George Washington
University Law School, predicts that Posner will also point out to
government negotiators that there is a gray area in Jackson's
initial ruling. The judge found that Microsoft's licenses with
equipment manufacturers and Internet companies went too far in
shutting competitors out of important markets. But he did not
define the boundary between acceptable and unacceptable contracts,
and Posner may well warn the government lawyers that they risk
losing everything if the appeals court decides that Jackson's final
ruling draws the line in the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   Posner will also make Microsoft squirm. He is regarded as a
jurist who interprets the law as it is, not as he would have
written it himself. He can point to cases where he has argued
forcefully, as have many other conservative judges, that appeals
courts should give deference to the findings of regulatory agencies
and trial judges. He will warn Microsoft that Jackson's finding of
facts will not be easily overturned by the conservatives on the
appeals court and that Microsoft bears an enormous risk by refusing
to settle now.
</P>
<P>
   There are other pressures at play. Jackson cited possible
divisions between the state attorneys general and the Justice
Department as a reason for asking Posner to mediate the dispute. If
state and federal officials demand different remedies, the case
could be tied up in legal tangles for years. Posner may wield
enough clout to bring the state officials in line with federal
antitrust officials.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also faces private lawsuits. The typical consumer has
little to gain from suing Microsoft. But spread across millions of
consumers, the amount at risk in a class-action suit provides a
potential bonanza for lawyers and a nightmare for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts argue that the threat of private lawsuits provides
no incentive for Microsoft to settle now because Jackson's initial
finding _ that Microsoft acted as an abusive monopolist _ is
already public and provides sufficient legal ammunition for private
plaintiffs to sue to recover damages for paying Microsoft
excessively high prices for its software. But Kovacic disagrees,
arguing that a settlement could in effect suppress Jackson's
initial ruling and strip private plaintiffs of most of its legal
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Posner's presence hardly guarantees a settlement. So far, there
is no obvious remedy that satisfies both sides. A seemingly modest
sanction, such as prohibiting Microsoft from writing contracts that
cut its competitors off from potential customers, would in fact
lead to immodest results _ perpetual judicial review of contracts
throughout the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   But relieving the government of continual oversight would
require a radical restructuring _ breaking up Microsoft, or forcing
it to license its operating system to other software companies so
they could modify and sell it on their own. Perhaps the odds of
finding a remedy acceptable to Microsoft and the government remain
low, but they are far higher with Posner than without him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991125.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-25 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1621 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SCHOOL-PRAYER-NY     11-25 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCHOOL-PRAYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PRAYER AND SCHOOL FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Nov. 26:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has agreed to decide whether a Texas school
district violated the Constitution by letting students lead others
in prayer over the public address system before high school
football games. The practice plainly breaches the First Amendment's
wall of separation between church and state, and the justices
should not hesitate to say so.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals found that the
school district's policy of using ``student surrogates to deliver
prayers before a captive audience'' was a deliberate attempt to
``circumvent'' the Supreme Court's principled but highly
controversial 1992 holding that public schools could not invite
members of the clergy to lead prayers at graduation ceremonies.
Written by Justice Anthony Kennedy, that thoughtful 5-4 decision
correctly recognized that ``prayer exercises in elementary and
secondary schools carry a particular risk of indirect coercion.''
It also recognized that students should not be made to feel like
outsiders by a religious observance that is not their own.
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas case, the fact that pregame prayers are led by
students rather than clergy does not lessen the pressure for
religious conformity. It may even increase it, given how
susceptible schoolchildren are to peer pressure and how seriously
Texans take football. Nor can the change in messengers mask the
school's role in organizing the religious worship, or transform the
occasion into a neutral public forum where all kinds of speech are
welcome. In reality, school officials maintained total control of
the program, the stated purpose of which was to ``solemnize'' the
occasion with prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The case could well resonate in the 2000 elections. Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the front-running Republican presidential
candidate, signed the brief submitted by Texas and eight other
states urging the court to allow prayer at school sporting events.
Earlier this month the House weighed in with a similar resolution
calling on the court to allow it.
</P>
<P>
   For mysterious reasons, the court has agreed to review only that
part of the 5th Circuit ruling that correctly held student-led
prayers to be unconstitutional at school sporting events. The court
declined to take up the 5th Circuit's contradictory holding that
students may offer ``nonsectarian and nonproselytizing'' prayers at
graduation ceremonies because commencement exercises, unlike school
sporting events, are ``singularly serious'' in nature. That
appeared to clash with the Supreme Court's past ruling against
clergy offering graduation prayers, and left unclear just where the
line is drawn on school-sponsored prayer.
</P>
<P>
   To resolve the muddle, the Supreme Court must make clear that
the First Amendment's protection against state establishment of
religion does not depend on whether the event is a commencement or
a football game, or whether the person delivering the prayer
happens to be a student.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
