<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NIGERIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NIGERIA'S CLEAN BROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Nov. 26:
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is Africa's most populous country, and potentially one
of its most prosperous. But for decades, a deeply rooted culture of
corruption has undermined Nigeria's economy, impoverished its
people and tarnished its international reputation. It has also
helped make Nigeria one of the world's leading centers of drug
smuggling, including much of the narcotics that reach the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Now, under a new democratic government, there are encouraging
signs of change. If President Olusegun Obasanjo continues his
aggressive campaign against bribery, kickbacks and consumer scams,
Washington and other Western governments should reward his efforts
by rescheduling some of the debts Nigeria incurred under the
corrupt military regimes of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo came to office with a deserved reputation as a
reformer. In the 1970s, he headed the only military government in
Nigeria's history to freely hand power to an elected successor.
Later, under the harsh 1990s dictatorship of Gen. Sani Abacha, he
spent three years in prison for opposing government repression. But
few expected a serious attack on corruption or a serious
investigation into the abuses of his military predecessors.
Obasanjo's earlier government was known for diverting oil revenues
and demanding payments for licenses and contracts, and his election
campaign this year had been financed by Nigeria's military
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   But since taking office six months ago, Obasanjo has removed
hundreds of corrupt military officers and government officials and
brought legal claims against their business cronies that could
permit the recovery of billions of stolen dollars. Corruption still
plays too big a role in Nigerian political life, and Obasanjo has
shown a disturbing tendency to wink at illicit conduct by his
closest political allies. But the change in Nigeria's ethical
climate is pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria's oil and mineral wealth should disqualify it from
outright debt relief. But when Obasanjo visited Washington in
October, President Clinton endorsed stretching out payments on some
of Nigeria's $30 billion international debt as further reforms
unfold. The Clinton administration should wait until Obasanjo's
strong anti-corruption legislation overcomes parliamentary
resistance. Washington should also demand compliance with
international human rights standards in the oil-producing Niger
Delta region, where the repressive policies of previous military
governments are still in force.
</P>
<P>
   But once these conditions are met, America should help make
Nigeria a showcase for the proposition that an honest, democratic
government can bring a demonstrably better life to ordinary people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
