<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN BACK IN BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ In his first game back since a second concussion
in as many games three weeks ago at Minnesota, quarterback Troy
Aikman finished yesterday's 20-0 victory against Miami with a
flurry.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman completed 9 of 10 passes for 163 yards in the second
half, including a 65-yard pass for a touchdown to Raghib Ismail.
Aikman did most of his damage in the fourth quarter, completing all
five pass attempts for 141 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an offensive standpoint, we knew it was going to be
awfully hard to move the ball 70 to 80 yards without making some
big plays,'' Aikman said. ``We needed to hopefully play good
defense and not have a high-scoring ballgame, and take shots when
we had them.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman spread the ball to nine receivers, only the third time he
has done that this season and the first time since hitting nine on
Oct. 24 against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman recovered from a difficult first half. At halftime,
Aikman was only 7-of-19 for 69 yards. Only one pass went for more
than eight yards, a 35-yard completion to Jason Tucker.
\Nsubheds:Emmitt gets 100 Emmitt Smith notched his sixth 100-yard
game of the season and his third 100-yard outing in the past three
games he has played. Smith missed the Green Bay game two weeks ago
with a broken hand. Smith finished with 103 yards on 31 carries _
his most carries this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys became the fifth team in 11 games to rush for more
than 100 yards against the Dolphins, who entered the game allowing
91.9 yards rushing a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying this all season, the strength of this offense
lies with those five guys up front,'' said Smith, who has 978
rushing yards this season. ``If we use them and continue to mix up
the calls then we can continue making big plays.''
\Nsubheds:Cunningham connects Richie Cunningham kicked two
fourth-quarter field goals, from 36 and 23 yards, to go 2-for-2
yesterday, but coach Chan Gailey bypassed two 50-yard field-goal
opportunities in the first half. Cunningham's first field goal gave
the Cowboys a 10-0 lead early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham has converted 10 of 19 (52 percent) after falling
below 50 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good with my approach and the way I hit the ball,''
Cunningham said. ``Any player wants the opportunity to go out and
play. If you don't you shouldn't be out there.'' \Nsubheds:Penalty
crunch Nine first-half penalties thwarted three promising Cowboys
drives and nearly led to a Miami touchdown. In all, Dallas was
penalized 13 times for 103 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys quashed two drives at the Miami 35 and 34 on
successive possessions. Penalties moved them out of field-goal
range each time, and they failed to convert on fourth-down plays
both times.
</P>
<P>
   A Deion Sanders interception of a Dan Marino pass in the end
zone ended a Miami drive to the Dallas 9, aided by two Cowboys
penalties for 20 yards. Ebenezer Ekuban kept the drive alive with a
15-yard roughing-the-quarterback penalty on third-and-11 from the
Miami 36. \Nsubheds:Right at home The Cowboys are at a loss to
explain why they are 5-0 at home and 1-5 on the road. They play at
New England next week and then have one road game remaining at New
Orleans on Dec. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go on the road,'' Deion Sanders said, ``you need to
pray for us.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail left the
game after suffering a ``mild concussion'' on a 7-yard catch on the
third play of the game. Chan Gailey said initially he didn't
believe Ismail would return. But Ismail did start the second half
and caught a 65-yard fourth-quarter touchdown pass from Troy Aikman
to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Center Mark Stepnoski left the game late in the third quarter
with what is being termed a strained left calf. His status for next
week is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had not been involved in a 0-0 game at halftime
since Oct. 30, 1988, against the Phoenix Cardinals. Coincidentally,
the Dolphins' last 0-0 tie at the half occurred on the same day
against Tampa Bay.
nn
</P>
