<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-THANKSGIVING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MORE STUFFING' IS N.Y. MAYOR'S CRY OF THE DAY, AND IT WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, whose frequent refrain is
that the highest form of compassion is to help people work to help
themselves, briefly shed his tough-love armor Thursday and donned
an apron to help pack up Thanksgiving meals for homebound AIDS
patients.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Giuliani displayed a softer image for the holiday,
the Police Department continued to enforce the mayor's edict to
stop the homeless from sleeping on city streets, by arresting them
if they refused to accept shelter or move along.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 34 homeless people were arrested on various
charges on Wednesday, the police said, bringing to 101 the total
arrested since Giuliani announced the effort last Friday. The
initiative was prompted by the attack on Nicole Barrett, who was
hit in the head with a paving stone, possibly by a homeless man.
</P>
<P>
   After riding in the Thanksgiving Day parade on a float with New
York Yankees manager Joe Torre, Giuliani visited Ms. Barrett and
her family at Bellevue Hospital Center, where she remains in
serious condition as she recovers from brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had started the day with a live television interview
and then arrived at 7:30 a.m. at the downtown Manhattan
headquarters of God's Love We Deliver, a social service
organization that provides about 1,100 meals a day to homebound
people with AIDS in New York City and in Hudson County, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, wearing an apron, plastic gloves and a baseball cap
imprinted with a heart and helping hand insignia, stood behind a
steel counter in the basement kitchen. He scooped stuffing into
small aluminum trays and passed them down the line, where other
workers added turkey, gravy and sweet potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   When the mound of stuffing in front of him ran low, Giuliani,
taking a cue from other workers in the kitchen, shouted,
``Stuffing. More stuffing'' and was immediately resupplied. But
while the organization appreciated the publicity surrounding the
mayor, some workers said they did not support him.
</P>
<P>
   After about 20 minutes packing food, Giuliani left to deliver a
meal and a holiday gift basket to a 48-year-old man with AIDS who
lives in a two-room apartment in a walk-up building on the Lower
East Side. Inside the apartment, Giuliani sat down to chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you doing.'' he asked. The man, wearing a purple
T-shirt and a worn Yankees cap, replied, ``Not well, honestly. I
just got out of the hospital 10 days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He also told the mayor that he believed the city was paying too
much for his subsidized apartment, and asked to be moved to public
housing closer to the hospital where he receives treatment.
Giuliani said he would try to help.
</P>
<P>
   At Police Headquarters on Thursday, Sgt. Rafael Andalia, a
department spokesman, said that officers made contact with 242
homeless people between 4 a.m. and midnight Wednesday. He said 37
were taken to shelters, 4 went to hospitals and 154 agreed to move
along. Sergeant Andalia said he did not expect the department to
have a tally of how many homeless people were arrested on
Thanksgiving until sometime today.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 34 arrested Wednesday, 13 were charged with misdemeanors,
said Andalia. An additional 13 homeless people were issued
summonses, he said. The Giuliani administration's initiative has
been criticized by advocates for the homeless and by civil
libertarians as cruel and unjustified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
