<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHOT-BLOCKING TREE TAKES THE GARDEN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Loren Woods was one tall tree at a college called
Wake Forest. From the bottoms of his feet to the top of his head he
measures 7 feet 1 inch, and he gets even loftier when he leaps and
waves his long limbs to block shots or intimidate opponents. But
Woods was not happy in two seasons at Wake Forest, and he was
willing to miss a year of competition to leave for another school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a problem with the coach,'' Woods said. ``I wasn't
fitting in the program how I thought I would. I really didn't have
a problem with the school. I loved the area.''
</P>
<P>
   He almost chose Seton Hall, but ended up at Arizona after
comparing the April weather in both places. ``If I had went to
Seton Hall in the summertime, it would have probably been an even
tougher decision,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Having served his idle year as a practice participant, Woods is
now the Wildcats' starting center. He and sophomore forward Michael
Wright will lead Arizona into the championship game of the
Preseason National Invitation Tournament on Friday night against
Kentucky at Madison Square Garden. The match of two teams called
the Wildcats was set up Wednesday night when Arizona defeated Notre
Dame by 76-60 and Kentucky held off Maryland by 61-58.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky and Arizona have met only four times. In the 1997 NCAA
championship game, Arizona defeated Kentucky by 84-79 in overtime.
Kentucky was the defending champion that year, and it won again in
1998. Since their 1997 title match, Arizona and Kentucky have met
just once, in the Maui tournament in November 1997, and that was an
89-74 victory for Arizona. One participant in those 1997 games was
Jamaal Magloire, the 6-10 senior center for Kentucky. He could be
matched against Woods on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamaal no doubt is a good center in the lane,'' Woods said.
``Kentucky is a great team, similar to us, an athletic team, with a
good big man down low and a no-nonsense defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Magloire concurred. ``It's going to be a fast-paced game,'' he
said. ``It's definitely going to be exciting for everyone to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Magloire and Woods played in the same all-star tournament when
they were in high school, but have never matched up head to head.
``He was a great player then,'' Magloire said. ``He's only improved
since then. It's going to be a tough game.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Irish on Wednesday, Woods scored 13 points, gathered
10 rebounds and blocked seven shots. It may have been a sample of
what is to come. Asked after that game whether he was game sharp
following his idleness, Woods replied: ``Not yet. You'll see it
when I'm game sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Arizona coach Lute Olson, it was Woods' best game
in his team's 3-0 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``By far,'' Olson said. ``Not only was he a shot-blocker and a
defensive intimidator, he broke their zone with great passes from
the high post.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not difficult to sense the happiness of Woods, who grew up
in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is like my family,'' he said. ``We're all like
brothers. We just have fun out there. It's a more comfortable
program for me. A more laid-back style of play. This program's
letting me do all the things I want to do: run the floor and play
defense, my two strongest attributes. I pretty much can get the
ball wherever I want it.''
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, how good can Woods be?
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky's the limit,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Wright had to defend against Troy Murphy, Notre Dame's
impressive forward, who scored 22 points. Wright also scored 22
points. When the Irish tried to draw Woods away from the basket by
moving Murphy out for higher shots, Olson switched to a zone
defense. It is a strategy he may use more frequently this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody's going to try to take Loren outside, we're not
going to let them take him outside, with his abilities inside,''
Olson said. ``So we've been a 99.9 percent man-to-man team, but we
have worked on the zone for this year because we feel it will be an
effective change for us.''
</P>
<P>
   That formation pleases Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I float around in a zone,'' he said. ``That's perfect for me.
Any shot they put up on the backboard, if it's close to me, I'm
going to get it. If I'm two or three arm lengths away, I'm going to
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   These words suggest bravado, but Olson said this was not
necessarily the case with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loren, No. 1, needs confidence,'' Olson said. ``I think he's a
little too hard on himself. Every game that he has like this, he's
going to be more confident and his teammates will show more
confidence in him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the tournament finale on national television in midtown
Manhattan, Woods said: ``Playing in the Garden is like every kid's
dream. Michael Jordan and all the pros play here. I was watching
the Knicks the other night and getting kind of nervous coming out
here. It's a great experience for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-99 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
