<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-FERGUSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERGUSON'S SUSPENSION SENDS THE JETS SCRAMBLING AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The Jets began scrambling Thursday to change
part of their game plan, their defensive alignments and their
special teams personnel in the wake of the suspension of nose
tackle Jason Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, described by coach Bill Parcells as his best and
strongest defensive lineman, learned after Wednesday's practice
that his appeal of a four-game suspension for violating the NFL's
steroid policy had been denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a domino effect,'' Parcells said of the way the Jets
rushed to make changes for Sunday's game against the Colts in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   With 52 players, the Jets are a man short on this week's roster
because they had not brought in an experienced lineman. This is
part of a series of personnel crises on this team because of
injuries. Parcells chose his words carefully Thursday but there was
little doubt of his exasperation with the penalty, and its timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through Wednesday's practice with Jason playing,'' the
coach said. ``Now we've got two days to change things.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Jets also have known for months that Ferguson faced
the suspension if his appeal was denied. Ferguson apparently tested
positive for a banned substance, which includes a range of
steroids, over the summer. Several teammates said Thursday that
Ferguson had been taking over-the-counter weight-reducing medicine
that contained a banned substance.
</P>
<P>
   In Ferguson's place, Jason Wiltz, a fourth-round rookie, will
see action along with the veteran Ernie Logan. They will be part of
a defensive line that attempts to contain the American Conference's
leading rusher, Edgerrin James, and the top-rated passer, Peyton
Manning.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets had increasingly used a four-man line, instead of three
in recent weeks, to improve the pass rush. It has worked well as
the defense has permitted a total of only 36 points during the
three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson's improved play in returning from a sprained right
ankle in the season's opener has been part of the surge. He missed
three games after the injury. He apparently had already tested
positive by the time of his injury.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to losing him on the line, Parcells said, Ferguson
was one of the club's best protectors on the field-goal kicking
unit, playing either right or left guard.
</P>
<P>
   According to an NFL official, a lengthy process unfolds after a
player and team are first notified following the results of the
random test. The process includes the right to a second test and an
appeal. Once the appeal is heard by Jeff Pash, the league's
executive vice president, then Pash, after consulting with
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue, makes the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the suspension came as soon as the appeals process
ended. Ferguson will be eligible to return for the next-to-last
game of the season, against the Dolphins on Dec. 27. He is not
permitted at the Jets' training complex until that week.
(Coincidentally, on Tuesday, the little-used Giants safety Lyle
West received a four-game suspension for steroid use.)
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was asked if this was an innocent mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``But it's a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells described Ferguson's reaction as ``very upset and
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not unlike Ferguson's reaction in 1997 after he had
tested positive for marijuana at the scouting combine and saw his
draft status sink drastically. He had been highly regarded out of
the University of Georgia and had expected to go in an early round.
Instead, he was the last player the Jets chose in the 1997 draft, a
seventh-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, he has impressed Parcells on and off the
field. Still, this latest incident piled more misery on the coach.
Ferguson is the fourth starter who will miss significant time or
whose season is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm anesthetized by now,'' Parcells said. ``You just try to go
on and do what you can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
