<SLUG> BC-NY-KOSOVARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, KOSOVAR REFUGEES OFFER THANKS FOR MANY REASONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sprawling Kosovar Albanian clan of Erbelis and
Devas celebrated their first Thanksgiving together Thursday. The
hostess, Lili Erbeli, raised her glass of merlot in a toast to the
three dozen cousins squeezed around her dining room table, three
generations of Albanian-Americans with three generations of their
refugee kin. ``Happy Thanksgiving everybody,'' she said. ``Welcome
to my house.''
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the gathering inside Lili and Rex Erbeli's
modest Sheepshead Bay duplex looked a lot like the unusual family
reunion they had over a late-night meal more than six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   On that night, in May of this year, 14 of the Erbelis' relatives
had arrived in New York, disheveled and disoriented refugees from
Mitrovica, one of Kosovo's most embattled cities. They ate chicken
cutlets almost wordlessly. None of the cousins, from here or there,
seemed eager to say much about the terror back home.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday night, many things had changed. The faces of the
Devas were decidedly less gaunt. The youngest of the refugees were
chattering in English. And Lili Erbeli's dining room was even more
crowded. Four other refugee cousins had arrived since the original
batch, which consisted of Lili's sister, Sytkije Deva, and her
husband, Musa, 72, their three grown children and their spouses,
and six grandchildren, ages 11 to 2.
</P>
<P>
   Four turkeys had been cooked, and the trimmings were as eclectic
as those at any immigrant family's Thanksgiving: There were heaps
of stuffed grape leaves alongside sweet potatoes, a giant tray of
Lili's famous custard as well and a pumpkin pie prepared by her
daughter, Ariana. The dining room table was joined with the kitchen
table, but dinner still had to be served in two shifts of 17. A
giant pot of egg noodles sat on the kitchen floor, for there was no
room anywhere else. The family cat slunk around carefully, with
scarce room to move about.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone could be there. The Erbelis' eldest daughter,
Betsy, had six of her husband's refugee kin at her house. Rex had
suggested she bring them along, but then, he joked, they would
probably spill out of the balcony.
</P>
<P>
   The second of three daughters, Albana, 26, couldn't be there,
either. She was spending Thanksgiving as an interpreter with the
U.S. Army at Camp Bondsteel, the U.S. military installation in
Kosovo where President Clinton and his daughter, Chelsea, stopped
off for a pre-Thanksgiving meal earlier this week.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was Lili's first Thanksgiving without Albana. ``Don't mention
it,'' is all she would say. She looked as though she would cry.
</P>
<P>
   For the newcomers, their first American Thanksgiving became an
occasion to reflect on their life here so far. While they once all
slept in the Erbelis' three-bedroom apartment, now they had
apartments of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Each in their own way, they debated still whether to stay here.
The eldest of the Deva siblings, Bujar, 38, and his wife, Yelldez,
36, were still the most reluctant to imagine a future here. After
nearly six months without work, Yelldez, who had been studying back
home to be a doctor, has recently been hired at a department store.
Looking ahead, she is also taking classes to be a medical
assistant. She is learning English by helping her boys _ ages 11
and 7 _ with their homework.
</P>
<P>
   The news from Mitrovica is dismal. Yelldez heard from her mother
that the electricity had been out for 13 days, that food prices
were absurdly steep and that hepatitis was rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, a relative sent a picture of the Deva family
house, which had been burned to the ground. Mensur, 32, the second
of the Deva siblings, said he was prepared for it. He and his
brother and sister learned the news shortly after they fled their
home and landed in a Macedonian refugee camp. They didn't tell
their parents until recently. Seeing the picture of the house,
Mensur said, was hardest on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-two years they lived there,'' he said. ``I was the
first child born there. They built it with their own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Mensur, who now works for an Albanian-American construction
company, said he hasn't entirely given up hopes of reclaiming the
family property. But it is impossible to think about doing anything
now. Mitrovica is occupied by French peacekeeping forces. Tensions
between Serbs and Albanians _ the Deva house was in the Serb part
of town _ are as bad there as anywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, Mensur and his siblings have found apartments in a
building in the Kings Highway neighborhood of Brooklyn, where
people of many nationalities and many faiths live together without
incident. His building, in fact, is packed with Russians. They
sided with the Serbs in their latest conflict with the Kosovars.
But there is no time to talk about such matters, he said, no time
to wonder where your neighbors are from, or what they might think
of you _ as he did back home.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, ``if your neighbor is a Serb, you must talk with them
differently, deal with them differently,'' he recalled. ``Here _
no.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he said, they all miss being at home. But what is there to
go back to? ``What can you do? Wait for mercy, help?'' he asked.
``We have nowhere to work there. It's better to work here.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, he added, he thinks he will get lucky. Still searching for
the proper English expressions, Mensur likened life here to sailing
down a river, ``waiting for a chance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A chance at what? Mensur shrugged, bounced his daughter, Bena,
2, in his arms. ``I going to make it,'' he said. ``I have a
feeling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
