<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOUSIANA-TECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OUTSIDER LOOKS WISTFULLY FOR A BOWL BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a personal ad worth circling:
</P>
<P>
   ``Road Warriors free for holidays. Southern team with 8-2
record. Enjoys travel _ played only three games at home. Loves
action _ brings nation's top-rated air attack led by second-most
productive passer in major college history. Flair for drama _ a
final-second touchdown pass by backup quarterback beat Alabama.
Solid references _ No. 6 in New York Times computer ranking, No. 25
in Associated Press poll. Seeks bowl game in Detroit. If interested
in having big fun and doing right thing, call Louisiana Tech Coach
Jack Bicknell III.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not try an ad? The Bulldogs have done everything else to
earn a spot in one of the 23 bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   They've cruised the country playing anyone anywhere this season
_ at top-ranked Florida State, at Alabama, and at Southern
California Friday evening in the Los Angeles Coliseum. They've won
eight straight after dropping the opener against the Seminoles and
losing their next game at home against No. 24 Texas A&AMP;M. But even
if Louisiana Tech crushes USC (5-6), there's a pretty good chance
the team will be home for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets pretty frustrating,'' said Bicknell, who is in his
first year as head coach at Louisiana Tech. ``Two years ago, we
went 9-2 and didn't go to a bowl game, and it really hurt the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the Bulldogs are an independent and have no
conference tie-in with a bowl. In the cut-and-paste world of bowl
match-making, this means Wake Forest (6-5) will travel to Hawaii to
play the winner of Saturday's game between Arizona (6-5) and
Arizona State (5-5) because the Aloha Bowl promises to match the
No. 4 team in the Atlantic Coast Conference to No. 5 in the
dreadful Pacific 10 Conference if both teams have the minimum six
victories to be eligible for a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That also means the country's best independent team might stay
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Louisiana Tech quarterback Tim Rattay said. ``We
beat Alabama at their place. There are teams with two, four, five
losses that we're better than, but the tie-ins aren't going our
way.''
</P>
<P>
   There is only one bowl invitation left for an at-large
invitation. A victory over Southern California Friday, combined
with a big performance by Rattay and a Pittsburgh loss at West
Virginia may be enough for Motor City Bowl organizers to invite
Louisiana Tech to Detroit. The Motor City Bowl, at the Pontiac's
Silverdome, is already locked in with the Mid-American Conference
champion, which is likely to be 10-0 Marshall. How about a matchup
between scoreboard-scorching teams with two of the best but least
publicized quarterbacks in the nation: Rattay and the Thundering
Herd's Chad Pennington?
</P>
<P>
   But first Rattay needs to get the Bulldogs past the Trojans. For
the third year in the row, he leads the nation in total offense
with 12,340 career yards. He trails only Brigham Young's Ty Detmer
on the career list and needs only 201 yards to overtake
Louisville's Chris Redman for second place.
</P>
<P>
   Will he do it? Bank on it. In 32 games, Rattay's career low is
239 yards against Auburn in 1998. In 26 games, Rattay, a senior,
has passed for 300 or more yards. In 11 of them he has passed for
more than 400 yards and, in seven others, surpassed 500 yards, an
unofficial National Collegiate Athletic Association record.
</P>
<P>
   Rattay, a 6-foot-1-inch native of Phoenix, played a year at
Scottsdale (Ariz.) Community College before he and Louisiana Tech,
in Ruston, got stuck with each other. His 28 junior college
touchdowns were impressive. His 21 interceptions weren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just throwing,'' Rattay said. ``We'd catch it sometimes,
they'd catch it sometimes. Nobody wanted me except Louisiana Tech.
I didn't even know if they were a Division I school, but I didn't
have much choice _ either stay in junior college or go there.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to raise its program's profile, as well make money
(the trip to Florida State was worth $500,000), Louisiana Tech has
endured one of the most competitive road schedules in recent years.
The Bulldogs have beaten Alabama twice, Mississippi State and
Auburn. And Rattay has rung up big numbers against top-notch
opponents before hostile crowds. At Nebraska last season, he threw
for 590 yards in a a 56-27 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to play in front of 80,000 people,'' said Rattay, who
this season has passed for 3,517 yards and 32 touchdowns, with only
nine interceptions. ``They may be booing you, but it's still 80,000
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bicknell, who played at Boston College and is the son of the
World Football League coach Jack Bicknell of the Barcelona Dragons,
intends to keep the Bulldogs on the road to challenge the best. On
the schedule for next season are Penn State, Miami and Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   In 2001, Louisiana Tech will join the Western Athletic
Conference, which has arrangements with bowl games in Las Vegas and
Mobile, Ala. It means definite opportunities for the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be a shame if Louisiana Tech and its 22 seniors are
left off the bowl roster this year, especially after earning the
first AP ranking in the school's history with an offense that
averages more than 470 yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like life; you never know when you've played the
last game,'' Rattay said.
</P>
<P>
   The Motor City organizers would do well to take a hard look at
the Bulldogs. You never know when you've found the team of your
dreams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
