<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANYWAY, DO FORTUNE-COOKIE MAKERS FACE CLASS-ACTION LAWSUITS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marketplace musings for a long Thanksgiving weekend:
</P>
<P>
   - With oil prices soaring but gasoline prices still well
behaved, why hasn't anyone called to compliment the oil companies
on their admirable pricing restraint?
</P>
<P>
   - Wake me when the proposed Power &AMP; Light District starts
revitalizing downtown Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   - Quick, when's the last time you heard something interesting,
insightful or informative on a sports-talk radio show?
</P>
<P>
   - One of the great paradoxes of the fledgling info technology
age is that the jurist sitting in judgment of Microsoft writes in
longhand.
</P>
<P>
   - How many people who object to banks charging noncustomers ATM
fees would themselves work for nothing or provide a service for
free?
</P>
<P>
   - When your conversational partner says, ``Anyway...'' after
you've finished having your say, do you feel as though what you've
just said was considered a bothersome interruption?
</P>
<P>
   - Those who worry about low voter turnout should stop wringing
their hands and start campaigning to have elections held on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   - When politicians say they're forced out of the presidential
race for lack of money, what they're really saying is that their
message hasn't given potential backers reason enough to support
them financially.
</P>
<P>
   - You're getting old if you can remember when Chinese fortune
cookies told your fortune instead of offering inoffensive
platitudes.
</P>
<P>
   - What is it exactly the Reform Party plans to reform?
</P>
<P>
   - Anyone who says teen-agers suffer sleep deficits has never
been a parent of a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   - If you send me an e-mail attachment without identifying
yourself by name and affiliation, don't expect me to download it.
</P>
<P>
   - You're getting old if you can remember the last time David
Letterman said something funny enough to prompt a good
laugh-out-loud guffaw.
</P>
<P>
   - Anyone not scheduled to spend time in an airport this holiday
has much to be thankful for.
</P>
<P>
   - Is it my imagination, or are tort lawyers the only people
really deriving any significant financial benefit from most
class-action lawsuits?
</P>
<P>
   - If they made copiers simple enough for normal people to use
with ease, maybe the machines wouldn't be out of service most of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   - Now that the Glass-Steagall law has been consigned to
history's dustbin, what will members of Congress do to make up for
all the campaign contributions they won't be getting from financial
industry lobbyists seeking favors?
</P>
<P>
   - The worst marketing idea of the late 20th century is the push
to start putting beer in plastic bottles.
</P>
<P>
   - Whatever happened to ``NYPD Blue''?
</P>
<P>
   - The new format of Forbes has a more cluttered look and is more
user-unfriendly than Fortune, if that's possible.
</P>
<P>
   - Most small-business operators don't know it, but they're about
to get clobbered by a federal regulatory blitz involving
ergonomics.
</P>
<P>
   - The best campaign-finance reform would be either a flat-rate
income tax or a national sales tax, because it would end the need
for individuals and businesses to contribute in hopes of gaining
tax favors or avoiding tax punishments.
</P>
<P>
   - Is it possible the fortune-cookie makers stopped telling
fortunes for fear of getting sued if the fortunes didn't come true?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
