<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESERVISTS-KOSOVO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI RESERVISTS BOUND FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eighteen Army reservists based in Bethany, Mo.,
will deploy to Kosovo next week, donning flak jackets and helmets
and doing what a grateful nation expects of them _ moving that
holiday mail.
</P>
<P>
   The 7,400 U.S. troops stationed as peacekeepers in the recent
Balkan war zone soon will expect incoming Christmas cards and
cookies from home, and that's where the 795th Adjutant General
Company (Postal) stands tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We move mail and they want us there for Christmas,'' said Sgt.
Richard Rucker, unit administrator. ``We see this all the time; we
get deployed right around the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   The northwest Missouri soldiers will ship out Thursday for a
nine-month tour. The 795th is the country's most-often deployed
postal unit out of 35 in the reserve system, Rucker said. It also
went to the Persian Gulf, Haiti and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The unit will relieve active duty personnel who have run the
postal operation in Kosovo since April, Rucker said. The reservists
will work at a receiving center in Macedonia and at two camps in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are greatly appreciated when we get over there,'' Rucker
said. ``People want their mail. Our people know that. We know how
important it is to the soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing is hard on spouses, children, relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you are going over there for a purpose, but you still
have a family at home, and that's always on your mind,'' said
reservist Daryl Brandt of Leavenworth, Kan., who has a wife and
2-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt is the only one of the 18 reservists heading to Kosovo
who also did postal duty in the Persian Gulf, Haiti and Bosnia. Two
of those assignments overlapped the Christmas holidays, and one
began in early January, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, no one wants to leave at Christmas,'' said
reservist Patrick Jones of Chillicothe, Mo., who also did Gulf
duty. ``But I'm the one who signed on the dotted line and said I
wanted to serve my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 18 soldiers being dispatched from the unit, six are
married with children. Two are women, and some members of the unit
are barely out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are 18, 19, 20, and it's a big adventure for them,''
Rucker said.
</P>
<P>
   The 795th has 63 members, mostly from northwest Missouri but
some from the Kansas City area. A few of the higher-ranking
personnel are under orders to go to Kosovo, while others
volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   Postal service is the only mission of the 795th, but only one of
the 63 reservists is a postal worker by profession. Brandt is a
construction contractor. Jones is a voucher examiner at Department
of Defense offices in Kansas City. Other professions range from
teachers to police officers. Some are college students.
</P>
<P>
   Rucker said the potential for holiday postal assignments
overseas doesn't drive people to other reserve units or dissuade
them from re-enlisting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people are a very tight-knit group, very family-oriented,''
Rucker said. ``They come here and they don't leave.'
</P>
</TEXT>
